	text-indent:-.25in;
	font-family:Wingdings;}
@list l35:level7
	{mso-level-number-format:bullet;
	mso-level-text:\F0B7;
	mso-level-tab-stop:4.25in;
	mso-level-number-position:left;
	margin-left:4.25in;
	text-indent:-.25in;
	font-family:Symbol;}
@list l35:level8
	{mso-level-number-format:bullet;
	mso-level-text:o;
	mso-level-tab-stop:4.75in;
	mso-level-number-position:left;
	margin-left:4.75in;
	text-indent:-.25in;
	font-family:"Courier New";}
@list l35:level9
	{mso-level-number-format:bullet;
	mso-level-text:\F0A7;
	mso-level-tab-stop:5.25in;
	mso-level-number-position:left;
	margin-left:5.25in;
	text-indent:-.25in;
	font-family:Wingdings;}
ol
	{margin-bottom:0in;}
ul
	{margin-bottom:0in;}
-->
</style>
<!--[if gte mso 10]>
<style>
 /* Style Definitions */
 table.MsoNormalTable
	{mso-style-name:"Table Normal";
	mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0;
	mso-tstyle-colband-size:0;
	mso-style-noshow:yes;
	mso-style-priority:99;
	mso-style-parent:" ;

<![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
 <o:shapedefaults v:ext="edit" spidmax="3074"/>
</xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
 <o:shapelayout v:ext="edit">
  <o:idmap v:ext="edit" data="1"/>
 </o:shapelayout></xml><![endif]-->
</head>

<body lang=EN-US link=blue vlink=purple style='tab-interval:.5in'>

<div class=Section1>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse;border:none;mso-border-alt:solid black .5pt;
 mso-yfti-tbllook:1184;mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;mso-border-insideh:
 .5pt solid black;mso-border-insidev:.5pt solid black'>
 <tr style='mso-yfti-irow:0;mso-yfti-firstrow:yes;mso-yfti-lastrow:yes;
  height:49.85pt'>
  <td width=111 valign=top style='width:83.4pt;border:solid black 1.0pt;
  mso-border-alt:solid black .5pt;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:49.85pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='font-size:48.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>E</span></b><b><span
  style='font-size:17.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=491 style='width:368.4pt;border:solid black 1.0pt;border-left:none;
  mso-border-left-alt:solid black .5pt;mso-border-alt:solid black .5pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:49.85pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='font-size:36.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>Ensuring Victory<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Since
your team always loses in football, you are now planning to tip the balance in
your favor by using a specially designed ball. To this end you construct many
balls of varying designs and from several different materials and ask your team
to try them out.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>As
expected, the feedback is rather random and inconsistent, with some players
liking some of the balls while others not liking those very same ones. Since
that is not helping, you decide on a more objective method of finding out which
ones are the best. You conduct a series of experiments and observe the behavior
of each of these balls when kicked. After the trials, you have worked out for
each ball an exact formula that gives the ball's position t seconds after being
kicked.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Using
that, you can determine the behavior of the balls in an actual game accurately
on paper. You are interested in knowing the position of the ball as well as the
speed at which it is travelling at specific moments in time. The position
(which is basically its Euclidean distance from a certain point) is found by
simply computing the value from the formula. The speed of the ball is defined
as the rate of change of distance with time at that moment (i.e. the <i>derivative</i>
of distance with respect to time). Since there are a lot of different balls,
you want to automate this process and get the results before the tournament
starts.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Unfortunately,
your football team is not any better at computing than they are at football
(you must have guessed that already). So it falls again on you to solve this
problem.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>Input<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Input
file will consist of a number of test cases (&lt;=50). Each test case consists
of two lines. The first line is a simple algebraic expression which gives the
distance covered by the ball in terms of <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>t</b>.
The length of this expression can be at most 200. It will consist of numbers
and the operators '*' and '+' and the variable <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>t</b>. The numbers will all be fractional numbers of the format X/Y,
where X is the numerator and Y the denominator. X and Y in this line will never
be negative and Y will never be 0. The expression might also contain
parentheses ( '(' and ')' ) to force precedence. The usual rules and precedence
of arithmetic apply when using the formula to compute the answer. The next line
consists of a single fractional number on a line by itself. It is the value of
t. This is also of the form X/Y, but here X and Y can also be negative. No
input line will be greater than 150 characters in length. There will be no
extra whitespace or any blank lines in input.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>Output<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Output
will consist of exactly as many lines as there are cases. For each case, print
a line of the form Case #C: A B. C is the case (starting from 1), while A and
B are fractional numbers in their simplest form. A is the distance of the ball
and B is its speed at time t. Both numbers are also of the form X/Y. If the
value is negative, print it as -X/Y. Zero should be printed as 0/1.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>Note:<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<ol style='margin-top:0in' start=1 type=1>
 <li class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-pagination:none;mso-list:
     l1 level1 lfo36;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:list .5in'><span
     style='font-size:12.0pt'>As these are specially built balls, their
     behavior will not always be like what you would expect from an ordinary
     ball. Don't make any assumptions.<o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <li class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-pagination:none;mso-list:
     l1 level1 lfo36;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:list .5in'><span
     style='font-size:12.0pt'>All calculations can be performed without any
     intermediate fraction, in their reduced forms, overflowing a 32-bit signed
     integer in their numerators and denominators. <o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <li class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-pagination:none;mso-list:
     l1 level1 lfo36;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:list .5in'><span
     style='font-size:12.0pt'>Both the distance and the speed can be negative -
     these trick footballs can actually move opposite to the direction they
     were kicked in.<o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <li class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-pagination:none;mso-list:
     l1 level1 lfo36;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:list .5in'><span
     style='font-size:12.0pt'>A fractional number X/Y is said to be in its most
     reduced or simplest form when there is no number other than 1 that evenly divides
     both X and Y. So, 3/1, 2/5 and 11/17 are in their simplest form but 9/3,
     5/20 and 10000/500 are not.<o:p></o:p></span></li>
</ol>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></b></p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse;border:none;mso-border-alt:double windowtext 1.5pt;
 mso-yfti-tbllook:1184;mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;mso-border-insideh:
 1.5pt double windowtext;mso-border-insidev:1.5pt double windowtext'>
 <tr style='mso-yfti-irow:0;mso-yfti-firstrow:yes'>
  <td width=295 valign=top style='width:221.4pt;border:double windowtext 1.5pt;
  padding:1.45pt 5.75pt 1.45pt 5.75pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>Sample Input<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=295 valign=top style='width:221.4pt;border:double windowtext 1.5pt;
  border-left:none;mso-border-left-alt:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:1.45pt 5.75pt 1.45pt 5.75pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>Sample Output<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='mso-yfti-irow:1;mso-yfti-lastrow:yes'>
  <td width=295 valign=top style='width:221.4pt;border:double windowtext 1.5pt;
  border-top:none;mso-border-top-alt:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:1.45pt 5.75pt 1.45pt 5.75pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b><span style='font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>((t*t)+2/1)
  <o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b><span style='font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>1/2
  <o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b><span style='font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>((t+t)*2/1)
  <o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b><span style='font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>1/2
  <o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b><span style='font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>(t*1/2)+(t*1/3)
  <o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b><span style='font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>1/4</span></b>
  </p>
  </td>
  <td width=295 valign=top style='width:221.4pt;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;border-right:double windowtext 1.5pt;
  mso-border-top-alt:double windowtext 1.5pt;mso-border-left-alt:double windowtext 1.5pt;
  padding:1.45pt 5.75pt 1.45pt 5.75pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b><span style='font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  #1: 9/4 1/1 <o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b><span style='font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  #2: 2/1 4/1 <o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b><span style='font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  #3: 5/24 5/6 <o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autospace:none'><b
  style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<div class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:45.8pt 91.6pt 137.4pt 183.2pt 229.0pt 274.8pt 320.6pt 366.4pt 412.2pt 458.0pt 503.8pt 549.6pt 595.4pt 641.2pt 687.0pt 732.8pt'>

<body lang=EN-US link=blue vlink=purple style='tab-interval:.5in'>

<div class=Section1>

<table border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 style='border-collapse:collapse;
 border:none;mso-border-alt:solid black .5pt;mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
 <tr style='height:49.85pt'>
  <td width=111 valign=top style='width:83.4pt;border:solid black .5pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:49.85pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='font-size:48.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Garamond'>F</span></b><b><span
  style='font-size:17.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Garamond'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=491 style='width:368.4pt;border:solid black .5pt;border-left:none;
  mso-border-left-alt:solid black .5pt;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:49.85pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='font-size:30.0pt;font-family:Garamond'>Floating-Point Numbers<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span class=apple-style-span><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;color:black'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Floating-point
numbers are represented differently in computers than integers. That is why a
32-bit floating-point number can represent values in the magnitude of 10<sup>38</sup>
while a 32-bit integer can only represent values as high as 2<sup>32</sup>.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Although
there are variations in the ways floating-point numbers are stored in
Computers, in this problem we will assume that floating-point numbers are
stored in the following way:<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><!--[if gte vml 1]><o:wrapblock><v:shapetype
  id="_x0000_t75" coordsize="21600,21600" o:spt="75" o:preferrelative="t"
  path="m@4@5l@4@11@9@11@9@5xe" filled="f" stroked="f">
  <v:stroke joinstyle="miter"/>
  <v:formulas>
   <v:f eqn="if lineDrawn pixelLineWidth 0"/>
   <v:f eqn="sum @0 1 0"/>
   <v:f eqn="sum 0 0 @1"/>
   <v:f eqn="prod @2 1 2"/>
   <v:f eqn="prod @3 21600 pixelWidth"/>
   <v:f eqn="prod @3 21600 pixelHeight"/>
   <v:f eqn="sum @0 0 1"/>
   <v:f eqn="prod @6 1 2"/>
   <v:f eqn="prod @7 21600 pixelWidth"/>
   <v:f eqn="sum @8 21600 0"/>
   <v:f eqn="prod @7 21600 pixelHeight"/>
   <v:f eqn="sum @10 21600 0"/>
  </v:formulas>
  <v:path o:extrusionok="f" gradientshapeok="t" o:connecttype="rect"/>
  <o:lock v:ext="edit" aspectratio="t"/>
 </v:shapetype><v:shape id="_x0000_s1065" type="#_x0000_t75" style='position:absolute;
  left:0;text-align:left;margin-left:18.45pt;margin-top:0;width:431.9pt;
  height:160.6pt;z-index:1'>
  <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
  <w:wrap type="topAndBottom"/>
 </v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><span style='mso-ignore:vglayout'>
 <table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
  <tr>
   <td width=25 height=0></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
   <td></td>
   <td><img width=575 height=214 src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  v:shapes="_x0000_s1065"></td>
  </tr>
 </table>
 </span><![endif]><!--[if gte vml 1]></o:wrapblock><![endif]--><br
style='mso-ignore:vglayout' clear=ALL>
<span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Floating-point numbers have two parts mantissa
and exponent. M-bits are allotted for mantissa and E bits are allotted for
exponent. There is also one bit that denotes the sign of number (If this bit is
0 then the number is positive and if it is 1 then the number is negative) and
another bit that denotes the sign of exponent (If this bit is 0 then exponent
is positive otherwise negative). The value of mantissa and exponent together
make the value of the floating-point number. If the value of mantissa is m then
it maintains the constraints <sub><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shape id="_x0000_i1026"
 type="#_x0000_t75" style='width:48.75pt;height:30.75pt' o:ole=" >
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=65 height=41
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  v:shapes="_x0000_i1026"><![endif]></sub><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
 <o:OLEObject Type="Embed" ProgID="Equation.3" ShapeID="_x0000_i1026"
  DrawAspect="Content" ObjectID="_1338842024">
 </o:OLEObject>
</xml><![endif]-->. The left most digit of mantissa must always be 1 to
maintain the constraint <sub><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shape id="_x0000_i1027"
 type="#_x0000_t75" style='width:48.75pt;height:30.75pt' o:ole=" >
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=65 height=41
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  v:shapes="_x0000_i1027"><![endif]></sub><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
 <o:OLEObject Type="Embed" ProgID="Equation.3" ShapeID="_x0000_i1027"
  DrawAspect="Content" ObjectID="_1338842025">
 </o:OLEObject>
</xml><![endif]-->. So this bit is not stored as it is always 1. So the bits in
mantissa actually denote the digits at the right side of decimal point of a
binary number (Excluding the digit just to the right of decimal point) <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>In
the figure above we can see a floating-point number where M=8 and E=6. The
largest value this floating-point number can represent is (in binary) <sub><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shape
 id="_x0000_i1029" type="#_x0000_t75" style='width:111pt;height:18pt' o:ole=" >
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=148 height=24
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  v:shapes="_x0000_i1029"><![endif]></sub><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
 <o:OLEObject Type="Embed" ProgID="Equation.3" ShapeID="_x0000_i1029"
  DrawAspect="Content" ObjectID="_1338842026">
 </o:OLEObject>
</xml><![endif]-->. The decimal equivalent to this number is: <sub><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shape
 id="_x0000_i1030" type="#_x0000_t75" style='width:225pt;height:18.75pt' o:ole=" >
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=300 height=25
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  v:shapes="_x0000_i1030"><![endif]></sub><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
 <o:OLEObject Type="Embed" ProgID="Equation.3" ShapeID="_x0000_i1030"
  DrawAspect="Content" ObjectID="_1338842027">
 </o:OLEObject>
</xml><![endif]-->. Given the maximum possible value represented by a certain
floating point type, you will have to find how many bits are allotted for
mantissa (M) and how many bits are allotted for exponent (E) in that certain
type.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span class=apple-style-span><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;color:black'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:Garamond;color:black'>Input<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:Garamond;color:black'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>The
input file contains around 300 line of input. Each line contains a
floating-point number F that denotes the maximum value that can be represented
by a certain floating-point type. The floating point number is expressed in
decimal exponent format. So a number AeB actually denotes the value <sub><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shape
 id="_x0000_i1028" type="#_x0000_t75" style='width:38.25pt;height:15.75pt'
 o:ole=" >
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=51 height=21
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  v:shapes="_x0000_i1028"><![endif]></sub><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
 <o:OLEObject Type="Embed" ProgID="Equation.3" ShapeID="_x0000_i1028"
  DrawAspect="Content" ObjectID="_1338842028">
 </o:OLEObject>
</xml><![endif]-->. A line containing 0e0 terminates input. The value of A will
satisfy the constraint 0&lt;A&lt;10 and will have exactly 15 digits after the
decimal point.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">   </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:Garamond;color:black'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;
mso-outline-level:3'><b><span style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:Garamond;
color:black'>Output<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;tab-stops:143.25pt'><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>For each line of input produce one line of output.
This line contains the value of M and E. You can assume that each of the inputs
(except the last one) has a possible and unique solution. You can also assume
that inputs will be such that the value of M and E will follow the constraints:
9 &#8805; M &#8805; 0 and 30 &#8805; E &#8805; 1. Also there is no need to
assume that (M+E+2) will be a multiple of 8.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;tab-stops:143.25pt'><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<table border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 style='border-collapse:collapse;
 border:none;mso-border-alt:double windowtext 1.5pt;mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>

  </td>

  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:Garamond'>Sample Output<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>

  <td width=295 valign=top style='width:221.4pt;border:double windowtext 1.5pt;
  border-top:none;mso-border-top-alt:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:.7pt 5.75pt .7pt 5.75pt'>

  <p class=MsoNormal style='tab-stops:165.0pt;mso-layout-grid-align:none;

  <p class=MsoNormal style='tab-stops:165.0pt;mso-layout-grid-align:none;

  6<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<body lang=EN-US link=blue vlink=purple style='tab-interval:.5in'>

<div class=Section1>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse;border:none;mso-border-alt:solid black .5pt;
 mso-yfti-tbllook:1184;mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;mso-border-insideh:

 <tr style='mso-yfti-irow:0;mso-yfti-firstrow:yes;mso-yfti-lastrow:yes;
  height:49.85pt'>
  <td width=111 valign=top style='width:83.4pt;border:solid black 1.0pt;
  mso-border-alt:solid black .5pt;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:49.85pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='font-size:48.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>G</span></b><b><span
  style='font-size:17.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=491 style='width:368.4pt;border:solid black 1.0pt;border-left:none;
  mso-border-left-alt:solid black .5pt;mso-border-alt:solid black .5pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:49.85pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='font-size:28.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:36.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>Gentle
  ping, to the old King</span></b><b><span style='font-size:36.0pt;font-family:
  "Garamond","serif"'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;text-align:justify'><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shapetype
 id="_x0000_t75" coordsize="21600,21600" o:spt="75" o:preferrelative="t"
 path="m@4@5l@4@11@9@11@9@5xe" filled="f" stroked="f">
 <v:stroke joinstyle="miter"/>
 <v:formulas>
  <v:f eqn="if lineDrawn pixelLineWidth 0"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum @0 1 0"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum 0 0 @1"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @2 1 2"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @3 21600 pixelWidth"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @3 21600 pixelHeight"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum @0 0 1"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @6 1 2"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @7 21600 pixelWidth"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum @8 21600 0"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @7 21600 pixelHeight"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum @10 21600 0"/>
 </v:formulas>
 <v:path o:extrusionok="f" gradientshapeok="t" o:connecttype="rect"/>
 <o:lock v:ext="edit" aspectratio="t"/>
</v:shapetype><v:shape id="Picture_x0020_4" o:spid="_x0000_s1071" type="#_x0000_t75"
 style='position:absolute;left:0;text-align:left;margin-left:0;margin-top:14.85pt;
 width:229.5pt;height:179.45pt;z-index:1;visibility:visible;
 mso-position-horizontal:left'>
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/g_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
 <w:wrap type="square"/>
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=306 height=239
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/g_files/image001.png"  align=left hspace=12 v:shapes="Picture_x0020_4"><![endif]><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>All of you must have heard
the name of <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>The Lord of the Rings</i>. As
we know that the ring, that was said to be the lord of the rings, was destroyed
by <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Frodo Baggins</i> in the mountain of
doom. And so, the evil spirit <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Sauron</i>
was not able to capture the ring and was finally destroyed. After defeating <i
style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Sauron</i>s army, <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'>Aragorn</i> became the king and with his coronation the world moved
into the dominion of Men. And they lived happily ever after.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>But thats not actually the whole story. Defeating <i
style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Sauron</i> was not the final victory over
&quot;evil&quot; as such. Because the evil dark lord and <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'>Sauron</i>s master - <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Morgoth</i>
can still recover, grow and take shape again.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>After the death of <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'>Sauron</i>, many years have passed. <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Aragorn</i>
is old now and his son <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Eldarion</i> is
the king. Things were going fine except one day they discovered the fact that <i
style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Morgoth</i> has recovered his powers and is
planning to take over the world. The whole middle Earth is again waiting for
another war.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Eldarion</span></i><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'> has made several plans with
the wise council to stop <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Morgoth</i>.
They have the map, so they are aware of the fact that there are some
territories in Middle-Earth. Many two-way roads exist between some pairs of
territories. The times to travel all roads are known to them. To go from a
territory to another one, they can use one or more roads. And all territories
are reachable from any territory.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Thats why they have the fear that if <i
style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Morgoth</i>s army enters to any territory
then they can invade any territory they want. To protect a road, huge number of
armies has to be placed there. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Eldarion</span></i><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'> is a man of honor like his
father. So, he doesnt want to leave any territory unguarded or weak. But since
his armies are little in number compared to <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Morgoth</i>s,
he is at a loss. Cause if he sends armies to protect the roads then they may
win, but some territories might go down. But if he sends the armies to protect
the territories, then if any territory goes down, more will be in danger
because <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Morgoth</i>s army will forward
their march using the unguarded roads and of course they can capture roads and
can hamper the communication amongst territories. But if <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'>Eldarion</i> places armies to protect both roads and territories then
both roads and territories will be weak since the number of armies protecting a
territory or a road will be too low to fight against <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'>Morgoth</i>s army.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>After a long discussion, they have got many ideas,
but no idea fascinated <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Eldarion</i>. So,
he went to his father, <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Aragorn</i> - the
old king. <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Aragorn</i> took a day to
think, and the next day he told his son about his idea. The idea is to keep as
fewer roads as possible such that the armies can still be sent from any
territory to all other territories. Rest of the roads will be destroyed. As
they have many trebuchets and catapults, they can destroy roads easily and
without heavy effort.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>After that they will pick some territories that have
the higher chances to be attacked first. These territories will be selected by
Aragorn himself from his past experience in battles, and these are called the <i
style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>prime territories</i>. All the armies will
be assigned to protect these territories only. When a territory is under
attack, either prime or non-prime, the informers in this territory will seek
help from a <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>prime territory</i>. This
helping territory will be randomly chosen. After the arrival of the armies, the
informers will seek help from another randomly chosen <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'>prime territory</i>. And they will continue seeking help until armies
from all the <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>prime territories</i> come.
The informers will always choose a new <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>prime
territory</i> for seeking help. So, the <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>estimated
time</i> for a territory is the total required time for armies from all <i
style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>prime territories</i> to reach this
territory. And the <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Total estimated time</i>
is the summation of <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>estimated times</i>
of all territories. You can assume that the time to inform other territories is
negligible.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Now, they are planning to use <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'>Aragorns</i> idea. So, they want to keep the roads such that the <i
style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Total estimated time</i> is as low as possible.
You are one of the head councilors and you know the map fully. Now you have to
find the minimum <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Total estimated time</i>.
Remember that the whole middle earth is depending on you.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b><span style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>Input<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>The first line of the input will contain <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>T (&lt;= 100)</b>, denoting the number of
cases.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Each case starts with a blank line. The next line
will contain three integers <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>n (2&lt;=n
&lt;= 16)</b>, <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>m</b> and <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>k (1 &lt;= k &lt;= n)</b>, where <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>n</b> is the number of territories, <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>m</b> is the total number of roads and <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>k</b> is the number of <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'>prime territories</i>. The territories are numbered from <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>0</b> to <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>n  1</b>. The next line contains <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>k</b>
integers separated by spaces. These integers denote the <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:
normal'>prime territories</i>. Each of the next <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>m</b> lines will contain three integers <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>u, v (0 &lt;= u, v &lt; n and u != v)</b> and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>w (1 &lt;= w &lt;= 1000)</b> denoting that there is a two way road
between territory <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>u</b> and <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>v</b> and the time to cross this road is <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>w</b> minutes. You can assume that all the
roads are valid, no road is listed more than once and multiple roads between
same pair of territories dont exist.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b><span style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>Output
<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>For each case, print the case number and the minimum
<i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Total estimated time</i>.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse;border:none;mso-border-alt:double windowtext 1.5pt;
 mso-yfti-tbllook:1184;mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;mso-border-insideh:
 1.5pt double windowtext;mso-border-insidev:1.5pt double windowtext'>
 <tr style='mso-yfti-irow:0;mso-yfti-firstrow:yes'>
  <td width=295 valign=top style='width:221.4pt;border:double windowtext 1.5pt;
  padding:1.45pt 5.75pt 1.45pt 5.75pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>Sample Input<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=295 valign=top style='width:221.4pt;border:double windowtext 1.5pt;
  border-left:none;mso-border-left-alt:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:1.45pt 5.75pt 1.45pt 5.75pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>Sample Output<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>

<body lang=EN-US link=blue vlink=purple style='tab-interval:.5in'>

<div class=Section1>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=631
 style='width:473.4pt;border-collapse:collapse;border:none;mso-border-alt:solid black .5pt;
 mso-yfti-tbllook:1184;mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;mso-border-insideh:

 <tr style='mso-yfti-irow:0;mso-yfti-firstrow:yes;mso-yfti-lastrow:yes;
  height:49.85pt'>
  <td width=111 valign=top style='width:83.4pt;border:solid black 1.0pt;
  mso-border-alt:solid black .5pt;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:49.85pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='font-size:48.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>H</span></b><b><span
  style='font-size:17.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=520 style='width:390.0pt;border:solid black 1.0pt;border-left:none;
  mso-border-left-alt:solid black .5pt;mso-border-alt:solid black .5pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:49.85pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='font-size:36.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>Hello, Mafia<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;text-indent:.5in'><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shapetype
 id="_x0000_t75" coordsize="21600,21600" o:spt="75" o:preferrelative="t"
 path="m@4@5l@4@11@9@11@9@5xe" filled="f" stroked="f">
 <v:stroke joinstyle="miter"/>
 <v:formulas>
  <v:f eqn="if lineDrawn pixelLineWidth 0"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum @0 1 0"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum 0 0 @1"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @2 1 2"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @3 21600 pixelWidth"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @3 21600 pixelHeight"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum @0 0 1"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @6 1 2"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @7 21600 pixelWidth"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum @8 21600 0"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @7 21600 pixelHeight"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum @10 21600 0"/>
 </v:formulas>
 <v:path o:extrusionok="f" gradientshapeok="t" o:connecttype="rect"/>
 <o:lock v:ext="edit" aspectratio="t"/>
</v:shapetype><v:shape id="_x0000_s1069" type="#_x0000_t75" style='position:absolute;
 left:0;text-align:left;margin-left:0;margin-top:1.55pt;width:153pt;height:184.2pt;
 z-index:1;mso-wrap-distance-left:0;mso-wrap-distance-right:0;
 mso-position-horizontal:left' filled="t">
 <v:fill color2="black"/>
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/h_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
 <w:wrap type="square" side="largest"/>
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=204 height=246
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/h_files/image001.png"  align=left v:shapes="_x0000_s1069"><![endif]><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>Programming contests are now too frequent in
Bangladesh. Just 5 years ago, you could participate in only one or two contest
per year, but now, there is one in almost every month. Moreover, they are also
in different cities around the country. Maybe, someday, you will see contests
in every week, or maybe every day.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;text-indent:.5in'><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>Due to the schedule of the contests, the contestants
are really conscious about optimizing the time spent in traveling. For example,
if the contest starts at 9:00AM, they plan to reach contest venue, just before
that time, so that, no time is wasted.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;text-indent:.5in'><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>Contestants will be using various forms of public
transportations like bus, train, taxi, rickshaw to reach the contest spot. Bus
and train may be used to transport between cities, taxi and rickshaws may be
used to move within cities. You will be given all the routes one can use to
move between cities. Since, contestants are optimizing their time spent in the
contest, they will always take the fastest route possible. Rickshaws and taxis
always use the fastest route, so you don't have to be concerned about them.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;text-indent:.5in'><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>As the programming contests have become popular, it
also caught interest of the mafias as well. They are planning to sabotage this
contest. For that, they will call strike in different cities, and thus, no
vehicle enters or leaves the city. You can't even use rickshaws and taxi to
move in the city during the strike. So, it won't be possible for any team to
travel through the city, and may have to use a longer route. If they can't use
their shortest route, they will surely be late, and thus, cannot attend the
contest.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;text-indent:.5in'><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>Mafia lords have a list of teams. They will call
strike in minimum number of cities, so that these teams are unable attend the
contest. There may be more than one set of cities they can call strike to
sabotage the contest, in those cases, they will probably choose the one that
affects minimum number of cities.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;text-indent:.5in'><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>You have some how managed to know about this evil
plan. Now, given the list of cities, you have to find the how many cities will
be affected by it.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<h2><span style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>Input<o:p></o:p></span></h2>

<p class=Constraints style='margin-left:0in;text-align:justify'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>Input starts with an integer <b><span
style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>T(T</span></b></span><b><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif";mso-fareast-font-family:"Liberation Serif";
mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>&#8804;3</span></b><b><span style='font-family:
"Times New Roman","serif";mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>0)</span></b><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>, the number of test cases.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoBodyText style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Each
test case starts with two integers <b><span style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>N,M</span></b>(<b><span
style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>1</span></b></span><b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:"Liberation Serif";mso-bidi-font-style:
italic'>&#8804;</span></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:
"DejaVu Sans";mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>N</span></b><b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:"Liberation Serif";mso-bidi-font-style:
italic'>&#8804;100000</span></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:
"DejaVu Sans";mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>, 0</span></b><b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:"Liberation Serif";mso-bidi-font-style:
italic'>&#8804;</span></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:
"DejaVu Sans";mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>M</span></b><b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:"Liberation Serif";mso-bidi-font-style:
italic'>&#8804;500000</span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>) the number of
cities and the number of direct routes between cities. Each city is denoted by
an integer between 0 and <b><span style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>N</span></b>-1.
The contest is going to be held in city 0. Each of the next <b><span
style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>M</span></b> lines each contain three
integers, <b><span style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>u</span>, <span
style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>v</span>, <span style='mso-bidi-font-style:
italic'>t</span>(0</b></span><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:
"Liberation Serif"'>&#8804;</span></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-fareast-font-family:"DejaVu Sans";mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>u</span></b><b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:"DejaVu Sans"'>, <span
style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>v</span>&lt;<span style='mso-bidi-font-style:
italic'>N</span>,1</span></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:
"Liberation Serif"'>&#8804;<span style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>t</span>&#8804;1000</span></b><b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>)</span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>, a route
between city <b><span style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>u</span></b> and <b><span
style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>v</span></b> that takes time <b><span
style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>t</span></b>. There will be at most one
direct route between two cities.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoBodyText style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>This
is followed by an integer <b><span style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>Q(1</span></b></span><b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:"Liberation Serif";mso-bidi-font-style:
italic'>&#8804;</span></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:
"DejaVu Sans";mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>Q</span></b><b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:"Liberation Serif";mso-bidi-font-style:
italic'>&#8804;</span></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:
"DejaVu Sans";mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>1000)</span></b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>, the number of queries. Next <b><span
style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>Q</span></b> lines each describe a query.
Each query starts with an integer <b><span style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>K(1</span></b></span><b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:"Liberation Serif";mso-bidi-font-style:
italic'>&#8804;</span></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:
"DejaVu Sans";mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>K</span></b><b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:"Liberation Serif";mso-bidi-font-style:
italic'>&#8804;</span></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:
"DejaVu Sans";mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>100)</span></b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>, the number of teams in the list, followed by <b><span
style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>K</span></b> integers <b><span
style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>n<sub>i</sub></span></b> <b><span
style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>(0</span></b></span><b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:"Liberation Serif";mso-bidi-font-style:
italic'>&#8804;</span></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-style:
italic'>n<sub>i</sub></span></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:
"Liberation Serif";mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>&lt;</span></b><b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>N)</span></b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'>.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoBodyText style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>There
will be a blank line before each test case.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<h2><span style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>Output<o:p></o:p></span></h2>

<p class=MsoBodyText><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>For each test case, output
the case number. For each query, output<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoBodyText style='margin-left:1.0in;tab-stops:74.6pt'><b><i><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'><span style='mso-tab-count:1'> </span>x</span></i></b><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'> possible way(s) to sabotage the contest.<br>
Teams from at least <b><i>y</i></b> cities will be late. <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoBodyText><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Where <b><i>x</i></b> is
the number of possible ways to sabotage, and <b><i>y</i></b> is the minimum
number cities, affected by the strike. If sabotaging is not necessary, output <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoBodyText style='tab-stops:74.6pt'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'><span
style='mso-tab-count:1'>            </span>Will not sabotage.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoBodyText><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>For formatting details, see
the sample output<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoBodyText style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

</head>

<body lang=EN-US link=blue vlink=purple style='tab-interval:.5in'>

<div class=Section1>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse;border:none;mso-border-alt:solid black .5pt;
 mso-yfti-tbllook:1184;mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;mso-border-insideh:
 .5pt solid black;mso-border-insidev:.5pt solid black'>
 <tr style='mso-yfti-irow:0;mso-yfti-firstrow:yes;mso-yfti-lastrow:yes;
  height:49.85pt'>
  <td width=111 valign=top style='width:83.4pt;border:solid black 1.0pt;
  mso-border-alt:solid black .5pt;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:49.85pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='font-size:48.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>I</span></b><b><span
  style='font-size:17.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=491 style='width:368.4pt;border:solid black 1.0pt;border-left:none;
  mso-border-left-alt:solid black .5pt;mso-border-alt:solid black .5pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:49.85pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b
  style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:23.0pt;font-family:
  "Garamond","serif"'>Innovative Procession Management<span style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
  bold'><o:p></o:p></span></span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p class=MsoBodyText><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Its
FIFA World Cup 2010. The whole world is waiting for the greatest event on the
planet. Since huge number of people will come to South Africa for the world
cup; its quite tough for them to maintain the flow of the people as well as
the traffic. Thats why they are planning to forbid vehicles to use some roads.
But if all the roads are forbidden then people would be in trouble.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:16.55pt;text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>The
World Cup authority has divided South Africa into <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>n</b> junctions and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>m</b> one
way roads. Before each match, the authority will consider some junctions as
interesting junctions, where people will get together and set out for the
stadium in processions. Now each procession will try to use the shortest path
towards the stadium. Thats why the World Cup authority wants to forbid
vehicles in the roads which may be used by the processions.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:16.55pt;text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>The
idea is as follows. They will first find the shortest path amongst the paths
from the interesting junctions to the stadium. They will block all the roads in
the path. If there are multiple shortest paths from one or multiple interesting
junctions to the stadium, they will block all of them. They will send some
vehicles along the paths which will put notice boards to the roads such that no
vehicles can go through. After that they will search for more shortest-paths
considering the blocked roads and send vehicles for the paths (if any). They
will continue blocking the roads until no path is found.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:16.55pt;text-align:justify'><span
style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Now
your task is to solve the problem for them.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoBodyText><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<h2 align=left style='margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;
margin-left:0in;text-align:left;mso-pagination:none;mso-hyphenate:none'><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>Input<o:p></o:p></span></h2>

<p class=Constraints style='margin-left:0in;text-align:justify'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>Input starts with an integer <b><span
style='mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>T </span></b><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>(&lt;= 100)</b>, denoting the number of test cases.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoBodyText style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Each
case starts with a blank line. The next line contains three integers <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>n (2 &lt;= n &lt;= 100), m (0 &lt;= m &lt;=
10000)</b>, and<b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'> S (1 &lt;= S &lt; n)</b>.
<b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>S</b> is the total number of interesting
junctions.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoBodyText style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>The
next line will contain <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>S + 1</b>
different integer (each of them lies between <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>1</b> and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>n</b>) separated by
spaces, where the first <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>S</b> integers
denote the interesting junctions, and the last one denotes the stadium.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoBodyText style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Each
of the next <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>m</b> lines will contain 3
integers <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>u v w (1 &lt;= u, v &lt;= n, u
!= v, 1&lt;=w&lt;=10000)</b> meaning that there is a road from <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>u</b> to <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>v</b>, and the length is <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>w</b>.
If multiple roads are listed for same junctions in either direction, you can
assume that the roads are different.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<h2 align=left style='margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;
margin-left:0in;text-align:left;mso-pagination:none;mso-hyphenate:none'><span
style='font-size:14.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>Output<o:p></o:p></span></h2>

<p class=MsoBodyText style='text-align:justify'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>For
each case print the case number in a single line. If no path is found then
print <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>No road to block</b>. If a
shortest path is found then print the path cost <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>c</b> as <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>The path cost is c</b>.
After that report the roads that are blocked in <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>u v w</b> form (as in input). They should be listed in ascending order
based on <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>u;</b> for same <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>u</b>, based on <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>v</b>. Report all the shortest path costs and the roads in similar
format. Check the samples for more details.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse;border:none;mso-border-alt:double windowtext 1.5pt;
 mso-yfti-tbllook:1184;mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;mso-border-insideh:
 1.5pt double windowtext;mso-border-insidev:1.5pt double windowtext'>

  </td>
  <td width=295 valign=top style='width:221.4pt;border:double windowtext 1.5pt;
  border-left:none;mso-border-left-alt:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:1.45pt 5.75pt 1.45pt 5.75pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span

  </td>

11813||||||false||||||
<html>
<h2>Problem A: Shopping</h2>

<img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11813.jpg"  align=right>

You have just moved into a new apartment and have a long list
of items you need to buy. Unfortunately, to buy this many items
requires going to many different stores. You would like to minimize
the amount of driving necessary to buy all the items you need.
<p>
Your city is organized as a set of intersections connected by roads.
Your house and every store is located at some intersection. Your task
is to find the shortest route that begins at your house, visits all the
stores that you need to shop at, and returns to your house.
<p>

<h3>Input Specification</h3>
The first line of input contains a single integer, the number of test
cases to follow.
Each test case begins with a line containing two integers N and M,
the number of intersections and roads in the city, respectively.
Each of these integers is between 1 and 100000, inclusive.
The intersections are numbered from 0 to N-1. 
Your house is at the intersection numbered 0.
M lines follow, each containing three integers X, Y, and D,
indicating that the intersections X and Y are connected
by a bidirectional road of length D.
The following line contains a single integer S, the number
of stores you need to visit, which is between 1 and ten, inclusive.
The subsequent S lines each contain one integer indicating
the intersection at which each store is located.
It is possible to reach all of the stores from your house.

<h3>Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
1
4 6
0 1 1
1 2 1
2 3 1
3 0 1
0 2 5
1 3 5
3
1
2
3
</pre>

<h3>Output Specification</h3>
For each test case, output a line containing a single integer,
the length of the shortest possible shopping trip from your house,
visiting all the stores, and returning to your house.

<h3>Output for Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
4
</pre>
<hr>
<i> Ond&#345;ej Lhot&aacute;k</i>
</html>

______________________________________________________
11814||||||false||||||
<html>
<h2>Problem B: Stack Machine</h2>

<img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11814.png"  align=right>

A mathematician observes one person get on a bus. Then two people get
off the bus. The mathematician says: "If one more person gets on the
bus, the bus will be empty."
<p>
A stack machine is a special kind of bus. It only has doors
at the front, and it is so narrow that the people on the bus
cannot move past each other. Of the people on the bus, the
person who got on the bus last must be the first to get off.
<p>
The bus travels in a city in which roads connect intersections,
and all the roads are unidirectional. Along each road, a 
person either gets on or off the bus.
<p>
The mathematician does not know the identity of the bus passengers,
but can estimate their height. Note that there may be multiple
people with the same height.
<p>
Your task is to plan the route of the bus. The bus must be empty
at the beginning and end
of the route. Along the route, it must pick up and drop off the
people corresponding to the roads it travels on. The height of the
person that gets on or off the bus is fixed for each road.
<p>

<h3>Input Specification</h3>
The first line of input contains a single integer, the number of test
cases to follow. Each test case begins with a line containing three
integers N, M, Q, the number of intersections and roads
in the city and the number of queries, respectively. The number of intersections is between 1
and 100, inclusive. The number of roads and the number of queries
are each between 1 and 100000, inclusive. 
Intersections in the city are numbered from 1 to N.
The first line of each test case is followed by M lines describing
the roads. Each of these lines contains three integers X, Y, and Z.
These integers indicate that a road exists from intersection X to
intersection Y, and that when the bus travels on this road, a person
who is Z centimetres tall gets on the bus, if Z is positive, or a person who
is
-Z centimetres tall gets off the bus, if Z is negative. For example, Z=170 indicates that
a 170 cm tall person gets on the bus, and Z=-170 indicates that a 170 cm tall person gets off the bus.
Each person is at least 40 cm and at most 220 cm tall.
The lines describing the roads are followed by Q more lines, each
describing a query. A line describing a query contains two integers,
the beginning and ending intersections of the bus route.

<h3>Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
1
2 2 4
1 2 100
2 1 -100
1 1
2 2
1 2
2 1
</pre>

<h3>Output Specification</h3>
For each query, output a line containing a single integer giving the
length of the shortest non-empty path that the bus can take from the
beginning to the end of the route. The input data will be such that this
length is no more than 10^9. If there is no such path, output
a line containing the word <tt>impossible</tt>.

<h3>Output for Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
2
impossible
impossible
impossible
</pre>
<hr>
<i> Ond&#345;ej Lhot&aacute;k</i>
</html>

______________________________________________________
11815||||||false||||||
<html>
<h2>Problem C: Ideas</h2>

<img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11815.png"  align=right>

A unique feature of ideas is that they are not consumed when used. A
good idea can benefit arbitrarily many people without diminishing the
value of the idea. An idea can even serve as the basis for creative
people to derive even better ideas. Each person relies on a specific
set of ideas to build on and create new ideas.
<p>
In order to realize these benefits, ideas need to be communicated to
the people who use them. People have developed an extensive worldwide
communication network to satisfy this need. The network is composed
of a series of tubes connecting people. The tubes are inhabited by
curious creatures called packets which carry ideas from one person to
another. In order to avoid collisions between packets, the tubes are all
unidirectional. Each person can have zero or more incoming and zero or
more outgoing tubes.
<p>
All of the packets start at the same person, and each packet follows
the following algorithm:
<ol>
    <li>Learn and remember the ideas created by the current person.
    <li>If there are no outgoing tubes from the current person, stop
        executing the algorithm.
    <li>Otherwise, choose an arbitrary outgoing tube and use it to
        travel to a new person.
    <li>Tell the new person all of the ideas that he or she needs from
        other people.
    <li>Go back to step 1.
</ol>
<p>
The input data is such that it is possible for a packet to reach
every person from person 0, and whenever a person P relies on a given
idea, every path a packet could have taken to reach P will have
visited at least one person who created that idea. It is possible
for more than one person to independently create the same idea.
<p>
To ease the strain on each packet, you would like to minimize the number
of ideas that it remembers at any given time by directing the
packet to forget certain ideas in certain tubes. However, in so doing,
you must ensure that no matter what path the packet takes, every time it
visits a person, the packet knows all of the ideas that the person needs.

<h3>Input Specification</h3>
The first line of input contains a single integer, the number of test
cases to follow. Each test case begins with a line containing three
integers N, M, I, the number of people, tubes, and ideas,
respectively. Each of these integers is between 1 and one thousand,
inclusive. People are numbered from 0 to N-1, ideas from 0 to I-1.
All of the packets start at person 0. 
2N lines follow, two lines for each person in order from 0 to N-1.
Each of these lines contains some number of integers separated by spaces.
For each person, the first line lists the ideas that the person
needs, and the second line lists the ideas that the person creates.
A given idea will never appear on both lines for the same person.
M more lines follow, each describing a tube using two integers:
the source and destination person of the tube.

<h3>Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
1
3 3 2

1
1
0
0
1
0 1
1 2
2 1
</pre>

<h3>Output Specification</h3>
For each test case, output M lines, each corresponding to one
of the tubes in the same order as in the input. For each tube,
output a list of integers: the minimal set of ideas the
packet must have in its memory when travelling through the
given tube. Output the ideas in each set in increasing order.

<h3>Output for Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
1
0
1
</pre>
<hr>
<i> Ond&#345;ej Lhot&aacute;k</i>
</html>

______________________________________________________
11816||||||false||||||
<html>
<h2>Problem D: HST</h2>

<img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11816.jpg"  align=right>

On July 1st, Ontario's Provincial Sales Tax (PST) was merged with the
Federal Goods and Services Tax (GST), creating the Harmonized Sales Tax (HST).
This changed the rate of tax Ontarians pay on various items.
<p>
Dalton would like to calculate how this change will affect
his personal monthly budget.
<p>
<h3>Input Specification</h3>
The first line of input contains a single integer, the number of test
cases to follow. Each test case begins with a line containing two
integers N, M,
the number of categories of items and the number of
purchases Dalton makes each month, respectively.
Each of these integers is between 1 and 100000, inclusive.
N lines follow, each describing a category of item.
Each of these lines contains a category name,
which is a string of at most 30 uppercase letters,
followed by three percentages, giving the PST, GST, and HST
rate on that category. Each percentage is a number with up
to two digits after the decimal point, and each percentage
is followed by the % symbol.
Each percentage is at least 0% and at most 100%.
These lines are followed by M more lines, each describing
one of Dalton's purchases.
Each of these lines contains a category name and a price in dollars
and cents and prefixed by the $ symbol. Each such line indicates
the amount of pre-tax money that Dalton spends on an item in
the specified category. The amount of each tax to be paid on
an item is rounded to the nearest cent; if the tax amount is exactly
half a cent more than a whole number of cents, it is rounded up to the
nearest greater whole number of cents.

<h3>Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
1
1 1
gas 0% 5% 13%
gas $100.00
</pre>

<h3>Output Specification</h3>
For each test case, output the difference, in dollars and cents,
between the total HST payable and the total sum of PST and GST payable
on Dalton's monthly purchases. If the HST is more than the PST+GST,
output a positive amount. If the HST is less than the PST+GST,
output a negative amount.

<h3>Output for Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
8.00
</pre>
<hr>
<i> Ond&#345;ej Lhot&aacute;k</i>
</html>

______________________________________________________
11817||||||false||||||
<html>
<h2>Problem E: Tunnelling the Earth</h2>

<img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11817.jpg"  align=right>

There are different methods of transporting people from
place to place: cars, bikes, boats, trains, planes, etc.
For very long distances, people generally fly in a plane.
But this has the disadvantage that the plane must fly around
the curved surface of the earth. A distance travelled would
be shorter if the traveller followed a straight line from
one point to the other through a tunnel through the earth.
<p>
For example, travelling from Waterloo to Cairo requires a
distance of 9293521 metres following the great circle route around
the earth, but only 8491188 metres following the straight line
through the earth.
<p>
For this problem, assume that the earth is a perfect sphere with
radius of 6371009 metres.

<h3>Input Specification</h3>
The first line of input contains a single integer, the number of test
cases to follow. Each test case is one line
containing four floating point numbers:
the latitude and longitude of the origin of the trip,
followed by the latitude and longitude of the destination of
the trip. All of these measurements are in degrees.
Positive numbers indicate North latitude and East longitude,
while negative numbers indicate South latitude and West longitude.

<h3>Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
1
43.466667 -80.516667 30.058056 31.228889
</pre>

<h3>Output Specification</h3>
For each test case, output a line containing a single integer, the
difference in the distance between the two points following the great
circle route around the surface of the earth and following the straight
line through the earth, in metres. Round the difference of the
distances to the nearest integer number of metres.

<h3>Output for Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
802333
</pre>
<hr>
<i> Ond&#345;ej Lhot&aacute;k</i>
</html>
