<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Optical Reader</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Optical Reader">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Optical Reader</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>
Professor John decided to apply only multiple-choice tests to his students. In each test,
each question will have five alternatives (A, B, C, D and E), and the teacher will distribute one
answer sheet for each student. At the end of the test, the answer sheets will be scanned and
processed digitally to obtain the test score for each student. Initially, he asked a nephew, who
knows computer programming, to write a program to extract the alternatives marked by the
students in the answer sheets. The nephew wrote a good piece of software, but cannot finish it
because he needs to study for the ICPC contest.

<P>
During processing, the answer sheets are scanned in gray levels between 0 (full black) and
255 (total white). After detecting the position for the five rectangles corresponding to each
of the alternatives of a question, the software calculates the average pixel gray level for each
rectangle, returning an integer value corresponding to each alternative. If the rectangle was
filled properly the average value is zero (all black). If the rectangle was left blank the average
value is 255 (white total). Thus, ideally, if the average values for each alternative of a question
are (255, 0, 255, 255, 255), we know that the student has marked alternative <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>B</I></SPAN> for that question.
However, as answer sheets are processed individually, the average gray level for a completely
filled rectangle is not necessarily 0 (may be higher), and the value for a rectangle not filled is
not necessarily 255 (may be less). Professor John determined that rectangle average gray levels
would be divided into two classes: those with values equal or lower to 127 are considered black
and those with values higher than 127 will be considered white.

<P>
Obviously, not necessarily all questions of all sheets are marked correctly. It can happen
that a student makes a mistake and marks more than one alternative for the same question, or
does not mark any alternative. In such cases, the answer to the question should be disregarded.

<P>
Professor John now needs a volunteer to write one program that, given the average gray
level values of the five rectangles corresponding to the alternatives of a question, determines
which alternative was marked, or whether the answer to the question should be disregarded.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
The input contains several test cases. The first line of a test case contains an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN>
indicating the number of questions in the answer sheet (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le N \le 255$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11839img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11839img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">255</SPAN>). Each of the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> following
lines describes the response to a question and contains five integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>A</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>B</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>D</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>E</I></SPAN>, indicating the values of average gray levels for each alternative (<!-- MATH
 $0 \le A, B, C, D, E \le 255$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11839img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>A</I>, <I>B</I>, <I>C</I>, <I>D</I>, <I>E</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11839img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">255</SPAN>).

<P>
The last test case is followed by a line containing only a number zero.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each test case the input your program must print <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines, each line corresponding to a
question. If the answer to the question was correctly filled in the answer sheet, the line should
contain the alternative selected (`<TT>A</TT>',`<TT>B'</TT>, `<TT>C</TT>', `<TT>D</TT>' or `<TT>E</TT>'). Otherwise, the line should contain the character `<TT>*</TT>' (asterisk).

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3
0 255 255 255 255
255 255 255 255 0
255 255 127 255 255
4
200 200 200 0 200
200 1 200 200 1
1 2 3 4 5
255 5 200 130 205
0
</PRE>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
A
E
C
D
*
*
B
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Tic-tac-toe</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Tic-tac-toe">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Tic-tac-toe</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>
<SPAN  CLASS="textit">Tic-tac-toe</SPAN> is one of the oldest games of mankind. The first records of this game are from
the first century BC, during the Roman Empire. John and Mary love to play the game, but
after a while they decided to play a variant of the old traditional game, <SPAN  CLASS="textit">Tic-tac-toe 1-D</SPAN>.

<P>
Tic-tac-toe 1-D is a game played by two players on a board <!-- MATH
 $1 \times N$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1 <TT>x</TT> <I>N</I></SPAN>; initially, all the squares of
the board are empty. Players take turns drawing a cross on an empty square. The first player
to complete a sequence of three or more crosses in contiguous squares wins the game.

<P>
Mary soon realized that, depending on the game situation, being her turn, she can guarantee
she will win, regardless of John's moves. This is relatively easy for smaller boards, but for larger
boards, after several moves, this task is more difficult. So, she asked you to write a program
that, given the state the board, decides whether there exists a winning strategy.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
The input contains several test cases. The first line of a test case contains an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN>,
indicating the size of the board (<!-- MATH
 $3 \le N \le 10^4$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">3<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11840img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11840img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<SUP>4</SUP></SPAN>). The next line contains a sequence of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN>
characters indicating which squares of the board have been marked: a `<TT>.</TT>' indicates that the
corresponding square is empty, while a `<TT>X</TT>' indicates that the square already has a cross drawn.
The input never contains three contiguous `<TT>X</TT>'.

<P>
The last test case is followed by a line containing a single number zero.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each test case in the input your program must print a single line containing a single
character, `<TT>S</TT>' if Mary has a winning strategy or `<TT>N</TT>' otherwise.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
5
.....
5
..X..
6
X.X.X.
12
............
0
</PRE>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
S
N
S
N
</PRE>

<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________
11841||||||false||||||

<!--Converted with LaTeX2HTML 2008 (1.71)
original version by:  Nikos Drakos, CBLU, University of Leeds
* revised and updated by:  Marcus Hennecke, Ross Moore, Herb Swan
* with significant contributions from:
  Jens Lippmann, Marek Rouchal, Martin Wilck and others -->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Y-game</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Y-game">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Y-game</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Willy and Benny enjoy very much playing <SPAN  CLASS="textit">Y-game</SPAN>! This is a game in which white and black tokens are placed on a triangular 
<EM><SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN>-grid</EM>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I> <IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11841img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \geq$"> 0</SPAN>, where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> is called the order of the grid. A <SPAN CLASS="MATH">3</SPAN>-grid is depicted in the figure below:

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11841a.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="588" HEIGHT="327" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11841img1.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11841a.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
In general, an <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN>-grid has <!-- MATH
 $(n+2)(n+1)/2$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>n</I> + 2)(<I>n</I> + 1)/2</SPAN> points with nonnegative ``baricentric coordinates'' <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>x</I>, <I>y</I>, <I>z</I>)</SPAN>, where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I> + <I>y</I> + <I>z</I> = <I>n</I></SPAN>. 
Coordinates in a <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN>-grid are assigned in such way that along right to left paths <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN>-coodinates are constant, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I></SPAN>-coordinates 
increase by one unit, and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>z</I></SPAN>-coordinates decrease by one unit (observe that this construction maintains <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I> + <I>y</I> + <I>z</I> = <I>n</I></SPAN> true). 
Symmetric situations may be observed for left to right (where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I></SPAN>-coordinates are constant) and horizontal (where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>z</I></SPAN>-coordinates 
are constant) paths. 
A point <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>x</I>, <I>y</I>, <I>z</I>)</SPAN> in a <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN>-grid is said to lay on the <EM><SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN> side</EM> (resp., <EM><SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I></SPAN> side</EM>, <EM><SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>z</I></SPAN> side</EM>) if and only if <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I> = 0</SPAN> 
(resp., <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I> = 0</SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>z</I> = 0</SPAN>). 

<P>
Willy uses white tokens and Benny uses black ones. Y-game rules are rather complicated, but the end of the game is attained when 
there is a token placed on every node of the grid. The winner is that player that has formed a <SPAN  CLASS="textit">Y</SPAN>, that is, his/her tokens 
are so placed that they include a connected set of points with a point on each side. For example, the following figure represents 
an end situation where Benny wins: 

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11841b.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="601" HEIGHT="319" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11841img1.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11841b.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
The winner is rather easy to determine when the grid is small. But Willy and Benny are not interested in that discussion today. 
Actually, they just want a software solution that computes the winner of ended <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Y</I></SPAN>-games. Could you help them?

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
The problem input consists of several cases. A case begins with a line with two integer numbers, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>m</I></SPAN>, where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> is the order 
of the grid and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>m</I></SPAN> the number of positions that have a black-coloured token (Benny's tokens), with <!-- MATH
 $0 \leq n \leq 20$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 <IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11841img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \leq$"> <I>n</I> <IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11841img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \leq$"> 20</SPAN> 
and <!-- MATH
 $0 \leq m \leq (n+2)(n+1)/2$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 <IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11841img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \leq$"> <I>m</I> <IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11841img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \leq$"> (<I>n</I> + 2)(<I>n</I> + 1)/2</SPAN>. 

<P>
Then, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>m</I></SPAN> lines follow, each one with <SPAN CLASS="MATH">3</SPAN> values <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>z</I></SPAN> representing coordinate <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>x</I>, <I>y</I>, <I>z</I>)</SPAN> of a point in the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN>-grid 
with a black token. Values on each input line are separated by one or more spaces.

<P>
The end of the input is signaled by a line 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
<TT>0 0</TT>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
Output texts for each input case are presented in the same order that the input is read. 
For an input case in the puzzle statement, the output should be a single line with the left-justified text 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
<TT>Willy</TT> 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
or 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
<TT>Benny</TT> 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
accordingly to the fact that Willy or, respectively, Benny wins in that case. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3 5
0 1 2
1 0 2
3 0 0
1 1 1
1 2 0
2 3
0 0 2
1 0 1
0 2 0
1 1
1 0 0
0 0
</PRE>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Benny
Willy
Willy
</PRE>

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________
11842||||||false||||||

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Flatland</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Flatland">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Flatland</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Once upon a time there was <EM>Flatland</EM>, a world whose inhabitants believed
was a 2D rectangular region. Flatlanders (the people inhabiting Flatland) assumed 
that if somebody traveled long enough in one direction, he/she would fall down 
over the edge of Flatland. Animated Caribbean Movies (ACM) plans to produce a film 
about Flatland. Before the script of the film is approved, ACM wants to become 
familiar with life as it was in Flatland by 
simulating how the world could evolve from given initial 
situations and some conditions determining life and death.

<P>
Flatlanders were nomads by nature as they were always traveling:
all of them traveled at the same speed rate on straight lines
but each individual had its own direction.
As you may imagine, if one observed the life of a lonely Flatlander, 
he/she would eventually reach Flatland's edge and die.
Nevertheless, if two Flatlanders collided, then their fate was improved
as their directions changed: the resulting directions were as the former ones
reflected in a mirror bisecting the angle between 
the former directions of the crashing inhabitants.
So, a Flatlander survived because a collision with another one could change his/her direction.

<P>
However, there were bad news when more than two Flatlanders collided in a single crash: 
in that case all of them died, disappearing right there.
Note that some Flatlanders could die at the same time. If this was the case, the last name of the list of deads was remembered as 
the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">Last Dead One</SPAN> in that moment (to simplify, we assume they used our modern English alphabet and lexicographic order). 
The survivors venerated the name of the Last Dead One until a new last dead appeared (and some Flatlander disappeared).

<P>
ACM's film begins with a given population in Flatland, where names, positions, and directions of every single individual are known. 
ACM wants you to help them to determine which would be the name of the last Last Dead One in the whole Flatland's life.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
There are <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>NC</I></SPAN> test cases to solve, <!-- MATH
 $0 < NC < 100$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 &lt; <I>NC</I> &lt; 100</SPAN>. The first line of the input file has <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>NC</I></SPAN>. 
After that, for each testcase, a set of lines:

<P>

<UL>
<LI>the first line contains a number <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN>, the number of Flatlanders in the initial world (<!-- MATH
 $1\le n\le 100$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11842img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>n</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11842img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100</SPAN>);
</LI>
<LI>the second line contains two positive integer numbers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>B</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>H</I></SPAN> separated by a space, representing the dimensions of 
Flatland (<!-- MATH
 $2\le B,H \le 100$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">2<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11842img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>B</I>, <I>H</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11842img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100</SPAN>). Coordinates in Flatland are points <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I>, <I>j</I>)</SPAN>, with <!-- MATH
 $0\le i\le B$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11842img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>i</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11842img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>B</I></SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $0\le j\le H$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11842img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>j</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11842img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>H</I></SPAN>. Flatland's edges 
are points with coordinates of the form <!-- MATH
 $(0,j), (i,0), (B,j)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(0, <I>j</I>),(<I>i</I>, 0),(<I>B</I>, <I>j</I>)</SPAN> or <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I>, <I>H</I>)</SPAN>; 
</LI>
<LI><SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> lines (one per Flatlander) with four numbers and one string: <!-- MATH
 $x,y,d_1,d_2$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I>, <I>y</I>, <I>d</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>d</I><SUB>2</SUB></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>name</I></SPAN>
separated by a blank. <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>x</I>, <I>y</I>)</SPAN> represents the position of the Flatlander (<!-- MATH
 $0 \!< \!x \!< \!B$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 &lt; <I>x</I> &lt; <I>B</I></SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $0 \!< \!y \!< \!H$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 &lt; <I>y</I> &lt; <I>H</I></SPAN>, and two 
Flatlanders cannot start in the same position), <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>d</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>d</I><SUB>2</SUB>)</SPAN> represents the direction: <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>d</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>d</I><SUB>2</SUB>)</SPAN> is a point on some Flatland's 
edge, so that the Flatlander is moving towards it; <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>name</I></SPAN> is a string of one to <SPAN CLASS="MATH">10</SPAN> alphabetical uppercase characters, which 
represents the name of the Flatlander. You may assume that every Flatlander has a unique name.
</LI>
</UL>   

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
For each given case, output one line with the name of the Last Dead One.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
2
2
20 23
1 1 0 0 BOB
3 3 3 0 ALICE
3
20 23
2 2 4 0 ALICE
4 2 2 0 BOB
1 3 0 3 CHARLES
</PRE>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
<PRE>
ALICE
BOB
</PRE>

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

11843||||||false||||||

  Jens Lippmann, Marek Rouchal, Martin Wilck and others -->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Guessing Game</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Guessing Game">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Guessing Game</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Alice and Bob love games, but they have already played every single game available at their local Games 'R U (Games foR U) store. 
Tired of playing the same games over and over again, and from not receiving news from the game store, they decided to create their 
own game. After a few weeks of hard intellectual work Alice came up with 
<SPAN  CLASS="textit">Guessing Game</SPAN>, a two player game consisting in Alice picking a number and letting Bob try to guess it.

<P>
Before playing the game, Alice and Bob agree in the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">size</SPAN> of the game, given by two integer positive numbers, the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">range</SPAN> <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> 
and the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">limit of strikes</SPAN> <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>S</I></SPAN>. Alice chooses a secret integer number <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I></SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $0 \leq X < N$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 <IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11843img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \leq$"> <I>X</I> &lt; <I>N</I></SPAN>. Then Bob uses turns telling Alice integer 
numbers in order to guess her choice. Each Bob's guess is answered by Alice with a <SPAN  CLASS="textit">strike</SPAN>, if Bob's number is greater than <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I></SPAN>, 
with a <SPAN  CLASS="textit">smile</SPAN>, if Bob's number is less than <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I></SPAN>, or with a <SPAN  CLASS="textit">stop</SPAN>, if Bob's number is precisely <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I></SPAN>. In this last case the 
game ends and Bob wins. If Bob receives <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>S</I></SPAN> strikes the game ends with Alice as winner.

<P>
Bob is very competitive. He wants to develop a winning strategy and he starts trying to do it in the case <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I> = 3</SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>S</I> = 2</SPAN>. He notes 
that guessing <SPAN CLASS="MATH">1</SPAN> in the first turn suffices to win: if he receives a strike, Alice's number must be <SPAN CLASS="MATH">0</SPAN> and he can guess it in the 
next turn; if Alice's number is <SPAN CLASS="MATH">1</SPAN>, he already wins; otherwise, he receives a smile, and Alice's number must be <SPAN CLASS="MATH">2</SPAN>. Either way he 
manages to guess the right number without receiving <SPAN CLASS="MATH">2</SPAN> strikes.   

<P>
Before facing Alice in an official match, Bob asks for a little help with his training. Indeed, he wants you to make a program that 
computes the minimum number of guesses needed by him to guess any number <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I></SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $0 \leq X < N$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 <IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11843img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \leq$"> <I>X</I> &lt; <I>N</I></SPAN>, receiving at most <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>S</I> - 1</SPAN> strikes.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
Input consists of several test cases. The first line of the input file contains a number <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN> specifying the number of cases in the file. 
Then <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN> lines follow, each one containing two integer numbers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>S</I></SPAN>, separated by a blank and representing the range and the 
limit of strikes of a Guessing Game, respectively. You may assume that <!-- MATH
 $1 \leq N \leq 1000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1 <IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11843img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \leq$"> <I>N</I> <IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11843img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \leq$"> 1000</SPAN> and <!-- MATH
 $1 \leq S \leq 20$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1 <IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11843img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \leq$"> <I>S</I> <IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11843img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \leq$"> 20</SPAN>.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each test case, a single line containing an integer number indicating the minimum number of guesses needed by Bob to guess every 
possible number picked by Alice.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3
5 1
3 2
7 2
</PRE>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
5
2
4
</PRE>

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________
11844||||||false||||||

<!--Converted with LaTeX2HTML 2008 (1.71)
original version by:  Nikos Drakos, CBLU, University of Leeds
* revised and updated by:  Marcus Hennecke, Ross Moore, Herb Swan
* with significant contributions from:
  Jens Lippmann, Marek Rouchal, Martin Wilck and others -->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Melding Plague</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="The Melding Plague">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
The Melding Plague</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>
The <EM>Nostalgia for Infinity</EM> is an ancient ship that once carried
hundreds of thousands, but now its crew is only a handful of Ultras
-highly-modified humans adapted to the rigors of long interstellar
spaceflight. And they are desperate to find a cure because most of their crew
members are still infected with the <EM>Melding Plague</EM>, an alien virus that
attacks human cells and machine nanotechnology in equal measure,
perverting them into grotesque combinations. It is believed that some
special mutations of the virus can help cure the dying Ultras.

<P>
The Ultras' patologists identified <EM>protein configurations</EM> as the
essential constituents of the Melding Plague, some sort of genetic
blueprint of the alien virus. Protein configurations are collections
of proteins without any internal order and in which proteins can occur
several times. For example, the following is
the protein configuration last found in the infected blood of
Nostalgia for Infinity's captain John Brannigan:

<P>
<P><!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
{\tt POMC} \quad {\tt CAD} \quad {\tt CAD} \quad {\tt SCN5A} \quad
{\tt XIRP2} \quad {\tt SCN5A} \quad {\tt ELTD1} \,.
\end{displaymath}
 -->
</P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER" CLASS="mathdisplay">
<IMG
 WIDTH="41" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \tt POMC$">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<IMG
 WIDTH="32" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \tt CAD$">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<IMG
 WIDTH="32" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \tt CAD$">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \tt SCN5A$">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \tt XIRP2$">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \tt SCN5A$">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \tt ELTD1$">&nbsp;.
</DIV><P></P>

<P>
Protein configurations <EM>mutate</EM> according to the individual
mutation of its proteins. In 1-step mutation <EM>all</EM> proteins in the
configuration that can mutate indeed mutate, and those which cannot
mutate stay the same. 
Mutations continue over and over, changing configurations step by step. 
Fortunately, Ultras' pathologists have identified protein configurations
that are curable with appropriate therapies.
Then, the hope for an Ultra infected with the Melding Plague is to have 
the protein configuration of the virus
mutating to a curable protein configuration. Of course, 
therapies must be applied within a limit of mutation steps. 

<P>
A <EM>protein mutation</EM> is described by an ordered pair of
protein names <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>p</I>, <I>q</I>)</SPAN> stating that protein <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>p</I></SPAN> mutates to protein
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>q</I></SPAN>. If <!-- MATH
 $\mathcal{M} = \{({\tt CAD}, {\tt CELR2}), ({\tt ELTD1}, {\tt XIRP2})\}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="26" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \mathcal {M}$"> = {(<IMG
 WIDTH="32" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \tt CAD$">,<IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \tt CELR2$">),(<IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \tt ELTD1$">,<IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \tt XIRP2$">)}</SPAN>
is a collection of protein mutations, then the protein configuration of
the virus in captain Brannigan's blood, depicted above,
mutates by <!-- MATH
 $\mathcal{M}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="26" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \mathcal {M}$"></SPAN> in 1-step to the protein configuration:

<P>
<P><!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
{\tt POMC} \quad {\tt CELR2} \quad {\tt CELR2} \quad {\tt SCN5A} \quad
{\tt XIRP2} \quad {\tt SCN5A} \quad {\tt XIRP2} \,.
\end{displaymath}
 -->
</P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER" CLASS="mathdisplay">
<IMG
 WIDTH="41" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \tt POMC$">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \tt CELR2$">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \tt CELR2$">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \tt SCN5A$">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \tt XIRP2$">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \tt SCN5A$">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<IMG
 WIDTH="50" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \tt XIRP2$">&nbsp;.
</DIV><P></P>

<P>
Please remember that because the order in the protein configurations
is immaterial, the first configuration can be written in 1260
different ways, and the 1-step mutation just shown in 630 different ways.

<P>
Your task today is to help the surviving Ultras by building a program
that, given a collection of protein mutations <!-- MATH
 $\mathcal{M}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="26" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \mathcal {M}$"></SPAN>, an
initial protein configuration <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>I</I></SPAN>, a cure protein configuration <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN>, 
and a natural number <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> representing a search bound:

<P>

<UL>
<LI>if <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>I</I></SPAN> mutates to <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN> within at most <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> steps, computes the minimal number
of such mutation steps;
</LI>
<LI>otherwise, it must inform the Ultras that <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>I</I></SPAN> cannot mutate
     to <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN> within <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> steps.
</LI>
</UL>

<P>
To easy your burden, Ultras' pathologist are providing you with extra 
knowledge: they have identified that if a cure by this method exists,
one need to consider only <EM>deterministic</EM> mutations <!-- MATH
 $\mathcal{M}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="26" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \mathcal {M}$"></SPAN>,
i.e., if <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>p</I>, <I>q</I><SUB>1</SUB>)</SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>p</I>, <I>q</I><SUB>2</SUB>)</SPAN> are in <!-- MATH
 $\mathcal{M}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="26" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \mathcal {M}$"></SPAN>, then <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>q</I><SUB>1</SUB> = <I>q</I><SUB>2</SUB></SPAN>.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
The input consists of several test cases. A test case begins with a
line containing four natural numbers 
<!-- MATH
 $N_{\mathcal{M}}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="21" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\scriptstyle \mathcal {M}$"></SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><SUB>I</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><SUB>C</SUB></SPAN>, and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> separated by a blank, and
with <!-- MATH
 $0 \leq N_{\mathcal{M}},N_{I}, N_{C}, n \leq 1000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 <IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \leq$"> <I>N</I><SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="21" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\scriptstyle \mathcal {M}$"></SUB>, <I>N</I><SUB>I</SUB>, <I>N</I><SUB>C</SUB>, <I>n</I> <IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \leq$"> 1000</SPAN>. 

<P>
If <!-- MATH
 $N_{\mathcal{M}}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="21" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\scriptstyle \mathcal {M}$"></SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><SUB>I</SUB></SPAN>, and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><SUB>C</SUB></SPAN> are greater than <SPAN CLASS="MATH">0</SPAN>, 
then <!-- MATH
 $N_{\mathcal{M}} + N_{I} + N_{C}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="21" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\scriptstyle \mathcal {M}$"></SUB> + <I>N</I><SUB>I</SUB> + <I>N</I><SUB>C</SUB></SPAN> lines
follow. The first <!-- MATH
 $N_{\mathcal{M}}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="21" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\scriptstyle \mathcal {M}$"></SUB></SPAN> lines define the collection <!-- MATH
 $\mathcal{M}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="26" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \mathcal {M}$"></SPAN> of
<EM>protein mutations</EM> in which each line consists of a pair of strings <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>p</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>q</I></SPAN>
separated by a blank, representing protein mutation <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>p</I>, <I>q</I>)</SPAN>. 
Each one of the following <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><SUB>I</SUB></SPAN> lines consist of a string <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>p</I></SPAN> and
a natural number <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I></SPAN> separated by a blank, representing the number
of occurrences <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I></SPAN> of protein <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>p</I></SPAN> in the <EM>initial protein configuration</EM> <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>I</I></SPAN>.
Each one of the last <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><SUB>C</SUB></SPAN> lines consist of a string <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>q</I></SPAN> and
a natural number <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>c</I></SPAN> separated by a blank, representing the number
of occurrences <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>c</I></SPAN> of protein <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>q</I></SPAN> in the <EM>cure protein configuration</EM> <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN>.
The natural number <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> defines the <EM>search bound</EM>.

<P>
The input ends with <!-- MATH
 $N_{\mathcal{M}} = N_{I} = N_{C} = n = 0$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="21" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$\scriptstyle \mathcal {M}$"></SUB> = <I>N</I><SUB>I</SUB> = <I>N</I><SUB>C</SUB> = <I>n</I> = 0</SPAN>.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
For each test case your program must output exactly one line as follows:

<P>

<UL>
<LI>if <!-- MATH
 $\mathcal{M}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="26" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \mathcal {M}$"></SPAN> is not deterministic, then output:

<P>
<TT>Protein mutations are not deterministic</TT>

<P>
</LI>
<LI>if <!-- MATH
 $\mathcal{M}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="26" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \mathcal {M}$"></SPAN> is deterministic and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>I</I></SPAN> mutates to <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN> by <!-- MATH
 $\mathcal{M}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="26" HEIGHT="16" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11844img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \mathcal {M}$"></SPAN> in at most <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN>
     mutation steps with a minimum of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>k</I></SPAN> mutation steps, then output:

<P>
<TT>Cure found in <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>k</I></SPAN> mutation(s)</TT>

<P>
</LI>
<LI>otherwise output:

<P>
<TT>Nostalgia for Infinity is doomed</TT>
</LI>
</UL>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
2 5 4 3
CAD CELR2
ELTD1 XIRP2
POMC 1
CAD 2
SCN5A 2
XIRP2 1
ELTD1 1
POMC 1
CELR2 2
SCN5A 2
XIRP2 2
2 3 3 3
GP183 NALCN
CAC1S GP183
CAC1S 2
YCFI 1
MRP6 3
YCFI 1
MRP6 3
NALCN 2
2 3 3 1
GP183 NALCN
CAC1S GP183
CAC1S 2
YCFI 1
MRP6 3
YCFI 1
MRP6 3
NALCN 2
3 2 1 2
CAD YCFI
ELTD1 XIRP2
CAD SCN5A
CAD 1
YCFI 1
YCFI 2
0 0 0 0
</PRE>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Cure found in 1 mutation(s)
Cure found in 2 mutation(s)
Nostalgia for Infinity is doomed
Protein mutations are not deterministic
</PRE>

<P>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Preferential Romance</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Preferential Romance">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Preferential Romance</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>
<EM>Marriage Success</EM> (MS) is a marriage counseling service 
advising couples on how to improve the `get along' experience. 
MS's idea is simple: each spouse writes down his/her preferences 
for various criteria of common interest. ``Our criteria go beyond 
physical appearance and passion that guide early romance and tend 
to blind judgement. We want to understand your values as you live day by day. 
Happy couples are those whose preferences are compatible or can be made compatible.''

<P>
Suppose <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Y</I></SPAN> are qualities to be considered. If a person declares that 
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I> &gt; <I>Y</I></SPAN>, it means that this person prefers quality <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I></SPAN> to quality <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Y</I></SPAN> 
(it does not mean that his/her mate should have a quality, it is only an opinion). 
Preferences are obviously irreflexive (i.e., <!-- MATH
 $X \not > X$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I> <IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \not&gt;$"><I>X</I></SPAN>) and they are transitive
(i.e., if <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I> &gt; <I>Y</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Y</I> &gt; <I>Z</I></SPAN>, then <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I> &gt; <I>Z</I></SPAN> -which can be abbreviated as <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I> &gt; <I>Y</I> &gt; <I>Z</I></SPAN>).

<P>
A couple is <EM>fully compatible</EM> if the preferences of the spouses are <EM>consistent</EM>, that is,
if it is possible to arrange the qualities of interest of the spouses in a
<EM>compatibility list</EM> reflecting both of their preferences. In this case, if a
spouse says <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I> &gt; <I>Y</I></SPAN>, qualities <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Y</I></SPAN> must occur in the compatibility list and 
moreover <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I></SPAN> must be preferred over <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Y</I></SPAN>. If a couple is not fully compatible, 
then perhaps at least it is <EM>passably compatible</EM>: their preferences can be 
made consistent if some spouse drops at most one preference.       

<P>
For example, newly-wed Alice and Bob declare their preferences with respect to the following 
qualities (that they observe in a possible mate): <I CLASS="sans">biker</I>, <I CLASS="sans">cultured</I>, 
<I CLASS="sans">enthusiastic</I>, <I CLASS="sans">foodie</I>, <I CLASS="sans">juggler</I>, <I CLASS="sans">kayaker</I>, <I CLASS="sans">movies</I>, 
<I CLASS="sans">organized</I>, <I CLASS="sans">puzzles</I>, <I CLASS="sans">rich</I>, <I CLASS="sans">theatre</I>, and <I CLASS="sans">windsurfer</I>. 
Their preferences are (observe that they could say nothing about qualities meaning 
that such quality does not have any importance): 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Alice: <!-- MATH
 ${\sf organized} > {\sf puzzles} > {\sf rich}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="73" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \sf organized$"> &gt; <IMG
 WIDTH="56" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \sf puzzles$"> &gt; <IMG
 WIDTH="31" HEIGHT="15" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \sf rich$"></SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 ${\sf windsurfer} > {\sf theatre}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="79" HEIGHT="15" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \sf windsurfer$"> &gt; <IMG
 WIDTH="56" HEIGHT="15" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \sf theatre$"></SPAN>, 
and <!-- MATH
 ${\sf rich} > {\sf movies}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="31" HEIGHT="15" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \sf rich$"> &gt; <IMG
 WIDTH="54" HEIGHT="15" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \sf movies$"></SPAN>. 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Bob: <!-- MATH
 ${\sf kayaker} > {\sf movies} > {\sf puzzles}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="58" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \sf kayaker$"> &gt; <IMG
 WIDTH="54" HEIGHT="15" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \sf movies$"> &gt; <IMG
 WIDTH="56" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \sf puzzles$"></SPAN> and <!-- MATH
 ${\sf rich} > {\sf theatre}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="31" HEIGHT="15" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \sf rich$"> &gt; <IMG
 WIDTH="56" HEIGHT="15" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \sf theatre$"></SPAN>.

<P>

<P>
<BR>
In this case Alice and Bob are not fully compatible. To see that, a compatibility list 
should have <I CLASS="sans">rich</I> before <I CLASS="sans">movies</I> (Alice), <I CLASS="sans">movies</I> before <I CLASS="sans">puzzles</I> (Bob), 
and <I CLASS="sans">puzzles</I> before <I CLASS="sans">rich</I> (Alice), meaning that <I CLASS="sans">rich</I> must occur before <I CLASS="sans">rich</I>
which is impossible. However, the couple is passably compatible: if Alice drops her 
preference <!-- MATH
 ${\sf rich} > {\sf movies}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="31" HEIGHT="15" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \sf rich$"> &gt; <IMG
 WIDTH="54" HEIGHT="15" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \sf movies$"></SPAN>, then there is a compatibility list modeling
both of their preferences:

<P>
<P><!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
{\sf kayaker} > {\sf organized} > {\sf movies} > {\sf puzzles} > {\sf rich} > {\sf windsurfer} > {\sf theatre}.
\end{displaymath}
 -->
</P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER" CLASS="mathdisplay">
<IMG
 WIDTH="58" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \sf kayaker$"> &gt; <IMG
 WIDTH="73" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \sf organized$"> &gt; <IMG
 WIDTH="54" HEIGHT="32" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \sf movies$"> &gt; <IMG
 WIDTH="56" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \sf puzzles$"> &gt; <IMG
 WIDTH="31" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \sf rich$"> &gt; <IMG
 WIDTH="80" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \sf windsurfer$"> &gt; <IMG
 WIDTH="56" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11845img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle \sf theatre$">.
</DIV><P></P>

<P>
MS needs a software solution to determine if clients are full compatible, 
passably compatible or none of these. Can you help?

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
The problem input consists of several test cases, each one defined by a set of lines 
establishing preferences of a couple. A test case is defined as follows:

<P>

<UL>
<LI>the first line contains two strings <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>A</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>B</I></SPAN>, separated by blanks, representing the name of 
the spouses,
</LI>
<LI>the second line is a sequence of strings of the form (one or more blanks separating items, including commas and final semicolon):
<P><!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
q_{11}\  q_{12}\   ...\   q_{1r_{1}}\  ,\  q_{21}\  q_{22}\  ...\  q_{2r_{2}}\  ,\  ...\  ,\  q_{m1}\  q_{m2}\  ...\  q_{mr_{m}} ;
\end{displaymath}
 -->
</P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER" CLASS="mathdisplay">
<I>q</I><SUB>11</SUB>&nbsp;<I>q</I><SUB>12</SUB>&nbsp;...&nbsp;<I>q</I><SUB>1r<SUB>1</SUB></SUB>&nbsp;,&nbsp;<I>q</I><SUB>21</SUB>&nbsp;<I>q</I><SUB>22</SUB>&nbsp;...&nbsp;<I>q</I><SUB>2r<SUB>2</SUB></SUB>&nbsp;,&nbsp;...&nbsp;,&nbsp;<I>q</I><SUB>m1</SUB>&nbsp;<I>q</I><SUB>m2</SUB>&nbsp;...&nbsp;<I>q</I><SUB>mr<SUB>m</SUB></SUB>;
</DIV><P></P>
meaning that person <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>A</I></SPAN> has sets of preferences (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>q</I><SUB>ij</SUB></SPAN>'s are strings denoting qualities):
<P><!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
q_{11} > q_{12} >  ... >  q_{1r_{1}} , q_{21} > q_{22} ... > q_{2r_{2}} , ... , q_{m1} > q_{m2} > ... > q_{mr_{m}}
\end{displaymath}
 -->
</P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER" CLASS="mathdisplay">
<I>q</I><SUB>11</SUB> &gt; <I>q</I><SUB>12</SUB> &gt; ... &gt; <I>q</I><SUB>1r<SUB>1</SUB></SUB>, <I>q</I><SUB>21</SUB> &gt; <I>q</I><SUB>22</SUB>... &gt; <I>q</I><SUB>2r<SUB>2</SUB></SUB>,..., <I>q</I><SUB>m1</SUB> &gt; <I>q</I><SUB>m2</SUB> &gt; ... &gt; <I>q</I><SUB>mr<SUB>m</SUB></SUB>
</DIV><P></P>
</LI>
<LI>the third line is of the form above representing
the preferences of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>B</I></SPAN>.
</LI>
</UL>

<P>
Please consider that a quality name is a string with more than 0 and less than 11 characters,
that couples may declare opinions about at most <SPAN CLASS="MATH">100</SPAN> different qualities, and 
that is guaranteed that the given data is well defined with respect to the above rules. 
Also, it is guaranteed that the information corresponding to each person does not include 
preference cycles (i.e., each person is self-compatible). 

<P>
The end of the input is recognized by a line with <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>A</I> = <I>B</I> = *</SPAN>. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
For each given case, output one line with a single character <TT>F</TT>, <TT>P</TT>, or <TT>N</TT>, 
meaning that couple with spouses <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>A</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>B</I></SPAN> is full compatible, passably compatible, or not 
compatible, respectively. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
<PRE>
Alice1 Bob1
organized puzzles rich , windsurfer theatre , rich movies ;
kayaker movies puzzles , rich theatre ;
Alice2 Bob2
organized puzzles rich , windsurfer theatre ;
kayaker movies puzzles , rich theatre ;
Alice3 Bob3
young busy rich , wallet tennis , rich movies , busy toys ;
toys movies busy , rich tennis busy , rich movies ; 
* *
</PRE>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
P
F
N
</PRE>

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Finding Seats Again</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Finding Seats Again">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Finding Seats Again</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>
A set of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I><SUP>2</SUP></SPAN> computer scientists went to the movies. Fortunately, the theater they chose has a square layout: <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> rows, each one 
with <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> seats. However, these scientists are not all from the same research area and they want to seat together. Indeed, there are 
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>K</I></SPAN> independent research groups of scientists among them (no scientist belongs to two of them) with a distiguished leader for each 
group. Then the leader bought the tickets for his whole group, and he did it in such a way that all his group could seat occupying 
a rectangular set of seats (and everyone in this set of seats belongs to the same group). Every group was placed satisfying this 
bizarre condition, although the scientists did not care where the actual assigned areas were.

<P>
The usher was informed of the situation and he decided to annotate in a theater map a satisfactory seats deploying. He thought that 
if he wrote the position of each group's leader in the map indicating besides the corresponding group size, he could tell where to 
accomodate every scientist. But he discovered that it is not so easy! 

<P>
The usher asks for your help. You must tell him a way to place the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>K</I></SPAN> rectangular areas with the given sizes, and with the 
corresponding leader for each group seated where it was originally assigned.   

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
Input consists of several test cases, each one defined by a set of lines:

<UL>
<LI>the first line in the case contains two numbers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>K</I></SPAN> separated by blanks, with <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> representing the size of the 
theater (<!-- MATH
 $0 < n < 20$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 &lt; <I>n</I> &lt; 20</SPAN>) and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>K</I></SPAN> the number of groups (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>K</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11846img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">26</SPAN>); 
</LI>
<LI>the next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> lines describe the usher's map. A one-digit decimal number in the map indicates the seat of a leader and the 
size of his group. A point indicates that no leader will sit there.
</LI>
</UL>

<P>
The end of the input is indicated by the line 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
<TT>0 0</TT>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
For each test case, display an answer consisting in <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> lines each one of them with <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> characters representing a seat occupation 
for the theater. Each group is assigned to an uppercase letter and all of its members are identified with that letter. No two groups 
are assigned to the same letter.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3 3
3.4
...
.2.
7 18
...4.2.
...45..
222..3.
...2..3
.24...2
...2.3.
22..3..
0 0
</PRE>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
ABB
ABB
ACC
AAAABCC
DDDDBEF
GHIIBEF
GHJKBEF
LLJKBMM
NOJPQQQ
NOJPRRR
</PRE>

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Cut the Silver Bar</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Cut the Silver Bar">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Cut the Silver Bar</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>
A creditor wants a daily payment during <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> days from a poor miner in debt. 
Since the miner can not pay his daily obligation, he has negotiated with the
creditor an alternative way, convenient for both parties, to pay his debt: 
the miner will give an equivalent of a <SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="15" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11847img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \mu$"></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH">= 0.001<I>mm</I></SPAN>) long piece 
of a silver bar as a guarantee towards the debt. 
The silver bar owned by the poor miner is initially <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I><IMG
 WIDTH="15" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11847img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \mu$"></SPAN> units long.

<P>
By the end of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> days the miner would not have any more silver to give  
and the creditor would have received an amount of silver equivalent to
that of the silver bar initially owned by the miner.
By then, the miner expected to have enough money to pay the debt 
at the next day so that he would have back all his silver.

<P>
With this negotiation in mind, the miner has realized that it was not necessary 
to cut exactly <SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="15" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11847img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \mu$"></SPAN> silver piece from the bar everyday. For instance, at the third day he 
could give the creditor a <SPAN CLASS="MATH">3<IMG
 WIDTH="15" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11847img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \mu$"></SPAN> silver piece, taking back the equivalent of a <SPAN CLASS="MATH">2<IMG
 WIDTH="15" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11847img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \mu$"></SPAN> 
silver piece which the creditor should already have. 

<P>
Since cutting the bar was 
rather laborious and time consuming, the miner wanted to minimize the 
number of cuts he needed to perform on his silver bar in order to make the daily silver deposits
during the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> days. Could you help him?  

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
Input consists of several cases, each one defined by a line containing a positive integer number <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> 
(representing the length in micras of the silver bar and the number of days of the amortization period). 
You may assume that <!-- MATH
 $0 < n < 20000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 &lt; <I>n</I> &lt; 20000</SPAN>.

<P>
The end of the input is recognized by a line with <SPAN CLASS="MATH">0</SPAN>.  

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
For each given case, output one line with a single number: the minimum number of cuts 
in which to cut a silver bar of length <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I><IMG
 WIDTH="15" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11847img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \mu$"></SPAN> to guarantee the debt during <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> days.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
<PRE>
1
5
3 
0
</PRE>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
0
2
1
</PRE>

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>
