<!--Converted with LaTeX2HTML 2008 (1.71)
original version by:  Nikos Drakos, CBLU, University of Leeds
* revised and updated by:  Marcus Hennecke, Ross Moore, Herb Swan
* with significant contributions from:
  Jens Lippmann, Marek Rouchal, Martin Wilck and others -->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Cargo Trains</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Cargo Trains">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Cargo Trains</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>
The International Cargo and Packaging Company Inc. (ICPC Inc.) transports
cargo between two cities: Source City and Sink City. ICPC Inc. does
not have its own fleet, instead it contracts the service of two train
companies, the company A and company B. Each company has its own network 
that connects some of the cities at prices that the company decides. 
For two given cities, it is possible that the route
between them is served by both companies, only one company, or none.
ICPC Inc. has reached an agreement with both companies that allows
it to use their combined services at a discount price,
but  it has to follow these rules:

<P>

<OL>
<LI>For a given shipment, ICPC Inc. must specify the percentage of participation
of each company given by <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I></SPAN> for company A and <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(1 - <I>a</I>)</SPAN> for company
B, for a given real number <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $0 \le a \le 1$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11848img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>a</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11848img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1</SPAN>).
</LI>
<LI>When the segment between two cities is served by only one company,
ICPC Inc. will pay the price corresponding to that company.
</LI>
<LI>When the segment between two cities is served by both companies, the
shipment can be shipped using a train from any of the two companies
and will pay a fare equal to 
<!-- MATH
 $a \times C_{A}+(1-a) \times C_{B}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I> <TT>x</TT> <I>C</I><SUB>A</SUB> + (1 - <I>a</I>) <TT>x</TT> <I>C</I><SUB>B</SUB></SPAN>,
where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I><SUB>A</SUB></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I><SUB>B</SUB></SPAN> correspond to the fares of company A and
B respectively.
</LI>
<LI>A shipment could pass through several intermediate cities. The total cost
of the shipment corresponds to the sum of the costs of the individual
segments between cities calculated according to rules 2 and 3.
</LI>
</OL>

<P>
ICPC Inc. needs your help to optimize its costs. Specificaly, ICPC Inc. needs 
to evaluate the
cost of different alternatives that combine the participation of the
two train companies in different proportions. Given the networks and 
prices of companies A and B, your task is to calculate the cost of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>k</I></SPAN> different 
combination alternatives. Each alternative is specified by the participation of 
company A, which corresponds to a real number <!-- MATH
 $0 \le a \le 1$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11848img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>a</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11848img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1</SPAN>.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
The input contains multiple test cases. Each test case starts with
a line with four integer values separated by spaces, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>m</I><SUB>a</SUB></SPAN>,
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>m</I><SUB>b</SUB></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>k</I></SPAN>, that correspond to the number of cities, the number
of edges in the network of company A, the number of edges in the network
of company B, and the number of combination alternatives respectively.
The ranges for the values are: <!-- MATH
 $2\le n\le100,$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">2<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11848img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>n</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11848img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100,</SPAN> <!-- MATH
 $1\le m_{a},m_{b}\le5000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11848img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>m</I><SUB>a</SUB>, <I>m</I><SUB>b</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11848img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">5000</SPAN>,
and <!-- MATH
 $1\le k\le10000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11848img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>k</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11848img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10000</SPAN>.

<P>
The next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>m</I><SUB>a</SUB></SPAN> lines specify the network of company A. Each line
has three integer values: <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><SUB>j</SUB></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I><SUB>i, j</SUB></SPAN>, separated
by spaces, with <!-- MATH
 $0\le N_{i},N_{j}<n$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11848img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I><SUB>i</SUB>, <I>N</I><SUB>j</SUB> &lt; <I>n</I></SPAN> and <!-- MATH
 $0\le C_{i,j}\le1000000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11848img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>C</I><SUB>i, j</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11848img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1000000</SPAN>.
The network is an undirected graph and each edge is only listed once.
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I><SUB>i, j</SUB></SPAN> corresponds to the cost of sending one kilogram of cargo
from city <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> to city <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><SUB>j</SUB></SPAN> or the other way around. Source
City corresponds to 0 and Sink City to <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I> - 1</SPAN>. Then next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>m</I><SUB>b</SUB></SPAN>
lines represent the graph corresponding to the network of company
B represented in the same way as the network of company A. The last
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>k</I></SPAN> lines of the test case contain the different combinations to
be evaluated, one combination per line. A combination is represented
by a real number, <!-- MATH
 $0\le a\le1$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11848img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>a</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11848img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1</SPAN>, with maximum 4 decimal digits. 
The value <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I></SPAN> specifies company A's participation.
Company B's participation is implicitely defined and corresponds to
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1 - <I>a</I></SPAN>. You can suppose that there is at least one path between the
Source City and the Sink City using routes served by any company.

<P>
The end of the input is indicated by the line

<P>

<P>
<BR>
<TT>-1 -1 -1 -1</TT>.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
For each combination alternative in each test case, the optimal cost
of a trip from a city <SPAN CLASS="MATH">0</SPAN> to city <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I> - 1</SPAN> must be printed. If the
answer has a decimal part, it has to be truncated without approximation.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3 2 2 3
0 1 100
1 2 200
0 1 200
1 2 150
0
1
0.5
-1 -1 -1 -1
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE> 
350
300
325
</PRE> 

<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________
11849||||||false||||||
<html>
<h2>Problem A: CD</h2>

<img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11849.jpg"  align=right>

Jack and Jill have decided to sell some of their 
Compact Discs, while they still have some value.
They have decided to sell one of each of the CD
titles that they both own.  How many CDs can
Jack and Jill sell?
<p>
Neither Jack nor Jill owns more than one copy of each CD.

<h3>Input Specification</h3>
The input consists of a sequence of test cases.
The first line of each test case contains two non-negative integers N
and M, each at most one million, specifying the number of CDs
owned by Jack and by Jill, respectively. This line is followed
by N lines listing the catalog numbers of the CDs owned by Jack
in increasing order,
and M more lines listing the catalog numbers of the CDs owned by Jill in increasing order. Each catalog number is a positive integer no greater than one billion.
The input is terminated by a line containing two zeros. This last line is not a test case and should not be processed.

<h3>Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
3 3
1
2
3
1
2
4
0 0
</pre>

<h3>Output Specification</h3>
For each test case, output a line containing one integer, the number of CDs
that Jack and Jill both own.


<h3>Output for Sample Input</h3>
<pre>
2
</pre>

<hr>
<i>Gordon Cormack</i>
</html>

______________________________________________________
11850||||||false||||||
<html>
<img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11850.png"  align=right>
<h2>Problem B: Alaska</h2>


The Alaska Highway runs 1422 miles from Dawson Creek, British Columbia
to Delta Junction, Alaska.  Brenda would like to be the first person
to drive her new electric car the length of the highway.  Her car
can travel up to 200 miles once charged at a special charging station.
There is a charging station in Dawson Creek, where she begins her
journey, and also several charging stations along the way.  Can
Brenda drive her car from Dawson City to Delta Juntion and back?
<p>

<h3>Input Specification</h3>
The input contains several scenario.  Each scenario begins with
a line containing <i>n</i>, a positive number indicating the
number of charging stations.  <i>n</i> lines follow, each giving
the location of a filling station on the highway, including
the one in Dawson City.  The location
is an integer between 0 and 1422, inclusive, indicating the distance
in miles from Dawson Creek.  No two filling stations are at
the same location.  A line containing 0 follows the last scenario.

<h3>Sample Input</h3>
<pre>
2
0
900
8
1400
1200
1000
800
600
400
200
0
0
</pre>

<h3>Output Specification</h3>
For each scenario, output a line containing <tt>POSSIBLE</tt> if
Brenda can make the trip.
Otherwise, output a line containing the word <tt>IMPOSSIBLE</tt>.

<h3>Output for Sample Input</h3>
<pre>
IMPOSSIBLE
POSSIBLE
</pre>

<hr>
<i>Ond&#345;ej Lhot&aacute;k</i>
</html>

______________________________________________________
11851||||||false||||||
<html>
<h2>Problem C: Celebrity Split</h2>

<img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11851.jpg"  align=right>

Jack and Jill have decided to
separate and divide their property equally.
Each of their N mansions has a value between
1,000,000 and 40,000,000 dollars.
Jack will receive some of the mansions;
Jill will receive some of the mansions;
the remaining mansions will be sold, and
the proceeds split equally.
<p>
Neither Jack nor Jill can tolerate the other
receiving property with higher total value.
The sum of the values of the mansions Jack
receives must be equal to the sum of the values
of the mansions Jill receives.  So long as
the value that each receives is equal,
Jack and Jill would like each to
receive property of the highest possible value.
<p>
Given the values of <b>N</b> mansions,
compute the value of the mansions
that must be sold so that the rest may be divided
so as to satisfy Jack and Jill.
<h3>Example</h3>
Suppose Jack and Jill own 5 mansions valued at
6,000,000, 30,000,000, 3,000,000, 11,000,000, and 3,000,000
dollars.  To satisfy their requirements, Jack or Jill would
receive the mansion worth 6,000,000 and the other would receive
both manstions worth 3,000,000 dollars.  The mansions worth
11,000,000 and 30,000,000 dollars would be sold, for a total
of 41,000,000 dollars.  The answer is therefore
41000000.

<h3>Input Specification</h3>
The input consists of a sequence of test cases.
The first line of each test case contains a single integer <b>N</b>,
the number of mansions, which will be no more than 24.
This line is followed by <b>N</b> lines, each giving the value
of a mansion.
The final line of input contains the integer zero. This line is not
a test case and should not be processed.

<h3>Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
5
6000000
30000000
3000000
11000000
3000000
0
</pre>

<h3>Output Specification</h3>
For each test case, output a line containing a single integer,
the value of the mansions
that must be sold so that the rest may be divided
so as to satisfy Jack and Jill.

<h3>Output for Sample Input</h3>
<pre>
41000000
</pre>

<hr>
<i>Gordon Cormack</i>
</html>

______________________________________________________
11852||||||false||||||
<html>
<h2>Problem D: Knight's Trip</h2>

<img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11852.png"  align=right>

In chess, each move of a knight consists of moving by two squares
horizontally and one square vertically, or by one square horizontally
and two squares vertically. A knight making one move from location (0,0) of an
infinite chess board would end up at one of the following eight locations:
(1,2), 
(-1,2), 
(1,-2), 
(-1,-2), 
(2,1),
(-2,1),
(2,-1),
(-2,-1).
<p>
Starting from location (0,0), what is the minimum number of moves required
for a knight to get to some other arbitrary location (x,y)?

<h3>Input Specification</h3>
Each line of input contains two integers <i>x</i> and <i>y</i>, each with
absolute value at most one billion. The integers designate a location
(<i>x</i>,<i>y</i>) on the infinite chess board.
The final line contains the word <tt>END</tt>.

<h3>Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
1 2
2 4
END
</pre>

<h3>Output Specification</h3>
For each location in the input, output a line containing one integer,
the minimum number of moves required for a knight to move from
(0,0) to (<i>x</i>, <i>y</i>).

<h3>Output for Sample Input</h3>
<pre>
1
2
</pre>

<hr>
<i>Ond&#345;ej Lhot&aacute;k</i>
</html>

______________________________________________________
11853||||||false||||||
<html>
<h2>Problem E - Paintball</h2>

<img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11853.jpg"  align=right>

You are playing paintball on a 1000x1000 square field.  A number
of your opponents are on the field hiding behind trees at various positions.
Each opponent can fire a paintball a certain distance in any direction.
Can you cross the field without being hit by a paintball?
<p>
Assume that the southwest corner of the field is at (0,0) and
the northwest corner at (0,1000).  

<p>

<h3>Input Specification</h3>
The input contains several scenario.  Each scenario consists of a line
containing n &lt;= 1000, the number of opponents.  A line follows
for each opponent, containing three real numbers:  the (x,y) location
of the opponent and its firing range.  The opponent can hit you with
a paintball if you ever pass within his firing range.
<p>
You must enter the field somewhere between the southwest and northwest
corner and must leave somewhere between the southeast and northeast
corners.
<p>

<h3>Output Specification</h3>
For each scenario, 
if you can complete the trip, output four real numbers with two digits after the decimal place, the coordinates at which you may enter
and leave the field, separated by spaces.  If you can enter and leave at several places,
give the most northerly.  If there is no such pair
of positions, print the line:
<br>
<tt>IMPOSSIBLE</tt>


<h3>Sample Input</h3>
<pre>
3
500 500 499
0 0 999
1000 1000 200
</pre>
<h3>Output for Sample Input</h3>
<pre>
0.00 1000.00 1000.00 800.00
</pre>

<hr>
<i>Gordon Cormack</i>
</html>

______________________________________________________
11854||||||false||||||
<title>Problem A: Egypt</title>
<img align=right width=300 src=p11854.gif>
<h2>Problem A: Egypt</h2>

A long time ago, the Egyptians figured out that a
triangle with sides of length 3, 4, and 5 had a
right angle as its largest angle.  
You must
determine if other triangles have a similar
property.

<h2>The Input</h2>

Input represents several test cases, followed
by a line containing 0 0 0.
Each test case has three positive
integers, less than 30,000,
denoting the lengths of the sides of
a triangle.

<h2>The Output</h2>

For each test case, a line containing "right" if
the triangle is a right triangle, and a line containing
"wrong" if the triangle is not a right triangle.

<h2>Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
6 8 10
25 52 60
5 12 13
0 0 0
</pre>
<h2>Output for Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
right
wrong
right
</pre>

______________________________________________________
11855||||||false||||||
<html>
<h2>Problem B: Buzzwords</h2>

<img width=500 src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11855.png"  align=right>

The word the is the most common three-letter word. It even shows
up inside other words, such as "o<b>the</b>r" and "ma<b>the</b>matics".
Sometimes it hides, split between two words, such as "no<b>t he</b>re".
Have you ever wondered what the most common words of lengths other than
three are?
<p>
Your task is the following. You will be given a text. In this text, find the
most common word of length one. If there are multiple such words, any one
will do. Then count how many times this most common word appears in the text.
If it appears more than once, output how many times it appears. Then repeat the
process with words of length 2, 3, and so on, until you reach such a length
that there is no longer any repeated word of that length in the text.

<h3>Input Specification</h3>
The input consists of a sequence of lines. The last line of input is empty and should not be processed.
Each line of input other than the last contains at least one but no more than one thousand uppercase letters and spaces.
The spaces are irrelevant and should be ignored.

<h3>Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
OTHER MATHEMATICS NOT HERE
AA

</pre>

Note that the last line of the sample input is a blank line.

<h3>Output Specification</h3>
For each line of input, output a sequence of lines, giving the number
of repetitions of words of length 1, 2, 3, and so on. When you reach a
length such that there are no repeated words of that length, output one
blank line, do not output anything further for that input line, and move
on to the next line of input.

<h3>Output for Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
5
4
4
2
2

2

</pre>

Note that the last line of the sample output is a blank line.
<hr>
<i>Ond&#345;ej Lhot&aacute;k</i>
</html>

______________________________________________________
11856||||||false||||||
<title>Problem C: Ferry Loading V</title>
<img align=right width=500 src=p11856.jpg>
<h2>Problem C: Ferry Loading V</h2>
Before bridges were common, ferries were used to transport vehicles across
rivers.  River ferries, unlike their larger cousins, run on a guide
line and are powered by the river's current.  Two lanes of vehicles drive
onto the ferry from one end, the ferry crosses the river, and the
vehicles exit from the other end of the ferry.
<p>
The vehicles waiting to board the
ferry form a single queue, and the operator directs each vehicle in turn
to drive onto the port (left) or starboard (right) lane of the ferry
so as to balance the load.
Each vehicle in the queue has a different weight, which the
operator estimates by inspecting the queue.
<p>
Given <i>n</i> vehicles, you are to compute how to divide them between the
port and starboard lanes so that the weight of vehicles on each side is
nearly equal.
<p>
Input contains several test cases.  Each test case begins with 1 &lt; 
<i>n</i> &le; 100; the number of vehicles to be boarded.
Consider the vehicles to be numbered 1 through <i>n</i>.  <i>n</i> lines
follow; the <i>i</i>th line gives the weight in tonnes of the <i>i</i>th vehicle - a
positive real number not greater than 100.  A line containing 0 follows the last
test case.
<p>
For each test case, output a single line giving the numbers of the vehicles
that should be directed to the starboard lane.  Assume that
the other vehicles will be directed to the port lane.  The total weight of
vehicles on the port side should not differ from that on the starboard
side by more than 2%.  If there are many solutions, any one will do.
There will always be a solution; indeed, there will always be a solution
that balances within 1%, but you aren't required to find it.
<h3>Sample Input</h3>
<pre>
5
10.0
50.0
90.0
38.0
7.1
0
</pre>
<h3>Possible Output for Sample Input</h3>
<pre>
3 5
</pre>
<hr>
Gordon V. Cormack

______________________________________________________
11857||||||false||||||
<html>
<h2>Problem D: Driving Range</h2>

<img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11857.jpg"  align=right>

These days, many carmakers are developing cars that run on electricity
instead of gasoline. The batteries used in these cars are generally
very heavy and expensive, so designers must make an important tradeoffs
when determining the battery capacity, and therefore the range, of these
vehicles. Your task is to help determine the minimum range necessary
so that it is possible for the car to travel between any two cities on
the continent.
<p>
The road network on the continent consists of cities connected by
bidirectional roads of different lengths. Each city contains a charging station.
Along a route between two cities, the car may pass through any
number of cities, but the distance between each pair of consecutive
cities along the route must be no longer than the range of the car.
What is the minimum range of the car so that there is a route
satisfying this constraint between every pair of cities on the continent?
<p>

<h3>Input Specification</h3>
The input consists of a sequence of road networks.
The first line of each road network contains two positive integers
<i>n</i> and <i>m</i>, the number of cities and roads.
Each of these integers is no larger than one million.
The cities are numbered from 0 to <i>n</i>-1.
The first line is followed by <i>m</i> more lines,
each describing a road. Each such line contains three non-negative
integers. The first two integers are the numbers of the two cities
connected by the road. The third integer is the length of the road.
The last road network is followed by a line containing two zeros,
indicating the end of the input.

<h3>Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
3 3
0 1 3
1 2 4
2 1 5
2 0
0 0
</pre>

<h3>Output Specification</h3>
For each road network, output a line containing one integer,
the minimum range of the car that enables it to drive from every
city to every other city. If it is not possible to drive from
some city to some other city regardless of the range of the
car, instead output a line containing the word <tt>IMPOSSIBLE</tt>.

<h3>Output for Sample Input</h3>
<pre>
4
IMPOSSIBLE
</pre>

<hr>
<i>Ond&#345;ej Lhot&aacute;k</i>
</html>

______________________________________________________
11858||||||false||||||
<html>
<h2>Problem E: Frosh Week</h2>

<img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11858.jpg"  align=right>

During Frosh Week, students play various fun games to get to know each
other and compete against other teams. In one such game, all the frosh
on a team stand in a line, and are then asked to arrange themselves
according to some criterion, such as their height, their birth date,
or their student number. This rearrangement of the line must be
accomplished only by successively swapping pairs of consecutive students.
The team that finishes fastest wins. Thus, in order to win,
you would like to minimize
the number of swaps required.

<h3>Input Specification</h3>
Input contains several test cases. For each test case, the first line of input 
contains one positive integer n, the number of students
on the team, which will be no more than one million. The following n lines
each contain one integer, the student number of each student on the team.
No student number will appear more than once.

<h3>Sample Input</h3>

<pre>
3
3
1
2
</pre>

<h3>Output Specification</h3>
For each test case, output a line containing the minimum number of swaps
required to arrange the students in increasing order by student number.

<h3>Output for Sample Input</h3>
<pre>
2
</pre>

<hr>
<i>Ond&#345;ej Lhot&aacute;k</i>
</html>

<div align=center>

  style='font-size:28.0pt;font-family:Impact;mso-bidi-font-family:Arial'>Division
  Game<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><b

  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shapetype

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Division game is a 2-player game.
In this game, there is a matrix of positive integers with N rows and M columns.
Players make their moves in turns. In each step, the current player selects a
row. If the row contains all 1s, the player looses. Otherwise, the player can
select any number of integers (but at least 1 and each of them should be
greater than 1) from that row and then divides each of the selected integers
with any divisor other than 1.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>For
example, 6 can be divided by 2, 3 and 6, but cannot be divided by 1, 4 and 5.
The player who first makes the matrix all 1s wins. In other words, if in
his/her move, player gets the matrix with all 1s, then he/she looses. Given the
matrix, your task is to determine whether the first player wins or not. Assume that
both of the players will play perfectly to win. </p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<h5 style='text-align:justify'><span class=StyleArial16pt><span
style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial'>Input</span></span><span
class=StyleArial16pt><span style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;
font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:"Arial Unicode MS"'><o:p></o:p></span></span></h5>

<p class=Constraints style='margin-left:0in'><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The
first line has a positive integer T, T &lt;= 50, denoting the number of
test cases. This is followed by each test case per line.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoBodyText style='text-align:justify'>Each test case starts with a
line containing 2 integers N and M representing the number of rows and columns
respectively. Both N and M are between 1 and 50 inclusive. Each of the next N
line each contains M integers. All these integers are between 2 and 10000
inclusive. </p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<h4><span class=StyleArial16pt><span style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
10.0pt;font-family:Arial'>Output <o:p></o:p></span></span></h4>

<p class=MsoBodyText style='margin-left:0in;text-indent:0in;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo2;
tab-stops:list 0in'>For each test case, the output contains a line in the
format Case #x: M, where x is the case number (starting from 1) and M is YES
when the first player has a winning strategy<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>and NO otherwise. </p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;tab-stops:143.25pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<h1 align=left style='text-align:left'><b><span style='font-size:16.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;font-style:normal'>Sample
Input<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">                             
</span>Output for Sample Input<o:p></o:p></span></b></h1>

Manzurur Rahman Khan<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

  Arial'>B<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=446 valign=top style='width:4.65in;border:solid windowtext .25pt;

  Analyzer<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><b

  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><b

  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shapetype

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>You work in a leading software
development company. As you are great in coding, most of the critical tasks are
allotted for you. You like the challenge and you feel excited to solve those
problems.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Recently your company is
developing a project named <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Document
Analyzer</i>. In this project you are assigned a task; of course a critical
task. The task is that you are given a document consisting of lowercase
letters, numbers and punctuations. You have to analyze the document and
separate the words first. Words are consecutive sequences of lower case
letters. After listing the words, in the order same as they occurred in the
document, you have to number them from <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>1, 2, ... n</span></b>. After that you have
to find the range <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>p</span></b> and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>q (p &#8804; q)</span></b> such
that all kinds of words occur between <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>p</span></b> and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>q</span></b> (inclusive). If
there are multiple such solutions you have to find the one where the difference
of <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>p</span></b>
and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>q</span></b>
is smallest. If still there is a tie, then find the solution where <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>p</span></b>
is smallest.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Since you do have other works to
do, you have to solve this task within <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>5</span></b> hours.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style="mso-spacerun:
yes"> </span></p>

<h5 style='text-align:justify'><span class=StyleArial16pt><span
style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial'>Input</span></span><span
class=StyleArial16pt><span style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;
font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:"Arial Unicode MS"'><o:p></o:p></span></span></h5>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>First line of input will contain <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>T
(&#8804; 20)</span></b> denoting number of documents.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Each document will be denoted by
one or more lines, each line having no more than <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>150</span></b> characters. A
document will contain either lowercase letters or numbers or punctuations. The
last line of a document will contain the word <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>END</span></b> which is of
course not the part of the document. You can assume that a document will
contain between <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:
"Courier New"'>1</span></b> and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>10<sup>5</sup></span></b> words (inclusive).</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<h4><span class=StyleArial16pt><span style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
10.0pt;font-family:Arial'>Output <o:p></o:p></span></span></h4>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>For each document, print the
document number first. After that, print <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>p</span></b> and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>q</span></b> as described
above. For exact formatting, see the samples.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;tab-stops:143.25pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<h1 align=left style='text-align:left'><b><span style='font-size:16.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;font-style:normal'>Sample Input<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">                             </span>Output for Sample
Input<o:p></o:p></span></b></h1>

 #CCCCCC;border-collapse:collapse;border:none;mso-border-alt:solid windowtext .5pt;

 <tr>
  <td width=307 valign=top style='width:3.2in;border:solid windowtext .5pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'><pre><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
  10.0pt;font-family:Courier'>3<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Courier'>1. a case is a case, <o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Courier'>2. case is not a case~<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre><span

input file size is about 9 MB, so use faster input techniques.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shape id="Picture_x0020_1"

 style='position:absolute;left:0;text-align:left;margin-left:0;margin-top:4.85pt;
 width:223.5pt;height:191.25pt;z-index:1;visibility:visible;
 mso-position-horizontal:left'>
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./c_files/image001.png"  o:title="Planet X"/>
 <v:textbox style='mso-rotate-with-shape:t'/>
 <w:wrap type="square" anchorx="page"/>
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=298 height=255
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./c_files/image001.png"  align=left hspace=12
alt="D:\Librarys\Pictures\My Photoshop Works\Graphix\Planet X.jpg" v:shapes="Picture_x0020_1"><![endif]>Planet
<i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Krypton</i> is about to explode. The
inhabitants of this planet have to leave the planet immediately. But the
problem is that, still some decisions have to be made  where to go, how to go
etc. So, the council of <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Krypton</i> has
invited some of the people to meet in a large hall.<b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'> </span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>There are <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>n</span></b> people in planet
Krypton, for simplicity they are given ids from <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>1</span></b> to <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>n</span></b>.
The council uses a super computer - <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Oracle</i>
to call them in the meeting. <i style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Oracle</i>
has four types of messages for invitation. The message format is <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>type
x y</span></b>, where <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>x</span></b> and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>y</span></b> are two different
persons ids and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:
"Courier New"'>type</span></b> is an integer as follows</p>

<p class=NoSpacing style='text-align:justify'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:
"Courier New"'>1 x y</span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
11.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman"'> means that either </span><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>x</span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman"'> or </span><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>y</span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman"'> should be present in
the meeting.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=NoSpacing style='text-align:justify'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:
"Courier New"'>2 x y</span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
11.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman"'> means that if </span><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>x</span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman"'> is present, then no
condition on </span><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>y</span></b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman"'>,
but if </span><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:
12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>x</span></b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
is absent </span><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:
12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>y</span></b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman"'>
should be absent<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=NoSpacing style='text-align:justify'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:
"Courier New"'>3 x y</span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
11.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman"'> means that either </span><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>x</span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman"'> or </span><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
11.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>y</span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman"'> must be absent.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>4 x y</span></b> means that
either <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>x</span></b>
or <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>y</span></b>
must be present but not both.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Each member of the council has an
opinion too. The message format is <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>type x y z</span></b>, where <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>x,
y </span></b>and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:
"Courier New"'>z</span></b> are three different persons ids and <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>type</span></b>
is an integer as follows</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>1 x y z</span></b> means that at least one of
<b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>x</span></b>,
<b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>y</span></b>
or <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>z</span></b>
should be present<br>
<b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>2
x y z</span></b> means that at least one of <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>x</span></b>, <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>y</span></b>
or <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>z</span></b>
should be absent</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Now you have to find whether the
members can be invited such that every message by oracle and the council
members are satisfied.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<h5 style='text-align:justify'><span class=StyleArial16pt><span
style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial'>Input</span></span><span
class=StyleArial16pt><span style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;
font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:"Arial Unicode MS"'><o:p></o:p></span></span></h5>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Input starts with in integer <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>T
(&#8804; 200)</span></b> denoting number of cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Each case starts with a blank
line. Next line contains <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>3</span></b> integers <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>n</span></b>, <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>m</span></b>
and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>k
(3 &#8804; n &#8804; 1000, 0 &#8804; m &#8804; 2000, 0 &#8804; k &#8804; 5)</span></b>
where <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>m</span></b>
means the number of messages by oracle, <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>k</span></b> means the total members in the
council. Each of the next <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>m</span></b> lines will contain a message of <i
style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>Oracle</i> in the format given above. Each
of the next <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:
"Courier New"'>k</span></b> lines will contain a message of a council member.
You can assume that all the ids given are correct.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<h4><span class=StyleArial16pt><span style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
10.0pt;font-family:Arial'>Output <o:p></o:p></span></span></h4>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>For each case, print the case
number and whether its possible to invite the people such that all the
messages are satisfied. If its not possible, then print <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Impossible.</span></b> in a
single line. Otherwise, print <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Possible</span></b> and the number of
invited people and the Ids of invited people in ascending order. Print the line
leaving a single space between fields. Terminate this line with a <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>.</span></b>.
See the samples for details. There can be multiple answers; print any valid
one.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<h1 align=left style='text-align:left'><b><span style='font-size:16.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;font-style:normal'>Sample
Input<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">                            </span>Output
for Sample Input<o:p></o:p></span></b></h1>

<table border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 bgcolor="#cccccc" style='background:
 #CCCCCC;border-collapse:collapse;border:none;mso-border-alt:solid windowtext .5pt;
 mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
 <tr>
  <td width=301 valign=top style='width:225.9pt;border:solid windowtext .5pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'><pre><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
  10.0pt;font-family:Courier'>3<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre><span

  style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Courier'>3 2 1<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre><span

  style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Courier'>4 5 0<o:p></o:p></span></pre><pre><span

<p class=MsoNormal>Special judge problem, wrong output format may also cause
wrong answer.</p>

<body lang=EN-US style='tab-interval:.5in'>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 style='border-collapse:collapse;

 <tr>
  <td width=97 valign=top style='width:73.1pt;border:solid windowtext .25pt;

  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-left:.25in;text-align:center;
  tab-stops:143.25pt'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-size:60.0pt;font-family:Arial'>D<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=446 valign=top style='width:4.65in;border:solid windowtext .25pt;
  border-left:none;mso-border-left-alt:solid windowtext .25pt;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><span
  style='font-size:28.0pt;font-family:Impact;mso-bidi-font-family:Arial'>Airbus
  vs. Boeing<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><b
  style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:Arial'>Input:</span></b><span

  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><b

  style='font-family:Arial'> Standard Output<o:p></o:p></span></p>

  border-left:none;mso-border-left-alt:solid windowtext .25pt;background:#E0E0E0;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shapetype

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>&nbsp;</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'>Airbus
&amp; Boeing are the two giant names in the aircraft manufacturing industry of
today. Both of these reputed companies have a number of distinguished
aircrafts. Due to the competitive nature of the market, comparisons have been
made between different aircraft models and very often a certain aircraft from
Airbus has been termed similar to some Boeing aircraft model. For example,
Boeing 737 has historically been linked with Airbus A320 as the same category
aircraft. To make things more complicated, the relationships are not always one
to one. The recent Boeing 787-9 DreamLiners are very well compared with both
Airbus A340-500 as well as Airbus A350-800. There are many other such cases. </p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'><!--[if gte vml 1]><o:wrapblock><v:shape
  id="_x0000_s1046" type="#_x0000_t75" style='position:absolute;left:0;
  text-align:left;margin-left:0;margin-top:0;width:217.25pt;height:157.9pt;
  z-index:1;mso-wrap-distance-left:0;mso-wrap-distance-right:0;
  mso-position-horizontal:center' filled="t">
  <v:fill color2="black"/>
  <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./d_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
  <v:textbox inset="0,0,0,0"/>
  <w:wrap type="topAndBottom" anchorx="page"/>
 </v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=290 height=211
 src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./d_files/image001.png"  v:shapes="_x0000_s1046"><![endif]><!--[if gte vml 1]></o:wrapblock><![endif]--><br
style='mso-ignore:vglayout' clear=ALL>
<![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<br style='mso-ignore:vglayout' clear=ALL>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'>In
your first day of work at 'So Many Problems' Airport, the airport manager hands
you over a list containing a number of aircraft pairs. At first observation you
realize that the list can essentially be modeled as a graph where an edge
between two aircraft models means that these two aircrafts are manufactured by
different companies but are similar to each other. You have also noticed that,
the graph never has a cycle. On the other hand, you have found that the list
has a major flaw. In this list, the aircrafts are mentioned only using the
model numbers but the manufacturer names are omitted. So, the fact that Boeing
747-8 is similar to Airbus A380, is stated as &quot;747-8 A380&quot; in the
list.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'>What
you are trying to do is to divide all the aircrafts from the input list into
two sublists - one per each manufacturer. Moreover, each of the lists will have
to be in sorted order i.e. if there are two aircrafts in a sublist, the better
aircraft between them should be ranked higher in the sublist. Now, you are not
given any input about which aircraft is better than whichever other aircraft.
Also, you have no idea about which models are Airbus models while which are
Boeing models. Naturally, you can create the two sorted sublists in many
possible way and still you won't know which one is the right one. By this time,
you have begun to doubt that some of the given similarity reports might not be
valid at all. For example, if your final sorted sublists are [A, B] &amp; [C,
D] &amp; your input list shows that A is similar to D &amp; B is similar to C -
clearly one of these two similarities are wrong. </p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'>The
first thing you are trying to find is, given the input similarities, at most
how many of them might be valid for any configuration of the two input
sublists.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Verdana'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<h5 style='text-align:justify'><span class=StyleArial16pt><span
style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial'>Input</span></span><span
class=StyleArial16pt><span style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;
font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:"Arial Unicode MS"'><o:p></o:p></span></span></h5>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'>There
will be at most 60 test cases in the input file. Each case begins with an
integer <b>N (1&lt;=N&lt;=100)</b>, the number of different aircraft models in
the list. Each of the next <b>N </b>lines contain a unique string, the name of
an aircraft model. This string will be upto 10 characters and will contain
upper case letter and digits only. Then follows an integer <b>E (E&gt;=0)</b>,
the number of similarities in the list. Each similarity is described in a line
by a pair of aircraft model names separated by a space. Each line denotes that
the pair of aircrafts in that line are created by two separate manufacturers
and are similar to each other. There will be no invalid model names.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'>The
end of input will be denoted by a case with <b>N = 0</b>. This case should not
be processed. </p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span class=StyleArial16pt><span
style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;font-weight:
normal'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></span></p>

<h4><span class=StyleArial16pt><span style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
10.0pt;font-family:Arial'>Output <o:p></o:p></span></span></h4>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'>For
each test case, print a line in the format, <b>Case X: Y</b>, where <b>X</b>
is the case number &amp; <b>Y</b> is the maximum possible number of valid
similarities in the input list. </p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;tab-stops:143.25pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<h1 align=left style='text-align:left'><b><span style='font-size:16.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;font-style:normal'>Sample
Input<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">                            </span>Output
for Sample Input<o:p></o:p></span></b></h1>

<table border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=602 bgcolor="#cccccc"
 style='width:451.8pt;background:#CCCCCC;border-collapse:collapse;border:none;

  <td width=301 valign=top style='width:225.9pt;border:solid windowtext .5pt;

  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:

  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>A380<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>A340<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>A320<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>737<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>747<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>757<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>6<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>777 A380<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>A380 747<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>777 A340<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>A340 757<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>777 A320<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>A320 737<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>0<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>
  <td width=301 valign=top style='width:225.9pt;border:solid windowtext .5pt;
  border-left:none;mso-border-left-alt:solid windowtext .5pt;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>Case 1: 6<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><span style='font-size:11.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
  "Courier New"'>Case 2: 5<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;line-height:11.0pt;layout-grid-mode:
  char'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><span style='font-size:11.0pt;
  mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'><o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>


<div class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:45.8pt 91.6pt 137.4pt 183.2pt 229.0pt 274.8pt 320.6pt 366.4pt 412.2pt 458.0pt 503.8pt 549.6pt 595.4pt 641.2pt 687.0pt 732.8pt'>

<hr size=2 width="100%" align=center>

</div>


<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;tab-stops:45.8pt 91.6pt 137.4pt 183.2pt 229.0pt 274.8pt 320.6pt 366.4pt 412.2pt 458.0pt 503.8pt 549.6pt 595.4pt 641.2pt 687.0pt 732.8pt'><span
style='font-family:Arial'>Problemsetter: Mohammad Mahmudur Rahman, Special
Thanks: Manzurur Rahman Khan <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'><b><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'><b>Explanation
of sample input:<o:p></o:p></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'>In the
first sample, the 7 aircraft models can be divided into two sorted lists with
keeping all the 6 similarities consistent. For example, suppose one of the list
is [A380, A340] (in given order) and the other list is [747, 787, 777, 757,
767] (in given order). Now, if we draw lines from aircrafts of left list to
it's similar aircrafts from right list, there will be no crossing.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-line-height-alt:11.0pt'>But in
the second sample, no matter how we divide and sort the input list, there will
be at least one inconsistent similarity. Let's assume our sorted lists are
[747, 777, 757, 737] and [A380, A340, A320]. Then we can see that, in the left
list, 777 is a higher rank aircraft than 757 while A340 is a higher rank
aircraft than A320. But in our input list, 777 is linked with A320 while 757
with A340. Clearly, one of these two similarities must be invalid. If you check
other possible combinations for the two lists, you will find that there are one
or more invalid similarities. So, the maximum number of valid similarities is 6
- 1 = 5.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;tab-stops:45.8pt 91.6pt 137.4pt 183.2pt 229.0pt 274.8pt 320.6pt 366.4pt 412.2pt 458.0pt 503.8pt 549.6pt 595.4pt 641.2pt 687.0pt 732.8pt'><span
style='font-family:Arial'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;tab-stops:45.8pt 91.6pt 137.4pt 183.2pt 229.0pt 274.8pt 320.6pt 366.4pt 412.2pt 458.0pt 503.8pt 549.6pt 595.4pt 641.2pt 687.0pt 732.8pt'><span
style='font-family:Arial'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

</div>

</body>

</html>

<body lang=EN-US style='tab-interval:.5in'>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 style='border-collapse:collapse;
 border:none;mso-border-alt:solid windowtext .25pt;mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
 <tr>
  <td width=97 valign=top style='width:73.1pt;border:solid windowtext .25pt;
  background:#E6E6E6;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><b
  style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:60.0pt;font-family:
  Arial'>E<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=446 valign=top style='width:4.65in;border:solid windowtext .25pt;
  border-left:none;mso-border-left-alt:solid windowtext .25pt;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><span
  style='font-size:28.0pt;font-family:Impact;mso-bidi-font-family:Arial'>Prime
  Game<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><b
  style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:Arial'>Input:</span></b><span
  style='font-family:Arial'> Standard Input<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><b
  style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:Arial'>Output:</span></b><span
  style='font-family:Arial'> Standard Output<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>
  <td width=101 valign=top style='width:75.4pt;border:solid windowtext .25pt;
  border-left:none;mso-border-left-alt:solid windowtext .25pt;background:#E0E0E0;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shapetype
   id="_x0000_t75" coordsize="21600,21600" o:spt="75" o:preferrelative="t"
   path="m@4@5l@4@11@9@11@9@5xe" filled="f" stroked="f">
   <v:stroke joinstyle="miter"/>
   <v:formulas>
    <v:f eqn="if lineDrawn pixelLineWidth 0"/>
    <v:f eqn="sum @0 1 0"/>
    <v:f eqn="sum 0 0 @1"/>
    <v:f eqn="prod @2 1 2"/>
    <v:f eqn="prod @3 21600 pixelWidth"/>

  </v:shapetype><v:shape id="_x0000_i1025" type="#_x0000_t75" alt="  style='width:64.5pt;
   height:63.75pt'>
   <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./e_files/image001.png"  o:href="http://www.informatik.uni-ulm.de/acm/images/acmlogo.gif"/>
  </v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=86 height=85

  </td>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shape id="_x0000_s1047"
 type="#_x0000_t75" alt="Description: C:\Users\sohel\Downloads\DSC00835.jpg"
 style='position:absolute;left:0;text-align:left;margin-left:0;margin-top:5.75pt;
 width:149.1pt;height:130.9pt;z-index:1;visibility:visible;
 mso-position-horizontal:left'>
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./e_files/image001.png"  o:title="DSC00835"/>
 <w:wrap type="square" anchorx="page"/>
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=199 height=174
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./e_files/image001.png"  align=left hspace=12
alt="Description: C:\Users\sohel\Downloads\DSC00835.jpg" v:shapes="_x0000_s1047"><![endif]>Soha
and Tara have stopped playing the game mouse and cheese which they invented
few months ago. One of the main reasons for discontinuing this game is that it
involves a mouse  <span style='mso-bidi-font-size:8.0pt'>(Tara is scared of
anything that has four legs and can move)</span>.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>Since Tara is fond of playing games, Soha came up with, yet,
another game that only involves a pen and a paper. This new game is called
Prime Game.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Initially Soha writes a
list of <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>N</b> integers on a piece of
paper. Its a two player game where the players make moves alternately. Soha,
being player 1, goes first. The rules of this game are described below.</p>

<p class=ListParagraph style='text-align:justify;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list:
l0 level1 lfo2'><![if !supportLists]><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
11.0pt;font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><![endif]><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman"'>In each move a player has to remove one or move
contiguous numbers either from left or right from the list.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>In his/her turn a player can say pass 
which means he/she doesnt have to remove any numbers in that move. However, a
player can pass at most <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>K</b> times.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=ListParagraph style='text-align:justify;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list:
l0 level1 lfo2'><![if !supportLists]><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
11.0pt;font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><![endif]><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The sum of these removed integers has to be a
prime number. Prime numbers are positive integers that have exactly two
distinct factors. So the first few prime numbers are 2 3 5 7 11 13..<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=ListParagraph style='text-align:justify;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list:
l0 level1 lfo2'><![if !supportLists]><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
11.0pt;font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><![endif]><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The number 42 is special and can take any value
that the player chooses. For example, a player can remove the integers {4 10
42} in one move; if 42 is treated as 3, then sum equals to 17  which is a
prime number.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=ListParagraph style='text-align:justify;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list:
l0 level1 lfo2'><![if !supportLists]><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
11.0pt;font-family:Symbol'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><![endif]><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman"'>If a player uses up all his/her passes and
doesnt have any valid move, then he/she is declared as the loser.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>If both the players play perfectly, who wins?</p>

<p class=MsoHeader style='tab-stops:.5in center 3.0in right 6.0in'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<h5 style='text-align:justify'><span class=StyleArial16pt><span
style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial'>Input</span></span><span
class=StyleArial16pt><span style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;
font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:"Arial Unicode MS"'><o:p></o:p></span></span></h5>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The first line of input file is
an integer, <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>T</b>(<b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>T </b>&lt; 100) that indicates the number of test cases. Each case
starts with 2 integers <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>N</b>(0 &lt; <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>N </b>&lt; 100) and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>K</b>(0 <span style='mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:
TimesNewRomanPSMT;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri'>&#8804; </span><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>K </b>&lt; 1000). The meanings of these are
mentioned above. The next line contains N space separated integers that Soha
initially writes. Each of these integers will be in the range [-1000, 1000].</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></b></p>

<h5 style='text-align:justify'><span class=StyleArial16pt><span
style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial'>Output</span></span><span
class=StyleArial16pt><span style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;
font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:"Arial Unicode MS"'><o:p></o:p></span></span></h5>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>For each case, output the case
number first followed by the name of the player who wins. Look at the sample
for exact format.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<h1 align=left style='text-align:left'><b><span style='font-size:16.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;font-style:normal'>Sample
Input<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">                               
</span>Output for Sample Input<o:p></o:p></span></b></h1>

<table border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 bgcolor="#d9d9d9" style='background:
 #D9D9D9;border-collapse:collapse;border:none;mso-border-alt:solid windowtext .5pt;
 mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
 <tr>
  <td width=319 valign=top style='width:239.4pt;border:solid windowtext .5pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-family:"Courier New"'>3<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-family:"Courier New"'>3 0<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-family:"Courier New"'>3 3 3<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-family:"Courier New"'>3 0<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-family:"Courier New"'>4 4 4<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-family:"Courier New"'>5 2<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-family:"Courier New"'>1 2 3 4 5</span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=319 valign=top style='width:239.4pt;border:solid windowtext .5pt;
  border-left:none;mso-border-left-alt:solid windowtext .5pt;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Case 1: Soha<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Case 2: Tara<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
  style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Case 3: Soha</span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><b

  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center;tab-stops:143.25pt'><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shapetype

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Boeing and Airbus are the two
Major Commercial plane-producing companies. The planes produced by Boeing have
two engines and the planes produced by Airbus have four engines. But this does
not guarantee that Airbus planes are safer than those of Boeing. Both Boeing
and Airbus try to hype up their products as much as possible but in this
problem will not try to cover this issue.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>There are some interesting
probability problems with 2-engine and 4-engine planes. Many people say that
for a plane to remain on air successfully, at least 50% of its engines must
remain operative. In this problem we will assume it to be true. So if a plane
has 5 engines then at least 3 of them needs to be operative to ensure a
successful flight. If all the engines have equal probability p of remaining
operative throughout the flight and failure of engines is independent of one
another then we can use binomial theorem to calculate the probability of
successful flight. For example the probability that a 5-engine plane will make
a successful flight is:</p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><sub><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shape
 id="_x0000_i1026" type="#_x0000_t75" style='width:264pt;height:43.5pt' o:ole=" >
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=352 height=58
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  v:shapes="_x0000_i1026"><![endif]><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
 <o:OLEObject Type="Embed" ProgID="Equation.3" ShapeID="_x0000_i1026"
  DrawAspect="Content" ObjectID="_1348050885">
 </o:OLEObject>
</xml><![endif]--></sub>, here <sub><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shape id="_x0000_i1027"
 type="#_x0000_t75" style='width:96pt;height:43.5pt' o:ole=" >
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=128 height=58
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  v:shapes="_x0000_i1027"><![endif]></sub><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
 <o:OLEObject Type="Embed" ProgID="Equation.3" ShapeID="_x0000_i1027"
  DrawAspect="Content" ObjectID="_1348050886">
 </o:OLEObject>
</xml><![endif]--></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>So in general, <sub><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shape
 id="_x0000_i1028" type="#_x0000_t75" style='width:204.75pt;height:67.5pt'
 o:ole=" >
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=273 height=90
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  v:shapes="_x0000_i1028"><![endif]></sub><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
 <o:OLEObject Type="Embed" ProgID="Equation.3" ShapeID="_x0000_i1028"
  DrawAspect="Content" ObjectID="_1348050887">
 </o:OLEObject>
</xml><![endif]--></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Another function CF is defined
as: <sub><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shape id="_x0000_i1029" type="#_x0000_t75"
 style='width:126.75pt;height:49.5pt' o:ole=" >
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=169 height=66
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  v:shapes="_x0000_i1029"><![endif]></sub><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
 <o:OLEObject Type="Embed" ProgID="Equation.3" ShapeID="_x0000_i1029"
  DrawAspect="Content" ObjectID="_1348050888">
 </o:OLEObject>
</xml><![endif]--></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>In the planes of present time we
generally dont see more than four engines. But some scientists are planning to
make planes with thousands of very small engines. The reasons are the
following:</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<ol style='margin-top:0in' start=1 type=1>
 <li class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo3;
     tab-stops:list .5in'>Results generated by probability theory matches with
     real life performances when the number of items or tests is high. For
     example the probability of a fair coin showing head is 0.5. But in real
     life if a fair coin is thrown 10 times it is highly likely that it will
     not show head exactly 5 times. But if it were thrown 10000 times it would
     show head around 5000 times.</li>
 <li class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo3;
     tab-stops:list .5in'>It is often very expensive to make an error free engine
     but it is not that expensive to make an engine with very low p (Such as
     0.6). So if a plane has 10000 engines, in real life the chance is very low
     that 50% of them will be out of order while in flight even if p is around
     0.6.</li>
</ol>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>In this problem your job is help
the new scientists by finding out the value of CF(m), given the value of m and
p. They claim that these values will be very helpful for their research.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<h6><span class=StyleArial16pt><span style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
10.0pt;font-family:Arial'>Input</span></span><span class=StyleArial16pt><span
style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;mso-fareast-font-family:
"Arial Unicode MS"'><o:p></o:p></span></span></h6>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The input file contains around 12
sets of inputs. The description of each set is given below:</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>The first line of each set
contains a floating-point number p (0&#8804;p&#8804;1) and an integer Q (0
&lt;Q &#8804; 2000). Here p is the probability that an engine will not fail
during flight and Q is the total number of query. Each of the next Q lines contains
an integer, which denotes a possible value of m (0&lt;m&lt;50001).</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'>Input is terminated by a case
where the value of Q is zero.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify'><span style="mso-spacerun:
yes"> </span></p>

<h4><span class=StyleArial16pt><span style='font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
10.0pt;font-family:Arial'>Output <o:p></o:p></span></span></h4>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;tab-stops:143.25pt'>For each set
of input Q+1 lines of output. The first line contains the serial of the set.
Each of the next Q lines contains one floating-point number which denotes the
value of CF(m). These floating-point numbers should have 8 digits after the
decimal point. Look at the output for sample input for details. Errors less
than max(2*10<sup>-8</sup>, 2*10<sup>-6 </sup>%) will be ignored.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;tab-stops:143.25pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<h1 align=left style='text-align:left'><b><span style='font-size:16.0pt;
mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Arial;font-style:normal'>Sample
Input<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">         </span><span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">                   </span>Output for Sample Input<o:p></o:p></span></b></h1>

</div>

</body>
