<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'>Now given the
radius of the circular boxes your job is to find out the length of the sides of
the square shaped box. But it is still not as simple as you think because of
his other requirements. Being a researcher Alfred has also discovered that if
the if the radius of the circular boxes is an integer then the length of the
sides L can be expressed in a expression like: <sub><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shape
 id="_x0000_i1025" type="#_x0000_t75" style='width:125.25pt;height:40.5pt'
 o:ole=" >
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=167 height=54
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  v:shapes="_x0000_i1025"><![endif]></sub><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
 <o:OLEObject Type="Embed" ProgID="Equation.3" ShapeID="_x0000_i1025"
  DrawAspect="Content" ObjectID="_1349150509">
 </o:OLEObject>
</xml><![endif]-->, where p, q, r, s, t are all integer values and q&lt;r. But
as he is busy doing his other research so you have to help him solving this
problem. So given the radius R of the circular boxes your job is to find out
such integer value of p, q, r, s and t such that <sub><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shape
 id="_x0000_i1026" type="#_x0000_t75" style='width:146.25pt;height:40.5pt'
 o:ole=" >
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=195 height=54
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./f_files/image001.png"  v:shapes="_x0000_i1026"><![endif]></sub><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>
 <o:OLEObject Type="Embed" ProgID="Equation.3" ShapeID="_x0000_i1026"
  DrawAspect="Content" ObjectID="_1349150510">
 </o:OLEObject>
</xml><![endif]--><sub><o:p></o:p></sub></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'><span
class=StyleArial16pt><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-ascii-font-family:"Times New Roman";
mso-hansi-font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Input</span></span><span
class=StyleArial16pt><span style='mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-ascii-font-family:
"Times New Roman";mso-hansi-font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-bidi-font-family:
Tahoma;font-weight:normal'><o:p></o:p></span></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'>The input file
contains around <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:
"Courier New"'>1000</span></b> lines of input. Each line contains an integer <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>R
(0 &lt; R &lt; 1501)</span></b> that denotes the radius of all the circular
boxes. A line containing a single zero terminates input. This line should not
be processed.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'><span
class=StyleArial16pt><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-ascii-font-family:"Times New Roman";
mso-hansi-font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Output
</span></span><span class=StyleArial16pt><span style='mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt;
mso-ascii-font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-hansi-font-family:"Times New Roman";
mso-bidi-font-family:Tahoma;font-weight:normal'><o:p></o:p></span></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'>For each line of
input produce one line of output. This line contains the serial of output
followed by <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:
"Courier New"'>5</span></b> integer numbers. These five numbers denote the
value of <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>p,
q, r, s</span></b> and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>t</span></b> respectively (Here <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>q
&lt; r</span></b>). You can safely assume that values of<span style='font-family:
"Courier New"'> <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>p, q, r, s</b></span>
and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>t</span></b>
will safely fit in a 64-bit signed integer. <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>Note that the values shown in the sample output is not correct.</b> The
values are there just to show the correct output formatting.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<body lang=EN-US style='tab-interval:.5in'>

<div class=Section1>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 style='margin-left:2.55pt;
 border-collapse:collapse;mso-padding-alt:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt'>
 <tr style='height:59.05pt'>
  <td width=90 rowspan=3 style='width:67.6pt;border:solid black .25pt;
  border-right:none;padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt;height:59.05pt'>
  <p class=TableContents align=center style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:center;
  layout-grid-mode:char'><b><span style='font-size:72.0pt'>G</span></b><b><span
  style='font-size:72.0pt;mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=573 colspan=2 style='width:429.8pt;border:solid black .25pt;
  padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt;height:59.05pt'>
  <p class=TableContents align=center style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:center;
  layout-grid-mode:char'><span style='font-size:36.0pt'>Travel Company</span><span
  style='font-size:36.0pt;mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:18.55pt'>
  <td width=278 valign=top style='width:208.4pt;border-top:none;border-left:
  solid black .25pt;border-bottom:solid black .25pt;border-right:none;
  padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt;height:18.55pt'>
  <p class=TableContents align=right style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:right;
  layout-grid-mode:char'><span style='font-size:10.0pt'>Input</span><span
  style='font-size:10.0pt;mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>
  <td width=295 valign=top style='width:221.4pt;border:solid black .25pt;
  border-top:none;padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt;height:18.55pt'>
  <p class=TableContents style='margin-top:6.0pt;layout-grid-mode:char'><span
  style='font-size:10.0pt'>Standard Input</span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;
  mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:1.15pt'>
  <td width=278 valign=top style='width:208.4pt;border-top:none;border-left:
  solid black .25pt;border-bottom:solid black .25pt;border-right:none;
  padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt;height:1.15pt'>
  <p class=TableContents align=right style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:right;
  layout-grid-mode:char'><span style='font-size:10.0pt'>Output</span><span
  style='font-size:10.0pt;mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>
  <td width=295 valign=top style='width:221.4pt;border:solid black .25pt;
  border-top:none;padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt;height:1.15pt'>
  <p class=TableContents style='margin-top:6.0pt;layout-grid-mode:char'><span
  style='font-size:10.0pt'>Standard Output</span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;
  mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'><span
style='font-family:"Liberation Serif";mso-fareast-font-family:"DejaVu Sans";
mso-hansi-font-family:"Liberation Serif";mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'>A travel company
is planning to launch their bus service in a new route. So they conducted a survey
and made a list of all possible roads connecting different cities. Each of the
roads has a certain amount of income based on current fare. But at the same
time, each road has some expenses too (this includes fuel and maintenance cost,
staff payments, taxes and tribute to labor union which is recently approved by
the Government). The travel company is looking for a cyclic route. That is, the
bus will start from any city, then visit one or more other cities each exactly
once and return to the starting city. The company is also concerned with the
profit on the route. In fact the directors of the company have a strict
requirement of a profit ratio strictly greater than <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>P</b>. Otherwise they will not launch the service. A profit ratio for a
route is the ratio between the total income to the total expenses for that
route. One of your friends works in that company and he asks for a little help
from you. All you have to do is to determine if there exists such route, so
that the company has a profit ratio of <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>P</b>.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
12.0pt'>Input<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'>The first line
of input is a positive integer <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>T (T &#8804; 100),</span></b> the number of
test cases. Then <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>T</b> test cases will
follow. Each of the test cases will start with 3 integers. <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>N, R, P (2 &#8804; N &#8804;
100, 0 &#8804; R &#8804; 9900, 1 &#8804; P &#8804; 100)</span></b><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>.</span></b><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'> N,
R and P</span></b> represents number of cities, number of road links and the
expected profit ratio. Then R lines will follow. Each line will contain 4
integers <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>A<sub>i</sub>,
B<sub>i</sub>, I<sub>i</sub>, E<sub>i</sub> (0 &#8804; A<sub>i</sub>, B<sub>i</sub>
&lt; N, 0 &#8804; I<sub>i</sub> &#8804; 5000, 1 &#8804; E<sub>i</sub> &#8804;
5000)</span></b>. <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>(A<sub>i</sub>, B<sub>i</sub>)</span></b>
represents directed road link from city <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>A<sub>i</sub></b>
to <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>B<sub>i</sub></b>. <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>I<sub>i</sub></b><sub> </sub>and <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>E<sub>i</sub></b><sub> </sub>are the income
and expenses of the road link respectively. Each test case will be followed by
a blank line. You may assume that <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>(A<sub>i</sub>, B<sub>i</sub>) &#8800; (A<sub>j</sub>,
B<sub>j</sub>)</span></b>, if <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>i &#8800; j</span></b> and <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>A<sub>i</sub>
&#8800; B<sub>i</sub></span> </b>for any <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>i</span></b>. </p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:
12.0pt'>Output</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'>For each test
case, output one line in the format <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Case k: s</span></b>. Here <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>k</span></b>
is the case number starting from 1 and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>s</b>
is a string either <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>YES</span></b> if there is a cyclic route
for which the profit ratio is greater than <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>P</span></b> or <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>NO</span></b>, if there is no
such route. See the sample input output for details.</p>

<span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-font-family:
"DejaVu Sans";mso-bidi-font-family:Tahoma;mso-font-kerning:1.5pt;mso-ansi-language:
EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-ZA;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA'><br clear=all
style='mso-special-character:line-break;page-break-before:always'>
</span>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

  8 2<br>

  </td>
  <td width=333 valign=top style='width:249.45pt;border:solid black .25pt;

  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:

  1: YES<br>
  Case 2: NO<br>

<hr size=2 width="100%" align=center>

</div>


<p class=MsoNormal style='text-align:justify;tab-stops:45.8pt 91.6pt 137.4pt 183.2pt 229.0pt 274.8pt 320.6pt 366.4pt 412.2pt 458.0pt 503.8pt 549.6pt 595.4pt 641.2pt 687.0pt 732.8pt'><span
style='font-family:Arial'>Problemsetter: Md. Towhidul Islam Talukder, Special
Thanks: Jane Alam Jan <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>Note:</b> For the first case, consider the cycle 1 -&gt; 4 -&gt; 3
-&gt; 1. Total income is 25 (5 + 11 + 9) and total expense is 8 (3 + 1 + 4).
Hence the profit ratio is 25 / 8 &gt; 3. </p>

</div>

</body>

</html>

<body lang=EN-US style='tab-interval:.5in'>

<div class=Section1>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=665 style='width:498.8pt;
 margin-left:2.55pt;border-collapse:collapse;mso-padding-alt:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt'>
 <tr style='height:59.05pt'>
  <td width=90 rowspan=3 style='width:67.6pt;border:solid black .25pt;
  border-right:none;padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt;height:59.05pt'>
  <p class=TableContents align=center style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:center;
  layout-grid-mode:char'><b><span style='font-size:72.0pt'>H</span></b><b><span
  style='font-size:72.0pt;mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=575 colspan=2 style='width:431.2pt;border:solid black .25pt;
  padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt;height:59.05pt'>
  <p class=TableContents align=center style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:center;
  layout-grid-mode:char'><span style='font-size:36.0pt'>Brick Game</span><span
  style='font-size:36.0pt;mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:18.55pt'>
  <td width=279 valign=top style='width:209.1pt;border-top:none;border-left:
  solid black .25pt;border-bottom:solid black .25pt;border-right:none;
  padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt;height:18.55pt'>
  <p class=TableContents align=right style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:right;
  layout-grid-mode:char'><span style='font-size:10.0pt'>Input</span><span
  style='font-size:10.0pt;mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>
  <td width=296 valign=top style='width:222.1pt;border:solid black .25pt;
  border-top:none;padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt;height:18.55pt'>
  <p class=TableContents style='margin-top:6.0pt;layout-grid-mode:char'><span
  style='font-size:10.0pt'>Standard Input</span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;
  mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:1.15pt'>
  <td width=279 valign=top style='width:209.1pt;border-top:none;border-left:
  solid black .25pt;border-bottom:solid black .25pt;border-right:none;
  padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt;height:1.15pt'>
  <p class=TableContents align=right style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:right;
  layout-grid-mode:char'><span style='font-size:10.0pt'>Output</span><span
  style='font-size:10.0pt;mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>
  <td width=296 valign=top style='width:222.1pt;border:solid black .25pt;
  border-top:none;padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt;height:1.15pt'>
  <p class=TableContents style='margin-top:6.0pt;layout-grid-mode:char'><span
  style='font-size:10.0pt'>Standard Output</span><span style='font-size:10.0pt;
  mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'><span
style='font-family:"Liberation Serif";mso-fareast-font-family:"DejaVu Sans";
mso-hansi-font-family:"Liberation Serif";mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'>There is a
village in Bangladesh, where brick game is very popular. Brick game is a team
game. Each team consists of odd number of players. Number of players must be
greater than 1 but cannot be greater than 10. Age of each player must be within
11 and 20. No two players can have the same age. There is a captain for each
team. The communication gap between two players depends on their age
difference, i.e. the communication gap is larger if the age difference is
larger. Hence they select the captain of a team in such a way so that the
number of players in the team who are younger than that captain is equal to the
number of players who are older than that captain.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'>Ages of all members
of the team are provided. You have to determine the age of the captain.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:14.0pt'>Input<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'>Input starts
with an integer <b><span style='font-family:"Courier New";mso-bidi-font-style:
italic'>T (T &#8804; 100)</span></b><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>,</span>
the number of test cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'>Each of the next
<b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>T</span></b>
lines will start with an integer <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>N (1 &lt; N &lt; 11)</span></b>, number of
team members followed by <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>N</span></b> space separated integers
representing ages of all of the members of a team. Each of these N integers
will be between <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:
"Courier New"'>11</span></b> and <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>20</span></b> (inclusive). Note that, ages
will be given in strictly increasing order or strictly decreasing order. We
will not mention which one is increasing and which one is decreasing, you have
to be careful enough to handle both situations.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-size:14.0pt'>Output<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'>For each test
case, output one line in the format <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Case x: a</span></b> (quotes for clarity),
where <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>x</span></b>
is the case number and a is the age of the captain.</p>

<p class=MsoBodyText style='margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
6.0pt;margin-left:16.4pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=665 style='width:498.7pt;
 margin-left:2.75pt;border-collapse:collapse;mso-padding-alt:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt'>
 <tr>
  <td width=332 valign=top style='width:249.25pt;border:solid black .25pt;
  border-right:none;padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt'>
  <p class=TableContents style='margin-top:6.0pt;layout-grid-mode:char'><b><span
  style='font-size:14.0pt'>Sample Input</span></b><b><span style='font-size:
  14.0pt;mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=333 valign=top style='width:249.45pt;border:solid black .25pt;
  padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt'>
  <p class=TableContents style='margin-top:6.0pt;layout-grid-mode:char'><b><span
  style='font-size:14.0pt'>Sample Output</span></b><b><span style='font-size:
  14.0pt;mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width=332 valign=top style='width:249.25pt;border-top:none;border-left:
  solid black .25pt;border-bottom:solid black .25pt;border-right:none;
  padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt'>
  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-left:0in;layout-grid-mode:char'><span
  style='font-family:"Courier New"'>2<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-left:0in;layout-grid-mode:char'><span
  style='font-family:"Courier New"'>5 19 17 16 14 12<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-left:0in'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>5
  12 14 16 17 18</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width=333 valign=top style='width:249.45pt;border:solid black .25pt;
  border-top:none;padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt'>
  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-left:0in;layout-grid-mode:char'><span
  style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Case 1: 16<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-left:0in'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  2: 16</span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:0in;
margin-left:16.55pt;margin-bottom:.0001pt'><span style='font-family:"Liberation Serif";
mso-fareast-font-family:"DejaVu Sans";mso-hansi-font-family:"Liberation Serif";
mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt'><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shapetype
 id="_x0000_t75" coordsize="21600,21600" o:spt="75" o:preferrelative="t"
 path="m@4@5l@4@11@9@11@9@5xe" filled="f" stroked="f">
 <v:stroke joinstyle="miter"/>
 <v:formulas>
  <v:f eqn="if lineDrawn pixelLineWidth 0"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum @0 1 0"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum 0 0 @1"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @2 1 2"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @3 21600 pixelWidth"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @3 21600 pixelHeight"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum @0 0 1"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @6 1 2"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @7 21600 pixelWidth"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum @8 21600 0"/>
  <v:f eqn="prod @7 21600 pixelHeight"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum @10 21600 0"/>
 </v:formulas>
 <v:path o:extrusionok="f" gradientshapeok="t" o:connecttype="rect"/>
 <o:lock v:ext="edit" aspectratio="t"/>
</v:shapetype><v:shape id="Picture_x0020_5" o:spid="_x0000_s1028" type="#_x0000_t75"
 style='position:absolute;margin-left:0;margin-top:4.1pt;width:195.75pt;
 height:86.3pt;z-index:1;visibility:visible;mso-position-horizontal:left'>
 <v:imagedata src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./i_files/image001.png"  o:title=" />
 <v:textbox style='mso-rotate-with-shape:t'/>
 <w:wrap type="square"/>
</v:shape><![endif]--><![if !vml]><img width=261 height=116
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/./i_files/image001.png"  align=left hspace=12 v:shapes="Picture_x0020_5"><![endif]><span
style='mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Consider an integer sequence <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>N</b> where,<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>N<sub>0</sub> = 1<br>
N<sub>i</sub> = N<sub>i-1</sub> + NOD(N<sub>i-1</sub>)- for i &gt; 0<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt'><span style='mso-bidi-font-family:
"Times New Roman"'>Here, NOD(<b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>x</b>) =
number of divisors of <b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>x</b>.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt'><span style='mso-bidi-font-family:
"Times New Roman"'>So the first few terms of this sequence are <i
style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>1 2 4 7 9 12 18
<o:p></o:p></i></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'><span
style='mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Given two integers <b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'>A</b> and B, find out the number of
integers in the above sequence that lies within the range [<b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'>A, B</b>].<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri'>Input</span></b><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'><span
style='mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri'>The first line of input is an integer </span><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>T
(T &lt; 100000),</span></b><span style='mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri'> that
indicates the number of test cases. Each case contains two integers, </span><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>A</span></b><span
style='mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri'> followed by </span><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>B (1 <span style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
bold;mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>&#8804;</span> A <span style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
bold;mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>&#8804;</span> B <span style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
bold;mso-bidi-font-style:italic'>&#8804;</span> 1000000)</span></b><span
style='mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri'>.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt'><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal'><span style='font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri'>Output</span></b><b
style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><span style='mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'><span
style='mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri'>For each case, output the case number
first followed by the required result.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:justify'><span
style="mso-spacerun: yes"> </span><span style='mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

 margin-left:2.75pt;border-collapse:collapse;mso-padding-alt:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt'>
 <tr>
  <td width=332 valign=top style='width:249.25pt;border:solid black .25pt;
  border-right:none;padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt'>
  <p class=TableContents style='margin-top:6.0pt;layout-grid-mode:char'><b><span
  style='font-size:14.0pt'>Sample Input</span></b><b><span style='font-size:
  14.0pt;mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=333 valign=top style='width:249.45pt;border:solid black .25pt;
  padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt'>
  <p class=TableContents style='margin-top:6.0pt;layout-grid-mode:char'><b><span
  style='font-size:14.0pt'>Sample Output</span></b><b><span style='font-size:
  14.0pt;mso-font-kerning:1.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width=332 valign=top style='width:249.25pt;border-top:none;border-left:
  solid black .25pt;border-bottom:solid black .25pt;border-right:none;
  padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>3<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>1 18<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>1 100<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-left:0in'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>3000
  4000</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width=333 valign=top style='width:249.45pt;border:solid black .25pt;
  border-top:none;padding:2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt 2.75pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Case 1: 7<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Case 2: 20<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-left:0in'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  3: 87</span></p>

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
The Coco-Cola Store</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>
 
Once upon a time, there is a special coco-cola store. If you return three empty bottles to the shop, you'll get a full bottle 
of coco-cola to drink. If you have n empty bottles right in your hand, how many full bottles of coco-cola can you drink? 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
There will be at most 10 test cases, each containing a single line with an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le n \le 100$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11877img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>n</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11877img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100</SPAN>). The input terminates with <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I> = 0</SPAN>, 
which should not be processed.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
For each test case, print the number of full bottles of coco-cola that you can drink.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>                              

<P>
<PRE>
3
10
81
0
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
1
5
40
</PRE> 

<P>

<P><P>
<BR>

<B>Spoiler</B>

<P>
Let me tell you how to drink 5 full bottles with 10 empty bottles: get 3 full bottles with 9 empty bottles, drink them to get 3 
empty bottles, and again get a full bottle from them. Now you have 2 empty bottles. <SPAN  CLASS="textit">Borrow another empty bottle from the shop</SPAN>, 
then get another full bottle. Drink it, and finally return this empty bottle to the shop!

<P>

<P><P>
<BR>

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Problemsetter:</SPAN> Rujia Liu, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Special Thanks:</SPAN> Yiming Li &amp; Sohel Hafiz

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Homework Checker</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Homework Checker">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Homework Checker</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>
 
Your younger brother has just finished his homework for the part "<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">additions and subtractions for integers not greater than one hundred</SPAN>" 
and asks you to check the answers. Each question (together with the answer computed by your younger brother) is formatted either as 
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I> + <I>b</I> = <I>c</I></SPAN> or <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I> - <I>b</I> = <I>c</I></SPAN>, where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>b</I></SPAN> are numbers prepared by the teacher (they are guaranteed to be non-negative integers not greater than 100), 
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>c</I></SPAN> is the answer computed by your younger brother and is either a non-negative integer not greater than 200, or a single character `<TT>?</TT>' 
(that means, he is unable to compute the answer). 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
There will be at most 100 lines in the input. Each line contains a question with your younger brother's answer, formatted as stated above. 
There will be no space characters in each line (excluding the newline character). Numbers will never have leading zeros.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
Print a single integer in a line, the number of correct answers.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>                      

<P>
<PRE>
1+2=3
3-1=5
6+7=?
99-0=99
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
2
</PRE> 

<P>

<P><P>
<BR>

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Problemsetter:</SPAN> Rujia Liu, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Special Thanks:</SPAN> Yiming Li

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Multiple of 17</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Multiple of 17">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Multiple of 17</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
<SPAN  CLASS="textit"><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Theorem:</SPAN> If you drop the last digit <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>d</I></SPAN> of an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11879img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \ge$">10</SPAN>), subtract <SPAN CLASS="MATH">5<I>d</I></SPAN> from the remaining integer, then the 
difference is a multiple of 17 if and only if <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> is a multiple of 17.</SPAN>

<P>
For example, 34 is a multiple of 17, because 3-20=-17 is a multiple of 17; 201 is not a multiple of 17, because 20-5=15 is not a 
multiple of 17. 

<P>
Given a positive integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN>, your task is to determine whether it is a multiple of 17.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
There will be at most 10 test cases, each containing a single line with an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le n \le 10100$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11879img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>n</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11879img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<sup>100</sup></SPAN>). The input terminates with <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I> = 0</SPAN>, 
which should not be processed.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
For each case, print 1 if the corresponding integer is a multiple of 17, print 0 otherwise.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>                                             
<PRE>
34
201
2098765413
1717171717171717171717171717171717171717171717171718
0
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
<PRE>
1
0
1
0
</PRE> 

<P>

<P><P>
<BR>

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Problemsetter:</SPAN> Rujia Liu, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Special Thanks:</SPAN> Yiming Li

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Ball in a Rectangle</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Ball in a Rectangle">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Ball in a Rectangle</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>
Input: Standard Input
Output: Standard Output

<P>
 
There is a rectangle on the cartesian plane, with bottom-left corner at (0,0) and top-right corner at <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>L</I>, <I>W</I>)</SPAN>. There is a ball 
centered at <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>x</I>, <I>y</I>)</SPAN>, with radius=<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I></SPAN>, shown below

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11880.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="417" HEIGHT="365" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11880.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11880.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
At time 0, the ball starts to move along a ray with polar angle <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I></SPAN> (the angle from positive <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN>-axis to the ray, rotating counter-clockwise). 
When hitting the rectangle boundary, the reflex angle always equals to the incidence angle. The ball's velocity is always <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I></SPAN> (i.e. it 
never changes when hitting the rectangle). Where is the center of the ball at time <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>s</I></SPAN>?

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
There will be at most 25 test cases, each contains a line with 8 integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>L</I></SPAN>,<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>W</I></SPAN>,<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN>,<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I></SPAN>,<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I></SPAN>,<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I></SPAN>,<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I></SPAN>,<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>s</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH">100<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11880.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>L</I></SPAN>,<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>W</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11880.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<sup>9</sup></SPAN>, 
<!-- MATH
 $1 \le R \le 5$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11880.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>R</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11880.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">5</SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $R \le x \le L-R$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11880.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>x</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11880.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>L</I> - <I>R</I></SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $R \le y \le W-R$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11880.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>y</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11880.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>W</I> - <I>R</I></SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $0 \le a < 360$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11880.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>a</I> &lt; 360</SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11880.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>v</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>s</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11880.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<sup>9</sup></SPAN>), as stated above. The input 
terminates with <!-- MATH
 $L=W=x=y=R=a=v=s=0$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>L</I> = <I>W</I> = <I>x</I> = <I>y</I> = <I>R</I> = <I>a</I> = <I>v</I> = <I>s</I> = 0</SPAN>, which should not be processed.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
For each test case, output a line containing two floating-point numbers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I></SPAN>, rounded to two decimal points, indicating 
that the center of ball will be at <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>x</I>, <I>y</I>)</SPAN> at time <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>s</I></SPAN>.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
100 100 80 10 5 90 2 23
110 100 70 10 5 180 1 9999
0 0 0 0 0 0 0 0
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
80.00 56.00
71.00 10.00
</PRE> 

<P>

<P><P>
<BR>

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Problemsetter:</SPAN> Rujia Liu, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Special Thanks:</SPAN> Yiming Li, Shamim Hafiz &amp; Sohel Hafiz 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Internal Rate of Return</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Internal Rate of Return">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Internal Rate of Return</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
In finance, Internal Rate of Return (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>IRR</I></SPAN>) is the discount rate of an investment when NPV equals zero. Formally, given <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>CF</I><SUB>0</SUB></SPAN>, 
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>CF</I><SUB>1</SUB></SPAN>, ..., <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>CF</I><SUB>T</SUB></SPAN>, then <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>IRR</I></SPAN> is the solution to the following equation:

<P>
<P><!-- MATH
 \begin{displaymath}
NPV= CF_0 + {CF_1 \over {1+IRR}} + {CF_2 \over {(1+IRR)^2}} + K + {CF_T \over {(1+IRR)^T}} = 0
\end{displaymath}
 -->
</P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER" CLASS="mathdisplay">
<I>NPV</I> = <I>CF</I><SUB>0</SUB> + <IMG
 WIDTH="74" HEIGHT="56" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11881img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle {CF_1 \over {1+IRR}}$"> + <IMG
 WIDTH="95" HEIGHT="56" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11881img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle {CF_2 \over {(1+IRR)^2}}$"> + <I>K</I> + <IMG
 WIDTH="98" HEIGHT="56" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11881img1.png" 
 ALT="$\displaystyle {CF_T \over {(1+IRR)^T}}$"> = 0
</DIV><P></P>

<P>
Your task is to find all valid <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>IRR</I></SPAN>s. In this problem, the initial cash-flow <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>CF</I><SUB>0</SUB> &lt; 0</SPAN>, while other cash-flows are all 
positive (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>CF</I><SUB>i</SUB> &gt; 0</SPAN> for all <!-- MATH
 $i=1, 2, \dots$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I> = 1, 2,...</SPAN>). 

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Important: <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>IRR</I></SPAN> can be negative, but it must be satisfied that <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>IRR</I> &gt; - 1</SPAN>.</SPAN>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
There will be at most 25 test cases. Each test case contains two lines. The first line contains a single integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le T \le 10$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11881img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11881img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10</SPAN>), 
the number of positive cash-flows. The second line contains <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I> + 1</SPAN> integers: <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>CF</I><SUB>0</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>CF</I><SUB>1</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>CF</I><SUB>2</SUB></SPAN>, ..., <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>CF</I><SUB>T</SUB></SPAN>, 
where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>CF</I><SUB>0</SUB> &lt; 0</SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $0<CF_i<10000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 &lt; <I>CF</I><SUB>i</SUB> &lt; 10000</SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $i=1,2,\dots,T$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I> = 1, 2,..., <I>T</I></SPAN>). The input terminates by <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I> = 0</SPAN>.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each test case, print a single line, containing the value of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>IRR</I></SPAN>, rounded to two decimal points. If no <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>IRR</I></SPAN> exists, 
print ``<TT>No</TT>" (without quotes); if there are multiple <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>IRR</I></SPAN>s, print ``<TT>Too many</TT>"(without quotes).

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
1
-1 2
2
-8 6 9
0
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
1.00
0.50
</PRE> 

<P>

<P><P>
<BR>

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Problemsetter:</SPAN> Rujia Liu, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Special Thanks:</SPAN> Yiming Li, Shamim Hafiz &amp; Sohel Hafiz 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Biggest Number</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Biggest Number">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Biggest Number</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
You have a maze with obstacles and non-zero digits in it:

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11882.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="879" HEIGHT="380" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11882.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11882.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
You can start from any square, walk in the maze, and finally stop at some square. Each step, you may only walk into one of 
the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">four neighbouring squares (up, down, left, right)</SPAN> and you cannot walk into obstacles or walk into a square more than 
once. When you finish, you can get a number by writing down the digits you encounter in the same order as you meet them. 
For example, you can get numbers 9784, 4832145, etc. The biggest number you can get is 791452384, shown in the picture above.

<P>
Your task is to find the biggest number you can get.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
There will be at most 25 test cases. Each test begins with two integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH">2<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11882.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>R</I></SPAN>,<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11882.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">15</SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $R*C \le 30$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I>*<I>C</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11882.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">30</SPAN>), the 
number of rows and columns of the maze. The next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I></SPAN> rows represent the maze. Each line contains exactly <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN> characters 
(without leading or trailing spaces), each of them will be either `<TT>#</TT>' or one of the nine non-zero digits. 
There will be at least one non-obstacle squares (i.e. squares with a non-zero 
digit in it) in the maze. The input is terminated by a test case with <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I> = <I>C</I> = 0</SPAN>, you should not process it.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
For each test case, print the biggest number you can find, on a single line.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>                          

<P>
<PRE>
3 7
##9784#
##123##
##45###
0 0
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">.</A>&nbsp;</FONT>

</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
791452384
</PRE>

<P>

<P><P>
<BR>

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Problemsetter:</SPAN> Rujia Liu, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Special Thanks:</SPAN> Yiming Li 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Repairing a Road</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Repairing a Road">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Repairing a Road</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
You live in a small town with <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I></SPAN> bidirectional roads connecting <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN> crossings and you want to go from crossing 1 to crossing <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN> as 
soon as possible. You can visit other crossings before arriving at crossing <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN>, but it's not mandatory. 

<P>
You have exactly one chance to ask your friend to repair exactly one existing road, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">from the time you leave crossing 1</SPAN>. 
If he repairs the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I></SPAN>-th road for t units of time, the crossing time after that would be <!-- MATH
 $v_ia_i^{-t}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I><SUB>i</SUB><I>a</I><SUB>i</SUB><SUP>-t</SUP></SPAN>. It's not difficult to see 
that it takes vi units of time to cross that road if your friend doesn't repair it. You cannot start to cross the road when 
your friend is repairing it.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
There will be at most 25 test cases. Each test case begins with two integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $2 \le C \le 100$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">2<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11883img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>C</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11883img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100</SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $1 \le R \le 500$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11883img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>R</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11883img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">500</SPAN>). 
Each of the next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I></SPAN> lines contains two integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le x_i, y_i \le C$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11883img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>x</I><SUB>i</SUB>, <I>y</I><SUB>i</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11883img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>C</I></SPAN>) and two positive floating-point numbers
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le v_i \le 20$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11883img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>v</I><SUB>i</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11883img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">45</SPAN>,<!-- MATH
 $1 \le a_i \le 5$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11883img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>a</I><SUB>i</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11883img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">5</SPAN>), indicating that there is a bidirectional road connecting crossing 
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN>, with parameters <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> (see above). Each pair of crossings can be connected by at most one road. 
The input is terminated by a test case with <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I> = <I>R</I> = 0</SPAN>, you should not process it.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each test case, print the smallest time it takes to reach crossing <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN> from crossing 1, rounded to 3 digits after decimal point. 
It's always possible to reach crossing <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN> from crossing 1.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3 2
1 2 1.5 1.8
2 3 2.0 1.5
2 1
1 2 2.0 1.8
0 0
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
2.589
1.976
</PRE> 

<P>

<P><P>
<BR>

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Problemsetter:</SPAN> Rujia Liu, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Special Thanks:</SPAN> Yiming Li, Tasnim Sunny &amp; Sohel Hafiz 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>A Shooting Game</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="A Shooting Game">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
A Shooting Game</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
A and B are playing a shooting game on a battlefield consisting of square-shaped unit blocks. The blocks are occupying some consecutive 
columns, and the perimeter of the figure equals the perimeter of its minimal bounding box. The figure (a) below is a valid battlefield, 
but (b) and (c) are not, because in (b), there is an empty column; in (c), the perimeter of figure is 14, but the perimeter of the 
bounding box (drawn with dashed lines) is 12. With the help of gravity, each block is either located on another block, 
or sitting on the ground. To make the battlefield look more exciting, it must not be a perfect rectangle (i.e. it is not allowed that 
every column has the same height)

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11884a.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="1029" HEIGHT="292" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11884a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11884a.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
Here is the rule of the game:

<OL>
<LI>A and B shoot by turn. A starts first.
</LI>
<LI>Before shooting, the player first select one row with at least one block, and one of the two directions "left" and "right", 
then shoot at this row along that direction. The power of the shoot is one of 1, 2 or 3, each with probability of 1/3. The power 
of shoot is the number of blocks (not necessarily consecutive) that can be destroyed in this shoot. If the total number of blocks 
on this row is less than the power of shoot, then all the blocks on this row is destroyed. For example, if the player chooses to 
shoot the 3rd row from the bottom, with direction "right", power 2, and there are 4 blocks on this row, then the left-most two 
blocks are destroyed.
</LI>
<LI>After each shoot, blocks in the air fall down vertically. The next player cannot shoot before all the blocks stop falling.
</LI>
<LI>Realize that the intermediate battlefields do not have to follow the constraints for starting battlefields. For example, 
it could happens some situations looking as figures (b) or (c), and then, if the power is <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>p</I></SPAN>, the leftmost/rightmost <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>p</I></SPAN> blocks
of columns which contain a block in this row are destroyed (skipping empty positions).
</LI>
<LI>He who destroys the last block wins. 
</LI>
</OL>

<P>
Assume the starting battlefield is 

<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11884b.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="224" HEIGHT="168" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11884a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11884b.eps}">
. According to rule 1, A shoots first. The table below shows three (not all) possible outcomes 
of the first shot:

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<TABLE COLS=5 BORDER FRAME=HSIDES RULES=GROUPS>
<COL ALIGN=CENTER><COL ALIGN=CENTER><COL ALIGN=CENTER><COL ALIGN=CENTER><COL ALIGN=CENTER>
<TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Row(from bottom)</SPAN> </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Direction</SPAN> </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Power</SPAN> </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Befrore Falling</SPAN> </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Stable</SPAN> </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>2 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> Left </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 1 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 

<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11884c.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="223" HEIGHT="168" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11884a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11884c.eps}"></TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> (Same as left) </TD></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 
1 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> Left </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 2 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 

<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11884d.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="168" HEIGHT="168" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11884a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11884d.eps}"></TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 

<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11884e.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="170" HEIGHT="166" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11884a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11884e.eps}"></TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>1 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> Right </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 3 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 

<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11884f.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="168" HEIGHT="169" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11884a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11884f.eps}"></TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 

<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11884g.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="169" HEIGHT="115" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11884a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11884g.eps}"></TD></TR>
</TBODY>
</TABLE>

</DIV>

<P>
Assume Alice and Bob are both very clever (always follows the strategy that maximizes the probability he/she wins), what is the 
probability that Alice wins?

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
There will be at most 25 test cases, each with two lines. The first line is a single integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le n \le 6$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11884a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>n</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11884a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">6</SPAN>), the number of 
columns. The second line contains <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>h</I><SUB>1</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>h</I><SUB>2</SUB></SPAN>, ..., <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>h</I><SUB>n</SUB></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le h_i \le 6$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11884a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>h</I><SUB>i</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11884a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">6</SPAN>), the heights of the columns from 
left to right. The battlefield is guaranteed to satisfy the restrictions in the problem (perimeter of figure equals that of 
the minimal bounding box, and is not a perfect rectangle). Input is terminated by <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I> = 0</SPAN>.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
For each test case, print a single line, the probability that A wins, to six decimal points. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3
2 1 1
0
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
0.555556
</PRE> 

<P>

<P><P>
<BR>

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Problemsetter:</SPAN> Rujia Liu, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Special Thanks:</SPAN> Yiming Li, Tanaeem M Moosa &amp; Sohel Hafiz 

<P>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Number of Battlefields</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Number of Battlefields">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Number of Battlefields</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
In the previous problem, we assume the perimeter of the figure equals to <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>p</I></SPAN>, how many battlefields are possible? For example, 
there are no battlefields possible for <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>p</I> &lt; 8</SPAN>, but two for <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>p</I> = 8</SPAN>:

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11885a.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="189" HEIGHT="64" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11885a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11885a.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
Here are the nine battlefields for p=10:

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11885b.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="975" HEIGHT="93" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11885a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11885b.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
You're asked to output the number of battlefields modulo 987654321.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
There will be at most 25 test cases, each with a single integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>p</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le p \le 109$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11885a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>p</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11885a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<SUP>9</SUP></SPAN>), the perimeter of the battlefield. 
The input is terminated by <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>p</I> = 0</SPAN>.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each test case, print a signle line, the number of battlefields, modulo 987654321. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>                                

<P>
<PRE>
8
9
10
0
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
0
2
0
9
</PRE> 

<P>

<P><P>
<BR>

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Problemsetter:</SPAN> Rujia Liu, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Special Thanks:</SPAN> Yiming Li, Tanaeem M Moosa &amp; Sohel Hafiz

<P>


<P>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Infinite Dictionaries</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Infinite Dictionaries">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Infinite Dictionaries</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
A dictionary is a set of key-value pairs, for example: {<TT>'color':'red'</TT>, <TT>'price':2</TT>, <TT>7:'test'</TT>, <TT>100:-100</TT> }. 
As you can see, keys and values can be strings or integers. What's more, values can also be dictionaries or variable references. 
Here is the formal definition of terms that will be used soon:

<P>
<PRE>
key   ::=      INTEGER | STRING
value ::=      INTEGER | STRING | dict
pair  ::=      key ':' value
dict  ::=      '{' [pair (',' pair)*] '}'
var   ::=      'a'|'b'|'c'|...|'z'
slot  ::=      var('[' key ']')*
lvar  ::=      slot
rvar  ::=      slot | value
</PRE> 

<P>
Here <TT>('[' key ']')*</TT> means zero or more subscripts, <TT>[pair (',' pair)*]</TT> means zero or more key-value pairs.

<P>
Strings are always enclosed by single quotes (<TT>''</TT>) and consists of up to 10 lower-case letters. Integers always 
have absolute values of no more than 1000. You can insert spaces anywhere, except inside strings or integers. 
For example, { <TT> 'a':-1</TT>} and {<TT>'a' : -1   </TT>} are the same, but {<TT>'a b':1</TT>} and {<TT>'a':- 1</TT>} 
are both illegal.

<P>
Your task is to execute a series of commands and print the results. There are 3 kinds of commands:

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textit"><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">1. Assignment:</SPAN></SPAN> <TT>&lt;lvar&gt; = &lt;rval&gt;</TT>

<P>
After assigning a slot to a slot (rather than a value), the left-hand slot will be holding a reference to the right-hand. For example, 
After executing the following commands, <TT>b[1][0]</TT> is 1, rather than 0:

<P>
<PRE>
a = {0:0}
b = {}
b[1] = a
a[0] = 1
</PRE> 

<P>
Slots must be assigned before it is read or subscripted, and integers and strings cannot be subscripted. Consider the following comammd list:

<P>
<PRE>
c = {}
c[0] = 3
c[1] = c[0]
d[0] = 'i'
c = d
d = c[1]['a']
c[2][2] = 2
</PRE> 

<P>
The first three commands are legal, but the next two are both illegal because slot d must be assigned before it is read or subscripted. 
The last three are also illegal.

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textit"><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">2. Length:</SPAN></SPAN> <TT>length(&lt;slot&gt;)</TT>

<P>
Output the number of key-value pairs in the slot. Note that nested pairs are not counted. For example:

<P>
<PRE>
a = {0: {0:0, 1:1}}
length(a)
</PRE> 

<P>
will output 1, not 3. In this command, it is guaranteed that <TT>&lt;slot</TT>&gt; is storing a dictionary, not a string or an integer.

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textit"><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">3. Infinity test:</SPAN></SPAN> <TT>test(&lt;slot&gt;)</TT>

<P>
If the slot can be subscripted indefinitely, output 1. Otherwise, output 0. For example, after executing the following command list:

<P>
<PRE>
d = {}
d[0] = d
</PRE> 

<P>
Then <TT>d</TT> is infinite, since <TT>d[0][0][0][0][0][0]...</TT> is always <TT>d</TT>. In this command, it is guaranteed 
that <TT>&lt;slot&gt;</TT> is storing a dictionary, not a string or an integer.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
The input contains at most 10000 lines of commands, each line will be non-empty and will contain no more than 300 characters. 
All the commands are legal.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
Print the output (one line for each length/test command).

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>     

<P>
<PRE>
c = {}
d = {'color': 'red', 'price': 2, 7: 'test', 100: -100}
length(d)
d[7] = {'this': 'is', 'a': 'book'}
length(d)
d[8] = {'this' : 'is', 'another' : {'a' : 'book', 'b': 'book2'} }
length(d)
c[7] = c
test(c)
test(d)
length(c)
d[0] = c
length(d)
test(d[0])
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
4
4
5
1
0
1
6
1
</PRE> 

<P>

<P><P>
<BR>

<B>Notes:</B>

<P>
The term definitions in this problem use a modified BNF grammar notation that is described in the official documentation of the 
Python programming language. Here is the explanation of the notation, extracted from the documentation:

<P>

<P>
<BR>
<SPAN  CLASS="textit">Each rule begins with a name (which is the name defined by the rule) and ::=. A vertical bar (|) is used to separate alternatives; it 
is the least binding operator in this notation. A star (*) means zero or more repetitions of the preceding item; likewise, a plus (+) 
means one or more repetitions, and a phrase enclosed in square brackets ([ ]) means zero or one occurrences (in other words, 
the enclosed phrase is optional). The * and + operators bind as tightly as possible; parentheses are used for grouping. 
Literal strings are enclosed in quotes. White space is only meaningful to separate tokens. Rules are normally contained on a single line; 
rules with many alternatives may be formatted alternatively with each line after the first beginning with a vertical bar.
</SPAN>

<P>

<P><P>
<BR>

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Problemsetter:</SPAN> Rujia Liu, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Special Thanks:</SPAN> Yiming Li

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Tetrahedrons and Spheres</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Tetrahedrons and Spheres">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Tetrahedrons and Spheres</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
There are a tetrahedrons and b spheres in the 3D-splace, you're asked to calculate the volume occupied by at least one of 
them (i.e. volume of the union of the objects).

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
There will be at most 20 test cases. Each case begins with two integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>b</I></SPAN>, the number of tetrahedrons and the number 
of spheres (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le a,b \le 5$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11887img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>a</I>, <I>b</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11887img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">5</SPAN>). The next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I></SPAN> lines each contains 12 integers: <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I><SUB>1</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I><SUB>1</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>z</I><SUB>1</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I><SUB>2</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I><SUB>2</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>z</I><SUB>2</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I><SUB>3</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I><SUB>3</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>z</I><SUB>3</SUB></SPAN>,
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I><SUB>4</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I><SUB>4</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>z</I><SUB>4</SUB></SPAN>, the coordinates <!-- MATH
 $(x_i, y_i, z_i)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>x</I><SUB>i</SUB>, <I>y</I><SUB>i</SUB>, <I>z</I><SUB>i</SUB>)</SPAN>(<!-- MATH
 $1 \le i \le 4$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11887img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>i</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11887img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">4</SPAN>) of the four vertices  of a tetrahedron. 
The next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>b</I></SPAN> lines each contains 4 integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>z</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>r</I></SPAN>, the coordinates of the center <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>x</I>, <I>y</I>, <I>z</I>)</SPAN> and the radius <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>r</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>r</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11887img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">3</SPAN>). 
All the coordinate values are integers with absolute values no more than 5. The input is terminated by <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I> = <I>b</I> = 0</SPAN>.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each test case, print a single line, the volume occupied by at least one of them, rounded to three decimal points. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
1 1
0 0 4 1 0 4 0 1 4 0 0 5
0 0 0 1
0 0
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
4.356
</PRE> 

<P>

<P><P>
<BR>

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Problemsetter:</SPAN> Rujia Liu, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Special Thanks:</SPAN> Jingbo Shang

<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Abnormal 89's</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Abnormal 89's">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Abnormal 89's</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
A palindrome is a word that can be read the same way in either direction. More formally if a string is
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>d</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>d</I> &gt; 0</SPAN>) characters length and the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I></SPAN>-th character is <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN>, the string is palindrome if 
and only if <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> equals
<!-- MATH
 $a_{(d-i+1)}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I><SUB>(d-i+1)</SUB></SPAN> for <!-- MATH
 $1 \le i \le d$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11888img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>i</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11888img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>d</I></SPAN>. For example "<TT>abcba</TT>" is palindrome while "<TT>aaab</TT>" is not.

<P>
It is known that everyone who gets to know palindromes, begin an emotional relationship with these
beautiful strings. The harmony between the letters makes them artistic. But the 89's (those who
entered AUT at 1389) claim they love another kind of strings. It is called <SPAN  CLASS="textit">alindrome</SPAN>. Actually an
alindrome is the result of concatenation of two palindromes. 
For example "<TT>abacc</TT>"="<TT>aba</TT>"+"<TT>cc</TT>" is
alindrome.

<P>
Now you should write a program to distinguish alindromes, palindromes and other kind of strings.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
The first line contains <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11888img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">50</SPAN>), the number of tests. Each test that comes in a separate line contains
a string to be checked. Input strings contain only lower case letters ( '<TT>a</TT>' to '<TT>z</TT>' ) and 
their length will be at most 200000.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each test output a single word in a single line. If the input string can be made by concatenating
two palindromes, output "<TT>alindrome</TT>". Otherwise if itâs a palindrome output "<TT>palindrome</TT>". In
any other case print "<TT>simple</TT>". (Quotes for clarity)

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
4
aaa
aabaa
aabaaa
abc
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
alindrome
palindrome
alindrome
simple
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>
