<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Benefit</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Benefit">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Benefit</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>
Recently <SPAN  CLASS="textit">Yaghoub</SPAN> is playing a new trick to sell some more. When somebody gives him <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>A</I></SPAN> Tomans, he
who never has appropriate changes, asks for <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>B</I></SPAN> Tomans such that lowest common multiple of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>A</I></SPAN> and
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>B</I></SPAN> equals to <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN> and he will pay back a round bill. Or otherwise take some snack instead of the
remaining of his money. He believes that finding such a number is hard enough that dissuades
students from paying that.

<P>
You should write a program that help poor students giving the appropriate amount of money to
Yaghoub. Of course if there are several answers you go for students' benefit which is the lowest of
them.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
The first line begin with an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $T \le 100000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11889img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100000</SPAN>), the number of tests. Each test that comes in a
separate line contains two integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>A</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le A, C \le 10^7$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11889img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>A</I>, <I>C</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11889img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<SUP>7</SUP></SPAN>).

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
Print the lowest integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>B</I></SPAN> such that <!-- MATH
 $LCM(A,B)=C$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>LCM</I>(<I>A</I>, <I>B</I>) = <I>C</I></SPAN> in a single line. If no such integer exists, print 
"<TT>NO SOLUTION</TT>" instead. (Quotes for clarity)

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3
2 6
32 1760
7 16
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3
55
NO SOLUTION
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

11890||||||false||||||

<!--Converted with LaTeX2HTML 2008 (1.71)

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Calculus Simplified</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Calculus Simplified">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Calculus Simplified</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
We define an expression as below: 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
<PRE>
&lt;expression&gt; := &lt;number&gt; | &lt;expression&gt;+&lt;expression&gt; |
&lt;expression&gt;-&lt;expression&gt; | (&lt;expression&gt;)
</PRE> 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
where number is defined to be an integer.

<P>
In  this  problem  you  are  given  an  expression  with  all  its  numbers  replaced  with  character 
 '<TT>x</TT>'.  Then you are given a set of numbers that were actually in the expression. We know that numbers 
were placed  in  the  expression  in  such  a  way  that  the  expression  evaluates  to  maximum  possible 
value among all other placements. Write a program that calculates this maximum value. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
In  the  first  line  there  is  an  integer  <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11890img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100</SPAN>),  the  number  of  tests.  Each  test  begins  
with  the expression itself. Next line is an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN>, the number of numbers in the expression. In the final 
line of  each  test  there  are  <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> integers  <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $|a_i| \le 3000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">| <I>a</I><SUB>i</SUB>|<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11890img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">3000</SPAN>).  Each  of  these  numbers  should  be  used  
in the expression exactly once. It is guaranteed that the expression can be parsed by the definition in the 
problem statement and its length  will  not exceed <SPAN CLASS="MATH">10<SUP>5</SUP></SPAN>. There are no whitespaces in the expression 
and all numbers are replaced with a single '<TT>x</TT>'. The number of '<TT>x</TT>'s in the expression is <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN>. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
For each test output the maximum possible value of the expression in a single line. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3
x
1
2
x-x
2
-1 1
(x)+(x)-(x)
3
1 1 1
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
2
2
1
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________
11891||||||false||||||

<!--Converted with LaTeX2HTML 2008 (1.71)

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Deep in Jungles</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Deep in Jungles">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Deep in Jungles</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
The <SPAN  CLASS="textit">Army of Computing Men</SPAN> (ACM) is one the strongest armies in the world. They are well-equipped 
and have trained and armed  programmers They  fight to spread creativity teamwork  and  innovation  among 
people.

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11891.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="307" HEIGHT="345" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11891.jpg" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11891.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
The  last victory  of  the  ACM  against  knowledge 
monopolies  brought  them  wealthy  spoils.  The  supply 
arms have located position of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> crates along a straight 
line in the jungle. Some trucks are to carry the crates to 
the army base. Since the jungle is so dense, it is costly 
for a truck  to  cut through  and bring  the  crates  back.  
Therefore  commanders  have  decided  to  group  the 
crates together in points and use the minimum number of trucks. For each such gathering point we 
should use a truck.  Each  truck  has a  maximum capacity  of  <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>K</I></SPAN> crates 
and has required fuel to bring only one shipment.  

<P>
The  army men  wany to  obey  their  commanders  with 
minimum effort.  Each crate  has a  weight.  The  effort 
needed  to handle a  crate along  the line can be formulized by the weight of the crate multiplied by
the distance it is carried. It is important not to change the order of crates while there are carried. 

<P>
You are  appointed to manage the shipping  procedures.  Higher ranked commanders asked you for a 
report  o minimum needed  resources.  You should  first  consider  minimizing  the number  of  trucks 
and then the army effort. Write your report as soon as possible.  

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
In the first line there will be <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11891.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$">50</SPAN>), number of tests. Each test begins with an integer 
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>K</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le N \le 10^5$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11891.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11891.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<SUP>5</SUP></SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $1 \le K \le 100$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11891.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>K</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11891.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100</SPAN>). It is followed by <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> pairs of integers 
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>p</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>w</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le p_i, w_i \le 10^6$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11891.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>p</I><SUB>i</SUB>, <I>w</I><SUB>i</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11891.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<SUP>6</SUP></SPAN>), 
position and the weight  of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I></SPAN>-th   crate.  Crates  appear in  the  input  in  increasing  order  of  
their  position.  No  two crates occupy the same position in the beginning. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
For  each test  print  the  minimum  number  of trucks  and  the  minimum  effort  needed  to  collect  all 
crates in a single line separated by a single space. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
2
5 2
1 1
4 2
5 10
6 10
10 2
5 5
1 1
4 2
5 10
6 10
10 2
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
3 10
1 26
</PRE> 

<P>

<P><P>
<BR>

<B>Hint</B>

<P>
In the first sample test, we need at least 3 trucks to carry the crates. the optimal solution is to carry 
crate number (1), (2, 3), (4, 5) in separate trucks with costs 0, 2 (for carrying crate 2 to the position of 
crate 3) and 8 (for carrying crate 5 to the position of crate 4) respec vely. 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ENimEN</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="ENimEN">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
ENimEN</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1> 
In deterministic games no chance is involved, meaning that the final result can be predicted from the 
initial arrangement assuming players play optimal. These games are so boring. 

<P>
<SPAN  CLASS="textit">piloop</SPAN>  and  <SPAN  CLASS="textit">poopi</SPAN>  are  professional  gamers.  They  play  games  only  to  study  
their  algorithmic 
properties. Their field of expertise is boring games. One of the boring games they often play is Nim. 
Nim is a two-player game which is played using distinct heaps, each containing a number of objects 
(e.g. stones). Players take turns removing non-zero number of objects from a heap of their choice. 
The player who removes the last object will win.   

<P>
They  wonder  if  they  can  change  the  game  to  make  it  more  fascinating.  Would  not  that  be  more 
interesting if make the rules stricter? For example what if each player is obliged to take objects from 
the  last  non-empty  heap  as  his  opponent  took  objects  from.  And  if  there  is  no  such  heap,  he  can 
choose one heap freely and take objects from it. <SPAN  CLASS="textit">ENimEN</SPAN> is their new invented game based on this 
rule.  

<P>
If  you  are  interested  in  ENimEN,  write  a  program  to  determine  the  winner  given  the  initial 
arrangement assuming both players, play optimal. We believe it has also some benefits for you! 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
The first line contains <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11892img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100</SPAN>), the number of test cases. Each test begins with an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $N \le
20000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11892img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">20000</SPAN>) in the first line, the number of heaps followed by <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le a_i \le 10^9$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11892img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>a</I><SUB>i</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11892img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<SUP>9</SUP></SPAN>), 
are the number 
of objects in <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I></SPAN>-th heap. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
If  in  the  optimal  strategy  the  first  player  is  the  winner  print  "<TT>poopi</TT>"  
(as  he  always  plays  first), 
otherwise print "<TT>piloop</TT>". (Quotes for clarity)  

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
2
2
1 1
4
1 2 1 1
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
piloop
poopi
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Fabulous DAGy</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Fabulous DAGy">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Fabulous DAGy</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1> 
Little poopi had something strange that was called <SPAN  CLASS="textit">DAGy</SPAN>. poopi liked DAGy so much, but when he 
showed DAGy to other children they scared and ran away! DAGy is not a pet or a toy; it is a special 
kind of graph! DAGy is made up of a directed acyclic graph plus one additional directed edge. With 
this additional edge a cycle forms that goes through every vertex in the graph. 

<P>
Once when poopi was playing with DAGy, it fell out of his hands and became totally deformed. He 
cried and cried. He denied new graphs because he wanted his own DAGy.  

<P>
It is said that computer programmers are supermen, because they can solve problems that nobody 
else  is  able  to  even  approach.  You,  the  computer  programmer!  Help  little  poopi  and  dispose  his 
DAGy again! 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
In the first line there is an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11893img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">40</SPAN>), the number of tests. You are given <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN> 
(<!-- MATH
 $1 \le N \le 400$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11893img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11893img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">400</SPAN>)  in  the  first  line  of  each  test,  which  are  the  number  of  
vertices  and  the  number  of  edges 
respectively. Next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN> pairs of integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>u</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11893img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>u</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I> &lt; <I>N</I></SPAN>) meaning that there is an edge 
from vertex <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>u</I></SPAN> 
to vertex <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I></SPAN>. There is at most one edge between each pair of vertices. It is guaranteed that each input 
graph is a directed acyclic graph with one additional edge between two distinct vertices of graph.  

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
DAGy can be put back in order if you find the maximal cycle that goes through every vertex. If you 
found such a cycle print "<TT>Yeah, I'm superman</TT>" in a single line. Otherwise 
print "<TT>Your DAGy was initially defected!</TT>" (Quotes for clarity)  
You are superman trying to help little poopi anyway!  

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
2
3 3
0 1
1 2
2 0
4 5
0 1
1 2
2 0
0 3
3 2
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Yeah, I'm superman
Your DAGy was initially defected!
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Genius MJ</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Genius MJ">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Genius MJ</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1> 
After proving that many of current port types like Serial, USB and ...are useless, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>MJ</I></SPAN> designed a new 
complicated port. His new port turned out to be extremely efficient, but it has one big problem. As 
the port is produced in diverse shapes for different purposes, people usually try to plug a male cable 
into  a  differing  female  socket,  causing  the  pins  to  damage.  So  MJ  proposed  computer  experts  to 
solve this problem.   

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11894.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="278" HEIGHT="134" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11894.jpg" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11894.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
You should write a program to check whether the two parts of a port match. The pins (and holes) of 
the  plug  (socket)  are  given  to  you  as  a  set  of  <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> distinct  points  in  2D  plane.  
You  can translate  the 
points in a set altogether. You can also rotate them around the origin in mul pliers of 90 degrees. 
(i.e.  90,  180  or  270  degrees)  Two  parts  match  each  other  if  a  one  to  one  correspondence can  be 
made between the points of the two sets using translation and rotation.   

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
In the first line there is an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11894.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$">20</SPAN>), the number of pairs of ports to check. Each test begins 
with an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le N \le 10^5$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11894.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11894.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<SUP>5</SUP></SPAN>), the number of pins (and holes). <SPAN CLASS="MATH">2*<I>N</I></SPAN> lines follow. First <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines are 
two integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $|x_i|, |y_i| \le 1000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">| <I>x</I><SUB>i</SUB>|,| <I>y</I><SUB>i</SUB>|<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11894.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1000</SPAN>), coordinates of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I></SPAN>-th pin of plug and next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines are coordinates 
of socket in the same format as the plug. Points in each set are distinct.   

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
For  each  set  output  a  single  word  "<TT>MATCHED</TT>"  if  the  two  parts  of  the  port  match  each  
other  and "<TT>NOT MATCHED</TT>" if they do not. (Quotes for clarity) 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
2
3
0 0
1 0
0 1
-2 0
-1 0
-1 -1
2
0 1
1 0
0 -1
0 0
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
MATCHED
NOT MATCHED
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________
11895||||||false||||||

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Honorary Tickets</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Honorary Tickets">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Honorary Tickets</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1> 
Chief  of  AUT  ICPC  public  relations  offers  an  honorary  visit  to  AUT  ICPC  site  to  lucky  winners.  It 
includes  acknowledging  former  members  <SPAN  CLASS="textit">Agha  Hadi</SPAN>,  <SPAN  CLASS="textit">smile2ka10</SPAN>  and  <!-- MATH
 $Agha  Reza$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>AghaReza</I></SPAN>;  
meeting  with 
current members! and an extra workshop to measure the performance of the site's computers. As it 
is a one time opportunity and everything is going to be renewed soon, many students registered. 

<P>
Selection mechanism takes registration priority, student intellectuality and their chance into account 
all  at  once.  There  are  <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN> bags.  Each  bag  contains  a  number  of  similar  envelopes  some  of  which 
contain a lucky ticket. Students know these amounts. They come one by one in order of registration 
and  take  one  envelope  from  one  of  the  bags.  If  it  contains  a  lucky  ticket,  the  student  takes  it.  In 
either situation the empty envelope is put inside the bag again. The winners are announced after all 
students tried their chance, so nobody knows the result of the students before him. 

<P>
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>nimA</I></SPAN> is <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>K</I></SPAN>-th student to try his chance. But he is worried that no lucky tickets are left. So he asked you 
to  compute  his  chance  of  winning  a  lucky  ticket  assuming  all  students  preceding  him  are  clever 
enough to take the best action.  

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
First line begins with an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11895img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">50</SPAN>), the number of tests. In the first line of each test there are 
two integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>K</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le N, K \le 10^5$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11895img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I>, <I>K</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11895img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<SUP>5</SUP></SPAN>), the number of bags and position of nimA in the queue. Next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> 
lines contain integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>t</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>l</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 &lt; <I>t</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN>), the total number of envelopes and number of envelopes which 
contain lucky tickets in the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I></SPAN>-th bag. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
For each test print the probability of nimA winning a lucky ticket in the form of a fraction  <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>p</I>/<I>q</I></SPAN> such 
that greatest common divisor of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>p</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>q</I></SPAN> equals to 1. It is guaranteed that such <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>p</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>q</I></SPAN>'s for nimA 
and all students preceding him will fit in 32-bit signed integer. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3
2 1
1 1
2 1
2 2
2 2
6 4
1 3
6 4
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
1/1
2/3
25/54
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________
11896||||||false||||||

<!--Converted with LaTeX2HTML 2008 (1.71)

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Inglorious Gangs</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Inglorious Gangs">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Inglorious Gangs</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1> 
In the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">Vice City</SPAN> gangs are disturbing people. Gangs usually drive in streets of Vice City in groups of 
cars.  The  cops  cannot  resist  because  the  number  of  gangs  is  much  greater.  Therefore  each  gang 
group can be chased by only one  cop.  But at some  intersections  in the  city, each of the  gang cars 
goes  in  one  direction.  The  lonely  cop  will  be  confused  which  one  to  follow,  and  the  gang  group 
escapes.

<P>
The  police  officers  know  the  fact  that  gang  groups  will  only  separate  if  they  can  gather together 
again somewhere in the city. They devised a plan and asked the mayor to block some of the roads to 
prevent the gang groups from separating. Now cops can chase gang groups till they catch them. 

<P>
You are hired to check whether or not the city is well prepared to trap the sinister gangs. Map of the 
city  is  in  the  form  of  a  directed  graph  where  nodes  indicate  intersections  and  directed  edges are 
roads of the city. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
In the first line there is <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11896img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100</SPAN>), the number of tests. Each test begins with integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> 
and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le N \le 5000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11896img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11896img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">5000</SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $M \le 10^5$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11896img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<SUP>5</SUP></SPAN>), the number of intersections and roads in the Vice City.  Next  <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN> 
lines are non-blocked roads of Vice City, each of which is a pair of integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>u</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I></SPAN> 
(<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11896img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>u</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11896img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>u</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11896img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \ne$"><I>v</I></SPAN>) meaning that 
there is a road from intersection <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>u</I></SPAN> to intersection <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I></SPAN>.   

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
Print a single word "<TT>Trapped</TT>" if we can trap the gangs and "<TT>Not Trapped</TT>" otherwise. (Quotes 
for clarity) 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
2
3 3
1 2
2 3
1 3
4 4
1 2
2 3
3 4
4 2

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Not Trapped
Trapped
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

11897||||||false||||||

<!--Converted with LaTeX2HTML 2008 (1.71)
original version by:  Nikos Drakos, CBLU, University of Leeds
* revised and updated by:  Marcus Hennecke, Ross Moore, Herb Swan

  Jens Lippmann, Marek Rouchal, Martin Wilck and others -->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Jingling Dominoes</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Jingling Dominoes">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Jingling Dominoes</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Domino  tiles  are  pieces  separated in  two  parts,  each  having  a  number  of  dot on  its  surface.  
Yet numerous  games  are  devised  with  these  simple  tiles.  One  the  most  amusing  of  these  games  is 
domino  spiral.  Domino  spiral  is  a  game  in  which  tiles  are  put  beside each  other  near  enough  
that toppling the first domino topples the second, and so on.  

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11897.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="288" HEIGHT="134" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11897.jpg" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11897.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
Continuing his adventures, this time the great <SPAN  CLASS="textit">Amoo Ardal</SPAN> has constructed the longest domino spiral
made  ever. In  fact  he is  going  to improve  his  last  reco in  Guinness  World  Records.  The spiral  is 
made  up  of  millions of  tiles  an will  take  minutes  to complete. He  has  arranged  a  magnificent 
ceremony. Many guests are invited from all around the world and press will record the event. One of 
the most famous and popular music bands will play the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">Jingling Dominoes</SPAN> piece 
during the event. To coordinate the music with dominos, the music band asked Amoo Ardal 
for the accurate ending time of the spiral. (i.e. the time for the last tile to fall) 

<P>
Amoo is confused. As it took month to  construct the spiral, he does not want  to ruin his  work for 
that purpose. So he asked you as a proficient programmer to do the job for him. 

<P>
Your  are given  the  domino  structure  in  form  of  a  weighted  graph  where  edge denote  a  series  of 
continuous dominoes and the length of the edges indicate how much time it takes for them to fall. 
For the  case of this  problem you can assume that falling of dominoes takes place at constant pace. 
Also  nodes  of  the  graph  show the  places  where  domino  lines  fork.  When  a  tile  falls down, all  the 
neighboring not-fallen dominoes will fall too. Do not make any other assumptions.  

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
In the first line of input there will be an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11897.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$">20</SPAN>). <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> test sets follow. Each begins with three 
integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>S</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $2 \le N \le 1000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">2<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11897.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11897.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1000</SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $M \le 4000000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11897.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$">4000000</SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $0 \le S < N$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11897.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>S</I> &lt; <I>N</I></SPAN>), number of nodes, edges and the starting 
node respectively. Each of next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN> lines contain three integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>u</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>t</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> 
(<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/p11897.jpg" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>u</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I><SUB>i</SUB> &lt; <I>N</I></SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $0 < t_i < 10^6$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 &lt; <I>t</I><SUB>i</SUB> &lt; 10<SUP>6</SUP></SPAN>) which 
are  the  endpoints  of  <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I></SPAN>-th  continuous  domin line  and  the  time  it takes  to  completely  fall.
It  is guaranteed that each node has at least one edge and the starting node has exactly one edge. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
If the domino spiral does not complete at all print "<TT>Sorry Amoo, your domino does not complete!</TT>" 
in a single line (Quotes for clarity). Otherwise print the time that the latest tile will fall 
rounded to two decimal digits after the decimal point. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3
4 3 0
0 1 1
1 2 2
2 3 3
4 4 1
1 0 1
0 2 2
2 3 2
0 3 3
4 2 2
0 1 1
3 2 2
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
6.00
4.50
Sorry Amoo, your domino does not complete!
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________

  Jens Lippmann, Marek Rouchal, Martin Wilck and others -->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Killer Problem</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Killer Problem">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Killer Problem</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
You are given an array of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> integers and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Q</I></SPAN> queries. Each query is a closed interval <SPAN CLASS="MATH">[<I>l</I>, <I>r</I>]</SPAN>. You should 
find the minimum absolute difference between all pairs in that interval. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
First line contains an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11898img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10</SPAN>). <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> sets follow. Each set begins with an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> 
(<!-- MATH
 $N \le 200000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11898img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">200000</SPAN>). 
In the next line there are <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>a</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le a_i \le 10^4$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11898img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>a</I><SUB>i</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11898img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<SUP>4</SUP></SPAN>), the number in the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I></SPAN>-th 
cell of the array. Next line 
will  contain  <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Q</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $Q  \le  10^4$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Q</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11898img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<SUP>4</SUP></SPAN>).  <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Q</I></SPAN> lines  follow,  each  containing  two  integers  <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>l</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN>,  <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>r</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> 
(<!-- MATH
 $1  \le  l_i$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11898img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>l</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN>,  <!-- MATH
 $r_i  \le  N$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>r</I><SUB>i</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11898img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I></SPAN>,  <!-- MATH
 $l_i  <  r_i$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>l</I><SUB>i</SUB> &lt; <I>r</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN>) 
describing the beginning and ending of of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I></SPAN>-th range. Total number of queries will be less than 15000. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 
For the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I></SPAN>-th query of each test output the minimum <!-- MATH
 $|a_j â a_k|$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">| <I>a</I><SUB>j</SUB>â<I>a</I><SUB>k</SUB>|</SPAN> for <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>l</I><SUB>i</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11898img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>j</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>k</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11898img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>r</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>j</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/118/11898img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \ne$"><I>k</I></SPAN>) 
a single line. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
1
10
1 2 4 7 11 10 8 5 1 10000
4
1 10
1 2
3 5
8 10
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
0
1
3
4
</PRE> 

<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0 width="54%"
 style='width:54.18%'>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="22%" valign=top style='width:22.16%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle style='line-height:115%'>A</p>
  </td>
  <td width="76%" valign=top style='width:76.62%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Writing the Whole &#960;</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal>Unless you are living under the rock you may have heard the
name of <b>N</b>awab <b>S</b>i<b>R</b>aj-ud-doula (we call him <b>NSR</b> for
simplicity). If you indeed live under the rock then let me say something about
him. He was smart and very good at programming and mathematics. One of his
favorite hobbies is to write the <b><span style='color:black'>&#960;</span></b><span
style='color:black'> to its whole, <b>3.14159</b>. As you might be wondering <b>3.14159</b>
is not the whole of <b>&#960;</b> and his friends say so.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>His friends tried to convince him that he can't write
irrational numbers to their whole. As an example they say that even <b>3.14159</b>
is not the best approximation of <b><span style='color:black'>&#960;</span></b><span
style='color:black'> using <b>7</b> </span><img width=195 height=195 src=p11899.jpg
align=right hspace=12><span style='color:black'>symbols. It is <b>355/113</b>.
This made NSR interested. So he decided to ask his friends for good
approximation of different irrational numbers</span>. </p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>The first line of input will contain <b>T (&#8804; 10000)</b>
denoting the number of cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case contains three integers <b>m (1 &lt; m &#8804; 10)</b>,
<b>n (1 &lt; n &#8804; 10000)</b> and <b>p</b> <b>(1 &lt; p &#8804; 10)</b>.
Now NSR wants you to find the best approximation of <b>m<sup>th</sup></b> root
of <b>n</b> using at most <b>p</b> symbols. You may assume that it will always
be an irrational number. You may also assume that <b>n &lt; 10<sup>p*m</sup></b>.
For this problem, digits, <b>'.'</b> and <b>'/'</b> are treated as symbols. To
make the problem easier, at most one non-digit symbol can be used to approximate
the number.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number and the approximation
as described in problem statement. If there are multiple solutions, output the
one with least number of symbols. If there is still a tie, output the
lexicographically earlier one.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="52%"
 style='width:52.38%;border-collapse:collapse'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:39.15pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing style='line-height:115%'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
  line-height:115%;font-family:"Courier New"'>2</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing style='line-height:115%'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
  line-height:115%;font-family:"Courier New"'>4 2 8</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing style='line-height:115%'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
  line-height:115%;font-family:"Courier New"'>4 2 9</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing style='line-height:115%'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
  line-height:115%;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case 1: 1.189207</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing style='line-height:115%'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
  line-height:115%;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case 2: 8969/7542</span></p>

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0 width="54%"
 style='width:54.18%'>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="22%" valign=top style='width:22.16%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle style='line-height:115%'>B</p>
  </td>
  <td width="76%" valign=top style='width:76.62%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Boiled Eggs</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal>Three of the trouble-makers went to Malaysia this year. A
rest house was booked for them. Unlike other rest houses, this rest house was
like a normal duplex house. So, it had a kitchen. And the trouble-makers were given
all the ingredients to cook, but they had to cook themselves.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><img width=219 height=164 src=p11900.jpg align=left hspace=12>None
of them had any previous cooking experience, but they became very excited and
planned to cook so many delicious foods! Ideas were coming from their minds
like rains from clouds. So, they went to the super market and bought a lot of
extra ingredients for their great recipes. For example, they bought <b>20</b>
eggs. The excited trouble-makers returned to the rest house and found that the
gas stove was not connected to the gas cylinder. So, they became very sad,
because it was not possible for them to connect such complex thing. And so many
foods were about to be rotten. But luckily, they found the microwave oven
working. So, they tried to boil all the eggs using the microwave oven (may be,
first time in history)! And they succeeded to boil the eggs!</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Now they have <b>n</b> eggs and a bowl. They put some eggs
in the bowl with some water. And after that they put the bowl into the oven to
boil the eggs. It's risky to put more than <b>P</b> eggs in the bowl and the
bowl can carry at most <b>Q</b> gm of eggs. It takes <b>12</b> minutes to boil
a bowl of eggs. Now you are given the weight of the eggs in gm, and the
trouble-makers have exactly <b>12</b> minutes in their hand. You have to find
the maximum number of eggs they can boil without taking any risk. </p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>The first line of input will contain <b>T (&#8804; 100)</b>
denoting the number of cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case starts with <b>3</b> integers <b>n (1 &#8804; n &#8804;
30)</b>, <b>P (1 &#8804; P &#8804; 30)</b> and <b>Q (1 &#8804; Q &#8804; 30)</b>.
The next line contains <b>n</b> positive integers (not greater than <b>10</b>)
in non-descending order. These integers denote the weight of the eggs in gm.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number and the desired result.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="52%"
 style='width:52.38%;border-collapse:collapse'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:39.15pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>2</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>3 2 10</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>1 2 3</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>4 5 5</span></pre>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing style='line-height:115%'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
  line-height:115%;font-family:Courier'>4 4 5 5</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>Case 1: 2</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>Case 2: 1</span></pre></td>
 </tr>
</table>

<div class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:center'><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>

<hr size=2 width="100%" align=center>

</span></div>

</head>

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0 width="54%"
 style='width:54.18%'>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="22%" valign=top style='width:22.16%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle style='line-height:115%'>C</p>
  </td>
  <td width="76%" valign=top style='width:76.62%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Ellipse Hazard</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal>Finding the intersection of two arbitrary ellipses can be
tricky. Actually even the intersection of two axis-parallel ellipses can be tricky,
let alone ellipses that are in rotated position like the two shown below:</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><img width=466 height=277 src=p11901a.jpg align=right hspace=12>For
two arbitrary ellipses, the following cases can occur:</p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>(a)</span><span
style='font-size:8.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>They do not intersect.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>(b)</span><span
style='font-size:8.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>They intersect each
other in two points.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>(c)</span><span
style='font-size:8.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>They intersect each
other in four points.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>(d)</span><span
style='font-size:8.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>They touch each other
in one point.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>(e)</span><span
style='font-size:8.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>They touch each other in
one point and intersect in another two points.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing style='margin-bottom:12.0pt'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>(f)</span><span style='font-size:8.0pt;
font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>They touch each other
in two points.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>In this problem you will not have to detect whether two
ellipses touch each other as the given ellipses will not touch each other: They
will either intersect each other in 2 or 4 different points or will not
intersect. In other words you will have to deal with only situation (a), (b)
and (c).</p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>There will be around <b>6000</b> cases for this problem.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case contains <b>10</b> integers <b>x<sub>1</sub>, y<sub>1</sub>,
a, b, </b><b><sub><img width=14 height=19 src=p11901b.jpg></sub></b><b>, x<sub>2</sub>,
y<sub>2</sub>, c, d, </b><b><sub><img width=17 height=18 src=p11901c.jpg></sub></b>.
Here</p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>a)</span><span
style='font-size:8.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>(x<sub>1</sub>,
y<sub>1</sub>)</span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>
= Coordinate of the center of first ellipse <b>(0 &#8804; x<sub>1</sub>, y<sub>1</sub>
&#8804; 1000)</b>.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>b)</span><span
style='font-size:8.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>(x<sub>2</sub>,
y<sub>2</sub>)</span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>
= Coordinate of the center of the second ellipse <b>(0 &#8804; x<sub>2</sub>, y<sub>2</sub>
&#8804; 1000)</b>.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>c)</span><span
style='font-size:8.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>a</span></b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'> = length of semi-major
axis of first ellipse <b>(10 &#8804; a &#8804; 500)</b>.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>d)</span><span
style='font-size:8.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>b</span></b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'> = length of semi-minor
axis of first ellipse <b>(10 &#8804; b &#8804; 500)</b>.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>e)</span><span
style='font-size:8.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>c</span></b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'> = length of the
semi-major axis of second ellipse <b>(10 &#8804; c &#8804; 500)</b>.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>f)</span><span
style='font-size:8.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>d</span></b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'> = length of the
semi-minor axis of second ellipse <b>(10 &#8804; d &#8804; 500)</b>.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>g)</span><span
style='font-size:8.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span><b><sub><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'><img
width=14 height=19 src=p11901b.jpg></span></sub></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>= angle (in degrees) the major axis of the
first ellipse creates with the positive direction of x-axis <b>(0 &#8804; </b></span><b><sub><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'><img width=14
height=19 src=p11901b.jpg></span></sub></b><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&#8804; 360)</span></b><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing style='margin-bottom:12.0pt'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>h)</span><span style='font-size:8.0pt;
font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><sub><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'><img width=17
height=18 src=p11901c.jpg></span></sub><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:
"Garamond","serif"'>= angle (in degrees) the major axis of second ellipse
creates with the positive direction of x-axis <b>(0 &#8804; </b></span><sub><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'><img width=17
height=18 src=p11901c.jpg></span></sub><sub><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;</span></sub><b><span style='font-size:
12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&#8804; 360).</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Input is terminated by a case where the value of <b>a, b, c</b>
and <b>d</b> are negative. This case should not be processed.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, produce two, three or five lines of outputs.
The first line contains the serial of output. If the two ellipses do not
intersect then in the next line print the line <b>&quot;Do_not_intersect.&quot;</b>
If the ellipses intersect in two points then print two floating-point numbers
in two lines and if the ellipses intersect in four points then print four
floating-point numbers in four lines. These floating-point numbers are actually
summation of abscissa and ordinate of the intersection points. These numbers
should be printed in ascending order and should have eight digits after the
decimal point. Errors less than <b>10<sup>-5</sup></b> will be ignored.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="52%"
 style='width:52.38%;border-collapse:collapse'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.34%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.66%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:96.75pt'>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.34%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:96.75pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>755 216 313 109
  130 671 997 355 85 338</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>861 654 216 319
  300 936 910 338 483 318</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>653 819 271 144
  325 145 959 145 49 185</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>653 819 -1 -1
  325 145 959 -1 -1 185</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.66%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:96.75pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Case 1:</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Do_not_intersect.</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Case 2:</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>1173.83963384</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>1754.28733987</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Case 3:</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing style='line-height:115%'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Do_not_intersect.</span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<div class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:center'><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>

<hr size=2 width="100%" align=center>

</span></div>

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0 width="54%"
 style='width:54.18%'>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="22%" valign=top style='width:22.16%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle style='line-height:115%'>D</p>
  </td>
  <td width="76%" valign=top style='width:76.62%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Dominator</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal>In graph theory, a node <b>X</b> dominates a node <b>Y</b>
if every path from the predefined start node to <b>Y</b> must go through <b>X</b>.
If <b>Y</b> is not reachable from the start node then node <b>Y</b> does not have
any dominator. By definition, every node reachable from the start node
dominates itself. In this problem, you will be given a directed graph and you
have to find the dominators of every node where <img
src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11902.jpg"  align=right hspace=12>the 0<sup>th</sup> node is the
start node.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>As an example, for the graph shown right, <b>3</b> dominates
<b>4</b> since all the paths from <b>0</b> to <b>4</b> must pass through <b>3</b>.
<b>1</b> doesn't dominate <b>3</b> since there is a path <b>0-2-3</b> that
doesn't include <b>1</b>. </p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>The first line of input will contain <b>T (&#8804; 100)</b>
denoting the number of cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case starts with an integer <b>N (0 &lt; N &lt; 100) </b>that
represents the number of nodes in the graph. The next <b>N</b> lines contain <b>N</b>
integers each. If the <b>j<sup>th</sup>(0 based)</b> integer of <b>i<sup>th</sup>(0
based)</b> line is <b>1</b>, it means that there is an edge from node <b>i</b>
to node <b>j</b> and similarly a <b>0</b> means there is no edge.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, output the case number first. Then output <b>2N+1</b>
lines that summarizes the dominator relationship between every pair of nodes.
If node <b>A</b> dominates node <b>B</b>, output <b>'Y'</b> in <b>cell (A, B)</b>,
otherwise output <b>'N'</b>. <b>Cell (A, B)</b> means cell at <b>A<sup>th</sup></b>
row and <b>B<sup>th</sup></b> column. Surround the output with <b>|</b>, <b>+</b>
and <b></b> to make it more legible. Look at the samples for exact format.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="52%"
 style='width:52.38%;border-collapse:collapse'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:39.15pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>2</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>5</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>0
  1 1 0 0</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>0
  0 0 1 0</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>0
  0 0 1 0</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>0
  0 0 0 1</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>0
  0 0 0 0</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>1</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>1</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  1:</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>+---------+</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>|Y|Y|Y|Y|Y|</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>+---------+</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>|N|Y|N|N|N|</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>+---------+</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>|N|N|Y|N|N|</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>+---------+</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>|N|N|N|Y|Y|</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>+---------+</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>|N|N|N|N|Y|</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>+---------+</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  2:</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>+-+</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>|Y|</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>+-+</span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

p.msotitlecxspfirst, li.msotitlecxspfirst, div.msotitlecxspfirst
	{mso-style-name:msotitlecxspfirst;
	mso-style-link:"Title Char";
	margin:0in;
	margin-bottom:.0001pt;
	text-align:center;
	font-size:36.0pt;
	font-family:"Bernard MT Condensed","serif";
	letter-spacing:.25pt;}
p.msotitlecxspmiddle, li.msotitlecxspmiddle, div.msotitlecxspmiddle
	{mso-style-name:msotitlecxspmiddle;
	mso-style-link:"Title Char";

	text-align:center;
	font-size:36.0pt;
	font-family:"Bernard MT Condensed","serif";
	letter-spacing:.25pt;}
p.msotitlecxsplast, li.msotitlecxsplast, div.msotitlecxsplast

	mso-style-link:"Title Char";
	margin:0in;
	margin-bottom:.0001pt;

	font-size:36.0pt;
	font-family:"Bernard MT Condensed","serif";

	{mso-style-name:"Table Contents";
	margin-top:0in;

	margin-bottom:10.0pt;
	margin-left:0in;
	line-height:115%;
	font-size:11.0pt;
	font-family:"Calibri","sans-serif";}
p.TableHeading, li.TableHeading, div.TableHeading
	{mso-style-name:"Table Heading";
	margin-top:0in;

div.Section1

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0 width="54%"
 style='width:54.18%'>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="22%" valign=top style='width:22.16%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle style='line-height:115%'>E</p>
  </td>
  <td width="76%" valign=top style='width:76.62%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>e-Friends</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal>Social networking web sites are very popular these days. I
am not mentioning any names because you know better than me. People do have a
lot of e-friends now, &quot;you may not know his real identity but he is your
friend&quot;. Sometimes, there can be rivalries between people, and thus people
gets blocked or deleted. And these rivalries don't have to be necessarily
commutative. That means <b>x</b> may think <b>y</b> as his enemy, but <b>y</b>
may or may not think so.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>However, what if you get the opportunity to see all your
e-friends live? Since you like social networks very much, you planned to
arrange a get-together with your e-friends. So, you invited <b>n</b> of your
e-friends in your home. For simplicity, you numbered them from <b>1</b> to <b>n</b>.
They were your friends, but rivalries existed amongst many of them. You asked
them to form a queue such that they can get food from the table. And you will
serve foods one by one. But your friends demanded that, no enemy should be the
next person in the queue. That means if <b>x</b> thinks that <b>y</b> is his
enemy and <b>x</b>'s position in the queue is <b>i</b>, then <b>y</b>'s
position shouldn't be <b>i-1</b>.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>So, it became very complex. That's why you decided to add a
dissatisfaction index <b>k</b> if one's demand is not fulfilled. And the total
dissatisfaction index is the summation of all the dissatisfaction indexes. Now
you know the rivalries and the maximum total dissatisfaction index you may
allow, you want to find the total number of possible arrangements.</p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>The first line of input will contain <b>T (&#8804; 30)</b>
denoting the number of cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case starts with <b>3</b> integers <b>n (1 &#8804; n
&#8804; 12)</b>, <b>k (0 &#8804; k &#8804; 10<sup>6</sup>)</b> and <b>q (1
&#8804; q &#8804; 1000) </b>which denotes the number of queries. Then there
will be <b>n</b> lines. The <b>i<sup>th</sup></b> line contains an integer <b>t<sub>i</sub>
(0 &#8804; t<sub>i</sub> &lt; n)</b> and ids of <b>t<sub>i</sub></b> distinct
friends. It means <b>i<sup>th</sup></b> person thinks the <b>t<sub>i</sub></b>
listed persons as his enemy. Each of the next <b>q</b> lines contains an
integer <b>r (0 &#8804; r &#8804; 10<sup>8</sup>)</b> denoting the total
allowable dissatisfaction index.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number first. Then for each
query, print the total number of arrangements possible not exceeding the given
total dissatisfaction index.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="52%"
 style='width:52.38%;border-collapse:collapse'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:39.15pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>1</span></pre><pre><span

  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>1 2</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>0</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>10</span></pre>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing style='line-height:115%'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
  line-height:115%;font-family:Courier'>5</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>Case 1:</span></pre><pre><span

</head>

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0 width="54%"
 style='width:54.18%'>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="22%" valign=top style='width:22.16%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle style='line-height:115%'>F</p>
  </td>
  <td width="76%" valign=top style='width:76.62%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>One Unit Machine</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal>OUM is a one unit machine which processes jobs. Since it
can't handle heavyweight jobs; jobs needs to be partitioned into units.
Initially, all the job information and unit partitions are given as input. Then
the machine allocates necessary time slots. And in each time slot it asks the
user for the name of the job to be processed. After getting the name; the
machine determines the next unprocessed unit of that job and processes that
unit in that slot. If there is no such unit, the machine crashes. A job is said
to be complete if all the units of that job are complete.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>For example, let <b>J<sub>1</sub></b> and <b>J<sub>2</sub></b>
be two jobs each having <b>2</b> units. So, OUM will create <b>4</b> time
slots. Now the user can give <b>J<sub>1</sub> J<sub>2</sub> J<sub>2</sub> J<sub>1</sub></b>
as input. That means it completes the <b>1<sup>st</sup></b> unit of <b>J<sub>1</sub></b>
in time slot <b>1</b> and then completes the <b>1<sup>st</sup></b> unit of <b>J<sub>2</sub></b>
in time slot <b>2.</b> After that it completes the <b>2<sup>nd</sup></b> unit
of <b>J<sub>­2</sub></b> and <b>2<sup>nd</sup></b> unit of <b>J<sub>1</sub></b>
in time slots <b>3</b> and <b>4</b> respectively. But if the user gives <b>J<sub>1</sub>
J<sub>1</sub> J<sub>2</sub> J<sub>1 </sub></b>as input, the machine crashes in
time slot <b>4</b> since it tries to process <b>3<sup>rd</sup></b> unit of <b>J<sub>1</sub></b>
which is not available.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Now, Sam is the owner of a software firm named ACM and he
has <b>n</b> jobs to complete using OUM. He wants to complete <b>Job<sub>i</sub></b>
before <b>Job<sub>i+1</sub></b> where <b>1 &#8804; i &lt; n</b>. Now he wants
to know the total number of ways he can complete these jobs without crashing the
OUM. He assigned you for this task. Two ways are different if at <b>t<sup>th</sup></b>
slot one processed a unit of <b>Job<sub>i</sub></b> and another processed a unit
of <b>Job<sub>j</sub></b> where <b>i &#8800; j</b>. For the example above,
there are three ways:</p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>J<sub>1</sub>
J<sub>1</sub> J<sub>2</sub> J<sub>2</sub></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>J<sub>1</sub>
J<sub>2</sub> J<sub>1</sub> J<sub>2</sub></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b>J<sub>2</sub> J<sub>1</sub> J<sub>1</sub> J<sub>2</sub></b></p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>The first line of input will contain <b>T (&#8804; 100)</b>
denoting the number of cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case starts with an integer <b>n (1 &#8804; n &#8804; 1000)</b>.
The next line contains <b>n</b> space separated positive integers <b>k<sub>1</sub>,
k<sub>2</sub>, k<sub>3</sub> ... k<sub>n</sub></b>. Where, <b>k<sub>i</sub></b>
denotes the number of units for the <b>i<sup>th</sup></b> job. You can assume
that total number of units for all the jobs in any case is not greater than <b>10<sup>6</sup></b>.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number and the result modulo <b>1000,000,007</b>.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="52%"
 style='width:52.38%;border-collapse:collapse'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:39.15pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>2</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>2</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>2 2</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>3</span></pre>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing style='line-height:115%'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
  line-height:115%;font-family:Courier'>2 2 3</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>Case 1: 3</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>Case 2: 45</span></pre></td>
 </tr>
</table>

<div class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:center'><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>

<hr size=2 width="100%" align=center>

</span></div>

<p class=MsoNormal>Problem Setter: Kazi Rakibul Hossain, Special Thanks: Jane
Alam Jan</p>

</div>

</body>

</html>
