</head>

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0 width="54%"
 style='width:54.18%'>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="22%" valign=top style='width:22.16%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle style='line-height:115%'>G</p>
  </td>
  <td width="76%" valign=top style='width:76.62%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Map Coloring</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal>Given a model of a map in a <b>2D</b> grid, you have to
color the map satisfying certain constraints.</p>

<p class=MsoListParagraph style='margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in'>1)<span
style='font-size:7.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>A map contains one or more regions. Each region is identified by an
uppercase English letter <b>L<sub>i</sub></b>. In the grid, there will be some
cells containing <b>L<sub>i</sub></b> to form the region. From any cell of that
region, it's possible to go to all cells (in that region) using adjacent moves.
Adjacent move means going to a cell which shares a side with the current cell
and belongs to the same region.</p>

<p class=MsoListParagraph style='margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in'>2)<span
style='font-size:7.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>A region <b>Q</b> may be surrounded by another region <b>P</b>. In such
case, <b>Q</b> is called a sub-region of <b>P</b> and <b>Q</b> may be erased
from the map. Mark all the cells that are surrounded by <b>P</b> with <b>P</b>'s
identifier letter.</p>

<p class=MsoListParagraph style='margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in'>3)<span
style='font-size:7.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>All regions that are not surrounded by other regions should be colored,
but two adjacent regions shouldn't be colored using the same color.</p>

<p class=MsoListParagraph style='margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in'>4)<span
style='font-size:7.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>Two regions <b>A</b> and <b>B</b> are said to be adjacent if there is a
cell of region <b>A</b>, and a cell of region <b>B</b>, share a side.</p>

<p class=MsoListParagraph style='margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in'>5)<span
style='font-size:7.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span>If two cells of a region share a corner, then there will always be at
least one cell which shares sides with both the cells.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Now your job is to find the minimum number of different
colors you need to color the map.</p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>The first line of input will contain <b>T (&#8804; 100)</b>
denoting the number of cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case starts with two integers <b>m</b> and <b>n (5 &#8804;
m, n &#8804; 50)</b> denoting the number of rows and columns respectively. Each
of the next <b>m</b> lines contains <b>n</b> characters each. Each character
will be either a <b>'.'</b> or any uppercase English letter. <b>'.'</b> means
empty place, and letters represent regions as described above. You can assume
that the input data satisfies the above constraints.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number and the minimum number
of colors. Print <b>m</b> lines, each line with <b>n</b> characters showing the
final grid after erasing sub-regions and filling the surrounding cells.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="52%"
 style='width:52.38%;border-collapse:collapse'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:39.15pt'>

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0 width="54%"
 style='width:54.18%'>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="22%" valign=top style='width:22.16%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle style='line-height:115%'>H</p>
  </td>
  <td width="76%" valign=top style='width:76.62%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Knight in War Grid</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal>Once upon an ancient time, a knight was preparing for the
great battle in GridLand. The GridLand is divided into square grids. There are <b>R
</b>horizontal and <b>C </b>vertical grids. Our particular knight in this case
can always give an <b>(M, N) </b>move, i.e. he can move <b>M </b>squares
horizontally and <b>N </b>squares vertically or he can move <b>M </b>squares
vertically and <b>N </b>squares horizontally in a single move. In other words
he can jump from square <b>(a, b) </b>to square <b>(c, d) </b>if and only if,
either <b>(|a - c| = M and |b - d| = N) </b>or <b>(|a - c| = N and |b - d| = M)</b>.
However, some of the squares in the war field are filled with water. For a
successful jump from one square to another, none of the squares should contain
water. Now, the knight wants to have a tour in the war field to check if
everything is alright or not. He will do the following:</p>

<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst style='text-indent:-.25in'>a)<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span>He
will start and end his tour in square <b>(0, 0)</b> but visit as many squares
as he can. </p>

<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle style='text-indent:-.25in'><span
style='line-height:115%'>b)<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='line-height:115%'>For each square <b>s<sub>i</sub></b>,
he counts the number <b>k<sub>i</sub></b> of distinct squares, from which he
can reach <b>s<sub>i</sub> </b>in one jump (satisfying the jumping condition). Then
he marks the square as an even square if <b>k<sub>i</sub></b> is even or marks
it odd if <b>k<sub>i</sub> </b>is odd. The squares he cannot visit remain
unmarked.</span></p>

<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpLast style='text-indent:-.25in'><span
style='line-height:115%'>c)<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='line-height:115%'>After coming back to square <b>(0,
0) </b>he counts the number of even and odd marked squares. He can visit a
square more than once.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>You, as an advisor of the knight, suggested that, he can do
it without visiting all the squares, just by writing a program. So the knight
told you to do so. He will check your result at the end of his visit.</p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>The first line of input will contain <b>T (&#8804; 50)</b>
denoting the number of cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case starts with four integers <b>R, C, M, N (1 &lt; R,
C </b><b>&#8804;</b><b> 100, 0 &#8804; M, N </b><b>&#8804;</b><b> 50, M + N
&gt; 0)</b>. Next line contains an integer <b>W (0 </b><b>&#8804;</b><b> W &lt;
R * C),</b> which is the number of distinct grids containing water. Each of the
next <b>W</b> lines contains a pair of integer <b>x<sub>i</sub>, y<sub>i</sub>
(0 </b><b>&#8804;</b><b> x<sub>i</sub> &lt; R, 0 </b><b>&#8804;</b><b> y<sub>i</sub>
&lt; C, x<sub>i</sub> + y<sub>i</sub> &gt; 0)</b>.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number and the number of even
and odd marked squares.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="52%"
 style='width:52.38%;border-collapse:collapse'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:39.15pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'>
  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-left:0in'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>2</span></p>
  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-left:0in'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>3
  3 2 1</span></p>
  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-left:0in'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>0</span></p>
  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-left:0in'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>4
  4 1 2</span></p>
  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-left:0in'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>2</span></p>
  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-left:0in'><span style='font-family:"Courier New"'>3
  3</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing style='line-height:115%'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
  line-height:115%;font-family:"Courier New"'>1 1</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'>
  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-left:0in;layout-grid-mode:char'><span
  style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Case 1: 8 0</span></p>
  <p class=SampleIO style='margin-left:0in;layout-grid-mode:char'><span
  style='font-family:"Courier New"'>Case 2: 4 10</span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

text-align:center'><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>

	font-family:"Calibri","sans-serif";}
p.msotitlecxspfirst, li.msotitlecxspfirst, div.msotitlecxspfirst
	{mso-style-name:msotitlecxspfirst;
	mso-style-link:"Title Char";
	margin:0in;
	margin-bottom:.0001pt;
	text-align:center;
	font-size:36.0pt;
	font-family:"Bernard MT Condensed","serif";
	letter-spacing:.25pt;}
p.msotitlecxspmiddle, li.msotitlecxspmiddle, div.msotitlecxspmiddle
	{mso-style-name:msotitlecxspmiddle;
	mso-style-link:"Title Char";
	margin:0in;
	margin-bottom:.0001pt;
	text-align:center;
	font-size:36.0pt;
	font-family:"Bernard MT Condensed","serif";
	letter-spacing:.25pt;}
p.msotitlecxsplast, li.msotitlecxsplast, div.msotitlecxsplast
	{mso-style-name:msotitlecxsplast;
	mso-style-link:"Title Char";
	margin:0in;
	margin-bottom:.0001pt;
	text-align:center;
	font-size:36.0pt;
	font-family:"Bernard MT Condensed","serif";
	letter-spacing:.25pt;}
p.TableContents, li.TableContents, div.TableContents
	{mso-style-name:"Table Contents";
	margin-top:0in;
	margin-right:0in;
	margin-bottom:10.0pt;
	margin-left:0in;
	line-height:115%;
	font-size:11.0pt;
	font-family:"Calibri","sans-serif";}
p.TableHeading, li.TableHeading, div.TableHeading
	{mso-style-name:"Table Heading";
	margin-top:0in;

	margin-left:0in;

	{mso-style-name:apple-style-span;}

	{font-size:10.0pt;}

	margin:1.0in 1.0in 1.0in 1.0in;}
div.Section1
	{page:Section1;}
-->
</style>

</head>

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0 width="54%"
 style='width:54.18%'>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="22%" valign=top style='width:22.16%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle style='line-height:115%'>I</p>
  </td>
  <td width="76%" valign=top style='width:76.62%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Collision of Bacteria</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:6.0pt'>An experiment is being conducted
to find out how different colonies of bacteria behave when they collide with
each other. The individual colonies are placed on a large dish and the dish can
be modeled in a <b>2D</b> plane. Initially, each colony occupies a rectangular
area (sides parallel to axis) and the sizes of these colonies grow with time.
The growth of the colonies occurs in the following manner:</p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>1.</span><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>The <b>x</b>
and <b>y</b> coordinate of the lower-left corner decrease.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>2.</span><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span><img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11907.jpg"  align=right
hspace=12 alt="http://apod.nasa.gov/apod/image/0209/drad_daly.jpg"><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>The <b>x</b> coordinate
of lower-right corner increases and the <b>y</b> coordinate decreases.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>3.</span><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>The <b>x</b>
and <b>y</b> coordinate of upper-right corner increase.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNoSpacing style='margin-bottom:6.0pt'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>4.</span><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>The <b>x</b> coordinate
of upper-left corner decreases and the <b>y</b> coordinate increases.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>All the increments/decrements mentioned above occur at a
constant rate<b> r </b>with respect to time. In this problem, you have to
determine the smallest unit of time that elapses when there are at least two
colonies that are not more than <b>d</b> distance apart. Here the distance refers
to the shortest Euclidean distance between the rectangular areas occupied by
the colonies.</p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>The first line of input will contain <b>T (&#8804; 100)</b>
denoting the number of cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case starts with an integer <b>n (2 &#8804; n &#8804;
50)</b> denoting the number of colonies. Each of the next <b>n</b> lines
contains <b>4</b> integers <b>x<sub>1</sub> y<sub>1</sub> x<sub>2</sub> y<sub>2</sub>
(0 &#8804; x<sub>1</sub>, y<sub>1</sub>, x<sub>2</sub>, y<sub>2</sub> &#8804;
10000, x<sub>1</sub> &lt; x<sub>2</sub>, y<sub>1</sub> &lt; y<sub>2</sub>) </b>where
<b>(x<sub>1</sub>, y<sub>1</sub>)</b> and <b>(x<sub>2</sub>, y<sub>2</sub>)</b>
denote the lower-left and upper-right corner of the colony respectively. Next
line contains two integers, <b>r</b> and <b>d (1 &#8804; r, d &#8804; 50)</b>.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number and the desired result
rounded to <b>3</b> places after the decimal point. If two colonies overlap or
just touch each other, they are considered to be zero distance apart.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="52%"
 style='width:52.38%;border-collapse:collapse'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:39.15pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing style='line-height:115%'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
  line-height:115%;font-family:"Courier New"'>2<br>
  2<br>
  0 0 1 1<br>
  3 0 4 1<br>
  1 1<br>
  2<br>
  0 0 1 1<br>
  0 1 3 2<br>
  1 1</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing style='line-height:115%'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
  line-height:115%;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case 1: 0.500<br>
  Case 2: 0.000</span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<div class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:center'><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0 width="54%"
 style='width:54.18%'>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="22%" valign=top style='width:22.16%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle style='line-height:115%'>J</p>
  </td>
  <td width="76%" valign=top style='width:76.62%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Skyscraper</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal>The Build n' Profit construction company is about to build
its tallest building. It will be huge, the tallest building in the world by a
wide margin. It will house hundreds of thousands of people and have
rocket-powered elevators to the upper floors. They even plan for a shuttle
docking station instead of a helipad on its roof. But any building of that size
is extremely costly to build and maintain, and even after selling and renting
out all the floor-space it will be very difficult to meet the costs. Luckily,
they have come up with a great solution. They will place advertisements on the
outer walls of the building for a hefty charge. This will help offset some of
the costs and bring in a profit.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>However, feedbacks from prospective buyers of this
advertisement space have brought up a new problem. Each customer wants a
specific sized advertisement placed at a specific height, and they will pay a
certain amount of money for it. Each advertisement order specifies its position
(i.e. the lowest floor of the advertisement) and its size (i.e. the number of
floors it covers, including the starting floor). Each advertisement spans the
whole face of the building, so no two advertisements can occupy the same floor
and no floors can be partially covered. Each order also includes the amount to
be earned if that advertisement is placed on the building. Of course, no money
is earned if only part of an advertisement is placed, or it is placed in any
other position.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Since many of the advertisements want some of the same
floors as others, it is often impossible to choose all of them. Can you help
choosing which of the orders to accept so that the above constraints are
fulfilled and the amount of profit is maximized?</p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>The first line of input will contain <b>T (&#8804; 50)</b>
denoting the number of cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case starts with an integer <b>N (1 &#8804; N &#8804; 30000)</b>
denoting the number of advertisement orders. Each of the next <b>N</b> lines
represents an advertisement by three integers <b>A (0 &#8804; A &#8804; 10<sup>5</sup>),
B (1 &#8804; B &#8804; 10<sup>5</sup>) </b>and<b> C (1 &#8804; C &#8804; 1000)</b>
denoting the lowest floor, the number of floors the advertisement covers
(including the lowest floor) and the amount of money earned for placing it,
respectively.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number and the maximum profit
they can achieve.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="52%"
 style='width:52.38%;border-collapse:collapse'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:39.15pt'>
  <td width="46%" valign=top style='width:46.42%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>1</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>3</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>1
  5 1</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>2
  10 3</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing style='line-height:115%'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
  line-height:115%;font-family:"Courier New"'>7 12 1</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width="53%" valign=top style='width:53.58%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:39.15pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  1: 3</span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<div class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:center'><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>

<hr size=2 width="100%" align=center>

</span></div>

<BODY>


<P><img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11909a.jpg"  align=right>

<P><font size=6>O</font>n the dining table we have a packet of soya milk. We can look at the packet as a rectangular box with height <b><i>h</i></b>, length <b><i>l</i></b> and width <b><i>w</i></b>.
   We tilt it against a base edge, as shown in the picture. Soya milk then comes out through the opening in the top face. This process stops when the milk level is no longer higher than the opening.
   

<P><b>Write a program</b> that computes the volume of soya milk remaining in the packet.

<P>Note that the problem description may not perfectly match the real-life situation, but to solve this problem you must follow our assumptions.

<P><img align=right src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11909a.jpg" >

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00001000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Input</FONT></A></H2>
<p>Each input file contains multiple test cases, and each test case starts on a new line.
<p>Each case consists of four positive integers <b><i>l</i></b>, <b><i>w</i></b>, <b><i>h</i></b> (in centimetres) and <b><i>&theta;</i></b>
   (in degrees), all strictly less than 90.

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00001000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Output</FONT></A></H2>

<p>For each test case, output a line containing the volume of soya milk inside the packet in millilitres, correct to 3 decimal places.

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00004000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Sample Input</FONT></A></H2>

<PRE>
9 6 19 20
</PRE>

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00004000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Sample Output</FONT></A></H2>

<PRE>
937.555 mL
</PRE>

<P><HR><ADDRESS><I>Problemsetter: Mak Yan Kei
</ADDRESS>
</BODY>
</HTML>

11910||||||false||||||
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Closest Fractions - Sixth Contest of Newbies</TITLE>
<META content="Closest Fractions" name=description>
<META content=1036 name=keywords>
<META content=document name=resource-type>
<META content=global name=distribution>
<META http-equiv=Content-Type content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
<META content="MSHTML 6.00.2800.1106" name=GENERATOR>

<BODY>


<P><img align=right src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11910a.png" >

<P><font size=6>E</font>very day we consider lots of real constants: <i>e</i>, <i>&pi;</i>, <img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11910a.png" >, to name but a few.
   These numbers may or may not be rational (i.e. representable as a quotient of two integers), but it is always interesting to give close 
   fraction approximations to them with small denominators and numerators. Arguably the most well-known result in history is from Liu Hui and Zu Chongzhi in China millenniums ago.
   The result <i>&pi;</i> &asymp; 355/113 = 3.141592920 is correct to 7 significant figures, and has remained the most accurate approximation available for the next 900 years. 
   
<P>You are asked to <b>write a program</b> that finds for any input value the three closest fractions <i>x</i>/<i>y</i>, with 1 &le; <i>x</i>, <i>y</i> &le; 1000,
  and <i>x</i>, <i>y</i> relatively prime (i.e. they have no positive common factors other than 1, so the fraction is in simplest form).

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00001000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Input</FONT></A></H2>
<p>Each input file contains multiple test cases, and each test case starts on a new line.
<p>Each case contains one number on a line, each with exactly ten digits.

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00001000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Output</FONT></A></H2>

<p>For each input number, list the corresponding approximate fractions, ordered by ascending distance to it, as shown in the sample output. You can assume that no ties will occur using our test data.

<p>You are advised to pay attention to the required output format. In particular, all output real numbers must have <b>exactly ten digits</b>.

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00004000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Sample Input</FONT></A></H2>

<PRE>
3.141592654
66.66666666
333.3333333
</PRE>

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00004000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Sample Output</FONT></A></H2>

<PRE>
Input : 3.141592654
    1 : 3.141592920 =  355 / 113
    2 : 3.141630901 =  732 / 233
    3 : 3.141552511 =  688 / 219
Input : 66.66666666
    1 : 66.66666667 =  200 / 3
    2 : 66.64285714 =  933 / 14
    3 : 66.69230769 =  867 / 13
Input : 333.3333333
    1 : 333.3333333 = 1000 / 3
    2 : 333.5000000 =  667 / 2
    3 : 333.0000000 =  333 / 1
</PRE>

<P><HR><ADDRESS><I>Problemsetter: Mak Yan Kei
</ADDRESS>
</BODY>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________
11911||||||false||||||
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Farther or Closer - Sixth Contest of Newbies</TITLE>
<META content="Farther or Closer" name=description>
<META content=document name=resource-type>
<META content=global name=distribution>
<META http-equiv=Content-Type content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
<META content="MSHTML 6.00.2800.1106" name=GENERATOR>
<META http-equiv=Content-Style-Type content=text/css></HEAD>

<BODY>



<P><font size=6>I</font>n an elementary English class kids are learning the notions of being far or near.
   To reinforce the kids' sense of these abstract concepts, the teacher introduces his newly invented little class activity called <i>Farther or Closer</i>
   (well it's not really a new invention; we all know the traditional indoor game called <i>Hotter Colder</i>):

<P><img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11911a.gif" >

<P>The teacher has prepared some boxes, arranged into a square as shown in Figure 1 above. As you can see, the numbers are in row-major order.
   The game roughly goes as follows: the player is to locate the box with a candy hidden inside, with reference to the hints given by other students.

<P>In each play, one student is chosen to be the <i>guesser</i>, who first turns around when others put a candy into one of the boxes. All the other boxes are empty. Then, the guesser starts making his guesses, one after another. Here a <i>guess</i> is the number written on an available box.
   If a guess is correct, the students all shout "<b>YES!!</b>" loudly and the box is opened. The guesser then gets the candy inside and the game is over.
   If the guess is incorrect, however, the guesser receives one of the following three replies from the other students:
<ul>
  <li><b>FARTHER</b> if the correct box is farther away from this guess than from the previous one;</li>
  <li><b>CLOSER</b> if it is nearer to the current guess; or</li>
  <li><b>SAME</b> if the distances are the same.</li>
</ul>

<P>By <i>distance</i> we mean the Euclidean distance between the centres of the boxes. For example, in Figure 2, the distance between boxes 8 and 9 is one unit, and that between 1 and 8 is <img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11911a.gif" > units. Hence, box 8 is closer to 9 than to 1.

<P>For the very first guess the situation is a little bit different. The only two possible replies are <b>CLOSER</b> (if the chosen box does not contain the candy) or <b>YES!!</b> (if it does).

<P>Under these rules, every player eventually gets a candy as a reward, and therefore there is no question of finding an <i>optimal strategy</i> to <i>win</i> the game. Nevertheless, the kids have come up with a clever guessing procedure, which works quite pleasingly in many cases. The method goes like this:
<ol>
  <li>Firstly, guess box 1.
  <li>If incorrect, try the largest numbered available box that possibly contains the candy.
  <li>If still wrong, guess the smallest numbered box that may contain the candy.
  <li>Repeat steps 2 and 3 until the candy is found.
</ol>

<p>To see how this method works in action, let us consider the case of <b>9</b> boxes, with the candy in box <b>8</b> (see Figure 2 again):

<p><img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11911a.gif" >
<P>In the first run, the player guesses 1, as stated above. The candy is not in box 1, so everyone replies "CLOSER".

<p><img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11911a.gif" >
<P>The player then guess 9, the largest numbered remaining box. Since box 8 is closer to 9 than to 1, the students reply "CLOSER" again. This leaves only two possibly correct boxes: 6 and 8.

<p><img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11911a.gif" >
<P>Now the guesser tries the smallest numbered available box, 6. But alas, the candy is not there. This time the guess is farther away from the correct box than before (<img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11911a.gif" > vs. 1).

<p><img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11911a.gif" >
<P>After three guesses the guesser is sure that the candy is in box 8. The game ends after the box is opened, and now he can finally enjoy his candy!

<P>Now your job is to <b>write a program</b> that imitates the above process.


<P><H2><A name=SECTION00001000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Input</FONT></A></H2>
<p>Each input file contains multiple test cases, and each test case starts on a new line.
<p>Every line of the input contains two integers <b><i>n</i></b> and <b><i>m</i></b> (1 &le; <b><i>m</i></b> &le; <b><i>n</i></b> &le; 100), which denote the number of boxes and the location of the candy respectively. In all cases <b><i>n</i></b> will be a square number.

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00002000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Output</FONT></A></H2>

<p>For each case, give the flow of the corresponding game in the format shown in the sample output below. Note that the numbers should be right aligned to the third column. Consecutive sets of output must be seperated by a blank line.

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00003000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Sample Input</FONT></A></H2>

<PRE>
9 8
9 2
</PRE>

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00004000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Sample Output</FONT></A></H2>

<PRE>
  1? - CLOSER
  9? - CLOSER
  6? - FARTHER
  8? - YES!!

  1? - CLOSER
  9? - FARTHER
  2? - YES!!
</PRE>

<P><HR>
<ADDRESS>Problemsetter: Mak Yan Kei</br>
Some pictures used above are from Wikimedia Commons, and have been released into the public domain by their respective copyright holders</ADDRESS>
</BODY>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________
11912||||||false||||||
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Chutes and Ladders - Sixth Contest of Newbies</TITLE>
<META content="Chutes and Ladders" name=description>
<META content=document name=resource-type>
<META content=global name=distribution>
<META http-equiv=Content-Type content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
<META content="MSHTML 6.00.2800.1106" name=GENERATOR>
<META http-equiv=Content-Style-Type content=text/css></HEAD>

<BODY>



<P><font size=6>A</font>s the title suggests, this problem is about the popular board game called <i>Chutes and Ladders</i>. (For copyright issues it might be inappropriate for us to give a photo of the game board here. Those who really need one may consider using Google.)

<P>In short, the game is played on a 10-by-10 board with squares numbered from 1 to 100. Starting from an "imaginary square 0" outside the board, players take turns using a spinner (or equivalently, a six-faced die) to determine how many squares to move their respective tokens forward.
   The player who first reaches the last square (i.e. 100) wins. If a move takes the player beyond the square 100, this move is ignored and the token is not moved.

<P>On the game board there are 9 ladders and 10 chutes (or slides). If a token lands on the bottom of a ladder after a move, it is immediately moved to the square at the top of the ladder. Similarly if it lands on the top of a chute, it is moved to the bottom. Here is a list of the ladders and chutes:
<ul>
  <li><b>Ladders</b>: (1, 38) (4, 14) (9, 31) (21, 42) (28, 84) (36, 44) (51, 67) (71, 91) (80, 100)</li>
  <li><b>Chutes</b>: (16, 6) (47, 26) (49, 11) (56, 53) (62, 19) (64, 60) (87, 24) (93, 73) (95, 75) (98, 78)</li>
</ul>

<P>The only source of uncertainty of Chutes and Ladders is the results of die rolls (or spinner turns). For an ordinary six-faced fair die, the shortest possible game takes only seven moves, and the average length of a game is around 39 moves.
   If we use a fair coin as a two-faced die instead (let Head = 1, Tail = 2, for instance), then the corresponding lengths are 15 and 61 respectively. For some "bad" dice like a one-sided die (?!), square 100 may simply be unreachable. We say that a case is <i>degenerate</i> if there exists some square reachable from square 0 using the given die, but one can never reach the last square from there.

<P><b>Write a program</b> to analyse the game if different dice are used.


<P><H2><A name=SECTION00001000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Input</FONT></A></H2>
<p>Each input file contains multiple test cases, and each test case starts on a new line.
<p>A line in the input file starts with an integer <b><i>n</i></b> (1 &le; <b><i>n</i></b> &le; 20), the number of faces on the die. This is followed by <b><i>n</i></b> numbers <b><i>p<sub>1</sub></i></b>, ..., <b><i>p<sub>n</sub></i></b>, with <b><i>p<sub>k</sub></i></b> being the probability that a die roll gives a <b><i>k</i></b>.
   Each of these numbers has exactly three decimal places, and of course the probabilities always add up to exactly 1.

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00002000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Output</FONT></A></H2>

<p>For each test case, output the length of the shortest possible game, followed by the average game length (rounded to the nearest integer). For degenerate cases, print the line "<b>Bad die!</b>" instead.

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00003000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Sample Input</FONT></A></H2>

<PRE>
6 0.167 0.167 0.166 0.166 0.167 0.167
2 0.500 0.500
1 1.000
</PRE>

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00004000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Sample Output</FONT></A></H2>

<PRE>
7 39
15 61
Bad die!
</PRE>

<P><HR>
<ADDRESS>Problemsetter: Mak Yan Kei</br>
Reference: S. C. Althoen, L. King and K. Schilling (March 1993). "How long is a game of snakes and ladders?". The Mathematical Gazette, Vol. 77, No. 478, pp. 71-76</ADDRESS>
</BODY>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________
11913||||||false||||||
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Tape Recording - Sixth Contest of Newbies</TITLE>
<META content="Tape Recording" name=description>
<META content=1036 name=keywords>
<META content=document name=resource-type>
<META content=global name=distribution>
<META http-equiv=Content-Type content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
<META content="MSHTML 6.00.2800.1106" name=GENERATOR>

<BODY>


<P><img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11913.png"  align=right>

<P><b>Note:</b> We see that recording TV shows is seen as copyright infringement in many countries. We feel sorry for that, and we believe that VHS tapes will always be part of our invaluable collective memory.

<P><font size=6>J</font>ay is a huge TV lover. He spends all his leisure time in the world of TV programmes; soap operas, game shows, charity shows, news, cartoons, cookery programmes... Jay watches them all.

<P>For many years there were only two TV channels in his town. In order not to miss any shows, Jay has bought two VHS tape recorders, so that he can record all shows on tapes and watch them at any time he wants.
   But now, more and more channels are in service, and Jay cannot afford buying more tape recorders. Thus, he would like to make the best use of the existing two recorders. Sometimes he would have to give up some great shows reluctantly.
   Moreover, he thinks that watching just part of a TV programme is no fun, so if he records a programme, he records the full show.

<P>To all shows in the TV schedule Jay has assigned a fun value in the range [1, 5]. Your job is to <b>write a program</b> to compute the maximum total fun that Jay can get if he uses his recorders optimally.

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00001000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Input</FONT></A></H2>

<P>Input consists of several test cases. Each test begins with a line containing an integer <b><i>n</i></b> (1 &le; <b><i>n</i></b> &le; 100).
   Then <b><i>n</i></b> lines follow, each giving the starting time, ending time, fun value and name of a show. The times will be in the format <b>HH:MM</b>, ranging from 00:00 to 23:59.
   No shows share the same name within a list, and no names have more than 60 characters.

<p>A <i>day</i> of TV broadcasting starts at 6 am. All TV programmes listed in the input are on the same day, and none will encompass 6 am. Also, the duration of any single show will not exceed the length of a tape, and the time taken to press the "Record" button etc. is negligible.
   You can further assume that Jay has a virtually unlimited supply of VHS tapes at home (just like any other TV maniac).

<p>Input ends with a dummy case where <b><i>n</i></b> = 0. Your program should ignore this test case.

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00001000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Output</FONT></A></H2>

<p>For each test case, output the maximum fun that Jay can get. Of course Jay will not record a same show in two tapes.

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00004000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Sample Input</FONT></A></H2>

<PRE>
4
21:15-23:30 5 Shrek
21:30-23:55 5 Howl's Moving Castle
21:45-22:45 4 The Life of Mammals
22:45-23:15 2 Late News
0
</PRE>

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00004000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Sample Output</FONT></A></H2>

<PRE>
Case 1: 11
</PRE>

<P><HR><ADDRESS><I>Problemsetter: Mak Yan Kei</br>
The picture of VHS tape is taken from OpenClipart.org, and has been released into the public domain by its copyright holder
</ADDRESS>
</BODY>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________
11914||||||false||||||
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>An Amazing Race - Sixth Contest of Newbies</TITLE>
<META content="An Amazing Race" name=description>
<META content=1036 name=keywords>
<META content=document name=resource-type>
<META content=global name=distribution>
<META http-equiv=Content-Type content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
<META content="MSHTML 6.00.2800.1106" name=GENERATOR>

<BODY>


<P><img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11914.gif"  align=right>

<P><font size=6>Y</font>ou are participating in an adventure game called <b>An Amazing Race</b>. You are now at the coast of a desert island, and you have to visit a number of checkpoints, then go to the target at the highest point of the island.
   Of course, the first person who arrives at the target wins the race.

<P>The temperature is now 45<sup>o</sup>C. It is a must to drink lots of water in such hot environment. However, you are not allowed to take any drinking water with you in your journey (!!). Water is only supplied at checkpoints as well as the starting and target locations, so you would like to choose your route such that the maximum distance between two consecutively visited water-supplying spots is minimized. Observing this, you would then like to find
   a shortest route. You may <b>write a program</b> to help you.

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00001000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Input</FONT></A></H2>

<p>The input contains several test cases. The first line of each case gives three integers <b><i>r</i></b>, <b><i>c</i></b>, <b><i>k</i></b> (3 &le; <b><i>r</i></b>, <b><i>c</i></b> &le; 20; 1 &le; <b><i>k</i></b> &le; 10). Then there are <b><i>r</i></b> lines, each with <b><i>c</i></b> characters, which is the map of the island. A tilde sign <b>~</b>
   in the map denotes sea area, which cannot be travelled past. A hash sign <b>#</b> denotes normal land area. The island is of course surrounded by sea. <b>S</b> marks the starting location, while <b>T</b> is the target. As mentioned above, the starting location is always on the coast.
   Each checkpoint is denoted by a unique letter from the set <b>{A, ..., K}</b>.
   You must visit at least <b><i>k</i></b> different checkpoints, and then finish your journey at the target location <b>T</b>. You may visit a checkpoint more than once, and the visiting order is also unimportant.

<p>In each step, you may travel from a land area to another only if they share a common edge, i.e. you may only go north, south, east or west (by 'north' we mean facing upwards). The island is rather flat, hence the time required to travel to an adjacent square is the same everywhere on the island (no need to consider the gradient). 
   You can further assume that all checkpoints are safely reachable, so it is indeed possible for you to win the race, provided that your route is planned optimally observing the above-mentioned requirements.

<p>The sample input corresponds to the figure on the right.

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00001000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Output</FONT></A></H2>

<p>For each case, your program should output a single line with the description of an optimal path. Use the letters <b>N</b>, <b>S</b>, <b>E</b> and <b>W</b> to denote north, south, east and west respectively. If there are many solutions, output the lexicographically smallest one.

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00004000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Sample Input</FONT></A></H2>

<PRE>
15 15 2
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
~~###~~~~~#~~~~
~##T###~#####~~
~~############~
~~###########~~
~~###########~~
~##B########~~~
~#########A##~~
~~###########~~
~~##########~~~
~##########~~~~
~~###~S#####~~~
~~~##~~####~~~~
~~~~~~~~##~~~~~
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
</PRE>

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00004000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Sample Output</FONT></A></H2>

<PRE>
EEEENNNNNWWWWWWWNNNN
</PRE>

<P><H2><A name=SECTION00004000000000000000><FONT color=#6666aa>Explanation</FONT></A></H2>

The optimal path is shown in <font color=red>red</font> below:
<PRE>
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
~~###~~~~~#~~~~
~##<font color=red>T</font>###~#####~~
~~#<font color=red>#</font>##########~
~~#<font color=red>#</font>#########~~
~~#<font color=red>#</font>#########~~
~##<font color=red>B#######</font>#~~~
~#########<font color=red>A</font>##~~
~~########<font color=red>#</font>##~~
~~########<font color=red>#</font>#~~~
~#########<font color=red>#</font>~~~~
~~###~<font color=red>S####</font>#~~~
~~~##~~####~~~~
~~~~~~~~##~~~~~
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
</PRE>

<P><HR><ADDRESS><I>Problemsetter: Mak Yan Kei
</ADDRESS>
</BODY>
</HTML>

11915||||||false||||||

<!--Converted with LaTeX2HTML 2008 (1.71)
original version by:  Nikos Drakos, CBLU, University of Leeds
* revised and updated by:  Marcus Hennecke, Ross Moore, Herb Swan
* with significant contributions from:
  Jens Lippmann, Marek Rouchal, Martin Wilck and others -->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Recurrence</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Recurrence">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Recurrence</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Consider a tuple <!-- MATH
 $P_1, P_2, P_3, \dots, P_n$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>P</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>3</SUB>,..., <I>P</I><SUB>n</SUB></SPAN>. Now consider the following recurrence function.

<P>

<UL>
<LI><!-- MATH
 $F(P_1, P_2, P_3, \dots, P_n) = 0$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>F</I>(<I>P</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>3</SUB>,..., <I>P</I><SUB>n</SUB>) = 0</SPAN> if any of the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>P</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> is negative or the tuple <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>P</I></SPAN> is not sorted in non-increasing order. 
</LI>
<LI><!-- MATH
 $F(P_1, P_2, P_3, \dots, P_n) = 1$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>F</I>(<I>P</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>3</SUB>,..., <I>P</I><SUB>n</SUB>) = 1</SPAN> if all of the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>P</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN>s is zero. 
</LI>
<LI><!-- MATH
 $F(P_1, P_2, P_3, \dots, P_n) = F(P_1-1, P_2, P_3, \dots, P_n) + F(P_1, P_2-1, P_3, \dots, P_n) + F(P_1, P_2, P_3-1, \dots, P_n) +
F(P_1, P_2, P_3, \dots, P_n-1)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>F</I>(<I>P</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>3</SUB>,..., <I>P</I><SUB>n</SUB>) = <I>F</I>(<I>P</I><SUB>1</SUB> -1, <I>P</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>3</SUB>,..., <I>P</I><SUB>n</SUB>) + <I>F</I>(<I>P</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>2</SUB> -1, <I>P</I><SUB>3</SUB>,..., <I>P</I><SUB>n</SUB>) + <I>F</I>(<I>P</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>3</SUB> -1,..., <I>P</I><SUB>n</SUB>) + <I>F</I>(<I>P</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>3</SUB>,..., <I>P</I><SUB>n</SUB> - 1)</SPAN> otherwise.
</LI>
</UL>

<P>
For example if <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> is 4 then the value 
<BR><!-- MATH
 $F(4,3,2,-1)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>F</I>(4, 3, 2, - 1)</SPAN> is 0 because the last parameter is negative. 
<BR><!-- MATH
 $F(4,3,2,5)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>F</I>(4, 3, 2, 5)</SPAN> is 0 because the tuple is not sorted from the largest to smallest. 
<BR><!-- MATH
 $F(3,3,2,1) = F(3,3,2,1) + F(4,2,2,1) + F(4,3,1,1) + F(4,3,2,0)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>F</I>(3, 3, 2, 1) = <I>F</I>(3, 3, 2, 1) + <I>F</I>(4, 2, 2, 1) + <I>F</I>(4, 3, 1, 1) + <I>F</I>(4, 3, 2, 0)</SPAN> 
<BR><!-- MATH
 $F(1, 1, 0, 0) = F(0,1,0,0)+F(1,0,0,0)+F(1,1,-1,0)+F(1,1,0,-1) = 2$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>F</I>(1, 1, 0, 0) = <I>F</I>(0, 1, 0, 0) + <I>F</I>(1, 0, 0, 0) + <I>F</I>(1, 1, - 1, 0) + <I>F</I>(1, 1, 0, - 1) = 2</SPAN> 
<BR>
Given the tuple <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>P</I></SPAN> your task is to calculate the value of <!-- MATH
 $F(P_1, P_2, P_3, \dots, P_n)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>F</I>(<I>P</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>3</SUB>,..., <I>P</I><SUB>n</SUB>)</SPAN>. The result can be very big so 
output the result <!-- MATH
 $\bmod 1,000,000,009$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">mod 1, 000, 000, 009</SPAN> (this is a prime number).

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
Input starts with an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11915img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">50</SPAN>), denoting the number of test cases.

<P>
Each test case consists of two lines. First line contains <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN>. Second line contains <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> integers separated by a single space. 
These are the tuple <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>P</I></SPAN>. <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I></SPAN> is between 1 and 1000 inclusive. Each of the numbers in tuple <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>P</I></SPAN> is between 1 and 1000 inclusive. 
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>P</I></SPAN> will be sorted in non-increasing order.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each test case output contains a line in the format `<TT>Case <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN>: <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I></SPAN></TT>' where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN> is the case number (starting from 1) 
and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I></SPAN> is the value of <!-- MATH
 $F(P_1, P_2, P_3, \dots, P_n) \bmod 1,000,000,009$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>F</I>(<I>P</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>P</I><SUB>3</SUB>,..., <I>P</I><SUB>n</SUB>) mod 1, 000, 000, 009</SPAN>.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
8
3
7 5 4
6
7 7 5 3 2 1
2
4 2
3
7 4 4
4
8 7 5 5
5
7 7 6 5 5
2
8 7
3
6 3 1
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Case 1: 100100
Case 2: 398009117
Case 3: 9
Case 4: 25025
Case 5: 923714728
Case 6: 311516464
Case 7: 1430
Case 8: 315
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

11916||||||false||||||

<!--Converted with LaTeX2HTML 2008 (1.71)
original version by:  Nikos Drakos, CBLU, University of Leeds

  Jens Lippmann, Marek Rouchal, Martin Wilck and others -->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Emoogle Grid</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Emoogle Grid">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Emoogle Grid</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
You have to color an <!-- MATH
 $M \times N$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I> <TT>x</TT> <I>N</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le M,N \le 10^8$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11916img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>M</I>, <I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11916img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<SUP>8</SUP></SPAN>) two dimensional grid. You will be provided 
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>K</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $2 \le K \le 10^8$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">2<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11916img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>K</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11916img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10<SUP>8</SUP></SPAN>) different colors to do so. You will also be provided a list of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>B</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $0 \le B \le 500$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11916img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>B</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11916img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">500</SPAN>)
list of blocked cells of this grid. You cannot color those blocked cells. A cell can be described as <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>x</I>, <I>y</I>)</SPAN>, which points to 
the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I></SPAN>-th cell from the left of the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN>-th row from the top. 

<P>
While coloring the grid, you have to follow these rules -

<P>

<OL>
<LI>You have to color each cell which is not blocked. 
</LI>
<LI>You cannot color a blocked cell. 
</LI>
<LI>You can choose exactly one color from <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>K</I></SPAN> given colors to color a cell. 
</LI>
<LI>No two vertically adjacent cells can have the same color, i.e. cell <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>x</I>, <I>y</I>)</SPAN> and cell <!-- MATH
 $(x + 1, y)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>x</I> + 1, <I>y</I>)</SPAN> 
cannot contain the same color.
</LI>
</OL>

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11916.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="376" HEIGHT="353" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11916img1.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11916.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
Now the great problem setter smiled with emotion and thought that he would ask the contestants to find how many ways the board can 
be colored. Since the number can be very large and he doesn't 
want the contestants to be in trouble dealing with big integers; he decided to ask them to find the result modulo 100,000,007. 
So he prepared the judge data for the problem using a random generator and saved this problem for a future contest as a giveaway 
(easiest) problem. 

<P>
But unfortunately he got married and forgot the problem completely. After some days he rediscovered his problem 
and became very excited. But after a while, he saw that, in the judge data, he forgot to add 
the integer which supposed to be the `number of rows'. He didn't find the input generator and his codes, but luckily he has the input 
file and the correct answer file. So, he asks your help to regenerate the data. Yes, you are given the input file which contains all 
the information except the `number of rows' and the answer file; you have to find the number of rows he might have used for this problem.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
Input starts with an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11916img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">150</SPAN>), denoting the number of test cases. 

<P>
Each test case starts with a line containing four 
integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>K</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>B</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $0 \le R < 100000007$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11916img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>R</I> &lt; 100000007</SPAN>) which denotes the result for this case. Each of the next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>B</I></SPAN> lines will 
contains two integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le x \le M$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11916img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>x</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11916img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>M</I></SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $1 \le y \le N$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11916img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>y</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11916img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I></SPAN>), denoting 
the row and column number of a blocked cell. All the cells will be distinct.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each case, print the case number and the minimum possible value of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN>. You can assume that solution exists for each case.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
4
3 3 0 1728
4 4 2 186624
3 1
3 3
2 5 2 20
1 2
2 2
2 3 0 989323
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Case 1: 3
Case 2: 3
Case 3: 2
Case 4: 20
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

11917||||||false||||||

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Do Your Own Homework!</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Do Your Own Homework!">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Do Your Own Homework!</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
These days Soha is so busy that he doesn't have time to do his own homework. 
But this is not a big problem since he has got many friends who are willing to help. 
One if his friend's name is Sparrow.
Whenever Soha is assigned any homework, he turns to Sparrow for her help.

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11917.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="498" HEIGHT="338" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11917.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11917.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
Sparrow has given a list of subjects that she is comfortable with along with the number of days it will take her to complete an assignment 
for each subject. Soha has got only <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>D</I></SPAN> days to complete his next assignment. However, the professor of this subject is a little flexible 
and allows late submissions up to 5 days. That means he will not accept any submission that is after <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>D</I> + 5</SPAN> days from now. 
Will Sparrow be able to do it for Soha this time?

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
First line of input is a positive integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $T \ le 100$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I>&nbsp;<I>le</I>100</SPAN>) that determines the number of test cases. 
Each case starts with a line containing an 
integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> that represents the number of subjects Sparrow is comfortable with. Each of the next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines contain the name of a subject 
followed by the number of days it will take Sparrow to complete an assignment of that subject. All these subject names will be distinct. 
The next line contains an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>D</I></SPAN>. The meaning of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>D</I></SPAN> is described above. The following line contains the name of the subject 
whose homework is due. All the subjects' names consist of lowercase letters and the length of each is at least 1 
and at most 20. All the integer inputs are positive in the range [1,100].

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each case, first output the case number first starting from 1. If Sparrow doesn't take more than <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>D</I></SPAN> days to completely
the assignment, output `<TT>Yesss</TT>'; if she takes more than <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>D</I></SPAN> days but not more than <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>D</I> + 5</SPAN>, output `<TT>Late</TT>'; if she takes 
more than <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>D</I> + 5</SPAN> days or if she isn't comfortable with the subject, output `<TT>Do your own homework!</TT>'.
Quotes are for clarify only and don't need to be part of the output. Look at the samples for more details. Be careful about the spelling.  

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3
3
compiler 4
cplusplus 1
java 8
5
compiler
2
algorithm 3
math 9
4
math
2
java 8
ai 3
6
calculus
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Case 1: Yesss
Case 2: Late
Case 3: Do your own homework!
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________
11918||||||false||||||

<!--Converted with LaTeX2HTML 2008 (1.71)
original version by:  Nikos Drakos, CBLU, University of Leeds
* revised and updated by:  Marcus Hennecke, Ross Moore, Herb Swan
* with significant contributions from:
  Jens Lippmann, Marek Rouchal, Martin Wilck and others -->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Traveler of Gridland</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Traveler of Gridland">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Traveler of Gridland</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Girdland is a square shaped country of size <!-- MATH
 $2000000000 \times 2000000000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">2000000000 <TT>x</TT> 2000000000</SPAN> units. We will identify any point in this land using 
Cartesian coordinate system. Using this system the coordinate of the center of Gridland is (0, 0), the coordinate of the lower-left 
corner is (-1000000000, -1000000000) and upper-right corner is (1000000000, 1000000000). So the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN>-axis is a horizontal line which 
divides the land into two equal rectangles and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I></SPAN>-axis is a vertical line which divides the land into two equal rectangles. 
There are roads in the country which goes through the grid lines only i.e. along 
<!-- MATH
 $x = -1000000000, -999999999, \dots, -1, 0, 1, \dots, 999999999, 1000000000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I> = - 1000000000, -999999999,..., -1, 0, 1,..., 999999999, 1000000000</SPAN> and 
<!-- MATH
 $y = -1000000000, -999999999, \dots, -1, 0, 1, \dots, 999999999, 1000000000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I> = - 1000000000, -999999999,..., -1, 0, 1,..., 999999999, 1000000000</SPAN>
So all roads are either a horizontal line or a vertical line having integer distance from axis.

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11918.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="433" HEIGHT="287" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11918.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11918.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
Travelers like this Gridland because of the simplicity of its road network. Each of the roads is so straight and axis parallel.

<P>
From any position <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>a</I>, <I>b</I>)</SPAN>, in unit time any traveler can move to 

<P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT>i.</DT>
<DD><!-- MATH
 $(a + 1, b)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>a</I> + 1, <I>b</I>)</SPAN> 
</DD>
<DT>ii.</DT>
<DD><!-- MATH
 $(a - 1, b)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>a</I> - 1, <I>b</I>)</SPAN> 
</DD>
<DT>iii.</DT>
<DD><!-- MATH
 $(a, b + 1)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>a</I>, <I>b</I> + 1)</SPAN> 
</DD>
<DT>iv.</DT>
<DD><!-- MATH
 $(a, b - 1)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>a</I>, <I>b</I> - 1)</SPAN>
</DD>
</DL>

<P>
A traveler cannot move outside the Gridland. She also cannot move to any position which is occupied by a monster. There may be some 
monsters in Gridland. There are three types of monsters 

<P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT>i.</DT>
<DD>Point monster 
</DD>
<DT>ii.</DT>
<DD>Line monster 
</DD>
<DT>iii.</DT>
<DD>Rectangle monster
</DD>
</DL>

<P>
A point monster can occupy only a single point, a line monster can occupy a straight line, and a rectangle monster can occupy a 
rectangular region. 

<P>
The position of the point monster can be specified by a pair of integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>u</I>, <I>v</I>)</SPAN>, which indicates that the 
monster occupies the coordinate position <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>u</I>, <I>v</I>)</SPAN>. 

<P>
The position of a line monster can be specified by two pair of integers <!-- MATH
 $(u_1, v_1)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>u</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>v</I><SUB>1</SUB>)</SPAN> 
and <!-- MATH
 $(u_2, v_2)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>u</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>v</I><SUB>2</SUB>)</SPAN>. <!-- MATH
 $(u_1, v_1)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>u</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>v</I><SUB>1</SUB>)</SPAN> is the one end of the line monster and <!-- MATH
 $(u_2, v_2)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>u</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>v</I><SUB>2</SUB>)</SPAN> is the other end of the monster. 
It is guaranteed that this line will always be axis parallel. The monster occupies the whole line region inclusively. 

<P>
The position of rectangle monster can be 
specified by two pairs of integers <!-- MATH
 $(u_1, v_1)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>u</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>v</I><SUB>1</SUB>)</SPAN> and <!-- MATH
 $(u_2, v_2)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>u</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>v</I><SUB>2</SUB>)</SPAN>. <!-- MATH
 $(u_1, v_1)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>u</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>v</I><SUB>1</SUB>)</SPAN> is the coordinate of the lower left 
corner of monster and <!-- MATH
 $(u_2, v_2)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>u</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>v</I><SUB>2</SUB>)</SPAN> 
is the upper right corner of the monster. It is guaranteed that the edges of monster will always be axis parallel. 
The monster occupies the whole rectangular region inclusively. 

<P>
Initially a traveler is in a position of coordinate <!-- MATH
 $(sourceX, sourceY)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>sourceX</I>, <I>sourceY</I>)</SPAN> 
in Gridland. She needs to reach the position of coordinate <!-- MATH
 $(destinationX, destinationY)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>destinationX</I>, <I>destinationY</I>)</SPAN>. You have to calculate the minimum unit time 
required for her to reach the destination. If it is not possible to reach the destination, you have to output `<TT>Impossible</TT>' 
(quotes for clarity).

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
Input starts with an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11918.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100</SPAN>), denoting the number of test cases. 

<P>
Each test case starts with four integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>sourceX</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>sourceY</I></SPAN>, 
<!-- MATH
 $destinationX$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>destinationX</I></SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $destinationY$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>destinationY</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $-1000000000 \le sourceX, sourceY, destinationX, destinationY \le 1000000000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">-1000000000<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11918.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>sourceX</I>, <I>sourceY</I>, <I>destinationX</I>, <I>destinationY</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11918.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1000000000</SPAN>). Next line contains three 
integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Q</I></SPAN>, the number of point monsters, the number of line monsters and the number of rectangle monsters. Total number 
of monsters can be at most 100, i.e. (<!-- MATH
 $0 \le M + N + Q \le 100$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11918.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>M</I> + <I>N</I> + <I>Q</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11918.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100</SPAN>). Each of the next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN> lines describe a point monster by two integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>u</I></SPAN> 
and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $-1000000000 \le u, v \le 1000000000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">-1000000000<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11918.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>u</I>, <I>v</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11918.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1000000000</SPAN>). Each of the next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines will describes a line monster by four integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>u</I><SUB>1</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I><SUB>1</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>u</I><SUB>2</SUB></SPAN> 
and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I><SUB>2</SUB></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $-1000000000 \le u_1, v_1, u_2, v_2 \le 1000000000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">-1000000000<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11918.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>u</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>v</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>u</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>v</I><SUB>2</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11918.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1000000000</SPAN>). Each of the next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Q</I></SPAN> lines will describes a rectangle monster by 
four integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>u</I><SUB>1</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I><SUB>1</SUB></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>u</I><SUB>2</SUB></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>v</I><SUB>2</SUB></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $-1000000000 \le u_1, v_1, u_2, v_2 \le 1000000000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">-1000000000<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11918.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>u</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>v</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>u</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>v</I><SUB>2</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11918.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1000000000</SPAN>). 
Note that one monster can overlap with another. 
You can safely assume that source and destination is not occupied by any monster.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each test case, output a single line in the format <TT>Case <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN>: <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN></TT>, where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>C</I></SPAN> will be replaced by the case 
number and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> will be replaced by the 
shortest path distance from source to destination. If it is not possible to reach source to destination replace `<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN>' 
by `<TT>Impossible</TT>' without quotes.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
1
1 2 4 3
1 1 1
4 6
4 1 7 1
2 1 3 5
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Case 1: 14
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________
11919||||||false||||||

<!--Converted with LaTeX2HTML 2008 (1.71)
original version by:  Nikos Drakos, CBLU, University of Leeds

  Jens Lippmann, Marek Rouchal, Martin Wilck and others -->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Hybrid Salientia</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Hybrid Salientia">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Hybrid Salientia</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
It's believed that frogs jump due to lack of natural physical defense against predators. However, there 
are some types of frogs that do not leap. In this problem, we will consider a hybrid version of a frog that can both leap and walk. 

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11919a.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="323" HEIGHT="247" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11919a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11919a.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
Consider a magical creek with <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> stones. The shape of each stone is either a circle or a square. Our frog is currently standing on 
stone 1 and it is going to make <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>N</I> - 1)</SPAN> leaps so that it can land on every stone. It is believed that after making <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I> - 1</SPAN> jumps, 
the frog will grow wings and fly away. After every jump, it loses 10% ot its `leaping energy'. That
means in the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>K</I></SPAN>-th leap it can jump to a maximum distance of <!-- MATH
 $L*0.9^{k-1}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>L</I>*0.9<SUP>k-1</SUP></SPAN>, where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>L</I></SPAN> is the initial <SPAN  CLASS="textit">maximum 
jump distance</SPAN>. The frog, however, can walk from any point to any other point within a stone without loss of any energy. 

<P>
In this problem, you have to find the minimum value of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>L</I></SPAN> that will enable the frog to visit all the stones starting from stone 1. 
Obviously, the visiting order of the stones will be such that the value of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>L</I></SPAN> is minimized. When calculating the distances, 
assume the frog is a point and the stones are circles and squares on a 2D Cartesian coordinate.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
The first line of input is an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11919a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">200</SPAN>) that indicates the number of test cases. Each case starts with a line containing an 
integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $2 \le N \le 15$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">2<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11919a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11919a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">15</SPAN>) that represents the number of stones. The next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines contain the descriptions of the stones starting from stone 1. 
Each stone will be given in the format `<!-- MATH
 $type \ X \ Y \ R$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>type</I>&nbsp;<I>X</I>&nbsp;<I>Y</I>&nbsp;<I>R</I></SPAN>'. <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>type</I></SPAN> can be `<TT>C</TT>' or `<TT>S</TT>' and represents circle and square respectively. If <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>type</I></SPAN> is equal to `<TT>C</TT>', 
then <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>X</I>, <I>Y</I>)</SPAN> will give you the center of the circle and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I></SPAN> will give you the radius. If type is `<TT>S</TT>', then <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>X</I>, <I>Y</I>)</SPAN> will give you the 
lower left corner of the square and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>R</I></SPAN> will give the length of the sides. The sides of the squares are axis parallel. <!-- MATH
 $0 \le X,Y \le 1000000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11919a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>X</I>, <I>Y</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11919a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1000000</SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $0 < R \le 1000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 &lt; <I>R</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11919a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1000</SPAN> and 
stones will be non-overlapping.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
For each case, output the minimum value of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>L</I></SPAN>. Errors less than <SPAN CLASS="MATH">10<SUP>-6</SUP></SPAN> will be ignored.

<P>

<P><P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Note:</SPAN> 
For the second sample we have the picture below. Initial value of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>L</I></SPAN> is 5.555556. First, the frog makes a leap to stone 3. 
It loses 10% of energy and that means the next leap distance can be at most 5.555556 * 0.9 = 5.000000. Since the shortest 
distance between stone 3 and stone 2 is 5.000000, the next leap will enable the frog to land safely on stone 2.

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11919b.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="551" HEIGHT="304" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11919a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11919b.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
2
2
C 0 0 5
C 10 0 2
3
C 0 0 2
S 10 1 4
S 3 1 2
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3.000000
5.555556
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<!--Converted with LaTeX2HTML 2008 (1.71)

  Jens Lippmann, Marek Rouchal, Martin Wilck and others -->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>0 s, 1 s and ? Marks</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="0 s, 1 s and ? Marks">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
0 s, 1 s and ? Marks</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Given a string consisting of <TT>0</TT>, <TT>1</TT> and <TT>?</TT> only, change all the <TT>?</TT> to <TT>0</TT>/<TT>1</TT>, so that the size of the largest group is minimized. 
A group is a substring that contains either all zeros or all ones. 

<P>
Consider the following example: 

<P>
<PRE>
0 1 1 ? 0 1 0 ? ? ?
</PRE>

<P>
We can replace the question marks (<TT>?</TT>) to get 

<P>
<PRE>
0 1 1 0 0 1 0 1 0 0
</PRE>

<P>
The groups are (<TT>0</TT>) (<TT>1 1</TT>) (<TT>0 0</TT>) (<TT>1</TT>) (<TT>0</TT>) (<TT>1</TT>) (<TT>0 0</TT>) and the corresponding 
sizes are 1, 2, 2, 1, 1, 1, 2. That means the above replacement would give us a maximum group size of 2. In fact, of all the <SPAN CLASS="MATH">2<SUP>4</SUP></SPAN> possible replacements, we won't get any maximum group size that is smaller than 2.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
The first line of input is an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $T \le 5000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11920img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">5000</SPAN>) that indicates the number of test cases. Each case is a line consisting of a string that contains <TT>0</TT>, <TT>1</TT> and <TT>?</TT> only. The length of the string will be in the range [1,1000].

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each case, output the case number first followed by the size of the minimized largest group.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
4
011?010???
???
000111
00000000000000
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Case 1: 2
Case 2: 1
Case 3: 3
Case 4: 14
</PRE>

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>
