11937||||||false||||||

<!--Converted with LaTeX2HTML 2008 (1.71)
original version by:  Nikos Drakos, CBLU, University of Leeds
* revised and updated by:  Marcus Hennecke, Ross Moore, Herb Swan
* with significant contributions from:
  Jens Lippmann, Marek Rouchal, Martin Wilck and others -->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Balanced ScoreCard</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Balanced ScoreCard">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
B: Balanced ScoreCard</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
The Balanced ScoreCard (BSC), first introduced by Robert Kaplan and David Norton, is a strategic planning and management system 
that is used extensively in organizations worldwide (industry, business, government and nonprofit) primarily to monitor individual 
and organizational performance against strategic goals. The BSC provides a tree-shaped hierarchical view of the status of every objective 
required to fulfill a specific organization goal. The root of the tree denotes the organization goal itself whereas the leaves 
refer to the most specific objectives (performance of an employee, sales of a specific product); inner nodes denote objectives 
per organizational area (business unit, department, product line, customers from a specific region). 

<P>
The performance of a given 
organization goal is in terms of what was expected to be done and what was actually done. This relationship is known as the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">result</SPAN> 
of and has to be calculated from the bottom-up. Every objective in the lowest level of the tree has a predefined expected value 
and a post-defined actual value. The percentile relationship between the actual and expected values gives the result of the objective. 
The result of inner objectives (including the root) is calculated according to a rule given to every objective. Typical rules include 
the following: 1) the result of an objective is the weighted average of the results of the children objectives, 2) the result of an 
objective is the worst result of the children objectives. To implement the first rule, objectives have to be accompanied with a 
<SPAN  CLASS="textit">weight</SPAN> value given as a percentage. To illustrate better this, consider the following example: 

<P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT></DT>
<DD>General rule = 2 

<OL>
<LI>Weight = 50%, rule = 1
<DL COMPACT>
<DT>1.1</DT>
<DD>Weight = 60%, value = 95.0
</DD>
<DT>1.2</DT>
<DD>Weight = 30%, value = 85.0
</DD>
<DT>1.3</DT>
<DD>Weight = 10%, value = 63.0
</DD>
</DL>
</LI>
<LI>2. Weight = 50%, rule = 2
<DL COMPACT>
<DT>1.1</DT>
<DD>Weight = 50%, value = 72.0
</DD>
<DT>1.2</DT>
<DD>Weight = 50%, value = 92.0 
</DD>
</DL>
</LI>
</OL>
</DD>
</DL>

<P>
The result of the organization goal is then calculated as follows: 
<BR>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER" CLASS="mathdisplay">
<!-- MATH
 \begin{eqnarray*}
Result & = & \min \{ ((95.0 \times 0.60) + (85.0 \times 0.30) + (63.0 \times 0.10), \min \{ 72.0, 92.0 \} \} \\
& = & \min \{ 88.8, 72.0 \} = 72.0
\end{eqnarray*}
 -->
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" ALIGN="CENTER" WIDTH="100%">
<TR VALIGN="MIDDLE"><TD NOWRAP WIDTH="50%" ALIGN="RIGHT"><I>Result</I></TD>
<TD WIDTH="10" ALIGN="CENTER" NOWRAP>=</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" NOWRAP WIDTH="50%">min{((95.0 <TT>x</TT> 0.60) + (85.0 <TT>x</TT> 0.30) + (63.0 <TT>x</TT> 0.10), min{72.0, 92.0}}</TD>
<TD CLASS="eqno" WIDTH=10 ALIGN="RIGHT">
&nbsp;</TD></TR>
<TR VALIGN="MIDDLE"><TD NOWRAP WIDTH="50%" ALIGN="RIGHT">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="10" ALIGN="CENTER" NOWRAP>=</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" NOWRAP WIDTH="50%">min{88.8, 72.0} = 72.0</TD>
<TD CLASS="eqno" WIDTH=10 ALIGN="RIGHT">
&nbsp;</TD></TR>
</TABLE></DIV>
<BR CLEAR="ALL">

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Notice that <SPAN  CLASS="textit">weight</SPAN> values are ignored when parent's rule is 2. 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
The problem consists in figuring out the result of an organization goal, 
given a BSC containing: 

<P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT>1)</DT>
<DD>The weight and the result, for every lowest-level objective
</DD>
<DT>2)</DT>
<DD>The weight, the rule and the children objectives, for every inner objective. 
</DD>
</DL>

<P>
And assuming the BSC is well-formed (no syntactic 
errors are expected). 

<P>
Nevertheless, the BSC may be unbalanced: the sum of the weight of a given group of sibling objectives is not 
equals to <!-- MATH
 $100.0\% \pm 0.01$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">100.0%<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11937img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \pm$">0.01</SPAN>, no matter the parent's rule. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
The first line contains an integer number, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I> &gt; 0</SPAN>, denoting the 
number of test cases. 

<P>
The next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines contain each the definition of an organization goal, having the following 
syntax: 

<P>
<PRE><TT>
<!-- MATH
 $<rule><blank><objective>\{<blank><objective>\}^*$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; <I>rule</I> &gt; &lt; <I>blank</I> &gt; &lt; <I>objective</I> &gt; { &lt; <I>blank</I> &gt; &lt; <I>objective</I> &gt; }<SUP>*</SUP></SPAN>, where: 
<BR><SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; <I>rule</I> &gt;</SPAN> is either 1 or 2, and follows the definition explained above. 
<BR><SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; <I>blank</I> &gt;</SPAN> is a blank space  
<BR><!-- MATH
 $<objective>$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; <I>objective</I> &gt;</SPAN> can be either <!-- MATH
 $<leaf-objective>$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; <I>leaf</I> - <I>objective</I> &gt;</SPAN> or <!-- MATH
 $<inner-objective>$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; <I>inner</I> - <I>objective</I> &gt;</SPAN> 
<BR><!-- MATH
 $\{\omega\}^*$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">{<IMG
 WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11937img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \omega$">}<SUP>*</SUP></SPAN> denotes 0 or more occurrences of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><IMG
 WIDTH="16" HEIGHT="18" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11937img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \omega$"></SPAN> 
<BR><!-- MATH
 $<leaf-objective>$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; <I>leaf</I> - <I>objective</I> &gt;</SPAN> is written as: <!-- MATH
 $<\texttt{(}><weight><;><value><\texttt{)}>$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; ( &gt; &lt; <I>weight</I> &gt; &lt; ; &gt; &lt; <I>value</I> &gt; &lt; ) &gt;</SPAN> 
<BR><SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; <I>weight</I> &gt;</SPAN> is a number greater than 0.0 but not greater than 100.0  
<BR><SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; <I>value</I> &gt;</SPAN> is a number between 0.0 and 100.0  
<BR><!-- MATH
 $<\texttt{(}>$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; ( &gt;</SPAN> is the symbol <TT>(</TT>  
<BR><!-- MATH
 $<\texttt{)}>$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; ) &gt;</SPAN> is the symbol <TT>)</TT>  
<BR><!-- MATH
 $<\texttt{;}>$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; ; &gt;</SPAN> is the symbol <TT>;</TT>  
<BR><!-- MATH
 $<inner-objective>$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; <I>inner</I> - <I>objective</I> &gt;</SPAN> is written as:  
<BR><!-- MATH
 $<\texttt{(}><weight><\texttt{;}><rule><\texttt{;}><\texttt{\{}><objective>\texttt{\{}<\texttt{,}><objective>\texttt{\}}^*<\texttt{\}}><\texttt{)}>$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; ( &gt; &lt; <I>weight</I> &gt; &lt; ; &gt; &lt; <I>rule</I> &gt; &lt; ; &gt; &lt; { &gt; &lt; <I>objective</I> &gt; { &lt; , &gt; &lt; <I>objective</I> &gt; }<SUP>*</SUP> &lt; } &gt; &lt; ) &gt;</SPAN> 
<BR><!-- MATH
 $<\texttt{\{}>$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; { &gt;</SPAN> is the symbol <TT>{</TT>  
<BR><!-- MATH
 $<\texttt{\}}>$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">&lt; } &gt;</SPAN> is the symbol <TT>}</TT>   
<BR>
</TT></PRE>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
The output consists of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines, where every line <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>k</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11937img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I></SPAN> contains a number in the range [0.0 ...100.0] which denotes the result 
of organization goal <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>k</I></SPAN>. Keep only the two most significant decimals. If the BSC <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>k</I></SPAN> is not balanced, line <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>k</I></SPAN> contains the 
word `<TT>Unbalanced</TT>' instead. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
3
1 (35;95) (65;78)
1 (72;83) (28;1;{(60;100),(30;97),(15;85)})
2 (50;1;{(60;95),(30;85),(10;63)}) (50;2;{(50;72),(50;92)})
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
83.95
Unbalanced
72.00
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Granny Pie Factory</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Granny Pie Factory">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
C: Granny Pie Factory</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Granny has always loved to bake pies. She has a very special recipe to prepare an apple pie. His grandson, Simon, has decided 
to turn Granny's hobbie into a family business. To do so, Simon has to combine two ingredients: fruit and dough. He buys these 
two ingredients and combines them to prepare apple pies through the appropriate process: cooking, packaging, delivering, etc.). 
He sells the pies to local grocery stores. As a good businessman, Simon wants to have the highest profit so he prepared a financial 
model for Granny Pie Factory where he defines input and output variables. Since the main idea is to get immediate profits, the only 
decision variable is the selling price for each pie. 

<P>
As we all know, the equation to obtain the profit is as follows: <!-- MATH
 $Profit = Income - Costs$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Profit</I> = <I>Income</I> - <I>Costs</I></SPAN> 

<P>
In order to get the cost right, Simon has to determine the process costs which he 
has assumed is a constant multiplied by the number of pies processed (Simon assumed that <!-- MATH
 $Processing \ Cost = 2.05 * Number \ of \ pies$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Processing</I>&nbsp;<I>Cost</I> = 2.05*<I>Number</I>&nbsp;<I>of</I>&nbsp;<I>pies</I></SPAN>). 
After several months of collecting data, Simon has realized that his assumption is false and needs to find a way to accurately predict 
processing costs. 

<P>
The next figure shows the data that Simon has collected

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11938.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="647" HEIGHT="580" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11938.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11938.eps}">
</DIV>
<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">Figure 1: Granny Pie Factory Processing Cost Data 

</DIV>

<P>
In short, the idea is to find the relationship between the number of pies processed 
and the processing cost.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
The input consists in datasets describing the number of pies processed (in thousands), the real processing cost and the assumed 
processing cost. The dataset is formatted as follows. 

<P>
First an integer denoting the number of pies processed followed by two reals 
denoting (in that order) the real processing cost and the assumed processed cost. Each number is separated by an space and there 
could be <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines of numbers in a dataset. 

<P>
A line consisting in `<TT>0 0 0</TT>' denotes the end of the dataset. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
For each dataset you 
will need to find the relationship between the number of pies processed and the real processing cost. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
8 12.80 16.40
10 17.50 20.50
12 21.60 24.60
14 25.90 28.70
16 32.80 32.80
18 39.60 36.90
20 46.00 41.00
22 56.10 45.10
24 63.60 49.20
0 0 0
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Linear coefficient: 0.9331
Quadratic coefficient: 0.0712

Equation: y = 0.0712 x2 + 0.9331 x
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

11939||||||false||||||

<!--Converted with LaTeX2HTML 2008 (1.71)
original version by:  Nikos Drakos, CBLU, University of Leeds
* revised and updated by:  Marcus Hennecke, Ross Moore, Herb Swan
* with significant contributions from:
  Jens Lippmann, Marek Rouchal, Martin Wilck and others -->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Landing Navigation</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Landing Navigation">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
D: Landing Navigation</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Landing a plane is a difficult operation. Modern planes include landing aids, in which a computer indicates, based on analysis of a 
number of variables, whether it is safe to attempt landing and, if so, how best to proceed. 

<P>
In this problem we will program a simplified 
landing aid. We assume the pilot engages this aid when the plane is in a specific position relative to the landing strip:

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11939.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="1007" HEIGHT="401" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11939.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11939.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
That is, when the plane is exactly at a height of one kilometer, and 20 kilometers away from the landing strip, the pilot starts 
the landing procedure and engages our landing aid. As shown in the picture, the plane is descending at an angle <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Phi</I></SPAN>, measured 
counterclockwise from ground; furthermore, we consider the horizontal <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN> direction to be positive in the direction towards the landing 
strip, and the vertical <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I></SPAN> direction to be positive downwards towards the ground. We also assume the plane velocity to be always 200Km/h 
in the direction from the plane straight towards the landing strip. The vertical and horizontal (scalar) speeds may vary, but the velocity 
will always be 200Km/h. 

<P>
When our landing aid is first engaged, it will inform the pilot the following: a) the current time into the descent 
is zero; b) condition is GO (meaning landing may proceed); c) what descent angle <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Phi</I></SPAN> should the plane be set to; d) the remaining flight 
time; and e) the current horizontal and vertical speeds. 

<P>
Under static conditions this would be all that is needed to safely land the plane. 
However, wind bursts may affect the plane's position and velocity during the descent. We assume bursts only occur in the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN> or <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I></SPAN> directions, 
but they may have positive or negative speed. The burst velocity is added to the plane's. The changes introduced by the burst will affect 
the plane velocity and the angle <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Phi</I></SPAN> needed to reach the landing strip. However, to have a safe landing we need to meet the following two 
conditions:

<P>

<UL>
<LI>the descent angle <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Phi</I></SPAN> must be equal to or greater than 1 degree, and equal to or less than 4 degrees 
</LI>
<LI>the plane speed in the y direction must be less than 4 meters per second
</LI>
</UL>

<P>
The plane has a burst detector, which indicates to our landing aid the direction and speed of the burst. 

<P>
We assume it is too risky for 
the pilot to make course changes during a burst, so our landing aid will behave as follows: 

<P>

<UL>
<LI>It will indicate to the pilot that 
a burst has started, as well as current time into the descent 
</LI>
<LI>Every five seconds, it will calculate the new angle <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Phi</I></SPAN> and plane velocity 
required to land, and will determine if a safe landing would still be possible if the burst ended at that exact moment. If safe landing 
is still possible, it will give the pilot a GO signal. Otherwise, it will give an ABORT signal. 
</LI>
<LI>At the end of the burst, it will indicate 
the pilot that the burst has ended, a GO or ABORT signal, and in case of a GO signal, the new flight conditions.
</LI>
</UL>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
Your program must read test cases from the standard input. Each test case has one or more lines. 
Each line has four numbers separated by spaces. The first number is the time into the flight (in seconds) when a burst starts. 
The second is the time when the burst stops. The third number is equal to 0 if the wind moves in the x direction and different 
than 0 if the wind moves in the y direction. The fourth and final number is the burst speed in Km/h; it may be positive or negative. 

<P>
Test cases are separated by lines where the first number is `<TT>0</TT>'. There may or may not be any number of such lines at the start, middle 
or end of the file. It may be assumed that bursts always occur in isolation and never coincide in time. Bursts have duration of at 
least one second. When ABORT conditions are set, the rest of the test case must be ignored, since the plane has interrupted the landing. 
There will always be at least one burst per test case, and one test case per input file. 

<P>
As an example, consider the Sample Input below. This file defines two test cases. 
In the first, there is a wind burst along the x direction that starts 50 seconds into the descent and lasts two seconds. 
Wind speed is 10km/h; the burst is pushing the plane towards the landing strip. The second test case has two bursts. 
The first burst starts 100 seconds into the flight and lasts 7 seconds, and moves in the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN>
direction at 10km/h. The second burst occurs 150 seconds into the flight, moves along the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I></SPAN> direction, and has negative 
speed (that is, it pushes the plane upwards). Times and speeds are not restricted to be integers and could be fractional. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
Let us analyze the program's output at Sample Output below. 

<P>
Test cases are separated by lines `<TT>--Start of test case--</TT>' and `<TT>--End of test case--</TT>'.

<P>
At the start of each test case, the landing aid outputs the following information:

<P>
<PRE><TT>
<TT>TIME = 0.00, GO</TT> 		 The current time (0.00) and a GO signal 
<BR><TT> RTIME = 360.45</TT> 		 Remaining flight time if conditions don't change 
<BR><TT> ANGLE = 2.86</TT> 		 Angle of descent that pilot must set, in degrees 
<BR><TT> VX = 55.49</TT> 		 Speed along x axis in m/s 
<BR><TT> VY = 2.77</TT> 		 Speed along y axis in m/s 
<BR>
</TT></PRE>

<P>
(Note that the last four lines are indented by two spaces, and all numbers are printed with two decimal figures). When a burst is 
detected, the pilot is informed of this, along with the current flight time in seconds, with a line as follows: 

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<TT>BURST START AT TIME = 100.00</TT> 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Then, every five seconds a GO or ABORT signal is given, along with the current flight time: 

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<TT>TIME = 105.00, GO</TT> 
<BR><TT>TIME = 110.00, GO</TT> 
<BR><TT>TIME = 115.00, GO</TT> 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
The pilot is informed of the end of the burst, along with the time, and if conditions are good, a GO signal and new flight 
information: 

<P>
<PRE><TT>
<TT>BURST END AT TIME = 117.00</TT> 		  Burst end is indicated, with time 
<BR><TT>TIME = 117.00, GO</TT> 		 GO signal is given (if appropriate)  
<BR><TT> RTIME = 239.21</TT> 		 Updated flight information is provided 
<BR><TT> ANGLE = 2.91</TT> 
<BR><TT> VX = 55.49</TT> 
<BR><TT> VY = 2.82</TT> 
<BR>
</TT></PRE>

<P>
In case the landing cannot be completed safely, an ABORT signal is given and the test case ends immediately: 

<P>
<PRE><TT>
<TT>BURST START AT TIME = 150.00</TT> 
<BR><TT>TIME = 155.00, GO</TT> 
<BR><TT>TIME = 160.00, GO</TT> 
<BR><TT>TIME = 165.00, ABORT</TT> 		 When ABORT is given, test case ends 
<BR><TT>--End of test case--</TT> 
<BR>
</TT></PRE>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
50 52 0 10
0 0 0 0
100 117 0 50
150 170 1 -60
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
---Start of test case---
TIME = 0.00, GO
 RTIME = 360.45
 ANGLE = 2.86
 VX = 55.49
 VY = 2.77
BURST START AT TIME = 50.00
BURST END AT TIME = 52.00
TIME = 52.00, GO
 RTIME = 308.35
 ANGLE = 2.86
 VX = 55.49
 VY = 2.78
---End of test case---
---Start of test case---
TIME = 0.00, GO
 RTIME = 360.45
 ANGLE = 2.86
 VX = 55.49
 VY = 2.77
BURST START AT TIME = 100.00
TIME = 105.00, GO
TIME = 110.00, GO
TIME = 115.00, GO
BURST END AT TIME = 117.00
TIME = 117.00, GO
 RTIME = 239.21
 ANGLE = 2.91
 VX = 55.49
 VY = 2.82
BURST START AT TIME = 150.00
TIME = 155.00, GO
TIME = 160.00, GO
TIME = 165.00, ABORT
---End of test case---
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Face the Maze</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Face the Maze">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
E: Face the Maze</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
This problem consists of traversing deterministically a discrete surface represented by a matrix of <!-- MATH
 $n \times n$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I> <TT>x</TT> <I>n</I></SPAN> cells (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I> &gt; 2</SPAN>), starting 
at a <SPAN  CLASS="textit">source</SPAN> cell, ending at a <SPAN  CLASS="textit">target</SPAN> cell, and considering the existence of static obstacles in the form of <SPAN  CLASS="textit">unavailable</SPAN> cells. 
The key idea is that from the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">source</SPAN> cell, the position of the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">target</SPAN> cell is unknown; thus, a path starting from <SPAN  CLASS="textit">source</SPAN> cell must 
be created on the run until <SPAN  CLASS="textit">target</SPAN> cell is found. 

<P>
Only vertical and horizontal movements are allowed. The choice of the next cell 
visited is given by the following list of priorities. 

<P>

<OL>
<LI>Go to the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">target</SPAN> cell, if it is adjacent vertical or horizontally 
</LI>
<LI>Go down, if the bottom cell is available and not visited yet 
</LI>
<LI>Go to the right, if the right cell is available and not visited yet 
</LI>
<LI>Go to the left, if the left cell is available and not visited yet 
</LI>
<LI>Go up, if the top cell is available and not visited yet 
</LI>
<LI>Go back to the previous cell. 
</LI>
</OL>

<P>
If either <SPAN  CLASS="textit">source</SPAN> cell or <SPAN  CLASS="textit">target</SPAN> cell is trapped in a dead end, eventually the path will return to 
the start point. In such a case, the travel must end. 

<P>
For a better understanding of this problem, consider the first test case 
from Sample Input, where <SPAN  CLASS="textit">source</SPAN> cell is at (2, 2), <SPAN  CLASS="textit">target</SPAN> is at (1, 1), and cells (3, 3) and (2, 4) are unavailable. 
As can be seen in the following figure, the path from <SPAN  CLASS="textit">source</SPAN> to <SPAN  CLASS="textit">target</SPAN> considering the priorities enlisted above is as 
follows: 1) go down, 2) go to the left, 3) go down, 4) go back, 5) go up, 6) go to the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">target</SPAN>.

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11940a.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="324" HEIGHT="318" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11940a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11940a.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
The first line contains an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I> &gt; 0</SPAN> denoting the number of test cases. 

<P>
The next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines contain a space-separated list 
starting with an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I> &gt; 1</SPAN> denoting the number of rows (or columns) in the surface, and followed by <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>m</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11940a.png" 
 ALT="$ \ge$">2</SPAN> pairs of integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I>, <I>j</I>)</SPAN>, 
such that: 

<P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT>a)</DT>
<DD><SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I></SPAN> is the column index
</DD>
<DT>b)</DT>
<DD><SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>j</I></SPAN> is the row index 
</DD>
<DT>c)</DT>
<DD><!-- MATH
 $1 \le i, j \le n$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11940a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>i</I>, <I>j</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11940a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>n</I></SPAN> 
</DD>
<DT>d)</DT>
<DD>The first pair <!-- MATH
 $(i_1, j_1)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>1</SUB>)</SPAN> denotes the position of the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">source</SPAN> cell 
</DD>
<DT>e)</DT>
<DD>The second pair <!-- MATH
 $(i_2, j_2)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>2</SUB>)</SPAN>, such that <!-- MATH
 $(i_2, j_2) \ne (i_1, j_1)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>2</SUB>)<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11940a.png" 
 ALT="$ \ne$">(<I>i</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>1</SUB>)</SPAN>, denotes the position of the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">target</SPAN> cell 
</DD>
<DT>f)</DT>
<DD>Every pair <!-- MATH
 $(i_k, j_k)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I><SUB>k</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>k</SUB>)</SPAN>, such that <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>k</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11940a.png" 
 ALT="$ \ge$">3</SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $(i_k, j_k) \ne (i_1, j_1)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I><SUB>k</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>k</SUB>)<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11940a.png" 
 ALT="$ \ne$">(<I>i</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>1</SUB>)</SPAN>, 
and <!-- MATH
 $(i_k, j_k) \ne (i_2, j_2)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I><SUB>k</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>k</SUB>)<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="34" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11940a.png" 
 ALT="$ \ne$">(<I>i</I><SUB>2</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>2</SUB>)</SPAN>, denotes an <SPAN  CLASS="textit">unavailable</SPAN> cell (obstacle)
</DD>
</DL>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
The output consists of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines containing the path produced at each test case. The path is specified by means of a space-separated 
list of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>m</I></SPAN> pairs of integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I>, <I>j</I>)</SPAN>, such that: 

<P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT>a)</DT>
<DD><!-- MATH
 $1 \le i, j \le n$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11940a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>i</I>, <I>j</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11940a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>n</I></SPAN> 
</DD>
<DT>b)</DT>
<DD>The first pair <!-- MATH
 $(i_1, j_1)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I><SUB>1</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>1</SUB>)</SPAN> denotes the position of the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">source</SPAN> cell 
</DD>
<DT>c)</DT>
<DD>Every pair <!-- MATH
 $(i_k, j_k)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I><SUB>k</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>k</SUB>)</SPAN>, where <SPAN CLASS="MATH">1 &lt; <I>k</I> &lt; <I>m</I></SPAN>, denotes the position of a cell employed in the path, such that <!-- MATH
 $(i_k, j_k)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I><SUB>k</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>k</SUB>)</SPAN> is not an 
<SPAN  CLASS="textit">unavailable</SPAN> cell and is horizontally or vertically adjacent to <!-- MATH
 $(i_{k-1}, j_{k-1})$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I><SUB>k-1</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>k-1</SUB>)</SPAN> 
</DD>
<DT>d)</DT>
<DD>The last pair <!-- MATH
 $(i_m, j_m)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I><SUB>m</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>m</SUB>)</SPAN> denotes either 
<DL COMPACT>
<DT>a.</DT>
<DD>The position of the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">target</SPAN> cell, if it was successfully reached 
</DD>
<DT>b.</DT>
<DD>The position of the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">source</SPAN> cell, otherwise 
</DD>
</DL>
</DD>
</DL>

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<B>Note:</B> Images from test cases 2 and 3

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11940b.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="684" HEIGHT="398" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11940a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11940b.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3
4 (2,2) (1,1) (3,3) (2,4)
5 (1,1) (5,5) (1,2) (2,2) (3,2) (4,2) (4,4) (5,4)
3 (1,1) (3,3) (3,2) (2,3)
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
(2,2) (2,3) (1,3) (1,4) (1,3) (1,2) (1,1)
(1,1) (2,1) (3,1) (4,1) (5,1) (5,2) (5,3) (4,3) (3,3) (3,4) (3,5) (4,5) (5,5)
(1,1) (1,2) (1,3) (1,2) (2,2) (2,1) (3,1) (2,1) (2,2) (1,2) (1,1)
</PRE> 

<P>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Creating a Quadtree</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Creating a Quadtree">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
F: Creating a Quadtree</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
A <SPAN  CLASS="textit">quadtree</SPAN>, first introduced by Finkel and Bentley, is a tree data-structure in which each internal node has exactly four children. 
Quadtrees are often used for problems that can be mapped into a two-dimensional space which is then recursively subdivided it into 
four equally-sized regions while a certain condition holds. Such problems include the following: collision detections, spatial data 
indexing, image compression and Conway's Game of Life. The problem consists in compressing a binary image represented by an <!-- MATH
 $n \times n$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I> <TT>x</TT> <I>n</I></SPAN> matrix, 
where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I> &gt; 1</SPAN> is a power of 2. The binary image is specified by means of rectangular areas containing only white pixels. 
Each area is given by the location of its upper-left and lower-right corners. The compressed image is given by a quadtree, 
where each node denotes a region in the image. A region is subdivided if it is not a pixel yet and it has both white and black pixels. 
The order in visiting regions is left-right, top-down. 

<P>
For a better understanding of this problem, consider the third test case from 
Sample Input where the binary image is a <!-- MATH
 $8 \times 8$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">8 <TT>x</TT> 8</SPAN> matrix composed by five white areas. In the following figure, such areas are 
highlighted with blue rectangles. Its corresponding quadtree is made up of five internal nodes and sixteen leaves (regions).

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11941.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="1203" HEIGHT="502" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11941.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11941.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
The first line contains an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I> &gt; 0</SPAN> denoting the number of test cases. The next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines contain a space-separated list 
starting with an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>n</I> &gt; 1</SPAN>, power of two, which denotes the matrix size, and followed by <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>m</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11941.png" 
 ALT="$ \ge$">2</SPAN> pairs of integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I><SUB>k</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>k</SUB>)</SPAN>, 
such that: 

<P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT>a)</DT>
<DD><SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>i</I><SUB>k</SUB></SPAN> is the column index 
</DD>
<DT>b)</DT>
<DD><SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>j</I><SUB>k</SUB></SPAN> is the row index
</DD>
<DT>c)</DT>
<DD><!-- MATH
 $1 \le i_k, j_k \le n$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11941.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>i</I><SUB>k</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>k</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11941.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>n</I></SPAN> 
</DD>
<DT>d)</DT>
<DD>Two consecutive pairs <!-- MATH
 $(i_{k-1}, j_{k-1})$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I><SUB>k-1</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>k-1</SUB>)</SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $(i_k, j_k)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I><SUB>k</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>k</SUB>)</SPAN>, where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>k</I></SPAN> is even, denotes respectively the position 
of the upper-left corner and lower-right corner of the <SPAN CLASS="MATH">1/2<I>k</I></SPAN>-th area 
</DD>
<DT>e)</DT>
<DD>If <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>m</I></SPAN> is odd, the pair <!-- MATH
 $(i_m, j_m)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>i</I><SUB>m</SUB>, <I>j</I><SUB>m</SUB>)</SPAN> is ignored 
</DD>
</DL>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
The output consists of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines containing either the quadtree produced at each test case, or the text `<TT>Size is invalid</TT>' if 
the matrix size is not a power of 2. The quadtree is specified by means of a sequence of <TT>0</TT>'s and <TT>1</TT>'s. For each black 
node add a `<TT>0</TT>' to the output; for each white node add a `<TT>1</TT>'; for each gray node add a `<TT>*</TT>' and repeat 
this process for each child node. 
Do not consider the root in the output. Traverse the quadtree in pre-order. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3
4 (1,1) (1,1) (4,1) (4,1) (1,3) (2,4)
15
8 (1,1) (4,4) (3,5) (7,6) (1,7) (2,8) (3,8) (3,8) (5,7) (6,8)
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
*1000*010010
Size is invalid
10*011*0010*1*101010
</PRE> 

<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Lumberjack Sequencing</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Lumberjack Sequencing">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
A: Lumberjack Sequencing</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Another tale of lumberjacks?. Let see ...

<P>
The lumberjacks are rude, bearded workers, while foremen tend to be bossy and simpleminded. The foremen like to harass the 
lumberjacks by making them line up in groups of ten, ordered by the length of their beards. The lumberjacks, being of 
different physical heights, vary their arrangements to confuse the foremen. Therefore, the foremen must actually measure the 
beards in centimeters to see if everyone is lined up in order. 

<P>
Your task is to write a program to assist the foremen in 
determining whether or not the lumberjacks are lined up properly, either from shortest to longest beard or from longest to shortest. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
The input starts with line containing a single integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $0 < N < 20$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 &lt; <I>N</I> &lt; 20</SPAN>, which is the number of groups to process. 
Following this are <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines, each containing ten distinct positive integers less than 100. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
There is a title line, then one line per set of beard lengths. See the sample output for capitalization and punctuation. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
3 
13 25 39 40 55 62 68 77 88 95 
88 62 77 20 40 10 99 56 45 36 
91 78 61 59 54 49 43 33 26 18
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
Lumberjacks: 
Ordered 
Unordered 
Ordered
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>The heart flu</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="The heart flu">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
B: The heart flu</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
It has been discovered that a new disease is attacking human beings. This new disease consists in a virus that attacks the 
heart, causing malfunction of it, leading to a permanent brain damage --in the best case scenario-- or death. Since a collective 
paranoia has been raised, all hospitals have exceeded their capacity to check every patient that comes into the ER. 

<P>
One of the new guidelines proposed by the hospital director was to create a triage, based on a computer program because 
there are no doctors enough to review all ECGs. 

<P>
The proposal is to admit a patient into the ER, take him/her to the ECG room were the patient lecture will be taken. 
The computer will take some specific points of the ECG and determine if the patient should be reviewed carefully by a 
doctor or if the patient is healthy and a psychiatrist needs to talk to him and explain the effects of the paranoia in 
his/her feelings. 

<P>
You have been assigned to create the program that will take the lecture points in the ECG. 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
The important complex in an ECG is called QRS complex. 

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Q is the first wave in the complex with negative value 
</LI>
<LI>R is the second wave in the complex with positive value, and in a classic ECG, is the biggest wave 
</LI>
<LI>S is the last wave in the complex with negative value that comes after R wave. 
</LI>
</UL>

<P>
In a normal ECG, the QRS complex has duration between 60 and 100 milliseconds, and a voltage no greater than 35 mV, and has no valleys. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
The input consists in the name of the patient, followed by an *, age an * and the points of lecture in the ECG separated 
by commas. Each point of data is 10 ms apart from each other. The point is given in mV. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
Each patient data will be separated by a `<TT>---</TT>' line. 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
The name of the patient 
<BR>
Age 
<BR><TT>Triage</TT> [<TT>PASS</TT> | <TT>NO PASS</TT>]

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
Gambino, Christine*35*0,0.1,-0.35,1.3,-0.55,0,.05,0 
Martim, Gustavo*29*0,0.1,-0.5,1.5,-1,0,0.075,0 
Guzman, Isabel*15*0,0,-0.05,-0.1,0.1,0.25,0.5,0.7,0.4,0.2,-0.01,-0.25,-0.5,-0.25
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
Gambino, Christine 
35 
Triage PASS 
---
Martim, Gustavo 
29 
Triage PASS 
---
Guzman, Isabel 
15 
Triage NO PASS
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>$ 10 to Win?</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="$ 10 to Win?">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
C: $ 10 to Win?</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Howdy Michael is a young and inexperienced gambler. Howdy bets much money in several Sport Games (basketball, baseball, 
hockey and football). This type of bet (combination of several Sport Games) is well-known like Parlay (gambling). 

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Parlay (gambling) Rules</SPAN> 

<P>
A parlay wager is a combination of individual independent wagers that only pays if no individual wager loses. The payout 
from each wager is applied or ``parlayed" to the next wager in turn. If any individual wager loses, the bettor receives 
nothing. If any individual wager is a tie or ``push", that wager is effectively ignored, reducing the ultimate payout. 

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">How to calculate payment of a Parlay (gambling)?</SPAN> 

<P>
The sports book quotes the payout rate for an individual wager as a ``money line", a nonzero integer in the range -2000 to 2000. 
To compute the payout for a successful wager, the money line is converted to a decimal multiplier as follows: if the money line 
is positive, it is divided by 100 to obtain the multiplier. If the money line is negative, 100 is divided into the absolute value 
to obtain the multiplier. The multiplier is always rounded to three digits after the decimal point. The wager is multiplied by this 
multiplier to determine the amount won. The amount won is always rounded to next value integer if the amounts won contains cents (no cents). 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Consider the following example for a five-way parlay wager: 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<TABLE COLS=4 BORDER RULES=GROUPS>
<COL ALIGN=CENTER><COL ALIGN=RIGHT><COL ALIGN=CENTER><COL ALIGN=RIGHT>
<TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Money Line</SPAN> </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP> <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Wager</SPAN> </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Multiplier</SPAN> </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP> <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Amount Won</SPAN> </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>-170 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP> $ 10   </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 100/170 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP> $6       </TD></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 
-160 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP> $ 16   </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 100/160 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP> $ 10     </TD></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 
125 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP> $ 26    </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 125/100 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP> $ 33     </TD></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 
-135 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP> $ 59   </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 100/135 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP> $ 44     </TD></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 
-140 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP> $ 103  </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 100/140 </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP> $ 74     </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD></TD><TD></TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>       Subtotal: </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP> <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">$ 167</SPAN>      </TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD></TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>    Original Wager:          </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>         <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">$ 10</SPAN>           </TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD></TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>       Total Returned:        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>        <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">$ 177.00</SPAN>           </TD></TR>
</TBODY>
</TABLE>

</DIV>             

<P>

<P>
<BR>
The maximum payout for any parlay wager is $1 million. If the calculated total exceeds that amount, 
the actual total returned will be $1 million. 

<P>
Write a program that helps us to Howdy Michael will calculate the total amount returned for a series of parlay wagers. 
For each parlay wager, your program is to print the total amount returned in dollars and cents on a single line starting in the 
first column without embedded or trailing whitespace. Print the leading dollar sign and insert commas at the millions and thousands 
positions as needed.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
Input will consist of several wagers. The first line of input to your program will contain the total number of parlay 
wagers as a single positive integer. 

<P>
Each wager that follows will be represented by a series of lines. 

<P>
The first line of each parlay wager contains the initial bet and the count of individual wagers as integers separated 
from each other by a single space. 

<P>
The following lines represent the individual wagers, one per line. Each individual wager is given as its money line. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
For each parlay wager, you should generate one line of output with the following values: The dataset number as a decimal 
integer (start counting at one), a space, and the total amount returned in dollars followed by ``.00" cents. Print the 
leading dollar sign and insert commas at the millions and thousands positions as needed.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
3 
10 5 
-170 
-160 
125 
-135 
-140 
10 8 
-170 
-160 
125 
-135 
-140 
110 
120 
130 
15 5 
100 
-100 
-250 
135 
-350
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
1 $177.00 
2 $1,884.00 
3 $255.00
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Financial Management</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Financial Management">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
D: Financial Management</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Michael graduated of ITESO this year and finally has a job. He's making a lot of money, but somehow never seems to have 
enough. Michael has decided that he needs to grab hold of his financial portfolio and solve his financing problems. 
The first step is to figure out what's been going on with his money. 

<P>
Michael has his bank account statements and wants 
to see how much money he has. Help Michael by writing a program to take his closing balance from each of the past twelve 
months and calculate his average account balance. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
The first line of input contains a single integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN>, (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le N \le 100$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11945img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11945img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100</SPAN>) which is the number of datasets that follow. 

<P>
Each dataset consists of twelve lines. Each line will contain the closing balance of his bank account for a particular 
month. Each number will be positive and displayed to the penny. No dollar sign will be included. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
For each dataset, you should generate one line of output with the following values: The dataset number as a decimal 
integer (start counting at one), a space, a character `<TT>$</TT>', and a single number, the average (mean) of the closing balances 
for the twelve months. It will be rounded to the nearest penny. 

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Note:</SPAN> Used comma (<TT>,</TT>) to separate the thousands. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
1 
100.00 
489.12 
12454.12 
1234.10 
823.05 
109.20 
5.27 
1542.25 
839.18 
83.99 
1295.01 
1.75
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
1 $1,581.42
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Code Number</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Code Number">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
E: Code Number</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Adrian and Maria are relatives that live in different towns. As they inhabit a rural area, it is very difficult for them to 
keep in touch. One way they found to overcome their communication problem was to send a line through their parents that used 
to visit each other. 

<P>
The point is that Adrian and Maria did not want that their parents read their messages, and they decided to create a 
secret code for the messages. The code is not very sophisticated, but you should keep in mind Adrian and Maria are just children. 

<P>
In general, the meaning of a message is based on changing some letters by numbers. Each message is composed by several lines using 
uppercase letters of the English alphabet, space and punctuation symbols: dot and comma. The letters that are changed by numbers 
can be seen in the following example; this change is the same for all messages between Adrian and Maria. 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Message in ``<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Code Number</SPAN>": 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
H<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">3</SPAN>LL<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">0</SPAN> MY L<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">0</SPAN>V<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">3</SPAN>, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">1</SPAN> M H<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">499</SPAN>Y <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">83</SPAN>C<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">4</SPAN>U<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">53 500</SPAN>N 
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">1</SPAN> W<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">1</SPAN>LL <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">83 70</SPAN> Y<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">0</SPAN>UR <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">51</SPAN>D<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">3</SPAN>. 
<BR><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">7</SPAN>H<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">15 71</SPAN>M<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">3</SPAN> W<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">17</SPAN>H<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">0</SPAN>U<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">7</SPAN> Y<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">0</SPAN>U H<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">45 833</SPAN>N 
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">373</SPAN>RN<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">4</SPAN>L. <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">1 1</SPAN>NV<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">173</SPAN> Y<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">0</SPAN>U <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">70 7</SPAN>H<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">3 200</SPAN> 
<BR><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">0</SPAN>N<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">3 70 533 7</SPAN>H<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">3 238</SPAN>R<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">42 4</SPAN>ND <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">60</SPAN>R<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">1</SPAN>L<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">42</SPAN>. 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Decode Message: 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
H<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">E</SPAN>LL<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">O</SPAN> MY L<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">O</SPAN>V<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">E</SPAN>, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">I</SPAN> M H<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">APP</SPAN>Y <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">BE</SPAN>C<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">A</SPAN>U<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">SE SOO</SPAN>N 
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">I</SPAN> W<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">I</SPAN>LL <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">BE TO</SPAN> Y<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">O</SPAN>UR <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">SI</SPAN>D<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">E</SPAN>. 
<BR><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">T</SPAN>H<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">IS TI</SPAN>M<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">E</SPAN> W<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">IT</SPAN>H<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">O</SPAN>U<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">T</SPAN> Y<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">O</SPAN>U H<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">AS BEE</SPAN>N 
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">ETE</SPAN>RN<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">A</SPAN>L. <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">I I</SPAN>NV<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">ITE</SPAN> Y<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">O</SPAN>U <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">TO T</SPAN>H<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">E ZOO</SPAN> 
<BR><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">O</SPAN>N<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">E TO SEE T</SPAN>H<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">E ZEB</SPAN>R<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">AS A</SPAN>ND <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">GO</SPAN>R<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">I</SPAN>L<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">AS</SPAN>. 

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hint:</SPAN> In this example, the relation Number-Letter between the message in ``Code Number" and the Decode Message 
this indicated by the numbers and letters in bold. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
The first line of input gives the number of test cases, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le T \le 30$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11946img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11946img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">30</SPAN>). Each test case represents a message 
written in <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Code Number</SPAN>, which is composed by <!-- MATH
 $1 \le N \le 100$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11946img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11946img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100</SPAN> lines and each line cannot exceed 80 characters of 
length. Two words in the same line are separated by one white space. One blank line separated each test case. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
For each test case you must print the decoded message. You must print a blank line between each test case.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
1
H3LL0 MY L0V3, 1 M H499Y 83C4U53 500N 1 W1LL 83 70 Y0UR 51D3. 7H15 
71M3 W17H0U7 Y0U H45 833N 373RN4L. 1 1NV173 Y0U 70 7H3 200 0N3 70 
533 7H3 238R45 4ND 60R1L45.
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
HELLO MY LOVE, I M HAPPY BECAUSE SOON I WILL BE TO YOUR SIDE. THIS 
TIME WITHOUT YOU HAS BEEN ETERNAL. I INVITE YOU TO THE ZOO ONE TO 
SEE THE ZEBRAS AND GORILAS.
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Cancer or Scorpio</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Cancer or Scorpio">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
F: Cancer or Scorpio</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Alice and Michael is a young couple who are planning on having their first child. Their wish their son Nelson was born 
on a special date for both of them. 

<P>
Alice has investigated in the internet and has found that the period of gestation 
is forty weeks. These forty weeks begin to count on the first day of the last menstrual cycle. 

<P>
Michael is passionate about astrology and even more about the zodiac signs, he has asked Alice to investigate 
the range of dates that correspond to each sign. 

<P>

<P>
<BR>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<TABLE COLS=3 BORDER FRAME=BOX RULES=GROUPS>
<COLGROUP><COL ALIGN=CENTER><COLGROUP><COL ALIGN=LEFT><COLGROUP><COL ALIGN=LEFT>
<TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>
 <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Sign</SPAN>              </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>     <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Begin</SPAN>                  </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>        <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">End</SPAN>          </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>Aquarius           </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    January, 21                   </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    February, 19              </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>Pisces             </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    February, 20                   </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>   March, 20               </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>Aries              </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    March, 21                   </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    April, 20              </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>Taurus             </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    April, 21                   </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    May, 21              </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>Gemini             </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    May, 22                   </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>     June, 21             </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>Cancer             </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    June, 22                   </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    July, 22              </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>Leo                </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    July, 23                   </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    August, 21              </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>Virgo              </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    August, 22                   </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    September, 23              </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>Libra              </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    September, 24                   </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>   October, 23               </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>Scorpio            </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    October, 24                   </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    November, 22              </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>Sagittarius        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    November, 23                   </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>   December, 22               </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>Capricorn          </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>    December, 23                   </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=LEFT NOWRAP>   January, 20               </TD></TR>
</TBODY>
</TABLE>

</DIV>

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Alice and Michael ask for help to calculate the date of birth of their son Nelson and his zodiac sign. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
The first line of input contains a single integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN>, (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le N \le 1000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11947img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11947img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1000</SPAN>) which is the number of datasets that follow. 

<P>
Each dataset consists of a single line of input that contains only eight digits that represent the date of the first day 
of the last menstrual cycle in format <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>MMDDYYYY</I></SPAN>. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
For each dataset, you should generate one line of output with the following values: The dataset number as a decimal 
integer (start counting at one), a space, the date of birth in format <!-- MATH
 $MM\texttt{/}DD\texttt{/}YYYY$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>MM</I>/<I>DD</I>/<I>YYYY</I></SPAN>, a space, and the name (in lowercase) of 
zodiac sign that correspond according to the date of birth.

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Note:</SPAN> Considers leap years. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
2 
01232009 
01232008
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
1 10/30/2009 scorpio 
2 10/29/2008 scorpio
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Reading a Quadtree</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Reading a Quadtree">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
G: Reading a Quadtree</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
A quadtree, first introduced by Finkel and Bentley, is a tree data-structure in which each internal node has exactly 
four children. Quadtrees are often used for problems that can be mapped into a two-dimensional space which is then 
recursively subdivided it into four equally-sized regions while a certain condition holds. The problem consists in 
reading a compressed binary image represented with a quadtree and determining which pixels are set to white. 

<P>
For a better understanding of this problem, consider the third test case from Sample Input, represented in the figure. 
The uncompressed binary image is composed by (8 x 8) pixels, where 35 of them are white. Notice each node in the quadtree 
is mapped into a square area from the target image. White nodes denote areas composed by white pixels exclusively, whereas 
black nodes denote areas with only black pixels; finally, gray nodes are composed by white and black pixels and thus, 
they need to be subdivided into four new square areas. Notice that the order of visiting square areas is: left to right and top to bottom.

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p11948.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="1146" HEIGHT="413" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11948.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p11948.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
The first line contains an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I> &gt; 0</SPAN> denoting the number of test cases. 

<P>
The next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines start each with the length <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>L</I></SPAN> of the target image; <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>L</I></SPAN> has to be a power of 2. 

<P>
The length is followed by a space and a sequence of <TT>0</TT>, <TT>1</TT> and <TT>*</TT>, denoting black, white and gray nodes of the quadtree, respectively. 
The quadtree is traversed in pre-order. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
The output consists of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines containing each a comma-separated list of either: 

<P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT>a)</DT>
<DD><SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>x</I>, <I>y</I>)</SPAN> position of a pixel adjacent horizontally by black pixels, or 
</DD>
<DT>b)</DT>
<DD><!-- MATH
 $(x_i-x_f,y)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>x</I><SUB>i</SUB> - <I>x</I><SUB>f</SUB>, <I>y</I>)</SPAN>, where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I><SUB>f</SUB> &gt; <I>x</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN>: a sequence of white pixels at row <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I></SPAN> surrounded by black pixels.
</DD>
</DL>

<P>
The following holds: <!-- MATH
 $1 \le x, x_i, x_f, y \le L$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11948.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>x</I>, <I>x</I><SUB>i</SUB>, <I>x</I><SUB>f</SUB>, <I>y</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11948.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>L</I></SPAN>. Traverse the binary image from left to right, top to bottom. 

<P>
If <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>L</I></SPAN> is not a power of 2, the output should display the text ``<TT>Invalid length</TT>", instead. 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
3 
4 **1000*010010 
7 *101*0100 
8 *10*011*0010*1*101010
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
(1,1),(4,1),(1-2,3),(1-2,4) 
Invalid length 
(1-4,1),(1-4,2),(1-4,3),(1-4,4),(3-7,5),(3-7,6),(1-2,7),(5-6,7),(1-3,8),(5-6,8)
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

  Jens Lippmann, Marek Rouchal, Martin Wilck and others -->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Calculating IRR</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Calculating IRR">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
H: Calculating IRR</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Johnny Money is a big-time investor well-known for having the ability to identify good business opportunities. To 
measure the profitability of a business or project, Johnny calculates the internal rate of return (IRR) based on a 
projected or existing cash-flow of such a business. If the IRR is greater than any interest rate offered by the bank, 
the investment is convenient. 

<P>
In more specific terms, the IRR of an investment is the interest rate (%) at which the sum of the present value of all 
projected costs (negative cash flows) and benefits (positive cash flows) of the investment equals the initial investment. 
The present value is calculated dividing the value by an interest rate as many times as the period indicates. 
For example, the present value of a cost of $100.00 projected for the 3rd period (or month) with an interest rate of 10% is $75.13. 

<P>
The problem consists of calculating the IRR given an initial investment and the cash flow. For a better understanding of the problem, 
consider the following example. The initial investment is $4,000.00 and five periods are projected. The first one results in a 
benefit of $3,852.56; the second period projects a cost of $2,954.21; the three following periods projects benefits 
of $1,500.00, $2,120.86 and $2,890.64, respectively. Was it a profitable investment? To answer that, we need to find an 
interest rate such that the sum of the present values equals the initial investment. From the table above, it is clear 
that such an interest rate is 22.294%, from which we conclude that Johnny Money will accept to invest in this business.

<P>

<P>
<BR>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<TABLE COLS=6 BORDER FRAME=BOX RULES=GROUPS>
<COLGROUP><COL ALIGN=CENTER><COLGROUP><COL ALIGN=RIGHT><COLGROUP><COL ALIGN=RIGHT><COLGROUP><COL ALIGN=RIGHT><COLGROUP><COL ALIGN=RIGHT><COLGROUP><COL ALIGN=RIGHT>
<TBODY>
<TR><TD></TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP COLSPAN=1> Actual</TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP COLSPAN=1> 10%</TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP COLSPAN=1> 20%</TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP COLSPAN=1> 30%</TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP COLSPAN=1> <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">22.294%</SPAN></TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP>1                </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   $ 3,852.56        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   $  3,502.33        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   $  3,210.47        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>    $ 2,963.51       </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   $ 3,150.24       </TD></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 
  2               </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   -$  2,954.21        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>  -$ 2,441.50         </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   -$   2,051.53        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   -$ 1,748.05        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   -$ 1,975.29       </TD></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 
   3              </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>    $  1,500.00       </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   $ 1,126.97        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   $  868.06        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>     $ 682.75      </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   $ 820.12       </TD></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 
    4             </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>    $  2,120.86       </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   $ 1,448.58        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   $  1,022.79        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   $ 742.57        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>     $ 948.18     </TD></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 
     5            </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>    $  2,890.64       </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   $ 1,794.86        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   $   1,161.68        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>    $ 778.53       </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>    $ 1,056.74      </TD></TR>
</TBODY><TBODY>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP><SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Sum</I></SPAN> </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>      $ 7,409.85     </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>    $ 5,431.24       </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>     $ 4,211.46       </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>    $ 3,419.31       </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>    <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">$ 3,999.99</SPAN>      </TD></TR>
<TR><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=CENTER NOWRAP> 
  <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Sum</I> - <I>Inv</I></SPAN> </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   $ 3,409.85        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>   $   1,431.24        </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>    $ 211.46       </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>    $ -580.69       </TD><TD VALIGN=BASELINE ALIGN=RIGHT NOWRAP>  <SPAN  CLASS="textbf"> $ 0.01</SPAN>       </TD></TR>
</TBODY>
</TABLE>

</DIV>         

<P>

<P>
<BR>
The reader is suggested to treat this problem as a root-finding problem, which can be solved by means of numerical methods, 
particularly, the <SPAN  CLASS="textit">bisection</SPAN> method. This method repeatedly cuts the current interval in half, defining two new subintervals; 
then it selects the one in which the root must lie: the functions of the first and last values of the subinterval have different signs. 
Assume that every IRR ranges from -100% to 100%. As an initial interval, the positive half if the sum of the projected values 
(in the table, $7,409.95) is greater than the investment; choose the negative half, otherwise.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
The first line contains an integer number, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I> &gt; 0</SPAN>, denoting the number of test cases. The next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines contain each a cash 
flow defined as a space-separated list of two-decimal numbers denoting costs (if negative) or benefits (if positive). 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
The output consists of <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines, where each line <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>k</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/11949img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I></SPAN> contains a three-decimal number in the range (-100.0 ...100.0) 
followed by the character `<TT>%</TT>', denoting the estimated IRR for cash flow <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>k</I></SPAN>. 

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hint:</SPAN> If there are more than 3 decimals in the output, it has to be rounded using the round-up algorithm.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
3 
500.00 75.60 174.40 -60.75 319.25 84.63 31.17 
100.00 42.27 35.00 -22.35 10.00 
4000.00 3852.56 -2954.21 1500.00 2120.86 2890.64
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2> 

<P>
<PRE>
6.873% 
-26.369% 
22.294% 
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Neverland</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Neverland">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">
