<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="9%" valign=top style='width:9.46%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle>B</p>
  </td>
  <td width="89%" valign=top style='width:89.32%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Fukushima Nuclear Blast</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal>One of the most disastrous nuclear accidents in history has
taken place at Japans Fukushima Daiichi nuclear plant. Reactor buildings have
been rocked by explosions, caused after damage was sustained from a <img
width=241 height=208 src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11978.jpg"  align=right hspace=12>massive
earthquake and tsunami on 11<sup>th</sup> march and thus releasing dangerous
radiation of unspecified proportions into the air.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>The radiation is spreading and it's not a threat only to
Japan but also to other countries. If the level of radiation reaches a high
level, it will surely cause harms to human health as well as the environment.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>You, one of the great programmers in the city, have planned
to find the zones that are vulnerable to radiation. If you can measure the
level of radiation in a certain city, further actions can be taken to prevent
the people from radiation related health consequences. So, at first you want to
find the time in which a certain percentage of an area is under radiation
threat.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>So, at first you modeled the map of a city in <b>2D</b>
space as a <b>simple polygon </b>[1]. You denoted the origin of the explosion
as a single point. From this origin, the radiation spreads circularly. You
plotted the map such that in each unit of time the radius of the radiation
grows one unit. Now, you want to find the time when <b>P%</b> of the area of a
city is under threat of radiation.</p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>Input starts with an integer <b>T (</b><b>&#8804; 70)</b>,
denoting the number of test cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each test case starts with a blank line. The next line
contains an integer <b>n (3 &#8804; n &#8804; 5000) </b>denoting the number of
vertices of the polygon. Each of the next <b>n</b> lines will contain two
integers <b>x<sub>i</sub>, y<sub>i</sub> </b>denoting the co-ordinate of a
vertex of the polygon. The vertices will be given in anticlockwise order. The
next line contains 3 integers <b>r<sub>x</sub>, r<sub>y</sub></b> and <b>P (0
&lt; P &#8804; 100)</b>, where <b>(r<sub>x</sub>, r<sub>y</sub>)</b> denotes
the co-ordinate of the origin of explosion and <b>P</b> denotes the percentage.
All values for the co-ordinates are between <b>-200</b> to <b>200</b>
(inclusive).</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number and the time when
exactly <b>P%</b> of the total area is under threat of radiation. Round the
time to nearest integer.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse;border:none'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:.95in'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:.95in'><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>2</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>&nbsp;</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>3</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>-5 0</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>5 0</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>0 5</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>0 0 100</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>&nbsp;</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>4</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>0 0</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>5 0</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>3 1</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>5 6</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>0 0 17</span></pre></td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:.95in'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  1: 5</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  2: 2</span></p>
  <pre><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>&nbsp;</span></pre></td>
 </tr>
</table>

<h1 style='margin-top:12.0pt'>Notes</h1>

<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:justify;text-indent:-.25in'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
line-height:115%;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>1.<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>In
geometry, a <b>simple polygon</b> is a closed polygonal chain of line segments
in the plane which do not have points in common other than the common vertices
of pairs of consecutive segments.</span></p>

<p class=MsoListParagraphCxSpLast style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:justify;text-indent:-.25in'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
line-height:115%;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>2.<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>The
judge data is prepared such that the result (before rounding) will not be
between <b>x.3 to x.7</b>. For example, the result can be like 5.8, 24.3 or
81.791. But the result will not be like 24.5, 78.4, etc.</span></p>

<div class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:center'><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>

</span></div>

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="9%" valign=top style='width:9.46%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle>C</p>
  </td>
  <td width="89%" valign=top style='width:89.3%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Hamming Base</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal>You are given <b>N</b> integers in base-<b>N</b> each of
them having exactly <b>M</b> digits (may be with some leading zeros).  Two
integers are called <b>K</b>-similar if they have the same digits in exactly <b>K</b>
positions. For example 321 and 213 are <b>0</b>-similar. 3456 and 6453 are <b>2</b>-similar,
123 and 453 are <b>1</b>-similar. You want to change these given <b>N</b>-integers
in such a way that each pair of these integers are <b>0</b>-similar. To achieve
this goal you can change the integers in several steps. In a single step you
can change a single digit of a single integer by 1 (incrementing or
decrementing). But you can't decrement if the digit is <b>0</b> or you can't
increment if the digit is <b>N-1</b>.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>You need to achieve your goal in minimum number of steps.</p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>Input starts with an integer <b>T (</b><b>&#8804; 50)</b>,
denoting the number of test cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case starts with a line containing two integers <b>N</b>
<b>(2 &#8804; N &#8804; 2000)</b> and <b>M (1 &#8804; M &#8804; 10)</b>. Each
of the next <b>N</b> lines contains <b>M</b> integers between <b>0</b> and <b>N-1</b>
inclusive. These <b>M</b> integers form an <b>M</b> digit number in base <b>N</b>.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number and the minimal steps
required to achieve your goal.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse;border:none'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:.95in'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:.95in'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>2</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>3
  3</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>0
  0 0</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>0
  0 0</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>0
  0 0</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>4
  2</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>0
  0</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>0
  0</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>0
  2</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>2
  0</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:.95in'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  1: 9</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  2: 8</span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<div class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:center'><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>

<hr size=2 width="100%" align=center>

</span></div>

p.MsoListParagraph, li.MsoListParagraph, div.MsoListParagraph
	{margin-top:0in;
	margin-right:0in;
	margin-bottom:10.0pt;
	margin-left:.5in;
	line-height:115%;
	font-size:11.0pt;
	font-family:"Calibri","sans-serif";}
p.MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst, li.MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst, div.MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst
	{margin-top:0in;

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="9%" valign=top style='width:9.46%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle>D</p>
  </td>
  <td width="89%" valign=top style='width:89.32%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Mad Scientist</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal><b>Sofdor Ali, </b>the mad scientist, is a well known figure
for his great inventions. He sent me a telegram saying, 'urgent need, write the
code and send me the output!'  And there was a pseudo code in the telegram. Finally,
I managed to write it in <b>C++</b> (my apology to non C programmers). Here is
the code:</p>

<div style='border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:1.0pt 4.0pt 1.0pt 4.0pt'>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New";color:blue'>#include</span><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'> <span style='color:#A31515'>&lt;cstdio&gt;</span></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New";color:blue'>#include</span><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'> <span style='color:#A31515'>&lt;algorithm&gt;</span></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New";color:blue'>using</span><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'> <span style='color:blue'>namespace</span>
<span style='color:#010001'>std</span>;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><b><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New";color:blue'>typedef</span></b><b><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'> <span style='color:blue'>long</span>
<span style='color:blue'>long</span> <span style='color:blue'>i64</span></span></b><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><b><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New";color:blue'>const</span></b><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'> <b><span style='color:blue'>i64</span></b>
<span style='color:#010001'>MOD</span> = (1 &lt;&lt; 30);</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><b><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New";color:blue'>void</span></b><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'> <span style='color:#010001'>solve</span>(
<b><span style='color:blue'>i64</span></b> <span style='color:#010001'>n</span>,
<b><span style='color:blue'>i64</span></b> <span style='color:#010001'>m</span>
) {</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>      <b><span
style='color:blue'>i64</span></b> <span style='color:#010001'>res1</span> = 0, <span
style='color:#010001'>res2</span> = 0, <span style='color:#010001'>k</span>, <span
style='color:#010001'>i</span>;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>      <b><span
style='color:blue'>for</span></b>( <span style='color:#010001'>k</span> = 0; <span
style='color:#010001'>k</span> &lt;= <span style='color:#010001'>m</span>; <span
style='color:#010001'>k</span>++ ) {</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>            <b><span
style='color:blue'>for</span></b>( <span style='color:#010001'>i</span> = 0; ; <span
style='color:#010001'>i</span>++ )</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>                  <b><span
style='color:blue'>if</span></b>( ( <span style='color:#010001'>n</span> ^ <span
style='color:#010001'>i</span> ) == <span style='color:#010001'>k</span> ) <span
style='color:green'>// n ^ i means n xor i</span></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>                        <b><span
style='color:blue'>break</span></b>;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>            <span
style='color:#010001'>res1</span> = <span style='color:#010001'>max</span>( <span
style='color:#010001'>res1</span>, <span style='color:#010001'>i</span> );</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>      }</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>      <b><span
style='color:blue'>for</span></b>( <span style='color:#010001'>i</span> = 0; <span
style='color:#010001'>i</span> &lt;= <span style='color:#010001'>res1</span>; <span
style='color:#010001'>i</span>++ ) {</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>            <b><span
style='color:blue'>if</span></b>( ( <span style='color:#010001'>n</span> ^ <span
style='color:#010001'>i</span> ) &gt; <span style='color:#010001'>m</span> ) {</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>                  <span
style='color:#010001'>res2</span> += ( <span style='color:#010001'>n</span> ^ <span
style='color:#010001'>i</span> );</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>                  <span
style='color:#010001'>res2</span> %= <span style='color:#010001'>MOD</span>;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>            }</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>      }</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>      <span
style='color:#010001'>printf</span>(<span style='color:#A31515'>&quot;%lld %lld\n&quot;</span>,
<span style='color:#010001'>res1</span>, <span style='color:#010001'>res2</span>);</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>}</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><b><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New";color:blue'>int</span></b><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'> <span style='color:#010001'>main</span>()
{</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>      <b><span
style='color:blue'>int</span></b> <span style='color:#010001'>T</span>, <span
style='color:#010001'>t</span>;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>      <b><span
style='color:blue'>i64</span></b> <span style='color:#010001'>n</span>, <span
style='color:#010001'>m</span>;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>      <span
style='color:#010001'>scanf</span>(<span style='color:#A31515'>&quot;%d&quot;</span>,
&amp;<span style='color:#010001'>T</span>);</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>      <b><span
style='color:blue'>for</span></b>( <span style='color:#010001'>t</span> = 1; <span
style='color:#010001'>t</span> &lt;= <span style='color:#010001'>T</span>; <span
style='color:#010001'>t</span>++ ) {</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>            <span
style='color:#010001'>scanf</span>(<span style='color:#A31515'>&quot;%lld
%lld&quot;</span>, &amp;<span style='color:#010001'>n</span>, &amp;<span
style='color:#010001'>m</span>);</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>            <span
style='color:#010001'>printf</span>(<span style='color:#A31515'>&quot;Case %d:
&quot;</span>, <span style='color:#010001'>t</span>);</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>            <span
style='color:#010001'>solve</span>( <span style='color:#010001'>n</span>, <span
style='color:#010001'>m</span> );</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>      }</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>      <b><span
style='color:blue'>return</span></b> 0;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=left style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:left;line-height:normal;text-autospace:none;border:none;padding:
0in'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>}</span></p>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:6.0pt'>But soon, I found that for inputs,
as specified in the telegram, the code takes huge time to compute the result.
And according to the structure of the code, it's clear that for some cases it
may take years to compute the output.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>So, I am asking you to help me optimizing the code such that
it can generate the output in reasonable amount of time.</p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>Input starts with an integer <b>T (</b><b>&#8804; 10000)</b>,
denoting the number of test cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case starts with a line containing two integers <b>n, m
(0 &#8804; n, m &#8804; 2<sup>60</sup>)</b>.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the output generated by the code.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse;border:none'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:53.1pt'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:53.1pt'><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>3</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>0 0</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>5 3</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>10 13</span></pre></td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:53.1pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  1: 0 0</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  2: 7 22</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  3: 15 29</span></p>
  <pre><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>&nbsp;</span></pre></td>

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="16%" valign=top style='width:16.86%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle>E</p>
  </td>
  <td width="81%" valign=top style='width:81.9%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Corrupted Friendship</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal>Many of us know a person named Mr. Haba Kom Khan. He is very
corrupted and lazy. He maintains links with a lot of (corrupted) persons. In order
to corrupt more lazy persons, he invites his friends in a recursive fashion in
a meeting. The idea is:</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>If X has some cards, he keeps one card and he invites one of
his friends Y who has no invitation cards yet and X gives all the remaining
cards to Y. Then we say that Y is invited by X. Y then has the responsibility
to distribute as many cards as he can, and Y keeps one card and continues the
same procedure as X. When Y cannot find any more friends to give the invitation
cards, he gives the remaining cards back to X. X then checks for his friends
who have no cards yet. If any such friend is found, X continues the same
procedure. Otherwise, if X was invited by Z then X gives the remaining cards
back to Z. X keeps the cards if there is no such person.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Initially Mr. Haba has <b>N</b> invitations cards, and he
starts the invitation process as stated. There are <b>N</b> persons, and they
are numbered from <b>1</b> to <b>N</b>. Mr. Haba is the person numbered <b>1</b>.
And the strange fact is that, after the invitation process, each person gets
exactly <b>1</b> card.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Given all the information of persons being invited by others,
Mr. Haba wants you to find the total number of invitations that was made. He
also asks you to find the number of different pairs of persons who are
certainly not friends. Help Mr. Haba Kom Khan to succeed in his corrupted life!</p>

<h1 align=left style='text-align:left'>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>The first line of input will contain <b>T (&#8804; 30)</b>
denoting the number of cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case starts with an integer <b>N (1 &#8804; N &#8804; 10<sup>5</sup>)</b>.
Each of the next <b>N-</b><b>1</b> lines will contain two integers, <b>X</b>
and <b>Y (1 &#8804; X, Y &#8804; N, X &#8800; Y)</b> denoting that person <b>Y</b>
received his invitation card from person <b>X</b>. Input is huge. So, faster
I/O methods (e.g. scanf, printf, BufferedReader, BufferedWriter) are
recommended.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number, total number of
invitations made, and the number of different pairs of persons who are surely
not friends. See samples for detailed formatting.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse;border:none'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.0%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.0%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:.95in'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.0%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:.95in'><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>2</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>2</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>1 2</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>3</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>1 2</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>1 3</span></pre></td>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.0%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:.95in'><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>Case 1: 1 0</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>Case 2: 2 1</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>&nbsp;</span></pre></td>
 </tr>

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="9%" valign=top style='width:9.46%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle>F</p>
  </td>
  <td width="89%" valign=top style='width:89.3%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Fantasy Cricket</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='line-height:115%'>ICC World Cup 2011 has just
finished. During the world cup, lots of cricket fans were playing an online
game named &quot;Fantasy Cricket&quot;.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='line-height:115%'>The score board of fantasy
cricket looks like the following image. After each match of the world cup the
score board of fantasy cricket updates.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-bottom:6.0pt;text-align:center'><img
width=624 height=307 id="Picture 67" src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11982a.png" ></p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><span
style='line-height:115%'>Figure 1</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='line-height:115%'>Each player plays a role of a
manager here. In the rank list there is a symbol besides each manger. There are
three kinds of symbols. These are explained in the following table.</span></p>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoTableColorfulListAccent5 border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse'>
 <tr>
  <td width=132 valign=top style='width:99.1pt;background:#DAEEF3;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='line-height:115%;color:black'>Symbol</span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=373 valign=top style='width:279.4pt;background:#DAEEF3;padding:
  0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='line-height:115%;color:black'>Explanation</span></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width=121 valign=top style='width:90.5pt;background:#DAEEF3;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-bottom:6.0pt;text-align:center'><b><span
  style='line-height:115%;color:black'>ASCII Representation</span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width=132 valign=top style='width:99.1pt;background:#EDF6F9;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><img width=44 height=44 src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11982a.png" 
  align=left hspace=12></p>
  </td>
  <td width=373 valign=top style='width:279.4pt;background:#EDF6F9;padding:
  0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><span style='line-height:115%;color:black'>The rank of the
  player has upgraded after last match, i.e. if the current rank of the player
  is <b>K</b>, the rank of the player before the last match was greater than <b>K</b>.</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width=121 valign=top style='width:90.5pt;background:#EDF6F9;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='line-height:115%;color:black'>U</span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width=132 valign=top style='width:99.1pt;background:#DAEEF3;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><img width=44 height=44 src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11982a.png" 
  align=left hspace=12></p>
  </td>
  <td width=373 valign=top style='width:279.4pt;background:#DAEEF3;padding:
  0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><span style='line-height:115%;color:black'>The rank of the
  player has downgraded after the last match, i.e. if the current rank of the
  player is <b>K</b>, the rank of the player before the last match was less
  than <b>K</b>.</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width=121 valign=top style='width:90.5pt;background:#DAEEF3;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='line-height:115%;color:black'>D</span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width=132 valign=top style='width:99.1pt;background:#EDF6F9;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><img width=46 height=46 src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11982a.png" 
  align=left hspace=12></p>
  </td>
  <td width=373 valign=top style='width:279.4pt;background:#EDF6F9;padding:
  0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal><span style='line-height:115%;color:black'>The rank of the
  player has not changed after the last match, i.e. if the current rank of the
  player is <b>K</b>, the rank of the player before the last match was also <b>K</b>.</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width=121 valign=top style='width:90.5pt;background:#EDF6F9;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><b><span
  style='line-height:115%;color:black'>E</span></b></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='line-height:115%'>You will be given such a
score board after a particular match. Can you determine any possible valid
ordering of the players exactly before that round? For this problem you have to
print the number of possible ordering before the last match.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='line-height:115%'>Here is an example </span></p>

</div>

<b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'><br
clear=all style='page-break-before:auto'>
</span></b>

<div class=Section2>

<div align=center>

<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-top:6.0pt;text-align:center'><span
style='line-height:115%'>Figure 3</span></p>

</div>

<span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'><br
clear=all style='page-break-before:auto'>
</span>

<div class=Section3>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='line-height:115%'>For this rank (figure 2),
only two different ordering are possible (figure 3) before the last match which
comply the current ordering with the symbols.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='line-height:115%'>Name of the managers are not
important for this problem. So, for a scoreboard, you will be given a sequence
of ASCII representation of the symbols (stated above), i.e. you will be given a
string which only contains <b>'U', 'D'</b> and <b>'E'</b>.</span></p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>Input starts with an integer <b>T (</b><b>&#8804; 300)</b>,
denoting the number of test cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case starts with a line containing a string. The length
of the string will be between <b>1</b> and <b>1000</b>. The string will contain
characters from <b>{'U', 'D', 'E'}</b>.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number and the number of
possible orderings modulo <b>1000000007</b>.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse;border:none'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:50.85pt'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:50.85pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>3</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>UDUD</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>EEE</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>DU</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:50.85pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  1: 2</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  2: 1</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  3: 0</span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<div class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:center'><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>

</span></div>

<body lang=EN-US link=blue vlink=purple>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="9%" valign=top style='width:9.46%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle>G</p>
  </td>
  <td width="89%" valign=top style='width:89.3%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Weird Advertisement</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoTitle style='margin-bottom:12.0pt'><span class=MsoSubtleEmphasis><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-style:normal'>Renat Mullakhanov (</span></span><a
href="http://www.topcoder.com/tc?module=MemberProfile&amp;cr=8394868"><span
class=MsoSubtleEmphasis><span style='font-size:12.0pt;color:#C00000;font-style:
normal;text-decoration:none'>rem</span></span></a><span
class=MsoSubtleEmphasis><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-style:normal'>), one
of the most talented programmers in the world, passed away on March 11, 2011.
This is very sad news for all of us. His team went to ACM ICPC World Finals -
2004, placed 4th and won gold medals. He really was a great programmer. May he
rest in peace. This problem is dedicated to him.</span></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b>2DPlaneLand</b> is a land just like a huge <b>2D</b>
plane. The range of <b>X</b> axis is <b>0</b> to <b>10<sup>9</sup></b> and the
range of <b>Y</b> axis is also <b>0</b> to <b>10<sup>9</sup></b>. People built
houses only in integer co-ordinates and there is exactly one house in each
integer co-ordinate.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Now <b>UseAndSmile</b> Soap Company is launching a new soap.
That's why they want to advertise this product as much as possible. So, they
selected <b>n</b> persons for this task. Each person will be given a
rectangular region. He will advertise the product to all the houses that lie in
his region. Each rectangular region is identified by <b>4</b> integers <b>x<sub>1</sub>,
y<sub>1</sub>, x<sub>2</sub></b> and <b>y<sub>2</sub></b>. That means this
person will advertise in all the houses whose <b>x</b> co-ordinate is between <b>x<sub>1</sub></b>
and <b>x<sub>2</sub></b> (inclusive) and <b>y</b> co-ordinate is between <b>y<sub>1</sub></b>
and <b>y<sub>2</sub></b> (inclusive).</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Now after a while they realized that some houses are being advertised
by more than one person. So, they want to find the number of houses that are
advertised by at least <b>k</b> persons. Since you are one of the best
programmers in the city; they asked you to solve this problem.</p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>Input starts with an integer <b>T (</b><b>&#8804; 13)</b>,
denoting the number of test cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case starts with a line containing two integers <b>n (1
&#8804; n &#8804; 30000), k (1 &#8804; k &#8804; 10)</b>. Each of the next <b>n</b>
lines will contain <b>4</b> integers <b>x<sub>1</sub>, y<sub>1</sub>, x<sub>2</sub>,
y<sub>2</sub> (0 &#8804; x<sub>1</sub>, y<sub>1</sub>, x<sub>2</sub>, y<sub>2</sub>
&#8804; 10<sup>9</sup>, x<sub>1</sub> &lt; x<sub>2</sub>, y<sub>1</sub> &lt; y<sub>2</sub>)</b>
denoting a rectangular region for a person.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number and the total number of
houses that are advertised by at least <b>k</b> people.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse;border:none'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:.95in'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:.95in'><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>2</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>2 1</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>0 0 4 4</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>1 1 2 5</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>2 2</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>0 0 4 4</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>1 1 2 5</span></pre></td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:.95in'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  1: 27</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  2: 8</span></p>
  <pre><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>&nbsp;</span></pre></td>

<body lang=EN-US link=blue vlink=purple>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="9%" valign=top style='width:9.46%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle>H</p>
  </td>
  <td width="89%" valign=top style='width:89.3%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>A Change in Thermal Unit</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal>Measuring temperature and temperature differences are common
task in many research and applications. Unfortunately, there exists more than
one unit of measuring temperatures. This introduces a lot of confusion at times.
Two popular units of measurements are Celsius(<b>C</b>) and Fahrenheit (<b>F</b>).
The conversion of <b>F</b> from <b>C</b> is given by the formula:</p>

<p class=MsoNormal align=center style='text-align:center'><img width=105
height=42 src=p11984.png></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>In this problem, you will be given an initial temperature in
<b>C</b> and an increase in temperature in <b>F</b>. You would have to
calculate the new temperature in <b>C</b>.</p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>Input starts with an integer <b>T (&#8804; 100)</b>,
denoting the number of test cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case contains a line with two integers <b>C</b> and <b>d
(0 &#8804; C, d &#8804; 100)</b>, where <b>C</b> represents the initial
temperature in Celsius and <b>d</b> represents the increase in temperature in
Fahrenheit.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number and the new temperature
in Celsius after rounding it to two digits after the decimal point.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:41.4pt'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:41.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>2</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>100
  0</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>0
  100</span></p>
  </td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:41.4pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  1: 100.00</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  2: 55.56</span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="9%" valign=top style='width:9.46%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle>I</p>
  </td>
  <td width="89%" valign=top style='width:89.3%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Prime Independence</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal>A set of integers is called prime independent if none of its
member is a prime multiple of another member. An integer <b>a</b> is said to be
a <b>prime multiple</b> of <b>b</b> if,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b>a = b × k </b>(where <b>k</b> is a prime [1])</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>So, <b>6</b> is a prime multiple of <b>2</b>, but <b>8</b>
is not. And for example, <b>{2, 8, 17}</b> is prime independent but <b>{2, 8,
16}</b> or <b>{3, 6}</b> are not.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Now, given a set of distinct positive integers, calculate
the largest prime independent subset.</p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>Input starts with an integer <b>T (</b><b>&#8804; 25)</b>,
denoting the number of test cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each case starts with an integer <b>N (1 &#8804; N &#8804;
40000)</b> denoting the size of the set. Next line contains <b>N</b> integers
separated by a single space. Each of these <b>N</b> integers are distinct and
between <b>1</b> and <b>500000</b> inclusive.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number and the size of the
largest prime independent subset.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse;border:none'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:.95in'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:.95in'><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>3</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>5</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>2 4 8 16 32</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>5</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>2 3 4 6 9</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>3</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>1 2 3</span></pre></td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:.95in'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  1: 3</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  2: 3</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  3: 2</span></p>
  <pre><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>&nbsp;</span></pre></td>
 </tr>
</table>

<h1 style='margin-top:12.0pt'>Notes</h1>

<p class=MsoListParagraph style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:justify;text-indent:-.25in'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
line-height:115%;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>1.<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>An
integer is said to be a prime if it's divisible by exactly two distinct
integers. First few prime numbers are <b>2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, ...</b></span></p>

<div class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:center'><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>

<body lang=EN-US>

<div class=Section1>

<div align=center>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=3 cellpadding=0>
 <tr style='height:41.5pt'>
  <td width="9%" valign=top style='width:9.46%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoTitle>J</p>
  </td>
  <td width="89%" valign=top style='width:89.3%;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;
  height:41.5pt'>
  <p class=MsoSubtitle>Save from Radiation</p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

</div>

<p class=MsoNormal>Most of you are aware of Nuclear Power Plant Explosion at
Fukushima after devastating earth quake and tsunami. Many people in Bangladesh
were seen to be concerned <img width=211 height=270 src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/119/p11986.jpg" 
align=left hspace=12>with radiation. The message says:</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>BBC Flash news: Japan Government confirms radiation leak at
Fukushima nuclear plants. Asian countries should take necessary precautions. If
rain comes, remain indoors first 24 hours. Close doors and windows. Swab neck
skin with betadine where thyroid area is, radiation hits thyroid first. Take
extra precautions. Radiation may hit Philippine at around 4 pm today. If it
rains today or in the next few days in Hong Kong, do not go under the rain. If
you get caught out, use an umbrella or raincoat, even if it is only a drizzle.
Radioactive particles, which may cause burns, alopecia or even cancer, may be
in the rain.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Many people suggested many things. We, the programmer
society, were not inactive. We uploaded a picture in a very popular social
network website, facenote and said, &quot;There are two ways to be safe from
radiation. One is the Disky way and another is the Buseen way.&quot; You may
get clear idea of those two ways from the picture.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Anyway, after the explosion of Fukushima Nuclear Power Plant
a bottle of water was sent to my laboratory for experiment. But my stupid robot
assistant kept it with <b>N</b> identical water bottles of which I can't
distinguish the special water bottle which came from Japan. I know that if a
rat drinks the water from the special bottle, it will die in the 5<sup>th</sup>
minute. Now, I want to identify the special bottle. But I do not like rat
either. So, I want to buy minimum number of rats. Can you help me to find out
the minimum number of rats I need for identifying the special bottle in 5
minutes?</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>I forgot to tell you that, only one drop of water from a
bottle is enough to find out if the water is safe or not. And you may also give
waters from several bottles to a single rat. If one of these bottles is the
special bottle then the rat will die, otherwise it will not. And assume that
the time to give waters to the rats is negligible, because once you decide the
strategy; you may ask the robot assistant to do it. And the robot can do it in
no time. And you can also assume that the bottles contain sufficient amount of
waters.</p>

<h1>Input</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>Input starts with an integer <b>T (</b><b>&#8804; 3000)</b>,
denoting the number of test cases.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Each test case starts with a line containing an integer <b>N</b>
<b>(0 &#8804; N &#8804; 10<sup>16</sup>)</b>.</p>

<h1>Output</h1>

<p class=MsoNormal>For each case, print the case number and the minimum number
of rats required for identifying the special bottle.</p>

<table class=MsoNormalTable border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0
 style='border-collapse:collapse;border:none'>
 <tr style='height:7.65pt'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border:solid windowtext 2.25pt;
  border-left:none;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:7.65pt'>
  <h1>Output for Sample Input</h1>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr style='height:27.0pt'>
  <td width="50%" valign=top style='width:50.56%;border:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  border-top:none;background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:27.0pt'><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>1</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>1</span></pre><pre><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:Courier'>2</span></pre></td>
  <td width="49%" valign=top style='width:49.44%;border-top:none;border-left:
  none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;border-right:solid windowtext 1.0pt;
  background:white;padding:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;height:27.0pt'>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  1: 1</span></p>
  <p class=MsoNoSpacing><span style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Courier New"'>Case
  2: 2</span></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<h1 style='margin-top:12.0pt'>Notes</h1>

<p class=MsoListParagraph style='margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;
text-align:justify;text-indent:-.25in'><span style='font-size:12.0pt;
line-height:115%;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>1.<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:12.0pt;line-height:115%;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>For
case 2, the robot assistant kept the special bottle with 2 identical bottles.
So, there are 3 bottles, one of them is the special bottle. The minimum number
of rats is 2. Because just give a drop from bottle 1 to the 1<sup>st</sup> rat
and a drop from bottle 2 to the 2<sup>nd</sup> rat. If the 1<sup>st</sup> rat
dies, so it's clear that bottle 1 is the special one. If the 2<sup>nd</sup> rat
dies, then the second bottle is the special one. And if none of them dies, then
the 3<sup>rd</sup> bottle is the special bottle. So, 2 rats are enough. But
there are other options, too. Like give the first rat two drops from bottle 1
and 2. And give the second rat a drop from bottle 2. Then the special bottle
can also be determined. So, there can be many options, but you need at least 2
rats.</span></p>

text-align:center'><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>

11987||||||false||||||
<html>
<head>
<title>Problem A: Almost Union-Find</title>
</head>
<body>

<center>
<h1>Problem A</h1>
<h2>Almost Union-Find</h2>
</center>

<p>I hope you know the beautiful Union-Find structure. In this problem, you're to implement something similar, but not identical.</p>

<p>The data structure you need to write is also a collection of disjoint sets, supporting 3 operations:</p>

<pre>1 p q</pre>

<p>Union the sets containing p and q. If p and q are already in the same set, ignore this command.</p>

<pre>2 p q</pre>
<p>Move p to the set containing q. If p and q are already in the same set, ignore this command</p>

<pre>3 p</pre>
<p>Return the number of elements and the sum of elements in the set containing p.</p>

<p>Initially, the collection contains n sets: {1}, {2}, {3}, ..., {n}.</p>

<h2>Input</h2>
<p>There are several test cases. Each test case begins with a line containing two integers n and m (1<=n,m<=100,000), the number of integers, and the number of commands. 
Each of the next m lines contains a command. For every operation, 1<=p,q<=n. The input is terminated by end-of-file (EOF). 
The size of input file does not exceed 5MB.</p>

<h2>Output</h2>
<p>For each type-3 command, output 2 integers: the number of elements and the sum of elements.</p>

<h2>Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
5 7
1 1 2
2 3 4
1 3 5
3 4
2 4 1
3 4
3 3
</pre>

<h2>Output for the Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
3 12
3 7
2 8
</pre>

<h2>Explanation</h2>
<p>Initially: {1}, {2}, {3}, {4}, {5}</p>
<p>Collection after operation 1 1 2: {1,2}, {3}, {4}, {5}</p>
<p>Collection after operation 2 3 4: {1,2}, {3,4}, {5} (we omit the empty set that is produced when taking out 3 from {3})</p>
<p>Collection after operation 1 3 5: {1,2}, {3,4,5}</p>
<p>Collection after operation 2 4 1: {1,2,4}, {3,5}</p>


<hr />
<i>Rujia Liu's Present 3: A Data Structure Contest Celebrating the 100th Anniversary of Tsinghua University</i><br />
<i>Special Thanks: Yiming Li</i><br />
<i>Note: Please make sure to test your program with the gift I/O files before submitting!</i><br />

</body>
</html>

11988||||||false||||||
<html>
<head>
<title>Problem B: Broken Keyboard (a.k.a. Beiju Text)</title>
</head>
<body>

<center>
<h1>Problem B</h1>
<h2>Broken Keyboard (a.k.a. Beiju Text)</h2>
</center>

<p>You're typing a long text with a broken keyboard. Well it's not so badly broken. The only problem with the keyboard is that sometimes the "home" key or the "end" key gets automatically pressed (internally). </p>

<p>You're not aware of this issue, since you're focusing on the text and did not even turn on the monitor! After you finished typing, you can see a text on the screen (if you turn on the monitor). </p>

<p>In Chinese, we can call it Beiju. Your task is to find the Beiju text.</p>

<h2>Input</h2>
<p>There are several test cases. Each test case is a single line containing at least one and at most 100,000 letters, underscores and two special characters '[' and ']'. '[' means the "Home" key is pressed internally, and ']' means the "End" key is pressed internally. The input is terminated by end-of-file (EOF). The size of input file does not exceed 5MB.</p>

<h2>Output</h2>
<p>For each case, print the Beiju text on the screen.</p>

<h2>Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
This_is_a_[Beiju]_text
[[]][][]Happy_Birthday_to_Tsinghua_University
</pre>

<h2>Output for the Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
BeijuThis_is_a__text
Happy_Birthday_to_Tsinghua_University
</pre>

<hr />
<i>Rujia Liu's Present 3: A Data Structure Contest Celebrating the 100th Anniversary of Tsinghua University</i><br />
<i>Special Thanks: Yiming Li</i><br />
<i>Note: Please make sure to test your program with the gift I/O files before submitting!</i><br />
</body>
</html>

11989||||||false||||||
<html>
<head>
<title>Problem C: Cake Cutting</title>
</head>
<body>

<center>
<h1>Problem C</h1>
<h2>Cake Cutting</h2>
</center>

<p>There is a very big rectangular (yes...) cake on the xy-plane, whose four corners are (0,0), (w,0), (w,h) and (0,h).</p>

<p>Each time you're hungry, you slice a piece from the cake and eat it. Your task is to output the area of the remaining cake, after each slice.</p>

<h2>Input</h2>
<p>There are several test cases. The first line contains threes integers n, w, h (1<=n<=200,000, 1<=w,h<=1000), the number of slices, the width and the height of the cake. Each of the following n lines contains four positive real numbers x1, y1, x2, y2 not greater than 1000. That means, you slice it along the straight line connecting (x1,y1) and (x2,y2), and eat the part on the right (if any), when looking from (x1,y1) to (x2,y2). The input is terminated by end-of-file (EOF). The size of input file does not exceed 10MB.</p>

<h2>Output</h2>
<p>For each slice, output the area of the cake after the slice, to at least three digits after the decimal point. We allow an absolute error of 10<sup>-3</sup> for each value you output.</p>

<h2>Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
2 20 10
15.0 0.0 15.0 5.0
1.0 2.0 2.0 2.0
</pre>

<h2>Output for the Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
150.000
120.000
</pre>

<hr />
<i>Rujia Liu's Present 3: A Data Structure Contest Celebrating the 100th Anniversary of Tsinghua University</i><br />
<i>Special Thanks: Dun Liang, Yeji Shen</i><br />
<i>Note: Please make sure to test your program with the gift I/O files before submitting!</i><br />
</body>
</html>

11990||||||false||||||
<html>
<head>
<title>Problem D: "Dynamic" Inversion</title>
</head>
<body>

<center>
<h1>Problem D</h1>
<h2>"Dynamic" Inversion</h2>
</center>

<p>You are given a permutation {1,2,3,...,n}. Remove m of them one by one, and output the number of inversion pairs <em>before</em> each removal. The number of inversion pairs of an array A is the number of ordered pairs (i,j) such that i < j and A[i] > A[j].</p>

<h2>Input</h2>
<p>The input contains several test cases. The first line of each case contains two integers n and m (1<=n<=200,000, 1<=m<=100,000). After that, n lines follow, representing the initial permutation. Then m lines follow, representing the removed integers, in the order of the removals. No integer will be removed twice. The input is terminated by end-of-file (EOF). The size of input file does not exceed 5MB.</p>

<h2>Output</h2>
<p>For each removal, output the number of inversion pairs before it.</p>

<h2>Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
5 4
1
5
3
4
2
5
1
4
2
</pre>

<h2>Output for the Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
5
2
2
1
</pre>

<h2>Explanation</h2>
<p>(1,5,3,4,2)->(1,3,4,2)->(3,4,2)->(3,2)->(3)</p>

<hr />
<i>Rujia Liu's Present 3: A Data Structure Contest Celebrating the 100th Anniversary of Tsinghua University</i><br />
<i>Special Thanks: Yi Chen, Dun Liang</i><br />
<i>Note: Please make sure to test your program with the gift I/O files before submitting!</i><br />
</body>
</html>

11991||||||false||||||
<html>
<head>
<title>Problem E: Easy Problem from Rujia Liu?</title>
</head>
<body>

<center>
<h1>Problem E</h1>
<h2>Easy Problem from Rujia Liu?</h2>
</center>

<p><i>Though Rujia Liu usually sets hard problems for contests (for example, regional contests like Xi'an 2006, Beijing 2007 and Wuhan 2009, or UVa OJ contests like Rujia Liu's Presents 1 and 2), he occasionally sets easy problem (for example, 'the Coco-Cola Store' in UVa OJ), to encourage more people to solve his problems :D</i></p>

<p>Given an array, your task is to find the k-th occurrence (from left to right) of an integer v. To make the problem more difficult (and interesting!), you'll have to answer m such queries.</p>

<h2>Input</h2>
<p>There are several test cases. The first line of each test case contains two integers n, m(1<=n,m<=100,000), the number of elements in the array, and the number of queries. The next line contains n positive integers not larger than 1,000,000. Each of the following m lines contains two integer k and v (1<=k<=n, 1<=v<=1,000,000). The input is terminated by end-of-file (EOF). The size of input file does not exceed 5MB.</p>

<h2>Output</h2>
<p>For each query, print the 1-based location of the occurrence. If there is no such element, output 0 instead.</p>

<h2>Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
8 4
1 3 2 2 4 3 2 1
1 3
2 4
3 2
4 2
</pre>

<h2>Output for the Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
2
0
7
0
</pre>

<hr />
<i>Rujia Liu's Present 3: A Data Structure Contest Celebrating the 100th Anniversary of Tsinghua University</i><br />
<i>Special Thanks: Yiming Li</i><br />
<i>Note: Please make sure to test your program with the gift I/O files before submitting!</i><br />
</body>

11992||||||false||||||
<html>
<head>
<title>Problem F: Fast Matrix Operations</title>
</head>
<body>

<center>
<h1>Problem F</h1>
<h2>Fast Matrix Operations</h2>
</center>

<p>There is a matrix containing at most 10<sup>6</sup> elements divided into r rows and c columns. Each element has a location (x,y) where 1<=x<=r,1<=y<=c. Initially, all the elements are zero. You need to handle four kinds of operations:</p>

<pre>1 x1 y1 x2 y2 v</pre>
<p>Increment each element (x,y) in submatrix (x1,y1,x2,y2) by v (v>0)</p>

<pre>2 x1 y1 x2 y2 v</pre>
<p>Set each element (x,y) in submatrix (x1,y1,x2,y2) to v</p>

<pre>3 x1 y1 x2 y2</pre>
<p>Output the summation, min value and max value of submatrix (x1,y1,x2,y2)</p>

<p>In the above descriptions, submatrix (x1,y1,x2,y2) means all the elements (x,y) satisfying x1<=x<=x2 and y1<=x<=y2. It is guaranteed that 1<=x1<=x2<=r, 1<=y1<=y2<=c. After any operation, the sum of all the elements in the matrix does not exceed 10<sup>9</sup>.</p>
</p>

<h2>Input</h2>
<p>There are several test cases. The first line of each case contains three positive integers r, c, m, where m (1<=m<=20,000) is the number of operations. Each of the next m lines contains a query. There will be at most twenty rows in the matrix. The input is terminated by end-of-file (EOF). The size of input file does not exceed 500KB.</p>

<h2>Output</h2>
<p>For each type-3 query, print the summation, min and max.</p>

<h2>Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
4 4 8
1 1 2 4 4 5
3 2 1 4 4
1 1 1 3 4 2
3 1 2 4 4
3 1 1 3 4
2 2 1 4 4 2
3 1 2 4 4
1 1 1 4 3 3
</pre>

<h2>Output for the Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
45 0 5
78 5 7
69 2 7
39 2 7
</pre>

<hr />
<i>Rujia Liu's Present 3: A Data Structure Contest Celebrating the 100th Anniversary of Tsinghua University</i><br />
<i>Special Thanks: Yeji Shen, Dun Liang</i><br />
<i>Note: Please make sure to test your program with the gift I/O files before submitting!</i><br />
</body>
</html>

11993||||||false||||||
<html>
<head>
<title>Problem G: Girls' Celebration</title>
</head>
<body>

<center>
<h1>Problem G</h1>
<h2>Girls' Celebration</h2>
</center>

<p>In order to celebrate the 100-th anniversary of Tsinghua University, n girls are planning to hold a party. They're experts at singing and dancing, and they love to perform in groups. In their current design, there will be a stage and a row of seats. When a group of girls need to sing or dance on the stage, they stand up from their seats, and go to the stage. When they've finished performing, they return to their own seat (they don't exchange seats, because every girl has a lot of personal belongings on her seat).</p>

<p>They want this procedure look cool, so for each performance, the actresses' seats should be consecutive. For example, if there are 4 girls, and a performance is done by girl 1, 2 and 4, then they cannot seat in order of 1-2-3-4, since when girl 1, 2 and 4 stand up, it's strange to see a non-actress (girl 3) sitting between girl 2 and 4.</p>

<p>As I mentioned, they're too good at singing and dancing, so they managed to come up with a lot of combinations. Now they become a bit worried: is there a way to seat all the girls, such that the requirement above can be satisfied (i.e. for every combination, the actresses' seats are consecutive).</p>

<p>As a decent programmer, you decide (I know that actually you're being decided, but...) to write a program that can calculate the number of seat arrangements. Since the girls' are constantly thinking about new combinations, your program should be able to read new combinations and adjust the answer accordingly. When there are only few possible arrangement (i.e. at most k feasible solutions), your program should output all of them.</p>

<h2>Input</h2>
<p>There are several test cases. The first line contains three integers n, m, k (1<=n,m,k<=200), where n is the number of girls, m is the number of combinations, and k is the parameter described above. Each of the next m lines contains a set of integers, terminated by a zero. These integers are the IDs of the girls in the combination (girls are numbered 1 to n). The input is terminated by end-of-file (EOF). The size of input file does not exceed 1MB.</p>

<h2>Output</h2>
<p>For each new combination, output the number of seat arrangements, after considering this combination. If there is no way, print 0 and <em>ignore the combination</em>. If there are at most k ways, print them one in a line, in lexicographical order.</p>

<h2>Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
4 4 10
1 2 3 0
2 3 4 0
1 4 0
2 4 0
</pre>

<h2>Output for the Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
12
4
1 2 3 4
1 3 2 4
4 2 3 1
4 3 2 1
0
2
1 3 2 4
4 2 3 1
</pre>

<hr />
<i>Rujia Liu's Present 3: A Data Structure Contest Celebrating the 100th Anniversary of Tsinghua University</i><br />
<i>Warning: Rujia Liu couldn't find anyone to write an alternative solution for this problem, so the probability that the I/O files are wrong, is higher than other problems in this problemset!</i><br />
<i>Note: Please make sure to test your program with the gift I/O files before submitting!</i><br />
</body>
</html>

______________________________________________________
11994||||||false||||||
<html>
<head>
<title>Problem H: Happy Painting!</title>
</head>
<body>

<center>
<h1>Problem H</h1>
<h2>Happy Painting!</h2>
</center>

<p>There is a forest of colorful rooted trees containing n nodes. You are given m operations. Execute them one by one, and output the results.</p>

<pre>1 x y c</pre>
<p>Change x's father to y. If x=y or x is a ancestor of y, simply ignore it. The edge between x and its old father is removed, and the new edge should be painted with color c.</p>

<pre>2 x y c</pre>
<p>Paint all the edges along the path x-y with color c. If there is no path between x and y, simply ignore it.</p>

<pre>3 x y</pre>
<p>Count the number of edges along the path x-y, and the total number of colors among these edges.</p>

<h2>Input</h2>
<p>The input contains several test cases. The first line of each test case contains two integers n and m (1<=n<=50,000, 1<=m<=200,000). Nodes are numbered from 1 to n. The second line contains n integers F[i] (0<=F[i]<=n), the father of each node (F[i]=0 means the node is the root of a tree). The next line contains n integers C[i] (1<=C[i]<=30), the colors of the edges between each node and its father (for root nodes, the corresponding color should be ignored). Each of the next m lines contains an operation. For all operations, 1<=x,y<=n, for each type-2 operation, 1<=c<=30. The input is terminated by end-of-file (EOF). The size of input file does not exceed 5MB.</p>

<h2>Output</h2>
<p>For each type-3 operation, output two integers: the number of edges and the number of colors among these edges.</p>

<h2>Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
6 6
0 1 1 3 3 0
1 2 1 1 1 1
3 2 3
1 3 2 3
3 2 3
3 5 6
1 6 1 1
3 4 6
</pre>

<h2>Output for the Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
2 2
1 1
0 0
4 3
</pre>

<hr />
<i>Rujia Liu's Present 3: A Data Structure Contest Celebrating the 100th Anniversary of Tsinghua University</i><br />
<i>Special Thanks: Dun Liang</i><br />
<i>Note: Please make sure to test your program with the gift I/O files before submitting!</i><br />
</body>
</html>

______________________________________________________
11995||||||false||||||
<html>
<head>
<title>Problem I: I Can Guess the Data Structure!</title>
</head>
<body>

<center>
<h1>Problem I</h1>
<h2>I Can Guess the Data Structure!</h2>
</center>

<p>There is a bag-like data structure, supporting two operations:</p>

<pre>1 x</pre>
<p>Throw an element x into the bag.</p>

<pre>2</pre>
<p>Take out an element from the bag.</p>

<p>Given a sequence of operations with return values, you're going to guess the data structure. It is a stack (Last-In, First-Out), a queue (First-In, First-Out), a priority-queue (Always take out larger elements first) or something else that you can hardly imagine!</p>

<h2>Input</h2>
<p>There are several test cases. Each test case begins with a line containing a single integer n (1<=n<=1000). Each of the next n lines is either a type-1 command, or an integer 2 followed by an integer x. That means after executing a type-2 command, we get an element x <em>without error</em>. The value of x is always a positive integer not larger than 100. The input is terminated by end-of-file (EOF). The size of input file does not exceed 1MB.</p>

<h2>Output</h2>
<p>For each test case, output one of the following:</p>

<pre>stack</pre>
<p>It's definitely a stack.</p>

<pre>queue</pre>
<p>It's definitely a queue.</p>

<pre>priority queue</pre>
<p>It's definitely a priority queue.</p>

<pre>impossible</pre>
<p>It can't be a stack, a queue or a priority queue.</p>

<pre>not sure</pre>
<p>It can be more than one of the three data structures mentioned above.</p>

<h2>Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
6
1 1
1 2
1 3
2 1
2 2
2 3
6
1 1
1 2
1 3
2 3
2 2
2 1
2
1 1
2 2
4
1 2
1 1
2 1
2 2
7
1 2
1 5
1 1
1 3
2 5
1 4
2 4
</pre>

<h2>Output for the Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
queue
not sure
impossible
stack
priority queue
</pre>

<hr />
<i>Rujia Liu's Present 3: A Data Structure Contest Celebrating the 100th Anniversary of Tsinghua University</i><br />
<i>Special Thanks: Yiming Li</i><br />
<i>Note: Please make sure to test your program with the gift I/O files before submitting!</i><br />
</body>
</html>

11996||||||false||||||
<html>
<head>
<title>Problem J: Jewel Magic</title>
</head>
<body>

<center>
<h1>Problem J</h1>
<h2>Jewel Magic</h2>
</center>

<p>I am a magician. I have a string of emeralds and pearls. I may insert new jewels in the string, or remove old ones. I may even reverse a consecutive part of the string. At anytime, if you point to two jewels and ask me, what is the length of the longest common prefix (LCP) of jewel strings starting from these two jewels, I can answer your question instantly. Can you do better than me?</p>

<p>Formally, you'll be given a string of 0 and 1. You're to deal with four kinds of operations (in the following descriptions, L denotes the current length of the string, and jewel positions are number 1 to L numbered from left to right):</p>

<pre>1 p c</pre>
<p>Insert a jewel c after position p (0<=p<=L. p=0 means insert before the whole string). c=0 means emerald, c=1 represents pearl.</p>

<pre>2 p</pre>
<p>Remove the jewel at position p (1<=p<=L).</p>

<pre>3 p1 p2</pre>
<p>Reverse the part starting from position p1, ending at position p2 (1<=p1 < p2<=L)</p>

<pre>4 p1 p2</pre>
<p>Output the LCP length of jewel strings starting from p1 and p2 (1<=p1 < p2<=L).</p>

<h2>Input</h2>
<p>There will be several test cases. The first line of each test case contains an integer n and m (1<=n,m<=200,000), where n is the number of pearls initially, m is the number of operations. The next line contains a 01 string of length n. Each of the next m lines contains an operation. The input is terminated by end-of-file (EOF). The size of input file does not exceed 5MB.</p>

<h2>Output</h2>
<p>For each type-4 operation, output the answer.</p>

<h2>Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
12 9
000100001100
1 0 1
4 2 6
3 7 10
4 1 7
2 9
4 3 11
4 1 9
4 1 7
4 2 3
</pre>

<h2>Output for the Sample Input</h2>
<pre>
3
6
2
0
3
2
</pre>

<h2>Explanation</h2>
<p>String after operation 1 0 1: 1000100001100</p>
<p>String after operation 3 7 10: 1000101000100</p>
<p>String after operation 2 9: 100010100100</p>


<hr />
<i>Rujia Liu's Present 3: A Data Structure Contest Celebrating the 100th Anniversary of Tsinghua University</i><br />
<i>Special Thanks: Xinhao Yuan, Yao Li, Liang Dun</i><br />
<i>Note: Please make sure to test your program with the gift I/O files before submitting!</i><br />
</body>
</html>
