<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Entertainment</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Maryanna and Lucyanna play tennis every Sunday afternoon during 10 years ago.

<P>
A tennis match is determined through 5 sets. Typically the first player to win
3 sets wins the match. A set consists of games, and games, in turn, consist of points.

<P>
A game consists of a sequence of points played with the same player serving.
A game is won by the first player to have won at least four points in total and at
least two points more than the opponent. The running score of each game is described
in a manner peculiar to tennis: scores from zero to three points are described as
"love", "fifteen", "thirty", and "forty" respectively. If at least three points have
been scored by each player, and the scores are equal, the score is "deuce". If at
least three points have been scored by each side and a player has one more point
than his opponent, the score of the game is "advantage" for the player in the lead.
During informal games, "advantage" can also be called "ad in" or "ad out", depending
on whether the serving player or receiving player is ahead, respectively.

<P>
A set consists of a sequence of games played with service alternating between
games, ending when the count of games won meets certain criteria. Typically, a player
wins a set by winning at least six games and at least two games more than the opponent.

<P>
The first servers of two consecutive sets are different.

<P>
Maryanna has found out when she is the server, her winning probability of this
point is <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN>%; otherwise, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Y</I></SPAN>%. She wants to know her winning probability of the whole
match if she serves first.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
The first line contains <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $T \le 10000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12013img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10000</SPAN>), the number of test cases. T lines follow.
Each line contains two space-separated positive integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Y</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $0 < M, Y < 100$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0 &lt; <I>M</I>, <I>Y</I> &lt; 100</SPAN>).

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
For each test case, output a single line, which should begin with the case number
counting from 1, followed by Maryanna's winning percentage accurate to 4 decimal
places. See the sample for more format details.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
2
50 50
51 51
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Case #1: 50.0000%
Case #2: 63.5654%
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

______________________________________________________
12014||||||false||||||
<P>
<B>Background</B>

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Students in Fudan University have various extracurricular lives. It seems to
be widely known that many students in the Zhangjiang Campus prefer <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Tractor</SPAN> (a game
of poker with four players, also named as `80-points' or `Upgrading'), but it is
true that a considerable mass of students (especially in Department of Computer S&amp;T)
love another four player game, Mahjong, very much. Mahjong is one of the most
historied multiplayer games in China. People in several provinces prefer this game
most with various modified rules respectively.

<P>
To begin this problem, firstly, we shall introduce some basic concepts about
the game:

<P>

<UL>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Game Going</SPAN>

<P>
The game of Mahjong is played with a special set of `Mahjong Tiles', which made
by piece of wood or stones, each tile have a corresponding image on one face, which
denotes particular signification. Initially, all tiles should be randomly shuffled
and put into a pile with their (tiles') faces down, thus all their contents are hidden.
After that, the participating players each get 13 tiles as there <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> (will
be definitely explained and discussed later). Consequently, players come to the
"Dealing Section" that everyone alternatively gets one tile from the hidden pile
and includes it into this player's Holding Tiles, then chooses one tile from the
current <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> to discard. This procedure will continue until there's no tile
in the hidden pile or any player meet the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Win</SPAN> condition (Practically, there are
further modified rules such as "Bloody Battle", which pronounced as "Shyue-Chan"
in Chinese, will break this traditional rule, but we do not take them into account
in this problem).

<P>
</LI>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN>

<P>
In the process of game, players should manage their own set of tiles; these tiles
are considered as <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> of each player respectively. <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> of one
player have two particular types: <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared</SPAN> and <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden</SPAN>. <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared Tiles</SPAN> are shown
into public while <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden Tiles</SPAN> are kept private, thus one can know all the four
players' <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared Tiles</SPAN> but only his or her own <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden Tiles</SPAN>. The event causing
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden Tiles</SPAN> into <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared</SPAN> will be discussed later.

<P>
</LI>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Win</SPAN>

<P>
Before introducing the concept of how to <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Win</SPAN> a game, we have to firstly give
out two essential sub-concepts, please remember that they are quite important for
solving this problem:

<P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT>(a)</DT>
<DD><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Architecture</SPAN>

<P>
A player's Holding Tiles are just a set of tiles, they can be separated and
assembled into special <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Components</SPAN>, and all these <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Components</SPAN> compose the
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Architecture</SPAN> of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN>.

<P>
</DD>
<DT>(b)</DT>
<DD><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analysis</SPAN>

<P>
The procedure and method to determine the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Architecture</SPAN> of one's <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN>
is called <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analysis</SPAN> (please ignore the changing part of speech). <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analyzing</SPAN> one's
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> should be based on a system of related rules and might be somewhat
complex and tricky, discussed later.
</DD>
</DL>

<P>
In the rules of Mahjong, the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Target Architecture</SPAN> will be defined. As the name
implies, if a player's <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> can be <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analyzed</SPAN> into a particular <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Architecture</SPAN>
coinciding the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Target Architecture</SPAN>, then this player can <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Win</SPAN> the game.

<P>
</LI>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Score</SPAN>

<P>
After one player <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Win</SPAN> a game, the score of this <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Win</SPAN> should be judged under a scoring
rules system. The score is used for determining the worth of this <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Win</SPAN> -- It is widely
known that Mahjong is originally invited for gambling.
</LI>
</UL>

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<B>Description</B>

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Now in China, people in Sichuan Province prefer the game of Mahjong much more
than people in other area; causally, most of students in Fudan University who prefer
Mahjong come from Sichuan. To this reason, we would like to use the rule of Sichuan
Mahjong to go on this problem. With related to the traditional Mahjong rule,
regulation of this game in Sichuan Province have been changed most obviously in the
following two ways:

<P>

<UL>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Tiles simplification</SPAN>

<P>
In the original rule of Chinese Mahjong, the game is based on a large set of
tiles. All these tiles can be classified into several <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Categories</SPAN> -- including <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Simple
Category</SPAN>, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Honor Category</SPAN>, and <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Bonus Category</SPAN> -- with different functions when the
game playing. The last two kinds of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Categories</SPAN> are used in rules of some other area
of China. (In other words, has nothing to do with this problem) Sichuan Mahjong only
uses <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Simple Category</SPAN> in the game:

<P>
There are three different <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Suits</SPAN> in <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Simple Category</SPAN> and each <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Suit</SPAN> is numbered
1 to 9. They are <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Dots</SPAN>, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Bamboo</SPAN> and <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Myriads</SPAN>.

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Dots numbered 1 to 9.

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014a.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014a.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Myriads numbered 1 to 9.

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014b.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014b.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Bamboo numbered 1 to 9.

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014c.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014c.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
There are four matching tiles for each value (e.g. there are four Dots tiles
with the number 2). Generally, there are two essential aspects of information for
determining the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Kind</SPAN> of a tile: the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Suit</SPAN> and <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">number</SPAN>, thus we can uniquely name a

<P>
tile with its order of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">number</SPAN> and <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Suit</SPAN>, for example: name <!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014d.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="40" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014d.eps}">
as `<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Third Bamboo</SPAN>' and name <!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014e.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="40" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014e.eps}">
as `<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">First Dots</SPAN>'. Uniquely, players always call <!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014f.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="40" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014f.eps}">
(<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">First Bamboo</SPAN>) as `Yao-Jhee'. It is easy to calculate that there in total 108 tiles used
in the game of Sichuan Mahjong, that is, there are nine kinds in each suit and four
tiles of each <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Kind</SPAN>.

<P>
</LI>
<LI>Two Suits Limitation

<P>
This limitation constrains that at most two suits are permitted in one's <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding
Tiles</SPAN>, that is, one with all the three suits in the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> can never <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Win</SPAN>
a game (Actually, would cause some penalty).

<P>
</LI>
</UL>

<P>
After clarifying these modifications, we can go on the description of Mahjong
game.

<P>
During the process that every player gets new tiles alternatively, there are
some situations which would cause case of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Interruption</SPAN>. In detail, the rule of
Mahjong allows players to meld (`meld' is a conventional glossary in Mahjong game,
<SPAN  CLASS="textit">it is better to understand it as `<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">adopt</SPAN>'</SPAN>) tiles discarded by others and, <SPAN  CLASS="textit">after that</SPAN>,
sometimes discard a <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> for exchange. In order to explain the concept of
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Interruption</SPAN> and the way to <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Win</SPAN> the game, we shall now define some concepts of
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">component</SPAN>s (we've mentioned before but never defined) of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN>. Please
review the concept of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Target Architecture</SPAN>, a <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Target Architecture</SPAN> is composed by
a set of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Component</SPAN>s, and there are two kinds of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Component</SPAN>s:

<P>

<UL>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Sentence</SPAN>

<P>
There are two kinds of sentences:

<P>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT>(a)</DT>
<DD><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Sequence</SPAN>

<P>
A <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Sequence</SPAN> is a triple of tiles with sequential number, for example:

<P>
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014g.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="130" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014g.eps}"> and <!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014h.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="130" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014h.eps}">

<P>
There must be no skipping of numbers, nor does 9 loop around to 1. <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">The sequence
must be in the same Suit</SPAN>.

<P>
</DD>
<DT>(b)</DT>
<DD><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunk</SPAN>

<P>
A <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunk</SPAN> is a triple of tiles with identical number, for example:

<P>
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014i.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="130" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014i.eps}"> and <!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014j.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="130" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014j.eps}">

<P>
There <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunk</SPAN> must be in the same suit.

<P>
</DD>
</DL>

<P>
</LI>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Pair</SPAN>
Similar to <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunk</SPAN>, A Pair is a couple of (two) tiles with identical number and
same suit, see the following example:

<P>
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014k.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014k.eps}"> and <!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014l.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="85" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014l.eps}">

<P>
</LI>
</UL>

<P>

<P>
<BR>
With the definition of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Component</SPAN>, there are three ways of melding others'
discarded tiles, and each time if a player calls for a melding, then an <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Interruption</SPAN>
was made. However, only two ways of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Interruption</SPAN> are used in rule of Sichuan Mahjong:

<P>

<UL>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Refine</SPAN> (pronounced as `Pong' in Chinese)

<P>
If someone discards a tile while you have a <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Pair</SPAN> of the same tile in your <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden
Tiles</SPAN>, you may (but not must) <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Refine</SPAN> the discarded tiles with the pair in your
hand, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">after that these three identical tiles should become Declared</SPAN>. As we have
mentioned before, each time you <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Refine</SPAN> a tile, you should discard another <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden
Tile</SPAN> for exchange.

<P>
</LI>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Upgrade</SPAN> (pronounced as `Kong' in Chinese)

<P>
If you have got a sentence of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunk</SPAN> in <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden Tiles</SPAN> while another player discards
the identical (in fact, the only one) tile -- or you get this only identical
tile by yourself -- you may (but not must) <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Upgrade</SPAN> the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunk</SPAN> into a <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Component</SPAN>
with four same tiles (a `Kong') by melding the discarded tile. The same with
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Refining</SPAN>, after <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Upgrading</SPAN> these four identical tiles should become <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared</SPAN>.
Specially, when making an <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Upgrade</SPAN>, you should never discard another <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden Tiles</SPAN>.
It seems that after an <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Upgrade</SPAN>, an extra tile is merged into one's <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN>
(Accurately, into <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden Tiles</SPAN>), in fact these four same tiles should also be
considered as a <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunk</SPAN>, the extra tile is only for `honor', which means being
used for calculate the score but never used when Analyzing the Architecture.
</LI>
</UL>

<P>

<P>
<BR>
According to the descriptions of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Refine &amp; Upgrade</SPAN>, we can consequently conclude
that:

<UL>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared Tiles</SPAN> of a player always come from one or more melding <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Interruption</SPAN>s.
</LI>
<LI>Once a tile becomes <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared</SPAN>, it will never be back to <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden</SPAN> and never be
discarded any more.
</LI>
</UL>

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Another type of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Interruption</SPAN> is <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Win</SPAN> -- Which has been defined above -- that is,
once another player discards a particular tile, or you get such a tile by yourself,
if you can merge such a tile into your <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> and then <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analyze</SPAN> all the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding
Tiles</SPAN> (14 tiles now) as a <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Target Architecture</SPAN>, then you can <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Win</SPAN> this game. Now,
we should give the detailed explanation of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Target Architecture</SPAN> under the rule of
Sichuan Mahjong. The <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Target Architecture</SPAN> of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> can be considered as that:

<P>

<UL>
<LI>Following the Two Suits Limitation.
</LI>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Component</SPAN>s in the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Architecture</SPAN> fits one of the following two structural styles:
<DL COMPACT>
<DT>(a)</DT>
<DD>Consist of FOUR <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Sentence</SPAN>s and ONE <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Pair</SPAN>, here we name the unique <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Pair</SPAN> as `Jong'.
We name this style as <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Regular Target</SPAN>.
</DD>
<DT>(b)</DT>
<DD>Consist of SEVEN <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Pair</SPAN>s.
</DD>
</DL>
</LI>
</UL>

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Remember that the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared Tiles</SPAN> is a group of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Sentences</SPAN> (an <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Upgraded Chunk</SPAN> can
be considered as an ordinary <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunk</SPAN> with `honor' for scoring, discussed later). <SPAN  CLASS="textit">When
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analyzing</SPAN> the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN>, the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared Tiles</SPAN> and <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden Tiles</SPAN> must be considered
separately and can never be mixed; furthermore, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared Tiles</SPAN> can only be <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analyzed</SPAN>
as several <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunks</SPAN> (ordinary <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunk</SPAN> or <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Upgraded Chunk</SPAN>) but never <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Sequences</SPAN>.</SPAN> To finish
a <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Target Architecture</SPAN>, we need 14 tiles, (ignored extra tile from <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Upgrading</SPAN>),
however, each one has only 13 <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN>. Therefore, players always need another
extra tile to complete the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Architecture</SPAN>; this situation gives the concept of
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Expected Tile</SPAN>: If a player's <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> can fit the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Target Architecture</SPAN> by adding
a particular and <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">existing</SPAN> tile, then such a tile is considered as one of the player's
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Expecting Tiles</SPAN>. <SPAN  CLASS="textit">Pay attention on the word `existing' please: that is, if you have
held all such existing (four) tiles, then this kind of tile cannot be considered
as <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Expected Tile</SPAN>.</SPAN>

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Now we come to specify the rule of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Scoring</SPAN>: once a player meets the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Target
Architecture</SPAN> (has got <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Win</SPAN>), he or she will have the basic score of ONE, that is,
the lowest score of a <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Win</SPAN> is ONE. In addition, there are lots of specific conditions
for awarding further extra scores. See the following items for description:

<P>

<UL>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Dragon</SPAN> (pronounced as `Kong' and `Gher' in Chinese, especially in Chengdu
dialect)

<P>
If a player has collected all the four tiles of same kind of tiles in his or
her <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN>, then we say this kind become a <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Dragon</SPAN>. Each Dragon gives the
owner ONE additional score.

<P>
Apparently, once a player making an <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Interruption</SPAN> of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Upgrade</SPAN>, a <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared Dragon</SPAN>
is created, but there's another situation: sometimes player shows a <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared
Chunk</SPAN> in <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared Tiles</SPAN> but hides the rest one of that kind of tiles in <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden
Tiles</SPAN>, or even hides all the four same tiles in <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden Tiles</SPAN>, these two cases
will also be acknowledged as <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Dragon</SPAN>.

<P>
</LI>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Seven Couples</SPAN> (pronounced as "Chee Dwee" in Chinese)

<P>
If the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Architecture</SPAN> meets the second style of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Target Architecture</SPAN> -- in other
words: consists by seven pairs -- then such an <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Architecture</SPAN> can be identified
as <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Seven Couples</SPAN>, this special style gives the owner TWO additional score.

<P>
</LI>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Purely</SPAN> (pronounced as "Ching Yi-Seh" in Chinese)

<P>
If one players all <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> (Attention, not only the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden</SPAN> or <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared
Tiles</SPAN>) have the same <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Suit</SPAN>, then <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Purely</SPAN> can be identified, TWO additional score
awarded.

<P>
</LI>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunkious</SPAN> (pronounced as "Dwee-Tsi Hoo" in Chinese)

<P>
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunkious</SPAN> is a special style of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Regular Target</SPAN>, the condition is that all
sentences of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> are <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunks</SPAN>, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Sequence</SPAN> never appears. <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunkious</SPAN> is
worth ONE additional score.

<P>
</LI>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Sky-ground Related</SPAN> (pronounced as "Tai Yao-Jhew" in Chinese)

<P>
This is a very unique and confusing rule in Sichuan Mahjong, even not all players
in Sichuan admit this condition, but in this problem we take it into account
for generalization.

<P>
No matter what style of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Target Architectures</SPAN>, the condition of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Sky-ground
Related</SPAN> asks each components in the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Architecture</SPAN> have at least one tile has
numbers of 1 or 9. For instance, the following components are acceptable:

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014m.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="500" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014m.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
This special style gives the owner TWO additional scores.

<P>
</LI>
<LI><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Royal Chunkious</SPAN> (pronounced as "Jong Dwee" in Chinese)

<P>
As the name implies, <SPAN  CLASS="textit">the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Royal Chunkious</SPAN> is a special style of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunkious</SPAN></SPAN>, thus
if an Architecture does not meet the condition of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunkious</SPAN>, it can never be
judged as <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Royal</SPAN>. This style means in an Architecture of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunkious</SPAN>, only tiles
with numbers 2, 5 and 8 appear. As examples, the following components are valid:

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014n.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014n.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Royal Chunkious</SPAN> worth TWO <SPAN  CLASS="textit"><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">more</SPAN></SPAN> scores <SPAN  CLASS="textit"><SPAN  CLASS="textbf">than</SPAN></SPAN> normal <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunkious</SPAN>.

<P>
</LI>
<LI>There are some other items relating to Scoring such as Seizing (`Chiang Kong'),
Lucky Flower (`Kong Hsiang-Hwa'), but are not considered in this problem.
</LI>
</UL>

<P>

<P>
<BR>
In order to solve this problem, the concept of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">CONSISTENCE</SPAN> might be somewhat
a critical logic. We've just listed all the special situation causing extra scores
for the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Winning</SPAN> player, you may come up with the idea that some of them can occur
simultaneously, for example, the following <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> (has <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Won</SPAN>):

<P>
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden Tiles</SPAN> are: <!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014o.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="400" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014o.eps}">
, and <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared Tiles</SPAN> are: <!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014p.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="200" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014p.eps}">
and <!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014q.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="130" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014q.eps}"><!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014r.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="40" HEIGHT="50" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014r.eps}">.

<P>
This set of Holding Tiles can be obviously <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analyzed</SPAN> as an <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Architecture</SPAN> which meeting
the condition of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunkious</SPAN>, <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Purely</SPAN> and double <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Dragons</SPAN> (just <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analyze</SPAN> as how they
are displayed in the example), and worth 1(basic) + 1(<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Chunkious</SPAN>) + 2(<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Purely</SPAN>) +
1(<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Dragon</SPAN>)*2 = 6 scores.

<P>
However, when we consider another example:

<P>
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden Tiles</SPAN> are (there is no <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared Tiles</SPAN> in this example):

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014s.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="500" HEIGHT="120" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014s.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
At first glance, we can <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analyze</SPAN> them as an <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Architecture</SPAN> fitting rule of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Seven Couples</SPAN>,
which is trivial; yet we can also <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analyze</SPAN> them in another way (fitting the rule of
<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Sky-ground Related</SPAN>):

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<!-- MATH
 $\epsfbox{p12014t.eps}$
 -->
<IMG
 WIDTH="500" HEIGHT="120" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="\epsfbox{p12014t.eps}">
</DIV>

<P>
This way, can we judge the score as 1(basic) + 2(<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Seven Couples</SPAN>) + 2(<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Sky-ground
Related</SPAN>) = 5? <SPAN  CLASS="textit">The answer is negative</SPAN>. For explaining this paradox, please remind
yourself to notice the definition of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Win</SPAN>: a player gets Win means he or she can <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analyze</SPAN>
the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> into a <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Target Architecture</SPAN>, when we calculate the score, we are
in fact aiming at such an resulting <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Architecture</SPAN>, scilicet, <SPAN  CLASS="textit">scoring is based on a
particular <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Architecture</SPAN> but not based on the set of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN></SPAN>, that is, if a
set of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN> can be <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analyzed</SPAN> as more than one <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Target Architectures</SPAN>, they
are independent when scoring and cannot merge. Now we can give the correct answer
of the last example: if <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analyze</SPAN> in first way, then 1(basic) + 2(<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Seven Couples</SPAN>) =
3; otherwise, if use the second way, then 1(basic) + 2(<SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Sky-ground Related</SPAN>) = 3,
therefore the final score should be considered as 3. The last remaining confusion
of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">scoring</SPAN> is that: if two or more <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analyzed Architecture</SPAN> has different scores, which
should be the delegate? The policy for dealing with this question is totally
determined by real players, in this problem we choose the higher one -- <SPAN  CLASS="textit">we choose
the highest possible score among all <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Analyzed Target Architecture</SPAN></SPAN>.

<P>

<P>
<BR>
Your task in this problem is: given a player's <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN>, please determine
all this player's <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Expected Tiles</SPAN> (if exists) and their corresponding scores.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
The first line of input file is a integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12014a.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100</SPAN>) indicating number of test
cases, then <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> lines are following. Each line describes a case of <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Holding Tiles</SPAN>: two
separated strings, the first string giving the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Hidden Tiles</SPAN> and the second one giving
the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared Tiles</SPAN>. If there are no <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Declared</SPAN> ones, the second string would be `<TT>NONE</TT>'
(quotes for clarity). Each tile contains two characters, the first one is a digit
character which indicates this tile's number and the second is a capital letter
within `<TT>D</TT>',`<TT>B</TT>' and `<TT>M</TT>', that `<TT>D</TT>' for Dots and `<TT>B</TT>' for Bamboo and `<TT>M</TT>' for Myriads,
indicating tile's Suit. For example, `<TT>7M</TT>' means Seventh Myriad and `<TT>1B</TT>' means First
Bamboo (also known as `Yao-Jhee'). <SPAN  CLASS="textit">You may assume that all the input cases are valid
in the rule of Sichuan Mahjong</SPAN>.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each case, firstly output a single line containing the case number counting
from 1. Then, if there's no <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Expected Tiles</SPAN>, output a single lines containing string
of `<TT>NONE</TT>' (quotes for clarity); otherwise, output all the player's <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Expected Tiles</SPAN>
(with the same format of input) and then output their corresponding scores after
each <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Expected Tiles</SPAN>, separated with a colon (`<TT>:</TT>') and a space. <SPAN  CLASS="textit">All the <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Expected
Tiles</SPAN> are printed in separated lines. Any extra blanks (spaces or empty lines) will
cause `Wrong Answer'</SPAN>. The outputted <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Expected Tiles</SPAN> should be sorted in this way:
first sorted by <SPAN  CLASS="textbf">Suits</SPAN>, `<TT>D</TT>' at first and then `<TT>B</TT>' and `<TT>M</TT>' in the last; second sorted
by their numbers, smaller number has higher priority.

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<B>Hints:</B>
Consider the third case of sample input, it seems that adding a tile `<TT>1D</TT>' may
construct the Target Architecture, however, there does not exist another `<TT>1D</TT>' in
all the tiles.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
7
8D8D8D5D2D2D2D 6D6D6D7D7D7D
8D8D8D5D2D2D2D6D6D6D7D7D7D NONE
1D1D1D1D 3D3D3D4D4D4D5D5D5D
2D2D2D5D5D5D2M2M2M5M5M8M8M NONE
1D1D1D1D2D2D2D2D3D3D3D3D9M NONE
1D1D1D1D9D9D9D9D1M1M1M1M9M NONE
2D2D3D3D4D5D5D6D6D7D7D8D8D NONE
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Case #1:
5D: 4
Case #2:
4D: 3
5D: 4
6D: 4
7D: 4
8D: 4
Case #3:
NONE
Case #4:
5M: 4
8M: 4
Case #5:
9M: 6
Case #6:
9M: 8
Case #7:
1D: 3
4D: 5
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Google is Feeling Lucky</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Google is Feeling Lucky">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Google is Feeling Lucky</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Google is one of the most famous Internet search engines which hosts and develops
a number of Internet-based services and products. On its search engine website, an
interesting button `I'm feeling lucky' attracts our eyes. This feature could allow
the user skip the search result page and goes directly to the first ranked page.
Amazing! It saves a lot of time.

<P>
The question is, when one types some keywords and presses `I'm feeling lucky'
button, which web page will appear? Google does a lot and comes up with excellent
approaches to deal with it. In this simplified problem, let us just consider that
Google assigns every web page an integer-valued relevance. The most related page
will be chosen. If there is a tie, all the pages with the highest relevance are
possible to be chosen.

<P>
Your task is simple, given 10 web pages and their relevance. Just pick out all
the possible candidates which will be served to the user when `I'm feeling lucky'.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
The input contains multiple test cases. The number of test cases <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> is in the
first line of the input file.

<P>
For each test case, there are 10 lines, describing the web page and the relevance.
Each line contains a character string without any blank characters denoting the URL
of this web page and an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>V</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> denoting the relevance of this web page. The length
of the URL is between 1 and 100 inclusively. (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le V_i \le 100$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12015img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>V</I><SUB>i</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12015img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100</SPAN>)

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each test case, output several lines which are the URLs of the web pages
which are possible to be chosen. The order of the URLs is the same as the input.
Please look at the sample output for further information of output format.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
2
www.youtube.com 1
www.google.com 2
www.google.com.hk 3
www.alibaba.com 10
www.taobao.com 5
www.bad.com 10
www.good.com 7
www.fudan.edu.cn 8
www.university.edu.cn 9
acm.university.edu.cn 10
www.youtube.com 1
www.google.com 2
www.google.com.hk 3
www.alibaba.com 11
www.taobao.com 5
www.bad.com 10
www.good.com 7
www.fudan.edu.cn 8
acm.university.edu.cn 9
acm.university.edu.cn 10
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Case #1:
www.alibaba.com
www.bad.com
acm.university.edu.cn
Case #2:
www.alibaba.com
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

  Jens Lippmann, Marek Rouchal, Martin Wilck and others -->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Herbicide</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Herbicide">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Herbicide</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Professor Z. has a courtyard beside his house. In the past, he loved to clean
it and prune the flowers in his yard. However, with the JavaFF class taught by
Professor Z. being offered, he indulged in assigning boring homework to the students
and had no time for caring his yard. Consequently, weeds begin to grow up and then
his yard becomes overgrown.

<P>
In the last weekend, after Professor Z. assigned a mass of boring homework again,
he suddenly brought his yard to mind. And after he saw the weedy ground, he decided
to remove the weeds. But he did not have much time to deal with the garden's problem
because of the uncompleted plans of further boring homework in the next JavaFF class.
He sprayed herbicide on the ground optionally and, strangely, herbicide was sprayed
as several simple polygons on the ground. In order to determine whether he should
continue his work or not, Professor Z. needed to know how many weeds were covered
by the herbicide. Notice that we assume that the weeds were not killed by the
herbicide applied before. In the other words, a single weed can be counted several
times in different polygon of herbicide.

<P>
It seems that counting this number is quite a tough job. Then he asked Maryanna,
one of his students in JavaFF class, for help. But Maryanna has no time because her
boring homework had never been finished. Please help her!

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
The very first line of input contains an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12016img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">100</SPAN>) indicating the
number of test cases.

<P>
The first line of each test case is an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $N \le 1000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12016img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1000</SPAN>), <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> is the number
of weeds in Professor Z's yard. In the following <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines, each line has a pair of
integers <!-- MATH
 $(X_i, Y_i)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>X</I><SUB>i</SUB>, <I>Y</I><SUB>i</SUB>)</SPAN> denoting the coordinate of a weed <!-- MATH
 $(-10000 \le X_i, Y_i \le 10000)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(- 10000<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12016img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>X</I><SUB>i</SUB>, <I>Y</I><SUB>i</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12016img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10000)</SPAN>.
You can assume all the coordinates are unique. The next line is an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $M \le
1000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12016img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1000</SPAN>) which denotes the number of polygons covered by herbicide, all these polygon's
vertices are located on one of the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> weeds, then <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN> polygons descriptions are following.
Each polygon <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>P</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> has two lines, the first line of ith polygon has an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>S</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> (<!-- MATH
 $3
\le S_i \le N$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">3<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12016img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>S</I><SUB>i</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12016img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I></SPAN>) denoting the number of vertices in this polygon. The following line
contains <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>S</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> integers, describing the vertices of this polygon in clockwise or
counter-clockwise order. In detail, each integer in this line is an index of the
coordinates of the <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> weeds listed before. Notice that the indexes start from 1. See
the sample input for further details.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
For each test case, output <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN> lines, each line has a single integer indicating
the number of weeds covered by the corresponding polygon. If a weed lies on the edge
of a polygon, then we consider such a weed as being covered.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
1
6
1 1
3 2
2 3
1 -1
-1 -2
-1 1
3
3
5 4 3
3
1 5 6
5
5 4 2 3 6
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Case #1:
4
3
6
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Imitation</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Imitation">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Imitation</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Iris is a student of ethology studying the animal behavior. She is interested
by the imitation behavior of animals. Imitation is an advanced behavior whereby an
individual observes and replicates another's.

<P>
Iris is such a good researcher that she builds a mathematical model to describe
the body figure of animals. She describes the body as a number of joints. And the
figure or the status of animal body can be denoted as a set of ordered pairs of two
different joints. To study the imitation of the animals, Iris defines the correlation
of joints. She defines the correlation as the transitive closure of the ordered pairs
of body status with its reflexive pairs eliminated. That is to say, the correlation
is an anti-reflexive relation. In this case, we could say that one body status is
imitating the other one when the correlations of both body statuses are the same.

<P>
For example, for the joint set <!-- MATH
 $\{J1, J2, J3\}$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">{<I>J</I>1, <I>J</I>2, <I>J</I>3}</SPAN>. The first body status contains the
ordered pair <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>J</I>1, <I>J</I>2)</SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>J</I>2, <I>J</I>3)</SPAN>. And the second body status contains the ordered
pair <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>J</I>1, <I>J</I>2)</SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>J</I>2, <I>J</I>3)</SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>J</I>1, <I>J</I>3)</SPAN>. We could say that the first body status is
imitating the other one because both of the correlation sets are <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>J</I>1, <I>J</I>2)</SPAN>, <SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>J</I>2, <I>J</I>3)</SPAN>,
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>J</I>1, <I>J</I>3)</SPAN> since the definition of the correlation is the transitive closure of body
status.

<P>
For a given body status, that is, a given set of ordered pairs of joints, Iris
want to get another body status, which is imitating the given one. At the same time,
the desired body status must contain the minimum number of ordered pairs or the
maximum number of ordered pairs. Your task is to calculate the minimum number and
the maximum number.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
There are several test cases. The first line of the input contains a single
integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN> denoting the number of test cases. There are about 100 test cases, but
90% of them are relatively small.

<P>
For each test case, the first line contains two integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN> where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> is the
number of joints of both the given body status and the desired body status, <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN> is
the number of ordered pairs of the given body status. (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le N \le 1000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12017img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12017img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1000</SPAN>, <!-- MATH
 $0 \le M \le
10000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12017img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>M</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12017img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">10000</SPAN>)

<P>
Next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>M</I></SPAN> lines, each line denoting an ordered pair <!-- MATH
 $(X_i, Y_i)$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">(<I>X</I><SUB>i</SUB>, <I>Y</I><SUB>i</SUB>)</SPAN>. The <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Y</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> are
integers between 1 and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN>. Note that we consider the joints as the number between
1 and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN>.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
For each test case, output two integers denoting the minimum and maximum number
of ordered pairs of the desired set. Two integers are separated by a single
whitespace.

<P>

<P>
<BR>

<B>Hint:</B>
In mathematics, the transitive closure of a binary relation <TT>R</TT> on a set <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I></SPAN> is the
transitive relation <TT>R+</TT> on set <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I></SPAN> such that <TT>R+</TT> contains <TT>R</TT> and <TT>R+</TT> is minimal. If the
binary relation itself is transitive, then the transitive closure will be that same
binary relation; otherwise, the transitive closure will be a different relation.
A relation <TT>R</TT> on a set <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I></SPAN> is transitive if, for all <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I>, <I>y</I>, <I>z</I></SPAN> in <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I></SPAN>, whenever 
<!-- MATH
 $x \texttt{R} y$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I><texttt>R</texttt><I>y</I></SPAN> and <!-- MATH
 $y \texttt{R} z$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I><texttt>R</texttt><I>z</I></SPAN> then <!-- MATH
 $x \texttt{R} z$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I><texttt>R</texttt><I>z</I></SPAN>. Examples of transitive relations include the equality relation
on any set, the "less than or equal" relation on any linearly ordered set, and the
relation "<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I></SPAN> was born before <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I></SPAN>" on the set of all people. Symbolically, this can be
denoted as: if <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I> &lt; <I>y</I></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>y</I> &lt; <I>z</I></SPAN> then <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>x</I> &lt; <I>z</I></SPAN>.

<P>
<DIV ALIGN="RIGHT">
(From Wikipedia::transitive closure) 

</DIV>

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
3
3 3
1 2
2 3
1 3
3 3
1 2
2 3
3 1
9 9
1 2
2 3
3 1
4 5
5 6
6 4
7 8
8 9
9 7
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Case #1: 2 3
Case #2: 3 6
Case #3: 9 18
</PRE> 

<P>


<P>
<BR><HR>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</HTML>

<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Juice Extractor</TITLE>
<META NAME="description" CONTENT="Juice Extractor">
<META NAME="keywords" CONTENT="htmlatex">
<META NAME="resource-type" CONTENT="document">
<META NAME="distribution" CONTENT="global">

<META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="LaTeX2HTML v2008">
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Style-Type" CONTENT="text/css">

<LINK REL="STYLESHEET" HREF="htmlatex.css">

</HEAD>

<BODY LANG="EN" BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>

<H1><BR CLEAR=ALL><CENTER><TABLE BGCOLOR=#0000ff><TR><TD><B><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR=#FFff00>&nbsp;<A NAME="SECTION0001000000000000000000">
Juice Extractor</A>&nbsp;</FONT></B></TABLE></CENTER>
</H1>

<P>
Jerry loses himself in the interesting game: Fruit Ninja. Fruit Ninja is a game
of iPhone and iPad in which the players cut the fruits coming from the bottom of
the screen and gain the bonus from cutting more than two fruits with a single slice.
Once a fruit is cut, it breaks into small pieces and cannot be cut any more.

<P>
After months of training, he becomes pro of this game. Actually, he can cut all
the fruits on the screen at any time. Jerry also has a bad habit that he has no willing
to leave some fruits for the future cutting. In the other words, after Jerry cuts
the fruits, all the fruits on the screen breaks and no one left. That is why all
his friends call him `Juice Extractor'.

<P>
Now he only consider about the bonus, when he cuts more than two fruits, he can
gain some bonus scores as same as the number of fruits he slice at that time. For
example, if Jerry cuts 4 fruits with a single slice, he can get 4 scores from this
slice.

<P>
After Jerry gets the fruit schedule, he knows the appearing time and the
disappearing time for every single fruit. He can only cut a fruit into pieces between
its appearing time and disappearing time inclusive. He wants to know the maximum
possible bonus scores he can receive.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001001000000000000000">
Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>
There are several test cases; the first line of the input contains a single
integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I></SPAN>, denoting the number of the test cases. (<SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>T</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12018img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">200</SPAN>)

<P>
For each test case, the first line contains an integer <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN>, denoting the total
number of fruits. (<!-- MATH
 $1 \le N \le 1000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">1<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12018img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>N</I><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12018img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1000</SPAN>)

<P>
The next <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>N</I></SPAN> lines, each line describe a fruit. For each line, there are two
integers <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Y</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN>, where <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>X</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> is the appearing time of the fruit and <SPAN CLASS="MATH"><I>Y</I><SUB>i</SUB></SPAN> is the
disappearing time of this fruit. (<!-- MATH
 $0 \le X_i \le Y_i \le 1000000000$
 -->
<SPAN CLASS="MATH">0<IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12018img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>X</I><SUB>i</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12018img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$"><I>Y</I><SUB>i</SUB><IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="31" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
 SRC="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/12018img1.png" 
 ALT="$ \le$">1000000000</SPAN>)

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001002000000000000000">
Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
For each test case, output a single integer denoting the maximum scores that
Jerry could possibly gain. See the sample for further details.

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001003000000000000000">
Sample Input</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
1
10
1 10
2 11
3 12
4 13
13 14
14 15
13 19
20 22
21 23
22 24
</PRE> 

<P>

<H2><FONT size=4 COLOR=#ff0000><A NAME="SECTION0001004000000000000000">
Sample Output</A>&nbsp;</FONT>
</H2>

<P>
<PRE>
Case #1: 10
</PRE> 

<P>

<P>

12019||||||false||||||
<html><head>
<meta name="autor" content="Gines Garcia Mateos, Murcia 05/05/11, dedicated to RYS">
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1"><title>Doom's Day Algorithm</title>

</head>
<body lang="EN">
<div align="center">
<center>
<table bgcolor="#0060f0" border="0">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><font color="#c0ffff" size="5"><b>&nbsp;A
- Doom's Day Algorithm&nbsp;</b></font></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</center>
</div>
<h2><a name="SECTION1"><font color="#0070e8">Background</font></a></h2>
<p>No. Doom's day algorithm is not a method to compute which day
the world will end. It is an algorithm created by the mathematician
John Horton Conway, to calculate which day of the week (Monday,
Tuesday, etc.) corresponds to a certain date.</p>
<p>This algorithm is based in the idea of the&nbsp;<span style="font-weight: bold;">doomsday</span>, a certain
day of
the week which always occurs in the same dates. For example, 4/4 (the
4th of April), 6/6 (the 6th of June), 8/8 (the 8th of August), 10/10
(the 10th of October) and 12/12 (the 12th of December) are dates which
always occur in doomsday. All years have their own doomsday.</p>
<p>In year 2011, doomsday is Monday. So all of 4/4, 6/6, 8/8,
10/10 and 12/12 are Mondays. Using that information, you can easily
compute any other date. For example, the 13th of December 2011 will be
Tuesday, the 14th of December 2011 will be Wednesday, etc.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION1"><font color="#0070e8">The
Problem</font></a></h2>
<p>Other days which occur on doomsday are 5/9, 9/5, 7/11 and
11/7. Also, in
leap years, we have the following doomsdays: 1/11 (the 11th of January)
and 2/22 (the 22nd of
Febrary), and in non-leap years 1/10 and 2/21.</p>
<p>Given a date of year 2011, you have to compute which day of
the week it occurs.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION2"><font color="#0070e8">Input</font></a></h2>
<p>The input can contain different test cases. The first line of
the input indicates the number of test cases.</p>
<p>For each test case, there is a line with two numbers: M D. M
represents the month (from 1 to 12) and D represents the day (from 1 to
31). The date will always be valid.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION2"><font color="#0070e8">Output</font></a></h2>
<p>For each test case, you have to output the day of the week
where that date occurs in 2011. The days of the week will be: Monday,
Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION3"><font color="#0070e8">Sample
Input</font></a></h2>
<pre>8<br>1 6<br>2 28<br>4 5<br>5 26<br>8 1<br>11 1<br>12 25<br>12 31<br><br></pre>
<h2><a name="SECTION4"><font color="#0070e8">Sample
Output</font></a></h2>
<pre>Thursday<br>Monday<br>Tuesday<br>Thursday<br>Monday<br>Tuesday<br>Sunday<br>Saturday<br><br></pre>
<hr>
<p align="right"><font color="#000040"><small><small><a href="http://dis.um.es/contest" target="_blank">OMP'11</a><br>
<a href="http://www.um.es/informatica" target="_blank">Facultad
de Informatica<br>
</a><a href="http://www.um.es" target="_blank">Universidad
de Murcia (SPAIN)</a></small></small></font></p>
</body></html>
______________________________________________________
12020||||||false||||||
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN">
<html><head>
<meta name="autor" content="Gines Garcia Mateos, Murcia 05/05/11">
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1"><title>The election day</title></head>
<body lang="EN">
<div align="center">
<center>
<table bgcolor="#0060f0" border="0">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><font color="#c0ffff" size="5"><b>&nbsp;B
- The Election Day&nbsp;</b></font></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</center>
</div>
<h2><a name="SECTION1"><font color="#0070e8">Background</font></a></h2>
<p>There are more than 8.000 municipalities in Spain. Each
municipality has a number of councilors, which have to be
elected in the upcoming municipal elections. The number of councilors
elected from each political party must be proportional to the number of
votes obtained by that party.</p>
<p>Obviously, this can be a little unfair. For example, assume
that we have to elect 2 councilors in a certain municipality where
party <span style="font-weight: bold;">A</span> has
received 65
votes, and party <span style="font-weight: bold;">B</span>
has received 35 votes. Then, both parties would obtain 50% of the
councilors (one councilor for each party).</p>
<p>Therefore, in order to reduce these unfair situations, we
decide that we will always elect 100 councilors for each municipality.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION1"><font color="#0070e8">The
Problem</font></a></h2>
<p>Given the number of votes for each party, you have to compute
the number of councilors assigned to each
party, assuming that the total number of councilors is 100.</p>
<p>You have to observe the <span style="font-weight: bold;">rule
of proportionality</span>: the number of
assigned councilors has to be proportional (the maximum possible) to
the number
of obtained votes. In other words, there exists a number of votes, <span style="font-style: italic;">x</span>, such that when a
party has <span style="font-style: italic;">x</span>
votes, then they win a councilor.</p>
<p>If
two or more parties have exactly the same proportion to obtain a
councilor, then you have to assign it to the first party in
alphabetical order. For example, if&nbsp;three parties have 1/3 of
the
votes, then the first party in alphabetical order would have 34
councilors, and the other parties 33 councilors.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION2"><font color="#0070e8">Input</font></a></h2>
<p>The input can contain different test cases. The first line of
the input indicates the number of test cases.</p>
<p>For each test case, the first line contains one natural number<span style="font-style: italic;"></span>, <span style="font-style: italic;">P</span>,&nbsp;indicating
the number of existing political parties. You can assume that <span style="font-style: italic;">P</span> &lt;= 4.</p>
<p>The following two lines contain the text:</p>
<p><span style="font-family: monospace;"><span style="font-weight: bold;">BLANK</span> </span><span style="font-style: italic; font-family: monospace;">B</span><br style="font-family: monospace;">
<span style="font-family: monospace;"><span style="font-weight: bold;">INVALID</span> </span><span style="font-style: italic; font-family: monospace;">I</span></p>
<p>Where <span style="font-style: italic;">B</span>
and <span style="font-style: italic;">I</span>
indicate the number of blank and invalid votes, respectively. Next,
there are <span style="font-style: italic;">P</span>
lines, one for each party. Each line contains two values: a string
without blank spaces, indicating the name of the party; and a number,
indicating the number of votes&nbsp;for that party.</p>
<p>You can assume that the number of votes for a party is always
between 0 and 1000,
inclusive.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION2"><font color="#0070e8">Output</font></a></h2>
<p>For each test case, you have to output the number of
councilors
obtained by each party, in the same order as they appear in the input.
Thus, you have to output <span style="font-style: italic;">P</span>
lines, with the name of the party and the
number of councilors assigned to that party, separated by a blank space.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION3"><font color="#0070e8">Sample
Input</font></a></h2>
<pre>4<br>2<br>BLANK 0<br>INVALID 4<br>A 65<br>B 35<br>3<br>BLANK 203<br>INVALID 287<br>Pragmatics 50<br>Paradigmatics 50<br>Programatics 50<br>3<br>BLANK 22<br>INVALID 1000<br>SimpleMinds 5<br>UniqueThinking 3<br>RunWithMoney 6<br>4<br>BLANK 0<br>INVALID 92<br>One 261<br>Two 283<br>Three 61<br>Four 12<br></pre>
<h2><a name="SECTION4"><font color="#0070e8">Sample
Output</font></a></h2>
<pre>A 65<br>B 35<br>Pragmatics 33<br>Paradigmatics 34<br>Programatics 33<br>SimpleMinds 36<br>UniqueThinking 21<br>RunWithMoney 43<br>One 43<br>Two 46<br>Three 10<br>Four 1<br></pre>
<p>* Observe that, in the last case, the number of votes to win
a councilor is <span style="font-style: italic;">x</span>
= 6.0695. That is, a party wins a councilor for each 6.0695 votes
obtained. </p>
<hr>
<p align="right"><font color="#000040"><small><small><a href="http://dis.um.es/contest" target="_blank">OMP'11</a><br>
<a href="http://www.um.es/informatica" target="_blank">Facultad
de Informatica<br>
</a><a href="http://www.um.es" target="_blank">Universidad
de Murcia (SPAIN)</a></small></small></font></p>
</body></html>
______________________________________________________
12021||||||false||||||
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN">
<html><head>
<meta name="autor" content="Gines Garcia Mateos, Murcia 05/05/11">
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1"><title>Universal elections</title>

</head>
<body lang="EN">
<div align="center">
<center>
<table bgcolor="#0060f0" border="0">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><font color="#c0ffff" size="5"><b>&nbsp;C
- Universal Elections<br>
<!-- Y, ¿por qué se llama "He did it again?" -->
</b></font>
<div style="text-align: center;"><font color="#c0ffff" size="5"><b>(or "he did it
again!")&nbsp;</b></font></div>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</center>
</div>
<h2><a name="SECTION1"><font color="#0070e8">Background</font></a></h2>
<!-- Pues muy sencillo, porque igual que el año pasado, aquí abajo viene la solución :-)))
No se lo digas a nadie ;-) -->
<p>After solving the easy problem of municipal elections... we
want more! More parties! More voters! More councilors!</p>
<p>Would you be able to deal with hundreds of parties, billions
of councilors, trillions of voters?</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION1"><font color="#0070e8">The
Problem</font></a></h2>
<p>Given the number of councilors that have to be elected, the
number of votes for each party, and the number of blank and invalid
votes, you have to compute the number of councilors assigned to each
party.</p>
<p>As in the previous problem, you have to observe the rule of
proportionality: the number of
assigned councilors has to be proportional (the maximum possible) to
the number
of obtained votes. In other words, there exists a number of votes, <span style="font-style: italic;">X</span>, such that when a
party has <span style="font-style: italic;">X</span>
votes, then they win a councilor. If
two or more parties have exactly the same proportion to obtain a
councilor, then you have to assign it to the first party in
alphabetical order.<br>
</p>
<!-- Lo primero de todo es usar el tipo long long. El proceso de asignación se puede hacer
en dos pasos. En primer lugar, se asignan los concejales de manera proporcional, tomando
partes enteras por abajo. Como resultado, pueden quedar algunos concejales sin asignar.
Así que el segundo paso es usar la ley D'Hont para asignar los concejales que queden. -->
<h2><a name="SECTION2"><font color="#0070e8">Input</font></a></h2>
<p>The input can contain different test cases. The first line of
the input indicates the number of test cases.</p>
<p>For each test case, the first line contains 2 natural numbers:
<span style="font-style: italic;">N</span>, <span style="font-style: italic;">P</span>. Number <span style="font-style: italic;">N</span> indicates the
number of councilors to be elected, while <span style="font-style: italic;">P</span> indicates the
number of existing political parties.</p>
<p>The following two lines contain the text:</p>
<p><span style="font-family: monospace;"><span style="font-weight: bold;">BLANK</span> </span><span style="font-style: italic; font-family: monospace;">B</span><br style="font-family: monospace;">
<span style="font-family: monospace;"><span style="font-weight: bold;">INVALID</span> </span><span style="font-style: italic; font-family: monospace;">I</span></p>
<p>Where <span style="font-style: italic;">B</span>
and <span style="font-style: italic;">I</span>
indicate the number of blank and invalid votes, respectively. Next,
there are <span style="font-style: italic;">P</span>
lines, one for each party. Each line contains two values: a string
without blank spaces, indicating the name of the party; and a number,
indicating the number of votes for that party.</p>
<p>You can assume that <span style="font-style: italic;">N</span>
and the number of votes are always between 0 and 10<sup>16</sup>,
inclusive.</p>
<!-- Como la ley D'Hont es un poco larga de explicar, va a ser más fácil poner el código...
void segundoReparto (void)
{
long double maxv, actv;
int nmax;
while (nconc < N) {
nmax= 0;
maxv= ((long double) votos[0])/((long double) concejales[0] + 1.0);
for (int i= 1; i<P; i++) {
actv= ((long double) votos[i])/((long double) concejales[i] + 1.0);
if (actv > maxv || (actv==maxv && nombres[i] < nombres[nmax])) {
nmax= i;
maxv= actv;
}
}
concejales[nmax]++;
nconc++;
}
}
-->
<h2><a name="SECTION2"><font color="#0070e8">Output</font></a></h2>
<p>For each test case, you have to output the councilors obtained
for each party, in the same order as they appear in the input.
Thus, you have to output <span style="font-style: italic;">P</span>
lines, with the name of the party and the
number of councilors assigned to that party, separated by a blank space.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION3"><font color="#0070e8">Sample
Input</font></a></h2>
<pre>4<br>2 2<br>BLANK 0<br>INVALID 4<br>A 65<br>B 35<br>4 3<br>BLANK 203<br>INVALID 287<br>Pragmatics 50<br>Paradigmatics 50<br>Programatics 50<br>360000000000 5<br>BLANK 0<br>INVALID 92<br>One 26572000000000<br>Two 28863000000000<br>Three 6231000000000<br>Four 832000000000<br>Five 0<br>360 5<br>BLANK 0<br>INVALID 92<br>One 26572000000000<br>Two 28863000000000<br>Three 6231000000000<br>Four 832000000000<br>Five 0<br><br></pre>
<!-- Y esta es la forma de hacer el primer reparto
void primerReparto (void)
{
long double proporcion= N;
proporcion/= V;
long long act;
nconc= 0;
for (int i= 0; i<P; i++) {
act= votos[i]*proporcion;
concejales[i]= act;
nconc+= act;
}
}

<h2><a name="SECTION4"><font color="#0070e8">Sample
Output</font></a></h2>
<pre>A 1<br>B 1<br>Pragmatics 1<br>Paradigmatics 2<br>Programatics 1<br>One 153059617908<br>Two 166256200199<br>Three 35891708534<br>Four 4792473359<br>Five 0<br>One 153<br>Two 167<br>Three 36<br>Four 4<br>Five 0<br></pre>

<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN">
<html><head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1"><title>Ordering T-shirts</title></head>
<body lang="EN">
<div align="center">
<center>
<table bgcolor="#0060f0" border="0">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><font color="#c0ffff" size="5"><b>&nbsp;D - Ordering
T-shirts&nbsp;</b></font></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</center>
</div>
<h2><a name="SECTION1"><font color="#0070e8">Background</font></a></h2>
<p>Working in a boutique folding and putting in order T-shirts
according to their sizes seems very easy. But is it really so simple?</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION1"><font color="#0070e8">The
Problem</font></a></h2>
<p>Given<span style="line-height: 115%;">&nbsp;<i>n</i></span>
objects of different sizes, how many different arrangements can be done using
relationships "&lt;" and "="?</p>
<p>For instance, with 2 objects, A and B, we have 3 possible arrangements:</p><p>A=B&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
A&lt;B&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; B&lt;A</p><p>With 3 objects, A, B and C, you must conclude
that 13 different arrangements exist:</p>
<p>A=B=C&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
A=B&lt;C&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
A&lt;B=C&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
A&lt;B&lt;C&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
A&lt;C&lt;B&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
A=C&lt;B&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
B&lt;A=C&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
B&lt;A&lt;C&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
B&lt;C&lt;A&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
B=C&lt;A&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
C&lt;A=B&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
C&lt;A&lt;B&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
C&lt;B&lt;A</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION2"><font color="#0070e8">The
Input</font></a></h2>
<p><span style="line-height: 115%;">The first line
of the input contains an integer,<em>&nbsp;t</em>,
indicating the number of test cases. For each test case, one line
appears, that contains a
number <i>n</i>, </span><span style="line-height: 115%;">1&lt;=<i>n</i>&lt;=11,
representing the number of objects.</span></p>
<h2><a name="SECTION2"><font color="#0070e8">The
Output</font></a></h2>
<p>For each test case, the output should contain a
single line with the number representing the different arrangements you
can do with <i>n</i> objects.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION3"><font color="#0070e8">Sample
Input</font></a></h2>
<pre>4<br>1<br>2<br>3<br>4<br><br></pre>
<h2><a name="SECTION4"><font color="#0070e8">Sample
Output</font></a></h2>
<pre>1<br>3<br>13<br>75<br></pre>
<hr>
<p align="right"><font color="#000040"><small><small><a href="http://dis.um.es/contest" target="_blank">OMP'11</a><br>
<a href="http://www.um.es/informatica" target="_blank">Facultad
de Informatica<br>
</a><a href="http://www.um.es" target="_blank">Universidad
de Murcia (SPAIN)</a></small></small></font></p>
</body></html>

<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN">
<html><head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1"><title>Escher and tessellations</title></head>
<body style="background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);" lang="EN">
<div align="center">
<center>
<table bgcolor="#0060f0" border="0">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><b><font color="#c0ffff" size="5">&nbsp;E
- Escher and Tessellations</font>&nbsp;</b></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</center>
</div>
<h2><font color="#0070e8">Background</font></h2>
<p>Maurits Cornelis Escher (commonly known as M.C. Escher) was a
famous Dutch
graphic artist. He is known for his mathematically inspired
pictures representing impossible constructions, explorations of
infinity, architecture, and tessellations. A tessellation (or tiling)
of the plane is a pattern of plane figures that fills the plane with
no overlaps and no gaps.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img style="width: 612px; height: 112px;" alt="Metamorphose" src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12023a.jpg" ></p>
<h2><font color="#0070e8">The Problem</font></h2>
<p>Anthony Joseph (known by his friends as A.J.) is a student of
the
School of Computer Science doing research on a particular kind of
tessellations. Essentially, the figures that are going to be
replicated across the plane are comprised of a certain number of
squares with a fixed size. A.J. wants to know if a given figure
tessellates on a given board (a rectangle).</p>
<p>You have to observe that when a figure protrudes the board by
one of its edges, it
appears at the opposite side (i.e., the board is <span style="font-style: italic;">circular</span>).</p>
<p>The following image gives an example of a figure that
tessellates
on a particular board and another example of a figure that does not
tessellate:</p>
<table align="center" border="1" cellpadding="10">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>
<p align="center"><img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12023a.jpg" ><br>
<em>This figure tessellates on an 8x8 board.</em></p>
</td>
<td>
<p align="center"><img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12023a.jpg" ><br>
<em>This figure does not tessellate on a 4x4 board.</em></p>
</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Note that a figure can tessellate on a board of certain
dimensions,
but could not tessellate on a board of other dimensions.
</p>
<p>Now, A.J. is asking you to write a program that helps him to
check
if a figure tessellates or not on a given board.</p>
<h2><font color="#0070e8">The Input</font></h2>
<p>The input consists of a first line with a number indicating
the
number of test cases. Then the test cases are separated by a new
line.</p>
<p>Each test case consists of three parts. First, two numbers
(&lt;= 8) indicating the height and width, respectively, of the
smallest
rectangle that completely surrounds the figure. Second, there are as
many lines
as the height of the figure, each one with as many characters as the
width of the figure. Each character can be one of these two symbols:
"#" and ".".</p>
<p>"#" indicates that this position is covered by the
figure. "." indicates that this position is not covered by the
figure. The last line of each test case contains two numbers (&lt;=
8) that
indicate the
height and the width of the board.</p>
<h2><font color="#0070e8">The Output</font></h2>
<p>For each input case, you must print a line containing the word
"YES" in case the given figure tessellates for the given board or
containing the word "NO" otherwise.</p>
<h2><font color="#0070e8">Sample Input</font></h2>
<pre>2<br><br>3 3<br>.##<br>###<br>###<br>8 8<br><br>2 2<br>#.<br>##<br>4 4<br></pre>
<h2><font color="#0070e8">Sample Output</font></h2>
<pre>YES<br>NO<br></pre>
<hr>
<p align="right"><font color="#000040"><small><small><a href="http://dis.um.es/contest" target="_blank">OMP'11</a><br>
<a href="http://www.um.es/informatica" target="_blank">Facultad
de Informatica<br>
</a><a href="http://www.um.es" target="_blank">Universidad
de Murcia (SPAIN)</a></small></small></font></p>
</body></html>

______________________________________________________
