<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN">
<html><head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1"><title>Hats</title></head>
<body lang="EN">
<div align="center">
<center>
<table bgcolor="#0060f0" border="0">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><font color="#c0ffff" size="5"><b>&nbsp;F
- Hats&nbsp;</b></font></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</center>
</div>
<h2><a name="SECTION1"><font color="#0070e8">Background</font></a><span style="position: absolute; left: 980px; top: 44px; z-index: -1;"><img src="http://uva.onlinejudge.org/external/120/p12024.jpg"  border="0" height="234" width="107"></span></h2>
<p>John Hatman, the honest cloakroom attendant of the Royal
Theatre of London, would like to know the solution to the following
problem.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION1"><font color="#0070e8">The
Problem</font></a></h2>
<h2><font size="3"><span style="font-weight: 400;">When
the show finishes,</span></font><span style="font-weight: 400;"><font size="3"> a</font></span><font size="3"><span style="font-weight: 400;">ll</span></font><font size="3"><span style="font-weight: 400;"> spectators in the theatre are in a hurry to see the Final of the UEFA
Championship. So, they run to the cloakroom to take their hats back.</span></font></h2>
<p>Some of them take a wrong hat. But, how likely is that
everyone take a wrong hat?</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION2"><font color="#0070e8">The
Input</font></a></h2>
<p><span style="line-height: 115%;">The first line
of the input contains an integer,<em>&nbsp;t</em>,
indicating the number of test cases. For each test case, one line
appears, that contains a
number <i>n</i>, 2&lt;=<i>n</i>&lt;=12,
representing the number of people and hats.</span></p>
<h2><a name="SECTION2"><font color="#0070e8">The
Output</font></a></h2>
<p>For each test case, the output should contain a
single line with the number representing the number of favourable cases
(i.e., the number of cases where all people take a wrong hat),
followed by a bar, "/", and followed by a number representing the
total number of possible cases.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION3"><font color="#0070e8">Sample
Input</font></a></h2>
<pre>3<br>2<br>3<br>4<br><br></pre>
<h2><a name="SECTION4"><font color="#0070e8">Sample
Output</font></a></h2>
<pre>1/2<br>2/6<br>9/24<br><br></pre>
<hr>
<p align="right"><font color="#000040"><small><small><a href="http://dis.um.es/contest" target="_blank">OMP'11</a><br>
<a href="http://www.um.es/informatica" target="_blank">Facultad
de Informatica<br>
</a><a href="http://www.um.es" target="_blank">Universidad
de Murcia (SPAIN)</a></small></small></font></p>
</body></html>

______________________________________________________
12025||||||false||||||
<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN">
<html><head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><title>Wrong keys</title>

</head>
<body style="background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);" lang="EN">
<div align="center">
<center>
<table summary="Table used for layout (ugh)" bgcolor="#0060f0" border="0">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><b>&nbsp;<font color="#c0ffff" size="5">G - Wrong Keys</font>&nbsp;</b></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</center>
</div>
<h2><font color="#0070e8">Background</font></h2>
<!-- Â¿DÃ³nde fue el h1? -->
<p>The <i>ACME Publishing Company</i> has bought
thousands of cheap keyboards from ACM (A Computer Manufacturer) and has
given one to each of their authors. ACME's writers are not great
typists and compose their exquisite novels typing with just one finger
of each hand and carefully looking for each one of the keys as they
need to press it. As a result, they cannot look at the screen while
they are typing. Also, due to the tight deadlines imposed by ACME, the
writers cannot revise what they write.</p>
<p>ACM keyboards were amazingly cheap, but that was only because
they were slightly defective: each keyboard had a couple of keys
incorrectly placed.</p>
<p>For example, one of the keyboards had the "b" and "t" keys
each placed where the other one should be. So, if Shakespeare had used
it to write <i>Hamlet</i> then the phrase "Bo te or nob bo
te" would be quite famous today.</p>
<p>Unfortunately, ACME didn't realize the problem until the
authors sent several hundreds of novels for publishing, each of them
written with a keyboard that had a pair of keys misplaced. Since
publishing such gibberish is not acceptable even for ACME standards,
they have decided to fix the novels before printing them.</p>
<h2><font color="#0070e8">The Problem</font></h2>
<p>You have to write a program that will read the novels and
decide how to fix each of them. For that, it will decide which letters
to switch so that the result contains as few <b>different</b> wrong words as possible according to a dictionary.</p>
<h2><font color="#0070e8">The Input</font></h2>
<p>The input format is as follows:</p>
<p>An integer in a single line which says the number of problems
to solve. Then, for each problem:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>An integer <i>nw</i> in a line of itself
denoting the number of words in the dictionary.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><i>nw</i> words, each in a single line. These
words will be in lowercase and contain only the characters quoted next:
"abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz'-".</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>An integer <i>nb</i> in a line of itself
telling the number of books to revise using the same dictionary.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><i>nb</i> books. Each book starts with a line
containing exactly the string ".ONCE UPON A TIME." and ends with a line
containing exactly the string ".THE END.". Books can contain any
character between those lines, but the words to be considered can
contain only uppercase or lowercase letters from "a" to "z", hyphens
("-") and apostrophes (" ' "), and cannot start nor end with either a
hyphen or an apostrophe. </p>
</li>
</ul>
<h2><font color="#0070e8">The Output</font></h2>
<p>The output consists of one line for each book showing the two
letters (from "a" to "z") that should be swapped in the text to obtain
a text containing the minimum possible number of different words that
cannot be found in the dictionary, separated by a space and in
alphabetic order. If there are several minimum solutions, only the
first one in lexicographic order should be shown.</p>
<p>The case of the letters of a word is not relevant when looking
it up in the dictionary. The two letters of the solution must be
different.</p>
<h2><font color="#0070e8">Sample Input</font></h2>
<pre>1<br>4<br>be<br>or<br>to<br>not<br>3<br>.ONCE UPON A TIME.<br>Bo te or nob bo te.<br>.THE END.<br>.ONCE UPON A TIME.<br>Now pay parbicular abbenbion bo bhis firsb clause, tecause ib's mosb imporbanb. <br>Bhere's bhe parby of bhe firsb parb shall te known in bhis conbracb as bhe <br>parby of bhe firsb parb. How do you like bhab, bhab's prebby neab eh?<br>.THE END.<br>.ONCE UPON A TIME.<br>Simple case :-)<br>.THE END.</pre>
<h2><font color="#0070e8">Sample Output</font></h2>
<pre>b t<br>b t<br>a b</pre>
<hr>
<p align="right"><font color="#000040"><small><small><a href="http://dis.um.es/contest" target="_blank">OMP'11</a><br>
<a href="http://www.um.es/informatica" target="_blank">Facultad
de Informatica<br>
</a><a href="http://www.um.es" target="_blank">Universidad
de Murcia (SPAIN)</a></small></small></font></p>
</body></html>
______________________________________________________
12026||||||false||||||
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN">
<html><head>
<meta http-equiv="CONTENT-TYPE" content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><title>Radars</title>

<meta name="CHANGEDBY" content="Domingo Gimenez">
</head>

<body style="direction: ltr;" lang="en-US">
<div align="center">
<center>
<table bgcolor="#0060f0" border="0">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><b>&nbsp;<font color="#c0ffff" size="5">H - Radars</font>&nbsp;</b></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</center>
</div>
<h2><font><font color="#0070e8">Background</font></font></h2>
<p>Some
radars have
been installed to control the airspace of a country. Each radar
covers an area of the country, and the government of the country
wants to know if all the space is covered by the radars.</p>
<h2><font><font color="#0070e8">The Problem</font></font></h2>
<p>The airspace is divided
into a square
mesh of NxN zones, and each zone is labeled with an integer number.
Each radar is situated in one of the zones, and the zone where a
radar is situated is labeled with 0 (zero). The
area of influence of each radar is determined by the values in its
four neighboring zones in vertical and horizontal. If the radar is in
zone (i,j), the mean of the values in zones
(i-1,j), (i+1,j), (i,j-1) and (i,j+1) indicates the extent
of the influence. To obtain the mean only neighbors in the NxN mesh
are considered.</p>
<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="en">So, for example, in the mesh:</p>
<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="en">0</p>
<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="en">the mean
is 0,</p>
<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="en">and in the mesh:</p>
<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="en">0 1</p>
<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="en">2 1</p>
<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="en">the mean
corresponding to the
radar is 3/2.</p>
<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm;" lang="en">Positions
(k,l) with Euclidean distance to (i,j) less or equal to the mean (as computed above) are in the
influence area of the radar in position (i,j). </p>
<p style="margin-bottom: 0cm; font-style: normal;">We want
to count
the number of zones not controlled by any radar.</p>
<h2><font><font color="#0070e8">The Input</font></font></h2>
<p style="font-style: normal;">The input begins with a
line where the
number of test cases (<span style="font-style: italic;">T</span>) is indicated. The data for each test case
appear in successive lines. For each test case, the first line
contains the dimension of the airspace (<span style="font-style: italic;">N</span>, and there are <span style="font-style: italic;">N</span> by <span style="font-style: italic;">N</span>
zones). Next, there are <span style="font-style: italic;">N</span> lines, each with <span style="font-style: italic;">N</span> integers greater or
equal to zero, separated by a space. </p>
<h2><font><font color="#0070e8">The Output</font></font></h2>
<p>The output consists of <span style="font-style: italic;">T</span> lines, one for each test case. <span style="font-style: normal;">For
each case, the number of zones not controlled by any radar is
represented.</span></p>
<h2><font><font color="#0070e8">Sample Input</font></font></h2>
<pre class="western">2<br>4<br>1 2 0 0<br>0 1 1 0<br>1 1 2 0<br>0 1 1 1<br>5<br>1 1 0 1 1<br>2 1 2 0 1<br>2 2 1 0 0<br>1 2 0 1 1<br>1 0 2 1 1</pre>
<h2><font><font color="#0070e8">Sample Output</font></font></h2>
<pre class="western">2<br>7</pre>
<hr>
<p align="right"><font color="#000040"><small><small><a href="http://dis.um.es/contest" target="_blank">OMP'11</a><br>
<a href="http://www.um.es/informatica" target="_blank">Facultad
de Informatica<br>
</a><a href="http://www.um.es" target="_blank">Universidad
de Murcia (SPAIN)</a></small></small></font></p>
</body></html>
______________________________________________________
12027||||||false||||||
<html><head>
<meta name="autor" content="Gines Garcia Mateos, Murcia 05/05/11">
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1"><title>Very big perfect squares</title>

</head>
<body lang="EN">
<div align="center">
<center>
<table bgcolor="#0060f0" border="0">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><font color="#c0ffff" size="5"><b>&nbsp; I
- Very Big Perfect Squares &nbsp;</b></font></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</center>
</div>
<h2><a name="SECTION1"><font color="#0070e8">Background</font></a></h2>
<p>An integer, <span style="font-style: italic;">n</span>,
is called <span style="font-style: italic;">a
perfect square</span> if there is another integer, <span style="font-style: italic;">m</span>, such that <span style="font-style: italic;">n</span> = <span style="font-style: italic;">m</span> x <span style="font-style: italic;">m</span>. Examples of
perfect squares are 1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, etc. That is: 1, 2<sup>2</sup>,
3<sup>2</sup>, 4<sup>2</sup>, 5<sup>2</sup>,
6<sup>2</sup>, etc.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION1"><font color="#0070e8">The
Problem</font></a></h2>
<p>Given a natural number, <em>A</em><em></em>,
we want to know how many perfect squares exist between 1 and <span style="font-style: italic;">A</span>,
inclusive. For example, between 1 and 1 there is only one perfect
square (1), between 1 and 5 there are 2 (1 and 4), between 1 and 40
there are 6 (1, 4, 9, 16, 25 and 36).</p>
<p>We
want to work with very big numbers, so we are not very interested in
accuracy. We only need the first digit of the result, and the
rest of digits can be 0.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION2"><font color="#0070e8">Input</font></a></h2>
<p>The input can contain different test cases.</p>
<p>For each test case, there is a line with a natural number <span style="font-style: italic;">A</span><span style="font-style: italic;"></span>.</p>
<p>You can assume that <em>A</em> is between
1 y 10<sup>1000</sup>,
inclusive.</p>
<p>The output ends with a line with the value: 0.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION2"><font color="#0070e8">Output</font></a></h2>
<p>For each test case, the output should be a line with a natural
number <span style="font-style: italic;">N</span>,
indicating how many perfect squares exist between 1 and <span style="font-style: italic;">A</span>, inclusive.</p>
<p>As we do not need too much precision, you only have to output
the most significant digit of the result. You have to complete the
rest of the result with zeros. For example, if the result is 59, then
you have to output 50; if the result is
12345, then you have to output: 10000.</p>
<h2><a name="SECTION3"><font color="#0070e8">Sample
Input</font></a></h2>
<pre>1<br>5<br>40<br>1000<br>0<br></pre>
<h2><a name="SECTION4"><font color="#0070e8">Sample
Output</font></a></h2>
<pre>1<br>2<br>6<br>30<br></pre>
